gene.set.statistics.name: mitochondrial genome maintenance
gene.set.statistics.description: The maintenance of the structure and integrity of the mitochondrial genome; includes replication and segregation of the mitochondrial chromosome.

gene.set.statistics.name: single strand break repair
gene.set.statistics.description: The repair of single strand breaks in DNA. Repair of such breaks is mediated by the same enzyme systems as are used in base excision repair.

gene.set.statistics.name: regulation of DNA recombination
gene.set.statistics.description: Any process that modulates the frequency, rate or extent of DNA recombination, a DNA metabolic process in which a new genotype is formed by reassortment of genes resulting in gene combinations different from those that were present in the parents.

gene.set.statistics.name: ribosomal large subunit assembly
gene.set.statistics.description: The aggregation, arrangement and bonding together of constituent RNAs and proteins to form the large ribosomal subunit.

gene.set.statistics.name: ribosomal small subunit assembly
gene.set.statistics.description: The aggregation, arrangement and bonding together of constituent RNAs and proteins to form the small ribosomal subunit.

gene.set.statistics.name: very long-chain fatty acid metabolic process
gene.set.statistics.description: The chemical reactions and pathways involving a fatty acid which has a chain length greater than C22.

gene.set.statistics.name: autophagosome assembly
gene.set.statistics.description: The formation of a double membrane-bounded structure, the autophagosome, that occurs when a specialized membrane sac, called the isolation membrane, starts to enclose a portion of the cytoplasm.

gene.set.statistics.name: urea cycle
gene.set.statistics.description: The sequence of reactions by which arginine is synthesized from ornithine, then cleaved to yield urea and regenerate ornithine. The overall reaction equation is NH3 + CO2 + aspartate + 3 ATP + 2 H2O = urea + fumarate + 2 ADP + 2 phosphate + AMP + diphosphate.

gene.set.statistics.name: citrulline metabolic process
gene.set.statistics.description: The chemical reactions and pathways involving citrulline, N5-carbamoyl-L-ornithine, an alpha amino acid not found in proteins.

gene.set.statistics.name: ribosomal subunit export from nucleus
gene.set.statistics.description: The directed movement of a ribosomal subunit from the nucleus into the cytoplasm.

gene.set.statistics.name: ribosomal large subunit export from nucleus
gene.set.statistics.description: The directed movement of a ribosomal large subunit from the nucleus into the cytoplasm.

gene.set.statistics.name: ribosomal small subunit export from nucleus
gene.set.statistics.description: The directed movement of a ribosomal small subunit from the nucleus into the cytoplasm.

gene.set.statistics.name: mitotic sister chromatid segregation
gene.set.statistics.description: The cell cycle process in which replicated homologous chromosomes are organized and then physically separated and apportioned to two sets during the mitotic cell cycle. Each replicated chromosome, composed of two sister chromatids, aligns at the cell equator, paired with its homologous partner. One homolog of each morphologic type goes into each of the resulting chromosome sets.

gene.set.statistics.name: DNA damage checkpoint signaling
gene.set.statistics.description: A signal transduction process that contributes to a DNA damage checkpoint.

gene.set.statistics.name: regulation of cyclin-dependent protein serine/threonine kinase activity
gene.set.statistics.description: Any process that modulates the frequency, rate or extent of cyclin-dependent protein serine/threonine kinase activity.

gene.set.statistics.name: G1/S transition of mitotic cell cycle
gene.set.statistics.description: The mitotic cell cycle transition by which a cell in G1 commits to S phase. The process begins with the build up of G1 cyclin-dependent kinase (G1 CDK), resulting in the activation of transcription of G1 cyclins. The process ends with the positive feedback of the G1 cyclins on the G1 CDK which commits the cell to S phase, in which DNA replication is initiated.

gene.set.statistics.name: regulation of transcription involved in G1/S transition of mitotic cell cycle
gene.set.statistics.description: Any process that regulates transcription such that the target genes are involved in the transition between G1 and S phase of the mitotic cell cycle.

gene.set.statistics.name: G2/M transition of mitotic cell cycle
gene.set.statistics.description: The mitotic cell cycle transition by which a cell in G2 commits to M phase. The process begins when the kinase activity of M cyclin/CDK complex reaches a threshold high enough for the cell cycle to proceed. This is accomplished by activating a positive feedback loop that results in the accumulation of unphosphorylated and active M cyclin/CDK complex.

gene.set.statistics.name: sulfur amino acid metabolic process
gene.set.statistics.description: The chemical reactions and pathways involving amino acids containing sulfur, comprising cysteine, homocysteine, methionine and selenocysteine.

gene.set.statistics.name: histidine biosynthetic process
gene.set.statistics.description: The chemical reactions and pathways resulting in the formation of histidine, 2-amino-3-(1H-imidazol-4-yl)propanoic acid.

gene.set.statistics.name: negative regulation of transcription by RNA polymerase II
gene.set.statistics.description: Any process that stops, prevents, or reduces the frequency, rate or extent of transcription mediated by RNA polymerase II.

gene.set.statistics.name: establishment of mitotic spindle orientation
gene.set.statistics.description: A cell cycle process that sets the alignment of mitotic spindle relative to other cellular structures.

gene.set.statistics.name: MAPK cascade
gene.set.statistics.description: An intracellular protein kinase cascade containing at least a MAPK, a MAPKK and a MAP3K. The cascade can also contain an additional tiers: the upstream MAP4K. The kinases in each tier phosphorylate and activate the kinase in the downstream tier to transmit a signal within a cell.

gene.set.statistics.name: rDNA heterochromatin assembly
gene.set.statistics.description: The assembly of chromatin characterized by the modified histone H3K9me3, into heterochromatin, resulting in the repression of transcription of rDNA.

gene.set.statistics.name: nuclear-transcribed mRNA catabolic process, nonsense-mediated decay
gene.set.statistics.description: The nonsense-mediated decay pathway for nuclear-transcribed mRNAs degrades mRNAs in which an amino-acid codon has changed to a nonsense codon; this prevents the translation of such mRNAs into truncated, and potentially harmful, proteins.

gene.set.statistics.name: activation of MAPKK activity
gene.set.statistics.description: The initiation of the activity of the inactive enzyme MAP kinase kinase (MAPKK).

gene.set.statistics.name: activation of MAPK activity
gene.set.statistics.description: The initiation of the activity of the inactive enzyme MAP kinase (MAPK).

gene.set.statistics.name: inactivation of MAPK activity
gene.set.statistics.description: Any process that terminates the activity of the active enzyme MAP kinase.

gene.set.statistics.name: protein polyubiquitination
gene.set.statistics.description: Addition of multiple ubiquitin groups to a protein, forming a ubiquitin chain.

gene.set.statistics.name: meiotic spindle organization
gene.set.statistics.description: A process that is carried out at the cellular level which results in the assembly, arrangement of constituent parts, or disassembly of the microtubule spindle during a meiotic cell cycle.

gene.set.statistics.name: microtubule cytoskeleton organization
gene.set.statistics.description: A process that is carried out at the cellular level which results in the assembly, arrangement of constituent parts, or disassembly of cytoskeletal structures comprising microtubules and their associated proteins.

gene.set.statistics.name: spliceosomal tri-snRNP complex assembly
gene.set.statistics.description: The formation of a tri-snRNP complex containing U4 and U6 (or U4atac and U6atac) snRNAs and U5 snRNAs and associated proteins. This includes reannealing of U4 and U6 (or U4atac and U6atac) snRNAs released from previous rounds of splicing to reform the U4/U6 snRNP (or U4atac/U6atac snRNP) as well as the subsequent association of the U5 snRNP with the U4/U6 snRNP (or U4atac/U6atac snRNP) to form a tri-snRNP that is ready to reassemble into another spliceosome complex.

gene.set.statistics.name: spliceosomal complex assembly
gene.set.statistics.description: The aggregation, arrangement and bonding together of a spliceosomal complex, a ribonucleoprotein apparatus that catalyzes nuclear mRNA splicing via transesterification reactions.

gene.set.statistics.name: mitochondrial fission
gene.set.statistics.description: The division of a mitochondrion within a cell to form two or more separate mitochondrial compartments.

gene.set.statistics.name: mitotic cell cycle
gene.set.statistics.description: Progression through the phases of the mitotic cell cycle, the most common eukaryotic cell cycle, which canonically comprises four successive phases called G1, S, G2, and M and includes replication of the genome and the subsequent segregation of chromosomes into daughter cells. In some variant cell cycles nuclear replication or nuclear division may not be followed by cell division, or G1 and G2 phases may be absent.

gene.set.statistics.name: mitotic cytokinesis
gene.set.statistics.description: A cell cycle process that results in the division of the cytoplasm of a cell after mitosis, resulting in the separation of the original cell into two daughter cells.

gene.set.statistics.name: nuclear-transcribed mRNA catabolic process, deadenylation-dependent decay
gene.set.statistics.description: A major pathway of degradation of nuclear-transcribed mRNAs that proceeds through a series of ordered steps that includes poly(A) tail shortening and that can regulate mRNA stability.

gene.set.statistics.name: nuclear-transcribed mRNA poly(A) tail shortening
gene.set.statistics.description: Shortening of the poly(A) tail of a nuclear-transcribed mRNA from full length to an oligo(A) length.

gene.set.statistics.name: nuclear-transcribed mRNA catabolic process, endonucleolytic cleavage-dependent decay
gene.set.statistics.description: A minor degradation pathway nuclear-transcribed mRNAs that begins with an endonucleolytic cleavage to generate unprotected ends.

gene.set.statistics.name: response to reactive oxygen species
gene.set.statistics.description: Any process that results in a change in state or activity of a cell or an organism (in terms of movement, secretion, enzyme production, gene expression, etc.) as a result of a reactive oxygen species stimulus. Reactive oxygen species include singlet oxygen, superoxide, and oxygen free radicals.

gene.set.statistics.name: response to superoxide
gene.set.statistics.description: Any process that results in a change in state or activity of a cell or an organism (in terms of movement, secretion, enzyme production, gene expression, etc.) as a result of a superoxide stimulus. Superoxide is the anion, oxygen-, formed by addition of one electron to dioxygen (O2) or any compound containing the superoxide anion.

gene.set.statistics.name: protein deneddylation
gene.set.statistics.description: The removal of a ubiquitin-like protein of the NEDD8 type from a protein.

gene.set.statistics.name: generation of catalytic spliceosome for first transesterification step
gene.set.statistics.description: Formation of a catalytic spliceosome complex ready to perform the first splicing reaction. This occurs by an ATP-dependent conformational change of the pre-catalytic spliceosome.

gene.set.statistics.name: RNA splicing, via transesterification reactions
gene.set.statistics.description: Splicing of RNA via a series of two transesterification reactions.

gene.set.statistics.name: alternative mRNA splicing, via spliceosome
gene.set.statistics.description: The process of generating multiple mRNA molecules from a given set of exons by differential use of exons from the primary transcript(s) to form multiple mature mRNAs that vary in their exon composition.

gene.set.statistics.name: regulation of alternative mRNA splicing, via spliceosome
gene.set.statistics.description: Any process that modulates the frequency, rate or extent of alternative splicing of nuclear mRNAs.

gene.set.statistics.name: spliceosomal snRNP assembly
gene.set.statistics.description: The aggregation, arrangement and bonding together of one or more snRNA and multiple protein components to form a ribonucleoprotein complex that is involved in formation of the spliceosome.

gene.set.statistics.name: mRNA 3'-splice site recognition
gene.set.statistics.description: Recognition of the intron 3'-splice site by components of the assembling U2- or U12-type spliceosome.

gene.set.statistics.name: mRNA 5'-splice site recognition
gene.set.statistics.description: Recognition of the intron 5'-splice site by components of the assembling spliceosome.

gene.set.statistics.name: mRNA splicing, via spliceosome
gene.set.statistics.description: The joining together of exons from one or more primary transcripts of messenger RNA (mRNA) and the excision of intron sequences, via a spliceosomal mechanism, so that mRNA consisting only of the joined exons is produced.

gene.set.statistics.name: protein peptidyl-prolyl isomerization
gene.set.statistics.description: The modification of a protein by cis-trans isomerization of a proline residue.

gene.set.statistics.name: autophagy of mitochondrion
gene.set.statistics.description: The autophagic process in which mitochondria are delivered to a type of vacuole and degraded in response to changing cellular conditions.

gene.set.statistics.name: mitophagy
gene.set.statistics.description: The selective autophagy process in which a mitochondrion is degraded by macroautophagy.

gene.set.statistics.name: pexophagy
gene.set.statistics.description: The selective autophagy process in which a peroxisome is degraded by macroautophagy.

gene.set.statistics.name: endonucleolytic cleavage in ITS1 to separate SSU-rRNA from 5.8S rRNA and LSU-rRNA from tricistronic rRNA transcript (SSU-rRNA, 5.8S rRNA, LSU-rRNA)
gene.set.statistics.description: Endonucleolytic cleavage between the SSU-rRNA and the 5.8S rRNA of an rRNA molecule originally produced as a tricistronic rRNA transcript that contained the Small SubUnit (SSU) rRNA, the 5.8S rRNA, and the Large SubUnit (LSU) rRNA, in that order, from 5' to 3' along the primary transcript.

gene.set.statistics.name: enzyme-directed rRNA pseudouridine synthesis
gene.set.statistics.description: The intramolecular conversion of uridine to pseudouridine during ribosome biogenesis where the enzyme specifies the site that becomes pseudouridylated without using a guide RNA.

gene.set.statistics.name: maturation of 5.8S rRNA
gene.set.statistics.description: Any process involved in the maturation of a precursor 5.8S ribosomal RNA (rRNA) molecule into a mature 5.8S rRNA molecule.

gene.set.statistics.name: maturation of SSU-rRNA from tricistronic rRNA transcript (SSU-rRNA, 5.8S rRNA, LSU-rRNA)
gene.set.statistics.description: Any process involved in the maturation of a precursor Small SubUnit (SSU) ribosomal RNA (rRNA) molecule into a mature SSU-rRNA molecule from the pre-rRNA molecule originally produced as a tricistronic rRNA transcript that contains the Small Subunit (SSU) rRNA, 5.8S rRNA, and the Large Subunit (LSU) in that order from 5' to 3' along the primary transcript.

gene.set.statistics.name: maturation of LSU-rRNA from tricistronic rRNA transcript (SSU-rRNA, 5.8S rRNA, LSU-rRNA)
gene.set.statistics.description: Any process involved in the maturation of a precursor Large SubUnit (LSU) ribosomal RNA (rRNA) molecule into a mature LSU-rRNA molecule from the pre-rRNA molecule originally produced as a tricistronic rRNA transcript that contains the Small Subunit (SSU) rRNA, 5.8S rRNA, and Large Subunit (LSU) in that order from 5' to 3' along the primary transcript.

gene.set.statistics.name: maturation of 5.8S rRNA from tricistronic rRNA transcript (SSU-rRNA, 5.8S rRNA, LSU-rRNA)
gene.set.statistics.description: Any process involved in the maturation of an rRNA molecule originally produced as part of a tricistronic rRNA transcript that contained the Small SubUnit (SSU) rRNA, the 5.8S rRNA, and the Large SubUnit (LSU) rRNA, in that order, from 5' to 3' along the primary transcript.

gene.set.statistics.name: maturation of LSU-rRNA
gene.set.statistics.description: Any process involved in the maturation of a precursor Large SubUnit (LSU) ribosomal RNA (rRNA) molecule into a mature LSU-rRNA molecule.

gene.set.statistics.name: endonucleolytic cleavage to generate mature 5'-end of SSU-rRNA from (SSU-rRNA, 5.8S rRNA, LSU-rRNA)
gene.set.statistics.description: Endonucleolytic cleavage between the 5'-External Transcribed Spacer (5'-ETS) and the 5' end of the SSU-rRNA of a tricistronic rRNA transcript that contains the Small Subunit (SSU) rRNA, the 5.8S rRNA, and the Large Subunit (LSU) rRNA in that order from 5' to 3' along the primary transcript, to produce the mature end of the SSU-rRNA.

gene.set.statistics.name: endonucleolytic cleavage in 5'-ETS of tricistronic rRNA transcript (SSU-rRNA, 5.8S rRNA, LSU-rRNA)
gene.set.statistics.description: Endonucleolytic cleavage within the 5'-External Transcribed Spacer (ETS) of a tricistronic rRNA transcript that contains the Small Subunit (SSU) rRNA, the 5.8S rRNA, and the Large Subunit (LSU) rRNA in that order from 5' to 3' along the primary transcript. Endonucleolytic cleavage within the 5'-ETS of the pre-RNA is conserved as one of the early steps of rRNA processing in all eukaryotes, but the specific position of cleavage is variable.

gene.set.statistics.name: box C/D snoRNP assembly
gene.set.statistics.description: The aggregation, arrangement and bonding together of proteins and a box C/D snoRNA to form a box C/D small nucleolar ribonucleoprotein (snoRNP) complex.

gene.set.statistics.name: resolution of meiotic recombination intermediates
gene.set.statistics.description: The cleavage and rejoining of intermediates, such as Holliday junctions, formed during meiotic recombination to produce two intact molecules in which genetic material has been exchanged.

gene.set.statistics.name: nucleotide-excision repair, DNA damage recognition
gene.set.statistics.description: The identification of lesions in DNA, such as pyrimidine-dimers, intrastrand cross-links, and bulky adducts. The wide range of substrate specificity suggests the repair complex recognizes distortions in the DNA helix.

gene.set.statistics.name: nucleotide-excision repair, DNA duplex unwinding
gene.set.statistics.description: The unwinding, or local denaturation, of the DNA duplex to create a bubble around the site of the DNA damage.

gene.set.statistics.name: telomere maintenance
gene.set.statistics.description: Any process that contributes to the maintenance of proper telomeric length and structure by affecting and monitoring the activity of telomeric proteins, the length of telomeric DNA and the replication and repair of the DNA. These processes includes those that shorten, lengthen, replicate and repair the telomeric DNA sequences.

gene.set.statistics.name: double-strand break repair via homologous recombination
gene.set.statistics.description: The error-free repair of a double-strand break in DNA in which the broken DNA molecule is repaired using homologous sequences. A strand in the broken DNA searches for a homologous region in an intact chromosome to serve as the template for DNA synthesis. The restoration of two intact DNA molecules results in the exchange, reciprocal or nonreciprocal, of genetic material between the intact DNA molecule and the broken DNA molecule.

gene.set.statistics.name: double-strand break repair via break-induced replication
gene.set.statistics.description: The error-free repair of a double-strand break in DNA in which the centromere-proximal end of a broken chromosome searches for a homologous region in an intact chromosome. DNA synthesis initiates from the 3' end of the invading DNA strand, using the intact chromosome as the template, and progresses to the end of the chromosome.

gene.set.statistics.name: DNA double-strand break processing
gene.set.statistics.description: The 5' to 3' exonucleolytic resection of the DNA at the site of the break to form a 3' single-strand DNA overhang.

gene.set.statistics.name: sister chromatid segregation
gene.set.statistics.description: The cell cycle process in which sister chromatids are organized and then physically separated and apportioned to two or more sets.

gene.set.statistics.name: cell morphogenesis
gene.set.statistics.description: The developmental process in which the size or shape of a cell is generated and organized.

gene.set.statistics.name: actomyosin contractile ring assembly
gene.set.statistics.description: The process of assembly of a ring composed of actin, myosin, and associated proteins that will function in cytokinesis.

gene.set.statistics.name: nuclear-transcribed mRNA catabolic process
gene.set.statistics.description: The chemical reactions and pathways resulting in the breakdown of nuclear-transcribed mRNAs in eukaryotic cells.

gene.set.statistics.name: negative regulation of mitochondrial RNA catabolic process
gene.set.statistics.description: Any process that stops, prevents, or reduces the frequency, rate or extent of the chemical reactions and pathways involving catabolism in the mitochondrion of RNA transcribed from the mitochondrial genome.

gene.set.statistics.name: transcription-dependent tethering of RNA polymerase II gene DNA at nuclear periphery
gene.set.statistics.description: The chromosome organization process in which the DNA sequence containing a gene transcribed by RNA polymerase II is maintained in a specific location at the nuclear periphery. In S. cerevisiae, this process involves cis-acting DNA sequences such as the TATA box and upstream activating sequence (UAS) elements, trans-acting transcriptional activators, and also the 3'-UTR of the transcript.

gene.set.statistics.name: RNA polymerase I preinitiation complex assembly
gene.set.statistics.description: The aggregation, arrangement and bonding together of proteins on promoter DNA to form the transcriptional preinitiation complex (PIC), the formation of which is a prerequisite for transcription from an RNA polymerase I promoter.

gene.set.statistics.name: skeletal system development
gene.set.statistics.description: The process whose specific outcome is the progression of the skeleton over time, from its formation to the mature structure. The skeleton is the bony framework of the body in vertebrates (endoskeleton) or the hard outer envelope of insects (exoskeleton or dermoskeleton).

gene.set.statistics.name: ossification
gene.set.statistics.description: The formation of bone or of a bony substance, or the conversion of fibrous tissue or of cartilage into bone or a bony substance.

gene.set.statistics.name: neurotransmitter uptake
gene.set.statistics.description: The directed movement of neurotransmitters into neurons or glial cells. This process leads to inactivation and recycling of neurotransmitters.

gene.set.statistics.name: RNA methylation
gene.set.statistics.description: Posttranscriptional addition of a methyl group to either a nucleotide or 2'-O ribose in a polyribonucleotide. Usually uses S-adenosylmethionine as a cofactor.

gene.set.statistics.name: prostaglandin biosynthetic process
gene.set.statistics.description: The chemical reactions and pathways resulting in the formation of prostaglandins, any of a group of biologically active metabolites which contain a cyclopentane ring.

gene.set.statistics.name: retinoid metabolic process
gene.set.statistics.description: The chemical reactions and pathways involving retinoids, any member of a class of isoprenoids that contain or are derived from four prenyl groups linked head-to-tail. Retinoids include retinol and retinal and structurally similar natural derivatives or synthetic compounds, but need not have vitamin A activity.

gene.set.statistics.name: angiogenesis
gene.set.statistics.description: Blood vessel formation when new vessels emerge from the proliferation of pre-existing blood vessels.

gene.set.statistics.name: ovarian follicle development
gene.set.statistics.description: The process whose specific outcome is the progression of the ovarian follicle over time, from its formation to the mature structure.

gene.set.statistics.name: luteinization
gene.set.statistics.description: The set of processes resulting in differentiation of theca and granulosa cells into luteal cells and in the formation of a corpus luteum after ovulation.

gene.set.statistics.name: luteolysis
gene.set.statistics.description: The lysis or structural demise of the corpus luteum. During normal luteolysis, two closely related events occur. First, there is loss of the capacity to synthesize and secrete progesterone (functional luteolysis) followed by loss of the cells that comprise the corpus luteum (structural luteolysis). Preventing luteolysis is crucial to maintain pregnancy.

gene.set.statistics.name: oocyte maturation
gene.set.statistics.description: A developmental process, independent of morphogenetic (shape) change, that is required for an oocyte to attain its fully functional state. Oocyte maturation commences after reinitiation of meiosis commonly starting with germinal vesicle breakdown, and continues up to the second meiotic arrest prior to fertilization.

gene.set.statistics.name: regulation of cell growth
gene.set.statistics.description: Any process that modulates the frequency, rate, extent or direction of cell growth.

gene.set.statistics.name: blood vessel development
gene.set.statistics.description: The process whose specific outcome is the progression of a blood vessel over time, from its formation to the mature structure. The blood vessel is the vasculature carrying blood.

gene.set.statistics.name: branching involved in blood vessel morphogenesis
gene.set.statistics.description: The process of coordinated growth and sprouting of blood vessels giving rise to the organized vascular system.

gene.set.statistics.name: vasculogenesis
gene.set.statistics.description: The differentiation of endothelial cells from progenitor cells during blood vessel development, and the de novo formation of blood vessels and tubes.

gene.set.statistics.name: microtubule bundle formation
gene.set.statistics.description: A process that results in a parallel arrangement of microtubules.

gene.set.statistics.name: medium-chain fatty acid transport
gene.set.statistics.description: The directed movement of medium-chain fatty acids into, out of or within a cell, or between cells, by means of some agent such as a transporter or pore. A medium-chain fatty acid is a fatty acid with a chain length of between C6 and C12.

gene.set.statistics.name: osteoblast differentiation
gene.set.statistics.description: The process whereby a relatively unspecialized cell acquires the specialized features of an osteoblast, a mesodermal or neural crest cell that gives rise to bone.

gene.set.statistics.name: eye development
gene.set.statistics.description: The process whose specific outcome is the progression of the eye over time, from its formation to the mature structure. The eye is the organ of sight.

gene.set.statistics.name: ureteric bud development
gene.set.statistics.description: The process whose specific outcome is the progression of the ureteric bud over time, from its formation to the mature structure.

gene.set.statistics.name: temperature homeostasis
gene.set.statistics.description: A homeostatic process in which an organism modulates its internal body temperature.

gene.set.statistics.name: behavioral fear response
gene.set.statistics.description: An acute behavioral change resulting from a perceived external threat.

gene.set.statistics.name: response to hypoxia
gene.set.statistics.description: Any process that results in a change in state or activity of a cell or an organism (in terms of movement, secretion, enzyme production, gene expression, etc.) as a result of a stimulus indicating lowered oxygen tension. Hypoxia, defined as a decline in O2 levels below normoxic levels of 20.8 - 20.95%, results in metabolic adaptation at both the cellular and organismal level.

gene.set.statistics.name: ameboidal-type cell migration
gene.set.statistics.description: Cell migration that is accomplished by extension and retraction of a pseudopodium.

gene.set.statistics.name: acrosome assembly
gene.set.statistics.description: The formation of the acrosome from the spermatid Golgi.

gene.set.statistics.name: long-chain fatty acid metabolic process
gene.set.statistics.description: The chemical reactions and pathways involving long-chain fatty acids, A long-chain fatty acid is a fatty acid with a chain length between C13 and C22.

gene.set.statistics.name: cellular glucose homeostasis
gene.set.statistics.description: A cellular homeostatic process involved in the maintenance of an internal steady state of glucose within a cell or between a cell and its external environment.

gene.set.statistics.name: tRNA 5'-leader removal
gene.set.statistics.description: Generation of the mature 5'-end of the tRNA, usually via an endonucleolytic cleavage by RNase P.

gene.set.statistics.name: in utero embryonic development
gene.set.statistics.description: The process whose specific outcome is the progression of the embryo in the uterus over time, from formation of the zygote in the oviduct, to birth. An example of this process is found in Mus musculus.

gene.set.statistics.name: gastrulation with mouth forming second
gene.set.statistics.description: A gastrulation process in which the initial invagination becomes the anus and the mouth forms second.

gene.set.statistics.name: endoderm formation
gene.set.statistics.description: The formation of the endoderm during gastrulation.

gene.set.statistics.name: mesoderm formation
gene.set.statistics.description: The process that gives rise to the mesoderm. This process pertains to the initial formation of the structure from unspecified parts.

gene.set.statistics.name: cell fate specification
gene.set.statistics.description: The process involved in the specification of cell identity. Once specification has taken place, a cell will be committed to differentiate down a specific pathway if left in its normal environment.

gene.set.statistics.name: endodermal cell fate commitment
gene.set.statistics.description: The cell differentiation process that results in commitment of a cell to become part of the endoderm.

gene.set.statistics.name: formation of translation preinitiation complex
gene.set.statistics.description: The joining of the small ribosomal subunit, ternary complex, and mRNA.

gene.set.statistics.name: formation of cytoplasmic translation initiation complex
gene.set.statistics.description: Joining of the large subunit, with release of IF2/eIF2 and IF3/eIF3. This leaves the functional ribosome at the AUG, with the methionyl/formyl-methionyl-tRNA positioned at the P site.

gene.set.statistics.name: morphogenesis of a polarized epithelium
gene.set.statistics.description: The morphogenetic process in which the anatomical structures of a polarized epithelium are generated and organized. A polarized epithelium is an epithelium where the epithelial sheet is oriented with respect to the planar axis.

gene.set.statistics.name: eye photoreceptor cell differentiation
gene.set.statistics.description: The process in which a relatively unspecialized cell acquires the specialized features of a photoreceptor cell, as found in the eye, the primary visual organ of most organisms.

gene.set.statistics.name: neural crest cell migration
gene.set.statistics.description: The characteristic movement of cells from the dorsal ridge of the neural tube to a variety of locations in a vertebrate embryo.

gene.set.statistics.name: somitogenesis
gene.set.statistics.description: The formation of mesodermal clusters that are arranged segmentally along the anterior posterior axis of an embryo.

gene.set.statistics.name: neuron migration
gene.set.statistics.description: The characteristic movement of an immature neuron from germinal zones to specific positions where they will reside as they mature.

gene.set.statistics.name: membrane raft assembly
gene.set.statistics.description: The aggregation, arrangement and bonding together of a set of components to form a membrane raft, a small (10-200 nm), heterogeneous, highly dynamic, sterol- and sphingolipid-enriched membrane domains that compartmentalizes cellular processes.

gene.set.statistics.name: establishment of T cell polarity
gene.set.statistics.description: The directed orientation of T cell signaling molecules and associated membrane rafts towards a chemokine gradient or a contact point with antigen presenting cell.

gene.set.statistics.name: immunological synapse formation
gene.set.statistics.description: The formation of an area of close contact between a lymphocyte (T-, B-, or natural killer cell) and a target cell through the clustering of particular signaling and adhesion molecules and their associated membrane rafts on both the lymphocyte and target cell, which facilitates activation of the lymphocyte, transfer of membrane from the target cell to the lymphocyte, and in some situations killing of the target cell through release of secretory granules and/or death-pathway ligand-receptor interaction.

gene.set.statistics.name: microglial cell activation
gene.set.statistics.description: The change in morphology and behavior of a microglial cell resulting from exposure to a cytokine, chemokine, cellular ligand, or soluble factor.

gene.set.statistics.name: plasma membrane repair
gene.set.statistics.description: The resealing of a cell plasma membrane after cellular wounding due to, for instance, mechanical stress.

gene.set.statistics.name: B cell homeostasis
gene.set.statistics.description: The process of regulating the proliferation and elimination of B cells such that the total number of B cells within a whole or part of an organism is stable over time in the absence of an outside stimulus.

gene.set.statistics.name: B cell apoptotic process
gene.set.statistics.description: Any apoptotic process in a B cell, a lymphocyte of B lineage with the phenotype CD19-positive and capable of B cell mediated immunity.

gene.set.statistics.name: regulation of cytokine production
gene.set.statistics.description: Any process that modulates the frequency, rate, or extent of production of a cytokine.

gene.set.statistics.name: negative regulation of cytokine production
gene.set.statistics.description: Any process that stops, prevents, or reduces the rate of production of a cytokine.

gene.set.statistics.name: positive regulation of cytokine production
gene.set.statistics.description: Any process that activates or increases the frequency, rate or extent of production of a cytokine.

gene.set.statistics.name: kidney development
gene.set.statistics.description: The process whose specific outcome is the progression of the kidney over time, from its formation to the mature structure. The kidney is an organ that filters the blood and/or excretes the end products of body metabolism in the form of urine.

gene.set.statistics.name: blastocyst development
gene.set.statistics.description: The process whose specific outcome is the progression of the blastocyst over time, from its formation to the mature structure. The mammalian blastocyst is a hollow ball of cells containing two cell types, the inner cell mass and the trophectoderm.

gene.set.statistics.name: blastocyst formation
gene.set.statistics.description: The initial formation of a blastocyst from a solid ball of cells known as a morula.

gene.set.statistics.name: trophectodermal cell differentiation
gene.set.statistics.description: The process in which a relatively unspecialized cell acquires the specialized features of a trophectoderm cell.

gene.set.statistics.name: blastocyst growth
gene.set.statistics.description: An increase in size of a blastocyst due to expansion of the blastocoelic cavity cell shape changes and cell proliferation.

gene.set.statistics.name: inner cell mass cell proliferation
gene.set.statistics.description: The proliferation of cells in the inner cell mass.

gene.set.statistics.name: trophectodermal cell proliferation
gene.set.statistics.description: The proliferation of cells in the trophectoderm.

gene.set.statistics.name: blastocyst hatching
gene.set.statistics.description: The hatching of the cellular blastocyst from the zona pellucida.

gene.set.statistics.name: release of cytochrome c from mitochondria
gene.set.statistics.description: The process that results in the movement of cytochrome c from the mitochondrial intermembrane space into the cytosol, which is part of the apoptotic signaling pathway and leads to caspase activation.

gene.set.statistics.name: epithelial to mesenchymal transition
gene.set.statistics.description: A transition where an epithelial cell loses apical/basolateral polarity, severs intercellular adhesive junctions, degrades basement membrane components and becomes a migratory mesenchymal cell.

gene.set.statistics.name: neural tube closure
gene.set.statistics.description: The last step in the formation of the neural tube, where the paired neural folds are brought together and fuse at the dorsal midline.

gene.set.statistics.name: protein insertion into mitochondrial membrane involved in apoptotic signaling pathway
gene.set.statistics.description: The process in which a protein is incorporated into a mitochondrial membrane as the initial phase of the mitochondrial membrane permeabilization that takes place in the apoptotic signaling pathway.

gene.set.statistics.name: phagolysosome assembly
gene.set.statistics.description: The process that results in the fusion of a phagosome, a vesicle formed by phagocytosis, with a lysosome.

gene.set.statistics.name: response to yeast
gene.set.statistics.description: Any process that results in a change in state or activity of a cell or an organism (in terms of movement, secretion, enzyme production, gene expression, etc.) as a result of a stimulus from a yeast species.

gene.set.statistics.name: receptor recycling
gene.set.statistics.description: The process that results in the return of receptor molecules to an active state and an active cellular location after they have been stimulated by a ligand. An active state is when the receptor is ready to receive a signal.

gene.set.statistics.name: endothelial cell morphogenesis
gene.set.statistics.description: The change in form (cell shape and size) that occurs during the differentiation of an endothelial cell.

gene.set.statistics.name: liver development
gene.set.statistics.description: The process whose specific outcome is the progression of the liver over time, from its formation to the mature structure. The liver is an exocrine gland which secretes bile and functions in metabolism of protein and carbohydrate and fat, synthesizes substances involved in the clotting of the blood, synthesizes vitamin A, detoxifies poisonous substances, stores glycogen, and breaks down worn-out erythrocytes.

gene.set.statistics.name: placenta development
gene.set.statistics.description: The process whose specific outcome is the progression of the placenta over time, from its formation to the mature structure. The placenta is an organ of metabolic interchange between fetus and mother, partly of embryonic origin and partly of maternal origin.

gene.set.statistics.name: maternal placenta development
gene.set.statistics.description: Maternally driven process whose specific outcome is the progression of the placenta over time, from its formation to the mature structure. The placenta is an organ of metabolic interchange between fetus and mother, partly of embryonic origin and partly of maternal origin.

gene.set.statistics.name: tissue homeostasis
gene.set.statistics.description: A homeostatic process involved in the maintenance of an internal steady state within a defined tissue of an organism, including control of cellular proliferation and death and control of metabolic function.

gene.set.statistics.name: retina homeostasis
gene.set.statistics.description: A tissue homeostatic process involved in the maintenance of an internal equilibrium within the retina of the eye, including control of cellular proliferation and death and control of metabolic function.

gene.set.statistics.name: T cell mediated cytotoxicity
gene.set.statistics.description: The directed killing of a target cell by a T cell through the release of granules containing cytotoxic mediators or through the engagement of death receptors.

gene.set.statistics.name: positive regulation of T cell mediated cytotoxicity
gene.set.statistics.description: Any process that activates or increases the frequency, rate or extent of T cell mediated cytotoxicity.

gene.set.statistics.name: regulation of receptor recycling
gene.set.statistics.description: Any process that modulates the frequency, rate, or extent of receptor recycling.

gene.set.statistics.name: positive regulation of receptor recycling
gene.set.statistics.description: Any process that activates or increases the frequency, rate or extent of receptor recycling.

gene.set.statistics.name: regulation of protein phosphorylation
gene.set.statistics.description: Any process that modulates the frequency, rate or extent of addition of phosphate groups into an amino acid in a protein.

gene.set.statistics.name: negative regulation of protein phosphorylation
gene.set.statistics.description: Any process that stops, prevents or reduces the rate of addition of phosphate groups to amino acids within a protein.

gene.set.statistics.name: positive regulation of protein phosphorylation
gene.set.statistics.description: Any process that activates or increases the frequency, rate or extent of addition of phosphate groups to amino acids within a protein.

gene.set.statistics.name: endothelial cell proliferation
gene.set.statistics.description: The multiplication or reproduction of endothelial cells, resulting in the expansion of a cell population. Endothelial cells are thin flattened cells which line the inside surfaces of body cavities, blood vessels, and lymph vessels, making up the endothelium.

gene.set.statistics.name: negative regulation of endothelial cell proliferation
gene.set.statistics.description: Any process that stops, prevents, or reduces the rate or extent of endothelial cell proliferation.

gene.set.statistics.name: positive regulation of endothelial cell proliferation
gene.set.statistics.description: Any process that activates or increases the rate or extent of endothelial cell proliferation.

gene.set.statistics.name: vasculature development
gene.set.statistics.description: The process whose specific outcome is the progression of the vasculature over time, from its formation to the mature structure. The vasculature is an interconnected tubular multi-tissue structure that contains fluid that is actively transported around the organism.

gene.set.statistics.name: intestinal D-glucose absorption
gene.set.statistics.description: Uptake of D-glucose into the blood by absorption from the small intestine.

gene.set.statistics.name: positive regulation of cell-matrix adhesion
gene.set.statistics.description: Any process that activates or increases the rate or extent of cell adhesion to an extracellular matrix.

gene.set.statistics.name: intramembranous ossification
gene.set.statistics.description: Direct ossification that occurs within mesenchyme or an accumulation of relatively unspecialized cells.

gene.set.statistics.name: endochondral ossification
gene.set.statistics.description: Replacement ossification wherein bone tissue replaces cartilage.

gene.set.statistics.name: negative regulation of cytokine-mediated signaling pathway
gene.set.statistics.description: Any process that stops, prevents, or reduces the frequency, rate or extent of the cytokine mediated signaling pathway.

gene.set.statistics.name: positive regulation of cytokine-mediated signaling pathway
gene.set.statistics.description: Any process that activates or increases the frequency, rate or extent of a cytokine mediated signaling pathway.

gene.set.statistics.name: negative regulation of activation of membrane attack complex
gene.set.statistics.description: Any process that stops, prevents, or reduces the frequency, rate or extent of the activation of the membrane attack complex components of the complement cascade.

gene.set.statistics.name: G protein-coupled adenosine receptor signaling pathway
gene.set.statistics.description: The series of molecular signals generated as a consequence of a receptor binding to extracellular adenosine and transmitting the signal to a heterotrimeric G-protein complex to initiate a change in cell activity.

gene.set.statistics.name: blood vessel remodeling
gene.set.statistics.description: The reorganization or renovation of existing blood vessels.

gene.set.statistics.name: response to amphetamine
gene.set.statistics.description: Any process that results in a change in state or activity of a cell or an organism (in terms of movement, secretion, enzyme production, gene expression, etc.) as a result of an amphetamine stimulus. Amphetamines consist of a group of compounds related to alpha-methylphenethylamine.

gene.set.statistics.name: angiotensin maturation
gene.set.statistics.description: The process leading to the attainment of the full functional capacity of angiotensin by conversion of angiotensinogen into mature angiotensin in the blood.

gene.set.statistics.name: morphogenesis of an epithelium
gene.set.statistics.description: The process in which the anatomical structures of epithelia are generated and organized. An epithelium consists of closely packed cells arranged in one or more layers, that covers the outer surfaces of the body or lines any internal cavity or tube.

gene.set.statistics.name: morphogenesis of an epithelial sheet
gene.set.statistics.description: The process in which the anatomical structures of an epithelial sheet are generated and organized. An epithelial sheet is a flat surface consisting of closely packed epithelial cells.

gene.set.statistics.name: regulation of the force of heart contraction
gene.set.statistics.description: Any process that modulates the extent of heart contraction, changing the force with which blood is propelled.

gene.set.statistics.name: regulation of heart rate
gene.set.statistics.description: Any process that modulates the frequency or rate of heart contraction.

gene.set.statistics.name: regulation of sodium ion transport
gene.set.statistics.description: Any process that modulates the frequency, rate or extent of the directed movement of sodium ions (Na+) into, out of or within a cell, or between cells, by means of some agent such as a transporter or pore.

gene.set.statistics.name: G protein-coupled receptor internalization
gene.set.statistics.description: The process that results in the uptake of a G protein-coupled receptor into an endocytic vesicle.

gene.set.statistics.name: sprouting angiogenesis
gene.set.statistics.description: The extension of new blood vessels from existing vessels into avascular tissues, this process includes the specialization of endothelial cells into leading tip and stalk cells, proliferation and migration of the endothelial cells and cell adhesion resulting in angiogenic sprout fusion or lumen formation.

gene.set.statistics.name: blood vessel endothelial cell proliferation involved in sprouting angiogenesis
gene.set.statistics.description: The multiplication or reproduction of blood vessel endothelial cells, resulting in the expansion of a cell population contributing to sprouting angiogenesis.

gene.set.statistics.name: positive regulation of mesenchymal cell proliferation
gene.set.statistics.description: The process of activating or increasing the rate or extent of mesenchymal cell proliferation. Mesenchymal cells are loosely organized embryonic cells.

gene.set.statistics.name: regulation of oxidative phosphorylation
gene.set.statistics.description: Any process that modulates the frequency, rate or extent of the chemical reactions and pathways resulting in the phosphorylation of ADP to ATP that accompanies the oxidation of a metabolite through the operation of the respiratory chain. Oxidation of compounds establishes a proton gradient across the membrane, providing the energy for ATP synthesis.

gene.set.statistics.name: protein depalmitoylation
gene.set.statistics.description: The removal of palymitoyl groups from a lipoprotein.

gene.set.statistics.name: lens development in camera-type eye
gene.set.statistics.description: The process whose specific outcome is the progression of the lens over time, from its formation to the mature structure. The lens is a transparent structure in the eye through which light is focused onto the retina. An example of this process is found in Mus musculus.

gene.set.statistics.name: negative regulation of receptor internalization
gene.set.statistics.description: Any process that stops, prevents, or reduces the frequency, rate or extent of receptor internalization.

gene.set.statistics.name: positive regulation of receptor internalization
gene.set.statistics.description: Any process that activates or increases the frequency, rate or extent of receptor internalization.

gene.set.statistics.name: desmosome assembly
gene.set.statistics.description: A cellular process that results in the aggregation, arrangement and bonding together of a set of components to form a desmosome. A desmosome is a patch-like intercellular junction found in vertebrate tissues, consisting of parallel zones of two cell membranes, separated by an space of 25-35 nm, and having dense fibrillar plaques in the subjacent cytoplasm.

gene.set.statistics.name: male germ cell proliferation
gene.set.statistics.description: The multiplication or reproduction of male germ cells, resulting in the expansion of a cell population.

gene.set.statistics.name: cytoplasmic translation
gene.set.statistics.description: The chemical reactions and pathways resulting in the formation of a protein in the cytoplasm. This is a ribosome-mediated process in which the information in messenger RNA (mRNA) is used to specify the sequence of amino acids in the protein.

gene.set.statistics.name: cytoplasmic translational initiation
gene.set.statistics.description: The process preceding formation of the peptide bond between the first two amino acids of a protein in the cytoplasm. This includes the formation of a complex of the ribosome, mRNA or circRNA, and an initiation complex that contains the first aminoacyl-tRNA.

gene.set.statistics.name: cytoplasmic translational termination
gene.set.statistics.description: The process resulting in the release of a polypeptide chain from the ribosome in the cytoplasm, usually in response to a termination codon.

gene.set.statistics.name: translation reinitiation
gene.set.statistics.description: A gene-specific translational control mechanism where the small ribosomal subunit remains attached to the mRNA following termination of translation, then resumes scanning on the same mRNA molecule and initiates again at a downstream start site. Reinitiation depends on de novo recruitment of the ternary complex that is required to recognize the next AUG codon.

gene.set.statistics.name: cap-dependent translational initiation
gene.set.statistics.description: The process where the cap structure, composed of a 7- methylguanosine (m7G) group and associated cap-binding proteins, located at the 5' end of an mRNA molecule, which serves as a molecular tag that marks the spot where the 40S ribosomal subunit, is recruited and will then scan in a 5' to 3' direction until an AUG codon is encountered in an appropriate sequence context to initiate mRNA translation.

gene.set.statistics.name: activation of innate immune response
gene.set.statistics.description: Any process that initiates an innate immune response. Innate immune responses are defense responses mediated by germline encoded components that directly recognize components of potential pathogens. Examples of this process include activation of the hypersensitive response of Arabidopsis thaliana and activation of any NOD or TLR signaling pathway in vertebrate species.

gene.set.statistics.name: stimulatory C-type lectin receptor signaling pathway
gene.set.statistics.description: Any series of molecular signals generated as a consequence of binding to a C-type lectin receptor capable of cellular activation.

gene.set.statistics.name: toll-like receptor signaling pathway
gene.set.statistics.description: Any series of molecular signals generated as a consequence of binding to a toll-like receptor. Toll-like receptors directly bind pattern motifs from a variety of microbial sources to initiate innate immune response.

gene.set.statistics.name: positive regulation of defense response to virus by host
gene.set.statistics.description: Any host process that results in the promotion of antiviral immune response mechanisms, thereby limiting viral replication.

gene.set.statistics.name: hematopoietic progenitor cell differentiation
gene.set.statistics.description: The process in which precursor cell type acquires the specialized features of a hematopoietic progenitor cell, a class of cell types including myeloid progenitor cells and lymphoid progenitor cells.

gene.set.statistics.name: adaptive immune response
gene.set.statistics.description: An immune response mediated by cells expressing specific receptors for antigen produced through a somatic diversification process, and allowing for an enhanced secondary response to subsequent exposures to the same antigen (immunological memory).

gene.set.statistics.name: myeloid cell homeostasis
gene.set.statistics.description: The process of regulating the proliferation and elimination of myeloid cells such that the total number of myeloid cells within a whole or part of an organism is stable over time in the absence of an outside stimulus.

gene.set.statistics.name: plasmacytoid dendritic cell activation
gene.set.statistics.description: A change in the morphology or behavior of a plasmacytoid dendritic cell resulting from exposure to an activating factor such as a cellular or soluble ligand.

gene.set.statistics.name: macrophage activation involved in immune response
gene.set.statistics.description: A change in morphology and behavior of a macrophage resulting from exposure to a cytokine, chemokine, cellular ligand, or soluble factor, leading to the initiation or perpetuation of an immune response.

gene.set.statistics.name: T-helper 1 cell lineage commitment
gene.set.statistics.description: The process in which a CD4-positive, alpha-beta T cell becomes committed to becoming a T-helper 1 cell, a CD4-positive, alpha-beta T cell specialized to promote immunological processes often associated with resistance to intracellular bacteria, fungi, and protozoa, and pathological conditions such as arthritis.

gene.set.statistics.name: T cell proliferation involved in immune response
gene.set.statistics.description: The expansion of a T cell population by cell division as part of an immune response.

gene.set.statistics.name: plasma cell differentiation
gene.set.statistics.description: The process in which a B cell acquires the specialized features of a plasma cell. A plasma cell is a lymphocyte which develops from a B cell and produces high amounts of antibody.

gene.set.statistics.name: pro-B cell differentiation
gene.set.statistics.description: The process in which a precursor cell type acquires the specialized features of a pro-B cell. Pro-B cells are the earliest stage of the B cell lineage and undergo heavy chain D and J gene rearrangements, although they are not fully committed.

gene.set.statistics.name: defense response to tumor cell
gene.set.statistics.description: Reactions triggered in response to the presence of a tumor cell that act to protect the cell or organism.

gene.set.statistics.name: T cell lineage commitment
gene.set.statistics.description: The process in which a lymphoid progenitor cell becomes committed to becoming any type of T cell.

gene.set.statistics.name: immune system process
gene.set.statistics.description: Any process involved in the development or functioning of the immune system, an organismal system for calibrated responses to potential internal or invasive threats.

gene.set.statistics.name: dendritic cell chemotaxis
gene.set.statistics.description: The movement of a dendritic cell in response to an external stimulus.

gene.set.statistics.name: inflammatory response to antigenic stimulus
gene.set.statistics.description: An inflammatory response to an antigenic stimulus, which can be include any number of T cell or B cell epitopes.

gene.set.statistics.name: chronic inflammatory response to antigenic stimulus
gene.set.statistics.description: A chronic inflammatory response to an antigenic stimulus. A chronic inflammatory response persists indefinitely during days, weeks, or months in the life of an individual.

gene.set.statistics.name: neutrophil mediated immunity
gene.set.statistics.description: Any process involved in the carrying out of an immune response by a neutrophil.

gene.set.statistics.name: germinal center formation
gene.set.statistics.description: The process in which germinal centers form. A germinal center is a specialized microenvironment formed when activated B cells enter lymphoid follicles. Germinal centers are the foci for B cell proliferation and somatic hypermutation.

gene.set.statistics.name: antigen processing and presentation of peptide antigen via MHC class I
gene.set.statistics.description: The process in which an antigen-presenting cell expresses a peptide antigen on its cell surface in association with an MHC class I protein complex. Class I here refers to classical class I molecules.

gene.set.statistics.name: antigen processing and presentation of exogenous peptide antigen via MHC class I, TAP-dependent
gene.set.statistics.description: The process in which an antigen-presenting cell expresses a peptide antigen of exogenous origin on its cell surface in association with an MHC class I protein complex following intracellular transport via a TAP (transporter associated with antigen processing) pathway. The peptide is typically a fragment of a larger exogenous protein which has been degraded within the cell and is dependent on TAP transport from the cytosol to ER for association with the MHC class I molecule. Class I here refers to classical class I molecules.

gene.set.statistics.name: acute inflammatory response
gene.set.statistics.description: Inflammation which comprises a rapid, short-lived, relatively uniform response to acute injury or antigenic challenge and is characterized by accumulations of fluid, plasma proteins, and granulocytic leukocytes. An acute inflammatory response occurs within a matter of minutes or hours, and either resolves within a few days or becomes a chronic inflammatory response.

gene.set.statistics.name: monocyte chemotaxis
gene.set.statistics.description: The movement of a monocyte in response to an external stimulus.

gene.set.statistics.name: mast cell chemotaxis
gene.set.statistics.description: The movement of a mast cell in response to an external stimulus.

gene.set.statistics.name: platelet degranulation
gene.set.statistics.description: The regulated exocytosis of secretory granules containing preformed mediators such as histamine and serotonin by a platelet.

gene.set.statistics.name: negative regulation of immunoglobulin production
gene.set.statistics.description: Any process that stops, prevents, or reduces the frequency, rate, or extent of immunoglobulin production.

gene.set.statistics.name: positive regulation of immunoglobulin production
gene.set.statistics.description: Any process that activates or increases the frequency, rate, or extent of immunoglobulin production.

gene.set.statistics.name: regulation of tolerance induction
gene.set.statistics.description: Any process that modulates the frequency, rate, or extent of tolerance induction.

gene.set.statistics.name: regulation of leukocyte migration
gene.set.statistics.description: Any process that modulates the frequency, rate, or extent of leukocyte migration.

gene.set.statistics.name: positive regulation of cytokine production involved in immune response
gene.set.statistics.description: Any process that activates or increases the frequency, rate, or extent of cytokine production that contributes to an immune response.

gene.set.statistics.name: positive regulation of myeloid dendritic cell cytokine production
gene.set.statistics.description: Any process that activates or increases the frequency, rate, or extent of myeloid dendritic cell cytokine production.

gene.set.statistics.name: cytoplasmic pattern recognition receptor signaling pathway
gene.set.statistics.description: Any series of molecular signals generated as a consequence of a cytoplasmic pattern recognition receptor (PRR) binding to one of its physiological ligands. PRRs bind pathogen-associated molecular pattern (PAMPs), structures conserved among microbial species.

gene.set.statistics.name: MyD88-dependent toll-like receptor signaling pathway
gene.set.statistics.description: Any series of molecular signals generated as a consequence of binding to a toll-like receptor where the MyD88 adaptor molecule mediates transduction of the signal. Toll-like receptors directly bind pattern motifs from a variety of microbial sources to initiate innate immune response.

gene.set.statistics.name: MyD88-independent toll-like receptor signaling pathway
gene.set.statistics.description: Any series of molecular signals generated as a consequence of binding to a toll-like receptor not relying on the MyD88 adaptor molecule. Toll-like receptors directly bind pattern motifs from a variety of microbial sources to initiate innate immune response.

gene.set.statistics.name: negative regulation of myeloid leukocyte differentiation
gene.set.statistics.description: Any process that stops, prevents, or reduces the frequency, rate, or extent of myeloid leukocyte differentiation.

gene.set.statistics.name: positive regulation of T cell mediated immune response to tumor cell
gene.set.statistics.description: Any process that activates or increases the frequency, rate, or extent of a T cell mediated immune response to tumor cell.

gene.set.statistics.name: negative regulation of inflammatory response to antigenic stimulus
gene.set.statistics.description: Any process that stops, prevents, or reduces the frequency, rate, or extent of an inflammatory response to an antigenic stimulus.

gene.set.statistics.name: positive regulation of inflammatory response to antigenic stimulus
gene.set.statistics.description: Any process that activates or increases the frequency, rate, or extent of an inflammatory response to an antigenic stimulus.

gene.set.statistics.name: positive regulation of B cell apoptotic process
gene.set.statistics.description: Any process that activates or increases the frequency, rate, or extent of B cell apoptotic process.

gene.set.statistics.name: response to ischemia
gene.set.statistics.description: Any process that results in a change in state or activity of an organism (in terms of movement, secretion, enzyme production, gene expression, etc.) as a result of a inadequate blood supply.

gene.set.statistics.name: desmosome organization
gene.set.statistics.description: A process that is carried out at the cellular level which results in the assembly, arrangement of constituent parts, or disassembly of a desmosome. A desmosome is a patch-like intercellular junction found in vertebrate tissues, consisting of parallel zones of two cell membranes, separated by an space of 25-35 nm, and having dense fibrillar plaques in the subjacent cytoplasm.

gene.set.statistics.name: developmental process involved in reproduction
gene.set.statistics.description: A developmental process in which a progressive change in the state of some part of an organism specifically contributes to its ability to form offspring.

gene.set.statistics.name: heart morphogenesis
gene.set.statistics.description: The developmental process in which the heart is generated and organized. The heart is a hollow, muscular organ, which, by contracting rhythmically, keeps up the circulation of the blood.

gene.set.statistics.name: skeletal muscle contraction
gene.set.statistics.description: A process in which force is generated within skeletal muscle tissue, resulting in a change in muscle geometry. Force generation involves a chemo-mechanical energy conversion step that is carried out by the actin/myosin complex activity, which generates force through ATP hydrolysis. In the skeletal muscle, the muscle contraction takes advantage of an ordered sarcomeric structure and in most cases it is under voluntary control.

gene.set.statistics.name: heart process
gene.set.statistics.description: A circulatory system process carried out by the heart. The heart is a hollow, muscular organ, which, by contracting rhythmically, keeps up the circulation of the blood. The heart is a hollow, muscular organ, which, by contracting rhythmically, keeps up the circulation of the blood.

gene.set.statistics.name: respiratory system process
gene.set.statistics.description: A process carried out by the organs or tissues of the respiratory system. The respiratory system is an organ system responsible for respiratory gaseous exchange.

gene.set.statistics.name: regulation of heart rate by hormone
gene.set.statistics.description: The process in which the hormones modulates the rate of heart muscle contraction. A hormone is one of a group of substances formed in very small amounts in one specialized organ or group of cells and carried (sometimes in the bloodstream) to another organ or group of cells, in the same organism, upon which they have a specific regulatory action.

gene.set.statistics.name: regulation of systemic arterial blood pressure
gene.set.statistics.description: The process that modulates the force with which blood travels through the systemic arterial circulatory system. The process is controlled by a balance of processes that increase pressure and decrease pressure.

gene.set.statistics.name: positive regulation of systemic arterial blood pressure
gene.set.statistics.description: The process that increases the force with which blood travels through the systemic arterial circulatory system.

gene.set.statistics.name: renal water homeostasis
gene.set.statistics.description: Renal process involved in the maintenance of an internal steady state of water in the body.

gene.set.statistics.name: glomerular filtration
gene.set.statistics.description: The process in which plasma is filtered through the glomerular membrane which consists of capillary endothelial cells, the basement membrane, and epithelial cells. The glomerular filtrate is the same as plasma except it has no significant amount of protein.

gene.set.statistics.name: renal sodium ion transport
gene.set.statistics.description: The directed movement of sodium ions (Na+) by the renal system.

gene.set.statistics.name: renal water transport
gene.set.statistics.description: The directed movement of water (H2O) by the renal system.

gene.set.statistics.name: embryonic heart tube morphogenesis
gene.set.statistics.description: The process in which the anatomical structures of the embryonic heart tube are generated and organized. The embryonic heart tube is an epithelial tube that will give rise to the mature heart.

gene.set.statistics.name: outflow tract septum morphogenesis
gene.set.statistics.description: The process in which the anatomical structures of the outflow tract septum are generated and organized. The outflow tract septum is a partition in the outflow tract.

gene.set.statistics.name: cardiac conduction system development
gene.set.statistics.description: The process whose specific outcome is the progression of the cardiac conduction system over time, from its formation to the mature structure. The cardiac conduction system consists of specialized cardiomyocytes that regulate the frequency of heart beat.

gene.set.statistics.name: heart valve development
gene.set.statistics.description: The progression of a heart valve over time, from its formation to the mature structure. A heart valve is a structure that restricts the flow of blood to different regions of the heart and forms from an endocardial cushion.

gene.set.statistics.name: heart valve morphogenesis
gene.set.statistics.description: The process in which the structure of a heart valve is generated and organized.

gene.set.statistics.name: ventricular compact myocardium morphogenesis
gene.set.statistics.description: The process in which the anatomical structures of the compact cardiac ventricle muscle are generated and organized.

gene.set.statistics.name: ventricular septum development
gene.set.statistics.description: The progression of the ventricular septum over time from its formation to the mature structure.

gene.set.statistics.name: amino acid transmembrane transport
gene.set.statistics.description: The process in which an amino acid is transported across a membrane.

gene.set.statistics.name: keratinocyte development
gene.set.statistics.description: The process whose specific outcome is the progression of a keratinocyte over time, from its formation to the mature structure.

gene.set.statistics.name: cilium movement
gene.set.statistics.description: The directed, self-propelled movement of a cilium.

gene.set.statistics.name: brainstem development
gene.set.statistics.description: The progression of the brainstem from its formation to the mature structure. The brainstem is the part of the brain that connects the brain with the spinal cord.

gene.set.statistics.name: dynamin family protein polymerization involved in mitochondrial fission
gene.set.statistics.description: The process of creating dynamin protein family polymers, compounds composed of a large number of dynamin family monomers around a lipid tube of a dividing mitochondrion. Dynamin polymers form around lipid tubes and contribute to membrane fission.

gene.set.statistics.name: sphingosine-1-phosphate receptor signaling pathway
gene.set.statistics.description: A series of molecular signals initiated by the sphingolipid sphingosine-1-phosphate (S1P) binding to a receptor on the surface of the cell, and which proceeds with the activated receptor transmitting the signal by promoting the exchange of GDP for GTP on the alpha-subunit of an associated heterotrimeric G-protein complex. The pathway ends with regulation of a downstream cellular process, e.g. transcription.

gene.set.statistics.name: epithelial cell morphogenesis
gene.set.statistics.description: The change in form that occurs when an epithelial cell progresses from its initial formation to its mature state.

gene.set.statistics.name: regulation of COPII vesicle coating
gene.set.statistics.description: Any process that modulates the rate, frequency, or extent of the addition of COPII proteins and adaptor proteins to ER membranes during the formation of transport vesicles, forming a vesicle coat.

gene.set.statistics.name: neural retina development
gene.set.statistics.description: The progression of the neural retina over time from its initial formation to the mature structure. The neural retina is the part of the retina that contains neurons and photoreceptor cells.

gene.set.statistics.name: chondrocyte development involved in endochondral bone morphogenesis
gene.set.statistics.description: The progression of a chondrocyte over time from after its commitment to its mature state where the chondrocyte will contribute to the shaping of an endochondral bone.

gene.set.statistics.name: carbohydrate metabolic process
gene.set.statistics.description: The chemical reactions and pathways involving carbohydrates, any of a group of organic compounds based of the general formula Cx(H2O)y. Includes the formation of carbohydrate derivatives by the addition of a carbohydrate residue to another molecule.

gene.set.statistics.name: glycogen metabolic process
gene.set.statistics.description: The chemical reactions and pathways involving glycogen, a polydisperse, highly branched glucan composed of chains of D-glucose residues in alpha-(1->4) glycosidic linkage, joined together by alpha-(1->6) glycosidic linkages.

gene.set.statistics.name: glycogen biosynthetic process
gene.set.statistics.description: The chemical reactions and pathways resulting in the formation of glycogen, a polydisperse, highly branched glucan composed of chains of D-glucose residues.

gene.set.statistics.name: regulation of glycogen biosynthetic process
gene.set.statistics.description: Any process that modulates the frequency, rate or extent of the chemical reactions and pathways resulting in the formation of glycogen.

gene.set.statistics.name: glycogen catabolic process
gene.set.statistics.description: The chemical reactions and pathways resulting in the breakdown of glycogen, a polydisperse, highly branched glucan composed of chains of D-glucose residues.

gene.set.statistics.name: regulation of glycogen catabolic process
gene.set.statistics.description: Any process that modulates the frequency, rate or extent of the chemical reactions and pathways resulting in the breakdown of glycogen.

gene.set.statistics.name: sucrose biosynthetic process
gene.set.statistics.description: The chemical reactions and pathways resulting in the formation of sucrose, the disaccharide fructofuranosyl-glucopyranoside.

gene.set.statistics.name: xylulose metabolic process
gene.set.statistics.description: The chemical reactions and pathways involving xylulose, the ketopentose threo-2-pentulose.

gene.set.statistics.name: xylulose biosynthetic process
gene.set.statistics.description: The chemical reactions and pathways resulting in the formation of xylulose, the ketopentose threo-2-pentulose.

gene.set.statistics.name: fructose metabolic process
gene.set.statistics.description: The chemical reactions and pathways involving fructose, the ketohexose arabino-2-hexulose. Fructose exists in a open chain form or as a ring compound. D-fructose is the sweetest of the sugars and is found free in a large number of fruits and honey.

gene.set.statistics.name: fructose 6-phosphate metabolic process
gene.set.statistics.description: The chemical reactions and pathways involving fructose 6-phosphate, also known as F6P. The D-enantiomer is an important intermediate in glycolysis, gluconeogenesis, and fructose metabolism.

gene.set.statistics.name: fructose 2,6-bisphosphate metabolic process
gene.set.statistics.description: The chemical reactions and pathways involving fructose 2,6-bisphosphate. The D enantiomer is an important regulator of the glycolytic and gluconeogenic pathways. It inhibits fructose 1,6-bisphosphatase and activates phosphofructokinase.

gene.set.statistics.name: glucose metabolic process
gene.set.statistics.description: The chemical reactions and pathways involving glucose, the aldohexose gluco-hexose. D-glucose is dextrorotatory and is sometimes known as dextrose; it is an important source of energy for living organisms and is found free as well as combined in homo- and hetero-oligosaccharides and polysaccharides.

gene.set.statistics.name: glucose catabolic process
gene.set.statistics.description: The chemical reactions and pathways resulting in the breakdown of glucose, the aldohexose gluco-hexose.

gene.set.statistics.name: UDP-glucose metabolic process
gene.set.statistics.description: The chemical reactions and pathways involving UDP-glucose, uridinediphosphoglucose, a substance composed of glucose in glycosidic linkage with uridine diphosphate.

gene.set.statistics.name: galactose metabolic process
gene.set.statistics.description: The chemical reactions and pathways involving galactose, the aldohexose galacto-hexose. D-galactose is widely distributed in combined form in plants, animals and microorganisms as a constituent of oligo- and polysaccharides; it also occurs in galactolipids and as its glucoside in lactose and melibiose.

gene.set.statistics.name: mannose metabolic process
gene.set.statistics.description: The chemical reactions and pathways involving mannose, the aldohexose manno-hexose, the C-2 epimer of glucose. The D-(+)-form is widely distributed in mannans and hemicelluloses and is of major importance in the core oligosaccharide of N-linked oligosaccharides of glycoproteins.

gene.set.statistics.name: 5-phosphoribose 1-diphosphate biosynthetic process
gene.set.statistics.description: The chemical reactions and pathways resulting in the formation of 5-phosphoribose 1-diphosphate, also known as 5-phosphoribosyl-1-pyrophosphate.

gene.set.statistics.name: glycosaminoglycan biosynthetic process
gene.set.statistics.description: The chemical reactions and pathways resulting in the formation of glycosaminoglycans, any of a group of polysaccharides that contain amino sugars.

gene.set.statistics.name: glycosaminoglycan catabolic process
gene.set.statistics.description: The chemical reactions and pathways resulting in the breakdown of glycosaminoglycans, any one of a group of polysaccharides that contain amino sugars.

gene.set.statistics.name: N-acetylglucosamine metabolic process
gene.set.statistics.description: The chemical reactions and pathways involving N-acetylglucosamine. The D isomer is a common structural unit of glycoproteins in plants, bacteria and animals; it is often the terminal sugar of an oligosaccharide group of a glycoprotein.

gene.set.statistics.name: UDP-N-acetylglucosamine metabolic process
gene.set.statistics.description: The chemical reactions and pathways involving UDP-N-acetylglucosamine, a substance composed of N-acetylglucosamine, a common structural unit of oligosaccharides, in glycosidic linkage with uridine diphosphate.

gene.set.statistics.name: UDP-N-acetylglucosamine biosynthetic process
gene.set.statistics.description: The chemical reactions and pathways resulting in the formation of UDP-N-acetylglucosamine, a substance composed of N-acetylglucosamine, a common structural unit of oligosaccharides, in glycosidic linkage with uridine diphosphate.

gene.set.statistics.name: UDP-glucuronate biosynthetic process
gene.set.statistics.description: The chemical reactions and pathways resulting in the formation of UDP-glucuronate, a substance composed of glucuronic acid in glycosidic linkage with uridine diphosphate.

gene.set.statistics.name: alcohol metabolic process
gene.set.statistics.description: The chemical reactions and pathways involving alcohols, any of a class of compounds containing one or more hydroxyl groups attached to a saturated carbon atom.

gene.set.statistics.name: ethanol catabolic process
gene.set.statistics.description: The chemical reactions and pathways resulting in the breakdown of ethanol, CH3-CH2-OH, a colorless, water-miscible, flammable liquid produced by alcoholic fermentation.

gene.set.statistics.name: ethanol oxidation
gene.set.statistics.description: An ethanol metabolic process in which ethanol is converted to acetyl-CoA via acetaldehyde and acetate.

gene.set.statistics.name: cellular aldehyde metabolic process
