gene.set.statistics.name: vesicle docking involved in exocytosis
gene.set.statistics.description: The initial attachment of a vesicle membrane to a target membrane, mediated by proteins protruding from the membrane of the vesicle and the target membrane, that contributes to exocytosis.

gene.set.statistics.name: vesicle fusion
gene.set.statistics.description: Fusion of the membrane of a transport vesicle with its target membrane.

gene.set.statistics.name: pinocytosis
gene.set.statistics.description: An endocytosis process that results in the uptake of liquid material by cells from their external environment; literally 'cell drinking'. Liquid is enclosed in vesicles, called pinosomes, formed by invagination of the plasma membrane.

gene.set.statistics.name: phagocytosis
gene.set.statistics.description: A vesicle-mediated transport process that results in the engulfment of external particulate material by phagocytes and their delivery to the lysosome. The particles are initially contained within phagocytic vacuoles (phagosomes), which then fuse with primary lysosomes to effect digestion of the particles.

gene.set.statistics.name: phagocytosis, engulfment
gene.set.statistics.description: The internalization of bacteria, immune complexes and other particulate matter or of an apoptotic cell by phagocytosis, including the membrane and cytoskeletal processes required, which involves one of three mechanisms: zippering of pseudopods around a target via repeated receptor-ligand interactions, sinking of the target directly into plasma membrane of the phagocytosing cell, or induced uptake via an enhanced membrane ruffling of the phagocytosing cell similar to macropinocytosis.

gene.set.statistics.name: nucleocytoplasmic transport
gene.set.statistics.description: The directed movement of molecules between the nucleus and the cytoplasm.

gene.set.statistics.name: autophagy
gene.set.statistics.description: The cellular catabolic process in which cells digest parts of their own cytoplasm; allows for both recycling of macromolecular constituents under conditions of cellular stress and remodeling the intracellular structure for cell differentiation.

gene.set.statistics.name: apoptotic process
gene.set.statistics.description: A programmed cell death process which begins when a cell receives an internal (e.g. DNA damage) or external signal (e.g. an extracellular death ligand), and proceeds through a series of biochemical events (signaling pathway phase) which trigger an execution phase. The execution phase is the last step of an apoptotic process, and is typically characterized by rounding-up of the cell, retraction of pseudopodes, reduction of cellular volume (pyknosis), chromatin condensation, nuclear fragmentation (karyorrhexis), plasma membrane blebbing and fragmentation of the cell into apoptotic bodies. When the execution phase is completed, the cell has died.

gene.set.statistics.name: activation of cysteine-type endopeptidase activity involved in apoptotic process
gene.set.statistics.description: Any process that initiates the activity of the inactive enzyme cysteine-type endopeptidase in the context of an apoptotic process.

gene.set.statistics.name: activation-induced cell death of T cells
gene.set.statistics.description: A T cell apoptotic process that occurs towards the end of the expansion phase following the initial activation of mature T cells by antigen and is triggered by T cell receptor stimulation and signals transmitted via various surface-expressed members of the TNF receptor family such as Fas ligand, Fas, and TNF and the p55 and p75 TNF receptors.

gene.set.statistics.name: substrate-dependent cell migration, cell extension
gene.set.statistics.description: The formation of a cell surface protrusion, such as a lamellipodium or filopodium, at the leading edge of a migrating cell.

gene.set.statistics.name: chemotaxis
gene.set.statistics.description: The directed movement of a motile cell or organism, or the directed growth of a cell guided by a specific chemical concentration gradient. Movement may be towards a higher concentration (positive chemotaxis) or towards a lower concentration (negative chemotaxis).

gene.set.statistics.name: muscle contraction
gene.set.statistics.description: A process in which force is generated within muscle tissue, resulting in a change in muscle geometry. Force generation involves a chemo-mechanical energy conversion step that is carried out by the actin/myosin complex activity, which generates force through ATP hydrolysis.

gene.set.statistics.name: regulation of muscle contraction
gene.set.statistics.description: Any process that modulates the frequency, rate or extent of muscle contraction.

gene.set.statistics.name: regulation of smooth muscle contraction
gene.set.statistics.description: Any process that modulates the frequency, rate or extent of smooth muscle contraction.

gene.set.statistics.name: striated muscle contraction
gene.set.statistics.description: A process in which force is generated within striated muscle tissue, resulting in the shortening of the muscle. Force generation involves a chemo-mechanical energy conversion step that is carried out by the actin/myosin complex activity, which generates force through ATP hydrolysis. Striated muscle is a type of muscle in which the repeating units (sarcomeres) of the contractile myofibrils are arranged in registry throughout the cell, resulting in transverse or oblique striations observable at the level of the light microscope.

gene.set.statistics.name: regulation of striated muscle contraction
gene.set.statistics.description: Any process that modulates the frequency, rate or extent of striated muscle contraction.

gene.set.statistics.name: defense response
gene.set.statistics.description: Reactions, triggered in response to the presence of a foreign body or the occurrence of an injury, which result in restriction of damage to the organism attacked or prevention/recovery from the infection caused by the attack.

gene.set.statistics.name: acute-phase response
gene.set.statistics.description: An acute inflammatory response that involves non-antibody proteins whose concentrations in the plasma increase in response to infection or injury of homeothermic animals.

gene.set.statistics.name: inflammatory response
gene.set.statistics.description: The immediate defensive reaction (by vertebrate tissue) to infection or injury caused by chemical or physical agents. The process is characterized by local vasodilation, extravasation of plasma into intercellular spaces and accumulation of white blood cells and macrophages.

gene.set.statistics.name: immune response
gene.set.statistics.description: Any immune system process that functions in the calibrated response of an organism to a potential internal or invasive threat.

gene.set.statistics.name: complement activation
gene.set.statistics.description: Any process involved in the activation of any of the steps of the complement cascade, which allows for the direct killing of microbes, the disposal of immune complexes, and the regulation of other immune processes; the initial steps of complement activation involve one of three pathways, the classical pathway, the alternative pathway, and the lectin pathway, all of which lead to the terminal complement pathway.

gene.set.statistics.name: complement activation, classical pathway
gene.set.statistics.description: Any process involved in the activation of any of the steps of the classical pathway of the complement cascade which allows for the direct killing of microbes, the disposal of immune complexes, and the regulation of other immune processes.

gene.set.statistics.name: response to osmotic stress
gene.set.statistics.description: Any process that results in a change in state or activity of a cell or an organism (in terms of movement, secretion, enzyme production, gene expression, etc.) as a result of a stimulus indicating an increase or decrease in the concentration of solutes outside the organism or cell.

gene.set.statistics.name: hyperosmotic response
gene.set.statistics.description: Any process that results in a change in state or activity of a cell or an organism (in terms of movement, secretion, enzyme production, gene expression, etc.) as a result of detection of, or exposure to, a hyperosmotic environment, i.e. an environment with a higher concentration of solutes than the organism or cell.

gene.set.statistics.name: cellular response to DNA damage stimulus
gene.set.statistics.description: Any process that results in a change in state or activity of a cell (in terms of movement, secretion, enzyme production, gene expression, etc.) as a result of a stimulus indicating damage to its DNA from environmental insults or errors during metabolism.

gene.set.statistics.name: DNA damage response, signal transduction by p53 class mediator resulting in cell cycle arrest
gene.set.statistics.description: A cascade of processes induced by the cell cycle regulator phosphoprotein p53, or an equivalent protein, in response to the detection of DNA damage and resulting in the stopping or reduction in rate of the cell cycle.

gene.set.statistics.name: response to oxidative stress
gene.set.statistics.description: Any process that results in a change in state or activity of a cell or an organism (in terms of movement, secretion, enzyme production, gene expression, etc.) as a result of oxidative stress, a state often resulting from exposure to high levels of reactive oxygen species, e.g. superoxide anions, hydrogen peroxide (H2O2), and hydroxyl radicals.

gene.set.statistics.name: ER overload response
gene.set.statistics.description: The series of molecular signals generated by the accumulation of normal or misfolded proteins in the endoplasmic reticulum and leading to activation of transcription by NF-kappaB.

gene.set.statistics.name: response to unfolded protein
gene.set.statistics.description: Any process that results in a change in state or activity of a cell or an organism (in terms of movement, secretion, enzyme production, gene expression, etc.) as a result of an unfolded protein stimulus.

gene.set.statistics.name: organelle organization
gene.set.statistics.description: A process that is carried out at the cellular level which results in the assembly, arrangement of constituent parts, or disassembly of an organelle within a cell. An organelle is an organized structure of distinctive morphology and function. Includes the nucleus, mitochondria, plastids, vacuoles, vesicles, ribosomes and the cytoskeleton. Excludes the plasma membrane.

gene.set.statistics.name: nucleus organization
gene.set.statistics.description: A process that is carried out at the cellular level which results in the assembly, arrangement of constituent parts, or disassembly of the nucleus.

gene.set.statistics.name: nuclear envelope organization
gene.set.statistics.description: A process that is carried out at the cellular level which results in the assembly, arrangement of constituent parts, or disassembly of the nuclear envelope.

gene.set.statistics.name: nuclear pore organization
gene.set.statistics.description: A process that is carried out at the cellular level which results in the assembly, arrangement of constituent parts, or disassembly of the nuclear pore.

gene.set.statistics.name: telomere maintenance via telomerase
gene.set.statistics.description: The maintenance of proper telomeric length by the addition of telomeric repeats by telomerase.

gene.set.statistics.name: mitochondrion organization
gene.set.statistics.description: A process that is carried out at the cellular level which results in the assembly, arrangement of constituent parts, or disassembly of a mitochondrion; includes mitochondrial morphogenesis and distribution, and replication of the mitochondrial genome as well as synthesis of new mitochondrial components.

gene.set.statistics.name: mitochondrial membrane organization
gene.set.statistics.description: A process that is carried out at the cellular level which results in the assembly, arrangement of constituent parts, or disassembly of a mitochondrial membrane, either of the lipid bilayer surrounding a mitochondrion.

gene.set.statistics.name: inner mitochondrial membrane organization
gene.set.statistics.description: A process that is carried out at the cellular level which results in the assembly, arrangement of constituent parts, or disassembly of the mitochondrial inner membrane.

gene.set.statistics.name: plasma membrane organization
gene.set.statistics.description: A process that is carried out at the cellular level which results in the assembly, arrangement of constituent parts, or disassembly of the plasma membrane.

gene.set.statistics.name: cytoskeleton organization
gene.set.statistics.description: A process that is carried out at the cellular level which results in the assembly, arrangement of constituent parts, or disassembly of cytoskeletal structures.

gene.set.statistics.name: actin filament organization
gene.set.statistics.description: A process that is carried out at the cellular level which results in the assembly, arrangement of constituent parts, or disassembly of cytoskeletal structures comprising actin filaments. Includes processes that control the spatial distribution of actin filaments, such as organizing filaments into meshworks, bundles, or other structures, as by cross-linking.

gene.set.statistics.name: microtubule-based process
gene.set.statistics.description: Any cellular process that depends upon or alters the microtubule cytoskeleton, that part of the cytoskeleton comprising microtubules and their associated proteins.

gene.set.statistics.name: microtubule-based movement
gene.set.statistics.description: A microtubule-based process that results in the movement of organelles, other microtubules, or other cellular components.  Examples include motor-driven movement along microtubules and movement driven by polymerization or depolymerization of microtubules.

gene.set.statistics.name: microtubule depolymerization
gene.set.statistics.description: The removal of tubulin heterodimers from one or both ends of a microtubule.

gene.set.statistics.name: microtubule nucleation
gene.set.statistics.description: The process in which tubulin alpha-beta heterodimers begin aggregation to form an oligomeric tubulin structure (a microtubule seed). Microtubule nucleation is the initiating step in the formation of a microtubule in the absence of any existing microtubules ('de novo' microtubule formation).

gene.set.statistics.name: tubulin complex assembly
gene.set.statistics.description: The aggregation and bonding together of alpha- and beta-tubulin to form a tubulin heterodimer.

gene.set.statistics.name: post-chaperonin tubulin folding pathway
gene.set.statistics.description: Completion of folding of alpha- and beta-tubulin; takes place subsequent to chaperonin-mediated partial folding; mediated by a complex of folding cofactors.

gene.set.statistics.name: cytoplasm organization
gene.set.statistics.description: A process that is carried out at the cellular level which results in the assembly, arrangement of constituent parts, or disassembly of the cytoplasm. The cytoplasm is all of the contents of a cell excluding the plasma membrane and nucleus, but including other subcellular structures.

gene.set.statistics.name: endoplasmic reticulum organization
gene.set.statistics.description: A process that is carried out at the cellular level which results in the assembly, arrangement of constituent parts, or disassembly of the endoplasmic reticulum.

gene.set.statistics.name: Golgi organization
gene.set.statistics.description: A process that is carried out at the cellular level which results in the assembly, arrangement of constituent parts, or disassembly of the Golgi apparatus.

gene.set.statistics.name: peroxisome organization
gene.set.statistics.description: A process that is carried out at the cellular level which results in the assembly, arrangement of constituent parts, or disassembly of a peroxisome. A peroxisome is a small, membrane-bounded organelle that uses dioxygen (O2) to oxidize organic molecules.

gene.set.statistics.name: endosome organization
gene.set.statistics.description: A process that is carried out at the cellular level which results in the assembly, arrangement of constituent parts, or disassembly of endosomes.

gene.set.statistics.name: vacuolar acidification
gene.set.statistics.description: Any process that reduces the pH of the vacuole, measured by the concentration of the hydrogen ion.

gene.set.statistics.name: lysosome organization
gene.set.statistics.description: A process that is carried out at the cellular level which results in the assembly, arrangement of constituent parts, or disassembly of a lysosome. A lysosome is a cytoplasmic, membrane-bounded organelle that is found in most animal cells and that contains a variety of hydrolases.

gene.set.statistics.name: lysosomal transport
gene.set.statistics.description: The directed movement of substances into, out of or within a lysosome.

gene.set.statistics.name: lysosomal lumen acidification
gene.set.statistics.description: Any process that reduces the pH of the lysosomal lumen, measured by the concentration of the hydrogen ion.

gene.set.statistics.name: cell-cell junction assembly
gene.set.statistics.description: The aggregation, arrangement and bonding together of a set of components to form a junction between cells.

gene.set.statistics.name: cell-substrate junction assembly
gene.set.statistics.description: The aggregation, arrangement and bonding together of a set of components to form a junction between a cell and its substrate.

gene.set.statistics.name: cell cycle
gene.set.statistics.description: The progression of biochemical and morphological phases and events that occur in a cell during successive cell replication or nuclear replication events. Canonically, the cell cycle comprises the replication and segregation of genetic material followed by the division of the cell, but in endocycles or syncytial cells nuclear replication or nuclear division may not be followed by cell division.

gene.set.statistics.name: spindle organization
gene.set.statistics.description: A process that is carried out at the cellular level which results in the assembly, arrangement of constituent parts, or disassembly of the spindle, the array of microtubules and associated molecules that forms between opposite poles of a eukaryotic cell during DNA segregation and serves to move the duplicated chromosomes apart.

gene.set.statistics.name: mitotic spindle organization
gene.set.statistics.description: A process that is carried out at the cellular level which results in the assembly, arrangement of constituent parts, or disassembly of the microtubule spindle during a mitotic cell cycle.

gene.set.statistics.name: spindle assembly involved in female meiosis
gene.set.statistics.description: The aggregation, arrangement and bonding together of a set of components to form the spindle during a meiotic cell cycle in females. An example of this is found in Drosophila melanogaster.

gene.set.statistics.name: chromosome segregation
gene.set.statistics.description: The process in which genetic material, in the form of chromosomes, is organized into specific structures and then physically separated and apportioned to two or more sets. In eukaryotes, chromosome segregation begins with the condensation of chromosomes, includes chromosome separation, and ends when chromosomes have completed movement to the spindle poles.

gene.set.statistics.name: sister chromatid cohesion
gene.set.statistics.description: The cell cycle process in which the sister chromatids of a replicated chromosome become tethered to each other.

gene.set.statistics.name: mitotic sister chromatid cohesion
gene.set.statistics.description: The cell cycle process in which the sister chromatids of a replicated chromosome are joined along the entire length of the chromosome, from their formation in S phase through metaphase during a mitotic cell cycle. This cohesion cycle is critical for high fidelity chromosome transmission.

gene.set.statistics.name: mitotic chromosome condensation
gene.set.statistics.description: The cell cycle process in which chromatin structure is compacted prior to and during mitosis in eukaryotic cells.

gene.set.statistics.name: mitotic nuclear membrane disassembly
gene.set.statistics.description: The mitotic cell cycle process in which the controlled partial or complete breakdown of the nuclear membranes during occurs during mitosis.

gene.set.statistics.name: mitotic chromosome movement towards spindle pole
gene.set.statistics.description: The cell cycle process in which the directed movement of chromosomes from the center of the spindle towards the spindle poles occurs. This mediates by the shortening of microtubules attached to the chromosomes, during mitosis.

gene.set.statistics.name: mitotic metaphase plate congression
gene.set.statistics.description: The cell cycle process in which chromosomes are aligned at the metaphase plate, a plane halfway between the poles of the mitotic spindle, during mitosis.

gene.set.statistics.name: mitotic nuclear membrane reassembly
gene.set.statistics.description: The mitotic cell cycle process involving ESCRTIII that results in reformation of the nuclear envelope after mitotic nuclear division. In organisms undergoing closed mitosis this involves resealing or 'repair' of the nuclear envelope in the nuclear bridge.

gene.set.statistics.name: regulation of mitotic nuclear division
gene.set.statistics.description: Any process that modulates the frequency, rate or extent of mitosis.

gene.set.statistics.name: mitotic cell cycle checkpoint signaling
gene.set.statistics.description: A signaling process that ensures accurate chromosome replication and segregation by preventing progression through a mitotic cell cycle until conditions are suitable for the cell to proceed to the next stage.

gene.set.statistics.name: mitotic spindle assembly checkpoint signaling
gene.set.statistics.description: A signal transduction process that contributes to a mitotic cell cycle spindle assembly checkpoint, that delays the metaphase/anaphase transition of a mitotic nuclear division until the spindle is correctly assembled and chromosomes are attached to the spindle.

gene.set.statistics.name: mitotic G2 DNA damage checkpoint signaling
gene.set.statistics.description: A mitotic cell cycle checkpoint that detects and negatively regulates progression through the G2/M transition of the cell cycle in response to DNA damage.

gene.set.statistics.name: regulation of exit from mitosis
gene.set.statistics.description: Any process involved in the progression from anaphase/telophase to G1 that is associated with a conversion from high to low mitotic CDK activity.

gene.set.statistics.name: nuclear migration
gene.set.statistics.description: The directed movement of the nucleus to a specific location within a cell.

gene.set.statistics.name: centrosome cycle
gene.set.statistics.description: The cell cycle process in which centrosome duplication and separation takes place. The centrosome cycle can operate with a considerable degree of independence from other processes of the cell cycle.

gene.set.statistics.name: centriole replication
gene.set.statistics.description: The cell cycle process in which a daughter centriole is formed perpendicular to an existing centriole. An immature centriole contains a ninefold radially symmetric array of single microtubules; mature centrioles consist of a radial array of nine microtubule triplets, doublets, or singlets depending upon the species and cell type. Duplicated centrioles also become the ciliary basal body in cells that form cilia during G0.

gene.set.statistics.name: mitotic centrosome separation
gene.set.statistics.description: Separation of duplicated centrosome components at the beginning of mitosis. The centriole pair within each centrosome becomes part of a separate microtubule organizing center that nucleates a radial array of microtubules called an aster. The two asters move to opposite sides of the nucleus to form the two poles of the mitotic spindle.

gene.set.statistics.name: endomitotic cell cycle
gene.set.statistics.description: A mitotic cell cycle in which chromosomes are replicated and sister chromatids separate, but spindle formation, nuclear membrane breakdown and nuclear division do not occur, resulting in an increased number of chromosomes in the cell.

gene.set.statistics.name: meiosis I
gene.set.statistics.description: The first meiotic nuclear division in which homologous chromosomes are paired and segregated from each other, producing two haploid daughter nuclei.

gene.set.statistics.name: homologous chromosome pairing at meiosis
gene.set.statistics.description: The meiotic cell cycle process where side by side pairing and physical juxtaposition of homologous chromosomes is created during meiotic prophase. Homologous chromosome pairing begins when the chromosome arms begin to pair from the clustered telomeres and ends when synaptonemal complex or linear element assembly is complete.

gene.set.statistics.name: female meiotic nuclear division
gene.set.statistics.description: A cell cycle process by which the cell nucleus divides as part of a meiotic cell cycle in the female germline.

gene.set.statistics.name: cell adhesion
gene.set.statistics.description: The attachment of a cell, either to another cell or to an underlying substrate such as the extracellular matrix, via cell adhesion molecules.

gene.set.statistics.name: homophilic cell adhesion via plasma membrane adhesion molecules
gene.set.statistics.description: The attachment of a plasma membrane adhesion molecule in one cell to an identical molecule in an adjacent cell.

gene.set.statistics.name: leukocyte cell-cell adhesion
gene.set.statistics.description: The attachment of a leukocyte to another cell via adhesion molecules.

gene.set.statistics.name: cell-matrix adhesion
gene.set.statistics.description: The binding of a cell to the extracellular matrix via adhesion molecules.

gene.set.statistics.name: calcium-independent cell-matrix adhesion
gene.set.statistics.description: The binding of a cell to the extracellular matrix via adhesion molecules that do not require the presence of calcium for the interaction.

gene.set.statistics.name: negative regulation of cell adhesion
gene.set.statistics.description: Any process that stops, prevents, or reduces the frequency, rate or extent of cell adhesion.

gene.set.statistics.name: establishment or maintenance of cell polarity
gene.set.statistics.description: Any cellular process that results in the specification, formation or maintenance of anisotropic intracellular organization or cell growth patterns.

gene.set.statistics.name: signal transduction
gene.set.statistics.description: The cellular process in which a signal is conveyed to trigger a change in the activity or state of a cell. Signal transduction begins with reception of a signal (e.g. a ligand binding to a receptor or receptor activation by a stimulus such as light), or for signal transduction in the absence of ligand, signal-withdrawal or the activity of a constitutively active receptor. Signal transduction ends with regulation of a downstream cellular process, e.g. regulation of transcription or regulation of a metabolic process. Signal transduction covers signaling from receptors located on the surface of the cell and signaling via molecules located within the cell. For signaling between cells, signal transduction is restricted to events at and within the receiving cell.

gene.set.statistics.name: cell surface receptor signaling pathway
gene.set.statistics.description: A series of molecular signals initiated by activation of a receptor on the surface of a cell. The pathway begins with binding of an extracellular ligand to a cell surface receptor, or for receptors that signal in the absence of a ligand, by ligand-withdrawal or the activity of a constitutively active receptor. The pathway ends with regulation of a downstream cellular process, e.g. transcription.

gene.set.statistics.name: transmembrane receptor protein tyrosine kinase signaling pathway
gene.set.statistics.description: A series of molecular signals initiated by the binding of an extracellular ligand to a receptor on the surface of the target cell where the receptor possesses tyrosine kinase activity, and ending with regulation of a downstream cellular process, e.g. transcription.

gene.set.statistics.name: epidermal growth factor receptor signaling pathway
gene.set.statistics.description: A series of molecular signals initiated by binding of a ligand to the tyrosine kinase receptor EGFR (ERBB1) on the surface of a cell. The pathway ends with regulation of a downstream cellular process, e.g. transcription.

gene.set.statistics.name: epidermal growth factor catabolic process
gene.set.statistics.description: The chemical reactions and pathways resulting in the breakdown of epidermal growth factor (EGF), following internalization of the receptor-bound ligand into the signal-receiving cell. Full breakdown of epidermal growth factor results in a ligand that is unable to bind and activate its receptor.

gene.set.statistics.name: transforming growth factor beta receptor signaling pathway
gene.set.statistics.description: A series of molecular signals initiated by the binding of an extracellular ligand to a transforming growth factor beta receptor on the surface of a target cell, and ending with regulation of a downstream cellular process, e.g. transcription.

gene.set.statistics.name: common-partner SMAD protein phosphorylation
gene.set.statistics.description: The process of introducing a phosphate group on to a common-partner SMAD protein. A common partner SMAD protein binds to pathway-restricted SMAD proteins forming a complex that translocates to the nucleus.

gene.set.statistics.name: SMAD protein complex assembly
gene.set.statistics.description: The aggregation, arrangement and bonding together of a set of components to form a protein complex that contains SMAD proteins.

gene.set.statistics.name: G protein-coupled receptor signaling pathway
gene.set.statistics.description: A series of molecular signals that proceeds with an activated receptor promoting the exchange of GDP for GTP on the alpha-subunit of an associated heterotrimeric G-protein complex. The GTP-bound activated alpha-G-protein then dissociates from the beta- and gamma-subunits to further transmit the signal within the cell. The pathway begins with receptor-ligand interaction, or for basal GPCR signaling the pathway begins with the receptor activating its G protein in the absence of an agonist, and ends with regulation of a downstream cellular process, e.g. transcription.  The pathway can start from the plasma membrane, Golgi or nuclear membrane.

gene.set.statistics.name: G protein-coupled receptor signaling pathway, coupled to cyclic nucleotide second messenger
gene.set.statistics.description: The series of molecular signals generated as a consequence of a G protein-coupled receptor binding to its physiological ligand, where the pathway proceeds with activation or inhibition of a nucleotide cyclase activity and a subsequent change in the concentration of a cyclic nucleotide.

gene.set.statistics.name: adenylate cyclase-modulating G protein-coupled receptor signaling pathway
gene.set.statistics.description: The series of molecular signals generated as a consequence of a G protein-coupled receptor binding to its physiological ligand, where the pathway proceeds through activation or inhibition of adenylyl cyclase activity and a subsequent change in the concentration of cyclic AMP (cAMP).

gene.set.statistics.name: adenylate cyclase-activating G protein-coupled receptor signaling pathway
gene.set.statistics.description: The series of molecular signals generated as a consequence of a G protein-coupled receptor binding to its physiological ligand, where the pathway proceeds through activation of adenylyl cyclase activity and a subsequent increase in the concentration of cyclic AMP (cAMP).

gene.set.statistics.name: activation of adenylate cyclase activity
gene.set.statistics.description: Any process that initiates the activity of the inactive enzyme adenylate cyclase.

gene.set.statistics.name: adenylate cyclase-activating dopamine receptor signaling pathway
gene.set.statistics.description: The series of molecular signals generated as a consequence of a dopamine receptor binding to its physiological ligand, where the pathway proceeds with activation of adenylyl cyclase and a subsequent increase in the concentration of cyclic AMP (cAMP).

gene.set.statistics.name: adenylate cyclase-inhibiting G protein-coupled receptor signaling pathway
gene.set.statistics.description: The series of molecular signals generated as a consequence of a G protein-coupled receptor binding to its physiological ligand, where the pathway proceeds through inhibition of adenylyl cyclase activity and a subsequent decrease in the concentration of cyclic AMP (cAMP).

gene.set.statistics.name: negative regulation of adenylate cyclase activity
gene.set.statistics.description: Any process that stops, prevents, or reduces the frequency, rate or extent of adenylate cyclase activity.

gene.set.statistics.name: adenylate cyclase-inhibiting dopamine receptor signaling pathway
gene.set.statistics.description: The series of molecular signals generated as a consequence of a dopamine receptor binding to its physiological ligand, where the pathway proceeds with inhibition of adenylyl cyclase and a subsequent decrease in the concentration of cyclic AMP (cAMP).

gene.set.statistics.name: phospholipase C-activating G protein-coupled receptor signaling pathway
gene.set.statistics.description: The series of molecular signals generated as a consequence of a G protein-coupled receptor binding to its physiological ligand, where the pathway proceeds with activation of phospholipase C (PLC) and a subsequent increase in the concentration of inositol trisphosphate (IP3) and diacylglycerol (DAG).

gene.set.statistics.name: activation of phospholipase C activity
gene.set.statistics.description: The initiation of the activity of the inactive enzyme phospolipase C as the result of a series of molecular signals generated as a consequence of a G protein-coupled receptor binding to its physiological ligand.

gene.set.statistics.name: positive regulation of cytosolic calcium ion concentration
gene.set.statistics.description: Any process that increases the concentration of calcium ions in the cytosol.

gene.set.statistics.name: dopamine receptor signaling pathway
gene.set.statistics.description: The series of molecular signals generated as a consequence of a dopamine receptor binding to one of its physiological ligands.

gene.set.statistics.name: G protein-coupled acetylcholine receptor signaling pathway
gene.set.statistics.description: Any series of molecular signals initiated by an acetylcholine receptor on the surface of the target cell binding to one of its physiological ligands, and proceeding with the activated receptor promoting the exchange of GDP for GTP on the alpha-subunit of an associated heterotrimeric G-protein complex. The GTP-bound activated alpha-G-protein then dissociates from the beta- and gamma-subunits to further transmit the signal within the cell. The pathway begins with receptor-ligand interaction and ends with regulation of a downstream cellular process, e.g. transcription.

gene.set.statistics.name: gamma-aminobutyric acid signaling pathway
gene.set.statistics.description: The series of molecular signals generated by the binding of gamma-aminobutyric acid (GABA, 4-aminobutyrate), an amino acid which acts as a neurotransmitter in some organisms, to a cell surface receptor.

gene.set.statistics.name: glutamate receptor signaling pathway
gene.set.statistics.description: A series of molecular signals initiated by the binding of glutamate to a glutamate receptor on the surface of a target cell, and ending with regulation of a downstream cellular process, e.g. transcription.

gene.set.statistics.name: Notch signaling pathway
gene.set.statistics.description: A series of molecular signals initiated by the binding of an extracellular ligand to the receptor Notch on the surface of a target cell, and ending with regulation of a downstream cellular process, e.g. transcription.

gene.set.statistics.name: positive regulation of transcription of Notch receptor target
gene.set.statistics.description: The activation of transcription of specific genes as a result of Notch signaling, mediated by the Notch intracellular domain.

gene.set.statistics.name: Wnt signaling pathway, calcium modulating pathway
gene.set.statistics.description: The series of molecular signals initiated by binding of a Wnt protein to a receptor on the surface of the target cell where activated receptors leads to an increase in intracellular calcium and activation of protein kinase C (PKC).

gene.set.statistics.name: smoothened signaling pathway
gene.set.statistics.description: A series of molecular signals generated as a consequence of activation of the transmembrane protein Smoothened.

gene.set.statistics.name: integrin-mediated signaling pathway
gene.set.statistics.description: A series of molecular signals initiated by the binding of extracellular ligand to an integrin on the surface of a target cell, and ending with regulation of a downstream cellular process, e.g. transcription.

gene.set.statistics.name: osmosensory signaling pathway
gene.set.statistics.description: The series of molecular signals initiated in response to osmotic change.

gene.set.statistics.name: I-kappaB kinase/NF-kappaB signaling
gene.set.statistics.description: The process in which a signal is passed on to downstream components within the cell through the I-kappaB-kinase (IKK)-dependent activation of NF-kappaB. The cascade begins with activation of a trimeric IKK complex (consisting of catalytic kinase subunits IKKalpha and/or IKKbeta, and the regulatory scaffold protein NEMO) and ends with the regulation of transcription of target genes by NF-kappaB. In a resting state, NF-kappaB dimers are bound to I-kappaB proteins, sequestering NF-kappaB in the cytoplasm. Phosphorylation of I-kappaB targets I-kappaB for ubiquitination and proteasomal degradation, thus releasing the NF-kappaB dimers, which can translocate to the nucleus to bind DNA and regulate transcription.

gene.set.statistics.name: activation of NF-kappaB-inducing kinase activity
gene.set.statistics.description: The stimulation of the activity of NF-kappaB-inducing kinase through phosphorylation at specific residues.

gene.set.statistics.name: I-kappaB phosphorylation
gene.set.statistics.description: The process of introducing a phosphate group into an inhibitor of kappa B (I-kappaB) protein. Phosphorylation of I-kappaB targets I-kappaB for ubiquitination and proteasomal degradation, thus releasing bound NF-kappaB dimers, which can translocate to the nucleus to bind DNA and regulate transcription.

gene.set.statistics.name: cytoplasmic sequestering of NF-kappaB
gene.set.statistics.description: The selective interaction of the transcription factor NF-kappaB with specific molecules in the cytoplasm, thereby inhibiting its translocation into the nucleus.

gene.set.statistics.name: JNK cascade
gene.set.statistics.description: An intracellular protein kinase cascade containing at least a JNK (a MAPK), a JNKK (a MAPKK) and a JUN3K (a MAP3K). The cascade can also contain an additional tier: the upstream MAP4K. The kinases in each tier phosphorylate and activate the kinases in the downstream tier to transmit a signal within a cell.

gene.set.statistics.name: activation of JNKK activity
gene.set.statistics.description: The initiation of the activity of the inactive enzyme JUN kinase kinase (JNKK) activity. JNKKs are involved in a signaling pathway that is primarily activated by cytokines and exposure to environmental stress.

gene.set.statistics.name: activation of JUN kinase activity
gene.set.statistics.description: The initiation of the activity of the inactive enzyme JUN kinase (JNK).

gene.set.statistics.name: receptor signaling pathway via JAK-STAT
gene.set.statistics.description: Any process in which STAT proteins (Signal Transducers and Activators of Transcription) and JAK (Janus Activated Kinase) proteins convey a signal to trigger a change in the activity or state of a cell. The receptor signaling pathway via JAK-STAT begins with activation of a receptor and proceeeds through STAT protein activation by members of the JAK family of tyrosine kinases. STAT proteins dimerize and subsequently translocate to the nucleus. The pathway ends with regulation of target gene expression by STAT proteins.

gene.set.statistics.name: nitric oxide mediated signal transduction
gene.set.statistics.description: Any intracellular signal transduction in which the signal is passed on within the cell via nitric oxide (NO). Includes synthesis of nitric oxide, receptors/sensors for nitric oxide (such as soluble guanylyl cyclase/sGC) and downstream effectors that further transmit the signal within the cell. Nitric oxide transmits its downstream effects through either cyclic GMP (cGMP)-dependent or independent mechanisms.

gene.set.statistics.name: small GTPase mediated signal transduction
gene.set.statistics.description: Any series of molecular signals in which a small monomeric GTPase relays one or more of the signals.

gene.set.statistics.name: Ras protein signal transduction
gene.set.statistics.description: A series of molecular signals within the cell that are mediated by a member of the Ras superfamily of proteins switching to a GTP-bound active state.

gene.set.statistics.name: Rho protein signal transduction
gene.set.statistics.description: A series of molecular signals within the cell that are mediated by a member of the Rho family of proteins switching to a GTP-bound active state.

gene.set.statistics.name: cell-cell signaling
gene.set.statistics.description: Any process that mediates the transfer of information from one cell to another. This process includes signal transduction in the receiving cell and, where applicable, release of a ligand and any processes that actively facilitate its transport and presentation to the receiving cell.  Examples include signaling via soluble ligands, via cell adhesion molecules and via gap junctions.

gene.set.statistics.name: chemical synaptic transmission
gene.set.statistics.description: The vesicular release of classical neurotransmitter molecules from a presynapse, across a chemical synapse, the subsequent activation of neurotransmitter receptors at the postsynapse of a target cell (neuron, muscle, or secretory cell) and the effects of this activation on the postsynaptic membrane potential and ionic composition of the postsynaptic cytosol. This process encompasses both spontaneous and evoked release of neurotransmitter and all parts of synaptic vesicle exocytosis. Evoked transmission starts with the arrival of an action potential at the presynapse.

gene.set.statistics.name: neurotransmitter secretion
gene.set.statistics.description: The regulated release of neurotransmitter from the presynapse into the synaptic cleft via calcium-regulated exocytosis during synaptic transmission.

gene.set.statistics.name: synaptic transmission, cholinergic
gene.set.statistics.description: The vesicular release of acetylcholine from a presynapse, across a chemical synapse, the subsequent activation of dopamine receptors at the postsynapse of a target cell (neuron, muscle, or secretory cell) and the effects of this activation on the postsynaptic membrane potential and ionic composition of the postsynaptic cytosol. This process encompasses both spontaneous and evoked release of neurotransmitter and all parts of synaptic vesicle exocytosis. Evoked transmission starts with the arrival of an action potential at the presynapse.

gene.set.statistics.name: neuromuscular synaptic transmission
gene.set.statistics.description: The process of synaptic transmission from a neuron to a muscle, across a synapse.

gene.set.statistics.name: multicellular organism development
gene.set.statistics.description: The biological process whose specific outcome is the progression of a multicellular organism over time from an initial condition (e.g. a zygote or a young adult) to a later condition (e.g. a multicellular animal or an aged adult).

gene.set.statistics.name: gamete generation
gene.set.statistics.description: The generation and maintenance of gametes in a multicellular organism. A gamete is a haploid reproductive cell.

gene.set.statistics.name: germ cell development
gene.set.statistics.description: The process whose specific outcome is the progression of an immature germ cell over time, from its formation to the mature structure (gamete). A germ cell is any reproductive cell in a multicellular organism.

gene.set.statistics.name: spermatogenesis
gene.set.statistics.description: The developmental process by which male germ line stem cells self renew or give rise to successive cell types resulting in the development of a spermatozoa.

gene.set.statistics.name: spermatid development
gene.set.statistics.description: The process whose specific outcome is the progression of a spermatid over time, from its formation to the mature structure.

gene.set.statistics.name: single fertilization
gene.set.statistics.description: The union of male and female gametes to form a zygote.

gene.set.statistics.name: binding of sperm to zona pellucida
gene.set.statistics.description: The process in which the sperm binds to the zona pellucida glycoprotein layer of the egg. The process begins with the attachment of the sperm plasma membrane to the zona pellucida and includes attachment of the acrosome inner membrane to the zona pellucida after the acrosomal reaction takes place.

gene.set.statistics.name: regulation of mitotic cell cycle
gene.set.statistics.description: Any process that modulates the rate or extent of progress through the mitotic cell cycle.

gene.set.statistics.name: zygotic specification of dorsal/ventral axis
gene.set.statistics.description: The specification of the dorsal/ventral axis of the embryo, through the products of genes expressed in the zygote.

gene.set.statistics.name: determination of left/right symmetry
gene.set.statistics.description: The establishment of an organism's body plan or part of an organism with respect to the left and right halves. The pattern can either be symmetric, such that the halves are mirror images, or asymmetric where the pattern deviates from this symmetry.

gene.set.statistics.name: gastrulation
gene.set.statistics.description: A complex and coordinated series of cellular movements that occurs at the end of cleavage during embryonic development of most animals. The details of gastrulation vary from species to species, but usually result in the formation of the three primary germ layers, ectoderm, mesoderm and endoderm.

gene.set.statistics.name: nervous system development
gene.set.statistics.description: The process whose specific outcome is the progression of nervous tissue over time, from its formation to its mature state.

gene.set.statistics.name: neuroblast proliferation
gene.set.statistics.description: The expansion of a neuroblast population by cell division. A neuroblast is any cell that will divide and give rise to a neuron.

gene.set.statistics.name: negative regulation of neuroblast proliferation
gene.set.statistics.description: Any process that stops, prevents, or reduces the frequency, rate or extent of the proliferation of neuroblasts.

gene.set.statistics.name: axonogenesis
gene.set.statistics.description: De novo generation of a long process of a neuron, including the terminal branched region. Refers to the morphogenesis or creation of shape or form of the developing axon, which carries efferent (outgoing) action potentials from the cell body towards target cells.

gene.set.statistics.name: axon guidance
gene.set.statistics.description: The chemotaxis process that directs the migration of an axon growth cone to a specific target site in response to a combination of attractive and repulsive cues.

gene.set.statistics.name: axonal fasciculation
gene.set.statistics.description: The collection of axons into a bundle of rods, known as a fascicle.

gene.set.statistics.name: synapse assembly
gene.set.statistics.description: The aggregation, arrangement and bonding together of a set of components to form a synapse.  This process ends when the synapse is mature (functional).

gene.set.statistics.name: central nervous system development
gene.set.statistics.description: The process whose specific outcome is the progression of the central nervous system over time, from its formation to the mature structure. The central nervous system is the core nervous system that serves an integrating and coordinating function. In vertebrates it consists of the brain and spinal cord. In those invertebrates with a central nervous system it typically consists of a brain, cerebral ganglia and a nerve cord.

gene.set.statistics.name: brain development
gene.set.statistics.description: The process whose specific outcome is the progression of the brain over time, from its formation to the mature structure. Brain development begins with patterning events in the neural tube and ends with the mature structure that is the center of thought and emotion. The brain is responsible for the coordination and control of bodily activities and the interpretation of information from the senses (sight, hearing, smell, etc.).

gene.set.statistics.name: peripheral nervous system development
gene.set.statistics.description: The process whose specific outcome is the progression of the peripheral nervous system over time, from its formation to the mature structure. The peripheral nervous system is one of the two major divisions of the nervous system. Nerves in the PNS connect the central nervous system (CNS) with sensory organs, other organs, muscles, blood vessels and glands.

gene.set.statistics.name: endoderm development
gene.set.statistics.description: The process whose specific outcome is the progression of the endoderm over time, from its formation to the mature structure. The endoderm is the innermost germ layer that develops into the gastrointestinal tract, the lungs and associated tissues.

gene.set.statistics.name: midgut development
gene.set.statistics.description: The process whose specific outcome is the progression of the midgut over time, from its formation to the mature structure. The midgut is the middle part of the alimentary canal from the stomach, or entrance of the bile duct, to, or including, the large intestine.

gene.set.statistics.name: mesoderm development
gene.set.statistics.description: The process whose specific outcome is the progression of the mesoderm over time, from its formation to the mature structure. The mesoderm is the middle germ layer that develops into muscle, bone, cartilage, blood and connective tissue.

gene.set.statistics.name: heart development
gene.set.statistics.description: The process whose specific outcome is the progression of the heart over time, from its formation to the mature structure. The heart is a hollow, muscular organ, which, by contracting rhythmically, keeps up the circulation of the blood.

gene.set.statistics.name: muscle organ development
gene.set.statistics.description: The process whose specific outcome is the progression of the muscle over time, from its formation to the mature structure. The muscle is an organ consisting of a tissue made up of various elongated cells that are specialized to contract and thus to produce movement and mechanical work.

gene.set.statistics.name: skeletal muscle tissue development
gene.set.statistics.description: The developmental sequence of events leading to the formation of adult skeletal muscle tissue. The main events are: the fusion of myoblasts to form myotubes that increase in size by further fusion to them of myoblasts, the formation of myofibrils within their cytoplasm and the establishment of functional neuromuscular junctions with motor neurons. At this stage they can be regarded as mature muscle fibers.

gene.set.statistics.name: myoblast fusion
gene.set.statistics.description: A process in which non-proliferating myoblasts fuse to existing fibers or to myotubes to form new fibers. A myoblast is a mononucleate cell type that, by fusion with other myoblasts, gives rise to the myotubes that eventually develop into skeletal muscle fibers.

gene.set.statistics.name: neuromuscular junction development
gene.set.statistics.description: A process that is carried out at the cellular level which results in the assembly, arrangement of constituent parts, or disassembly of a neuromuscular junction.

gene.set.statistics.name: dosage compensation
gene.set.statistics.description: Compensating for the variation in the unpaired sex chromosome:autosome chromosome ratios between sexes by activation or inactivation of genes on one or both of the sex chromosomes.

gene.set.statistics.name: female pregnancy
gene.set.statistics.description: The set of physiological processes that allow an embryo or foetus to develop within the body of a female animal. It covers the time from fertilization of a female ovum by a male spermatozoon until birth.

gene.set.statistics.name: embryo implantation
gene.set.statistics.description: Attachment of the blastocyst to the uterine lining.

gene.set.statistics.name: aging
gene.set.statistics.description: A developmental process that is a deterioration and loss of function over time. Aging includes loss of functions such as resistance to disease, homeostasis, and fertility, as well as wear and tear. Aging includes cellular senescence, but is more inclusive. May precede death and may succeed developmental maturation (GO:0021700).

gene.set.statistics.name: cell aging
gene.set.statistics.description: An aging process that has as participant a cell after a cell has stopped dividing. Cell aging may occur when a cell has temporarily stopped dividing through cell cycle arrest (GO:0007050) or when a cell has permanently stopped dividing, in which case it is undergoing cellular senescence (GO:0090398). May precede cell death (GO:0008219) and succeed cell maturation (GO:0048469).

gene.set.statistics.name: response to nutrient
gene.set.statistics.description: Any process that results in a change in state or activity of a cell or an organism (in terms of movement, secretion, enzyme production, gene expression, etc.) as a result of a nutrient stimulus.

gene.set.statistics.name: excretion
gene.set.statistics.description: The elimination by an organism of the waste products that arise as a result of metabolic activity. These products include water, carbon dioxide (CO2), and nitrogenous compounds.

gene.set.statistics.name: body fluid secretion
gene.set.statistics.description: The controlled release of a fluid by a cell or tissue in an animal.

gene.set.statistics.name: lactation
gene.set.statistics.description: The regulated release of milk from the mammary glands and the period of time that a mother lactates to feed her young.

gene.set.statistics.name: blood coagulation
gene.set.statistics.description: The sequential process in which the multiple coagulation factors of the blood interact, ultimately resulting in the formation of an insoluble fibrin clot; it may be divided into three stages: stage 1, the formation of intrinsic and extrinsic prothrombin converting principle; stage 2, the formation of thrombin; stage 3, the formation of stable fibrin polymers.

gene.set.statistics.name: blood coagulation, intrinsic pathway
gene.set.statistics.description: A protein activation cascade that contributes to blood coagulation and consists of the interactions among high molecular weight kininogen, prekallikrein, and factor XII that lead to the activation of clotting factor X.

gene.set.statistics.name: visual perception
gene.set.statistics.description: The series of events required for an organism to receive a visual stimulus, convert it to a molecular signal, and recognize and characterize the signal. Visual stimuli are detected in the form of photons and are processed to form an image.

gene.set.statistics.name: sensory perception of sound
gene.set.statistics.description: The series of events required for an organism to receive an auditory stimulus, convert it to a molecular signal, and recognize and characterize the signal. Sonic stimuli are detected in the form of vibrations and are processed to form a sound.

gene.set.statistics.name: behavior
gene.set.statistics.description: The internally coordinated responses (actions or inactions) of animals (individuals or groups) to internal or external stimuli, via a mechanism that involves nervous system activity.

gene.set.statistics.name: learning or memory
gene.set.statistics.description: The acquisition and processing of information and/or the storage and retrieval of this information over time.

gene.set.statistics.name: learning
gene.set.statistics.description: Any process in an organism in which a relatively long-lasting adaptive behavioral change occurs as the result of experience.

gene.set.statistics.name: memory
gene.set.statistics.description: The activities involved in the mental information processing system that receives (registers), modifies, stores, and retrieves informational stimuli. The main stages involved in the formation and retrieval of memory are encoding (processing of received information by acquisition), storage (building a permanent record of received information as a result of consolidation) and retrieval (calling back the stored information and use it in a suitable way to execute a given task).

gene.set.statistics.name: short-term memory
gene.set.statistics.description: The memory process that deals with the storage, retrieval and modification of information received a short time (up to about 30 minutes) ago. This type of memory is typically dependent on direct, transient effects of second messenger activation.

gene.set.statistics.name: long-term memory
gene.set.statistics.description: The memory process that deals with the storage, retrieval and modification of information a long time (typically weeks, months or years) after receiving that information. This type of memory is typically dependent on gene transcription regulated by second messenger activation.

gene.set.statistics.name: circadian rhythm
gene.set.statistics.description: Any biological process in an organism that recurs with a regularity of approximately 24 hours.

gene.set.statistics.name: grooming behavior
gene.set.statistics.description: The specific behavior of an organism relating to grooming, cleaning and brushing to remove dirt and parasites.

gene.set.statistics.name: locomotory behavior
gene.set.statistics.description: The specific movement from place to place of an organism in response to external or internal stimuli. Locomotion of a whole organism in a manner dependent upon some combination of that organism's internal state and external conditions.

gene.set.statistics.name: adult walking behavior
gene.set.statistics.description: The behavior of an adult relating to the progression of that organism along the ground by the process of lifting and setting down each leg.

gene.set.statistics.name: feeding behavior
gene.set.statistics.description: Behavior associated with the intake of food.

gene.set.statistics.name: visual behavior
gene.set.statistics.description: The behavior of an organism in response to a visual stimulus.

gene.set.statistics.name: blood circulation
gene.set.statistics.description: The flow of blood through the body of an animal, enabling the transport of nutrients to the tissues and the removal of waste products.

gene.set.statistics.name: regulation of heart contraction
gene.set.statistics.description: Any process that modulates the frequency, rate or extent of heart contraction. Heart contraction is the process in which the heart decreases in volume in a characteristic way to propel blood through the body.

gene.set.statistics.name: tRNA processing
gene.set.statistics.description: The process in which a pre-tRNA molecule is converted to a mature tRNA, ready for addition of an aminoacyl group.

gene.set.statistics.name: motor neuron axon guidance
gene.set.statistics.description: The process in which the migration of an axon growth cone of a motor neuron is directed to a specific target site in response to a combination of attractive and repulsive cues.

gene.set.statistics.name: mitochondrial fusion
gene.set.statistics.description: Merging of two or more mitochondria within a cell to form a single compartment.

gene.set.statistics.name: anterograde axonal transport
gene.set.statistics.description: The directed movement of organelles or molecules along microtubules from the cell body toward the cell periphery in nerve cell axons.

gene.set.statistics.name: retrograde axonal transport
gene.set.statistics.description: The directed movement of organelles or molecules along microtubules from the cell periphery toward the cell body in nerve cell axons.

gene.set.statistics.name: protein localization
gene.set.statistics.description: Any process in which a protein is transported to, or maintained in, a specific location.

gene.set.statistics.name: biological_process
gene.set.statistics.description: A biological process represents a specific objective that the organism is genetically programmed to achieve. Biological processes are often described by their outcome or ending state, e.g., the biological process of cell division results in the creation of two daughter cells (a divided cell) from a single parent cell. A biological process is accomplished by a particular set of molecular functions carried out by specific gene products (or macromolecular complexes), often in a highly regulated manner and in a particular temporal sequence.

gene.set.statistics.name: actin polymerization or depolymerization
gene.set.statistics.description: Assembly or disassembly of actin filaments by the addition or removal of actin monomers from a filament.

gene.set.statistics.name: negative regulation of DNA replication
gene.set.statistics.description: Any process that stops, prevents, or reduces the frequency, rate or extent of DNA replication.

gene.set.statistics.name: steroid metabolic process
gene.set.statistics.description: The chemical reactions and pathways involving steroids, compounds with a 1,2,cyclopentanoperhydrophenanthrene nucleus.

gene.set.statistics.name: cholesterol metabolic process
gene.set.statistics.description: The chemical reactions and pathways involving cholesterol, cholest-5-en-3 beta-ol, the principal sterol of vertebrates and the precursor of many steroids, including bile acids and steroid hormones. It is a component of the plasma membrane lipid bilayer and of plasma lipoproteins and can be found in all animal tissues.

gene.set.statistics.name: bile acid metabolic process
gene.set.statistics.description: The chemical reactions and pathways involving bile acids, any of a group of steroid carboxylic acids occurring in bile, where they are present as the sodium salts of their amides with glycine or taurine.

gene.set.statistics.name: C21-steroid hormone metabolic process
gene.set.statistics.description: The chemical reactions and pathways involving C21-steroid hormones, steroid compounds containing 21 carbons which function as hormones.

gene.set.statistics.name: androgen metabolic process
gene.set.statistics.description: The chemical reactions and pathways involving androgens, C19 steroid hormones that can stimulate the development of male sexual characteristics.

gene.set.statistics.name: estrogen metabolic process
gene.set.statistics.description: The chemical reactions and pathways involving estrogens, C18 steroid hormones that can stimulate the development of female sexual characteristics. Also found in plants.

gene.set.statistics.name: regulation of blood pressure
gene.set.statistics.description: Any process that modulates the force with which blood travels through the circulatory system. The process is controlled by a balance of processes that increase pressure and decrease pressure.

gene.set.statistics.name: cell death
gene.set.statistics.description: Any biological process that results in permanent cessation of all vital functions of a cell. A cell should be considered dead when any one of the following molecular or morphological criteria is met: (1) the cell has lost the integrity of its plasma membrane; (2) the cell, including its nucleus, has undergone complete fragmentation into discrete bodies (frequently referred to as apoptotic bodies). The cell corpse (or its fragments) may be engulfed by an adjacent cell in vivo, but engulfment of whole cells should not be considered a strict criteria to define cell death as, under some circumstances, live engulfed cells can be released from phagosomes (see PMID:18045538).

gene.set.statistics.name: sulfate transport
gene.set.statistics.description: The directed movement of sulfate into, out of or within a cell, or between cells, by means of some agent such as a transporter or pore.

gene.set.statistics.name: regulation of G protein-coupled receptor signaling pathway
gene.set.statistics.description: Any process that modulates the frequency, rate or extent of G protein-coupled receptor signaling pathway.

gene.set.statistics.name: cell population proliferation
gene.set.statistics.description: The multiplication or reproduction of cells, resulting in the expansion of a cell population.

gene.set.statistics.name: positive regulation of cell population proliferation
gene.set.statistics.description: Any process that activates or increases the rate or extent of cell proliferation.

gene.set.statistics.name: negative regulation of cell population proliferation
gene.set.statistics.description: Any process that stops, prevents or reduces the rate or extent of cell proliferation.

gene.set.statistics.name: insulin receptor signaling pathway
gene.set.statistics.description: The series of molecular signals generated as a consequence of the insulin receptor binding to insulin.

gene.set.statistics.name: associative learning
gene.set.statistics.description: Learning by associating a stimulus (the cause) with a particular outcome (the effect).

gene.set.statistics.name: endosome to lysosome transport
gene.set.statistics.description: The directed movement of substances from endosomes to lysosomes.

gene.set.statistics.name: histone mRNA metabolic process
gene.set.statistics.description: The chemical reactions and pathways involving an mRNA encoding a histone.

gene.set.statistics.name: adult locomotory behavior
gene.set.statistics.description: Locomotory behavior in a fully developed and mature organism.

gene.set.statistics.name: asymmetric cell division
gene.set.statistics.description: The asymmetric division of cells to produce two daughter cells with different developmental potentials. It is of fundamental significance for the generation of cell diversity.

gene.set.statistics.name: regulation of cell shape
gene.set.statistics.description: Any process that modulates the surface configuration of a cell.

gene.set.statistics.name: regulation of cell size
gene.set.statistics.description: Any process that modulates the size of a cell.

gene.set.statistics.name: RNA splicing
gene.set.statistics.description: The process of removing sections of the primary RNA transcript to remove sequences not present in the mature form of the RNA and joining the remaining sections to form the mature form of the RNA.

gene.set.statistics.name: respiratory chain complex IV assembly
gene.set.statistics.description: The aggregation, arrangement and bonding together of a set of components to form respiratory chain complex IV (also known as cytochrome c oxidase), the terminal member of the respiratory chain of the mitochondrion and some aerobic bacteria. Cytochrome c oxidases are multi-subunit enzymes containing from 13 subunits in the mammalian mitochondrial form to 3-4 subunits in the bacterial forms.

gene.set.statistics.name: visual learning
gene.set.statistics.description: Any process in an organism in which a change in behavior of an individual occurs in response to repeated exposure to a visual cue.

gene.set.statistics.name: fibroblast growth factor receptor signaling pathway
gene.set.statistics.description: The series of molecular signals generated as a consequence of a fibroblast growth factor receptor binding to one of its physiological ligands.

gene.set.statistics.name: epidermis development
gene.set.statistics.description: The process whose specific outcome is the progression of the epidermis over time, from its formation to the mature structure. The epidermis is the outer epithelial layer of an animal, it may be a single layer that produces an extracellular material (e.g. the cuticle of arthropods) or a complex stratified squamous epithelium, as in the case of many vertebrate species.

gene.set.statistics.name: male gonad development
gene.set.statistics.description: The process whose specific outcome is the progression of the male gonad over time, from its formation to the mature structure.

gene.set.statistics.name: female gonad development
gene.set.statistics.description: The process whose specific outcome is the progression of the female gonad over time, from its formation to the mature structure.

gene.set.statistics.name: attachment of spindle microtubules to kinetochore
gene.set.statistics.description: The process in which spindle microtubules become physically associated with the proteins making up the kinetochore complex.

gene.set.statistics.name: lipid biosynthetic process
gene.set.statistics.description: The chemical reactions and pathways resulting in the formation of lipids, compounds soluble in an organic solvent but not, or sparingly, in an aqueous solvent.

gene.set.statistics.name: ether lipid biosynthetic process
gene.set.statistics.description: The chemical reactions and pathways resulting in the formation of ether lipids, lipids that contain (normally) one lipid alcohol in ether linkage to one of the carbon atoms (normally C-1) of glycerol.

gene.set.statistics.name: extrinsic apoptotic signaling pathway via death domain receptors
gene.set.statistics.description: A series of molecular signals in which a signal is conveyed from the cell surface to trigger the apoptotic death of a cell. The pathway starts with a ligand binding to a death domain receptor on the cell surface, and ends when the execution phase of apoptosis is triggered.

gene.set.statistics.name: intrinsic apoptotic signaling pathway in response to DNA damage
gene.set.statistics.description: A series of molecular signals in which an intracellular signal is conveyed to trigger the apoptotic death of a cell. The pathway is induced by the detection of DNA damage, and ends when the execution phase of apoptosis is triggered.

gene.set.statistics.name: intrinsic apoptotic signaling pathway in response to oxidative stress
gene.set.statistics.description: A series of molecular signals in which an intracellular signal is conveyed to trigger the apoptotic death of a cell. The pathway is induced in response to oxidative stress, a state often resulting from exposure to high levels of reactive oxygen species, and ends when the execution phase of apoptosis is triggered.

gene.set.statistics.name: activation of cysteine-type endopeptidase activity involved in apoptotic process by cytochrome c
gene.set.statistics.description: Any process that initiates the activity of the inactive enzyme cysteine-type endopeptidase in the context of an apoptotic process and is mediated by cytochrome c.

gene.set.statistics.name: apoptotic mitochondrial changes
gene.set.statistics.description: The morphological and physiological alterations undergone by mitochondria during apoptosis.

gene.set.statistics.name: phospholipid biosynthetic process
gene.set.statistics.description: The chemical reactions and pathways resulting in the formation of phospholipids, any lipid containing phosphoric acid as a mono- or diester.

gene.set.statistics.name: dosage compensation by inactivation of X chromosome
gene.set.statistics.description: Compensating for the two-fold variation in X-chromosome:autosome ratios between sexes by a global inactivation of all, or most of, the genes on one of the X-chromosomes in the XX sex.

gene.set.statistics.name: pentose-phosphate shunt, oxidative branch
gene.set.statistics.description: The branch of the pentose-phosphate shunt which involves the oxidation of glucose 6-P and produces ribulose 5-P, reduced NADP+ and carbon dioxide (CO2).

gene.set.statistics.name: pentose-phosphate shunt, non-oxidative branch
gene.set.statistics.description: The branch of the pentose-phosphate shunt which does not involve oxidation reactions. It comprises a series of sugar phosphate interconversions, starting with ribulose 5-P and producing fructose 6-P and glyceraldehyde 3-P.

gene.set.statistics.name: biosynthetic process
gene.set.statistics.description: The chemical reactions and pathways resulting in the formation of substances; typically the energy-requiring part of metabolism in which simpler substances are transformed into more complex ones.

gene.set.statistics.name: aerobic respiration
gene.set.statistics.description: The enzymatic release of energy from inorganic and organic compounds (especially carbohydrates and fats) which requires oxygen as the terminal electron acceptor.

gene.set.statistics.name: fatty acid catabolic process
gene.set.statistics.description: The chemical reactions and pathways resulting in the breakdown of a fatty acid, any of the aliphatic monocarboxylic acids that can be liberated by hydrolysis from naturally occurring fats and oils. Fatty acids are predominantly straight-chain acids of 4 to 24 carbon atoms, which may be saturated or unsaturated; branched fatty acids and hydroxy fatty acids also occur, and very long chain acids of over 30 carbons are found in waxes.

gene.set.statistics.name: glutamine family amino acid metabolic process
gene.set.statistics.description: The chemical reactions and pathways involving amino acids of the glutamine family, comprising arginine, glutamate, glutamine and proline.

gene.set.statistics.name: aspartate family amino acid metabolic process
gene.set.statistics.description: The chemical reactions and pathways involving amino acids of the aspartate family, comprising asparagine, aspartate, lysine, methionine and threonine.

gene.set.statistics.name: serine family amino acid metabolic process
gene.set.statistics.description: The chemical reactions and pathways involving amino acids of the serine family, comprising cysteine, glycine, homoserine, selenocysteine and serine.

gene.set.statistics.name: aromatic amino acid family metabolic process
gene.set.statistics.description: The chemical reactions and pathways involving aromatic amino acid family, amino acids with aromatic ring (phenylalanine, tyrosine, tryptophan).

gene.set.statistics.name: branched-chain amino acid catabolic process
gene.set.statistics.description: The chemical reactions and pathways resulting in the breakdown of amino acids containing a branched carbon skeleton, comprising isoleucine, leucine and valine.

gene.set.statistics.name: methionine biosynthetic process
gene.set.statistics.description: The chemical reactions and pathways resulting in the formation of methionine (2-amino-4-(methylthio)butanoic acid), a sulfur-containing, essential amino acid found in peptide linkage in proteins.

gene.set.statistics.name: glycoprotein biosynthetic process
gene.set.statistics.description: The chemical reactions and pathways resulting in the formation of glycoproteins, any protein that contains covalently bound glycose (i.e. monosaccharide) residues; the glycose occurs most commonly as oligosaccharide or fairly small polysaccharide but occasionally as monosaccharide.

gene.set.statistics.name: purine nucleobase biosynthetic process
gene.set.statistics.description: The chemical reactions and pathways resulting in the formation of purine nucleobases, one of the two classes of nitrogen-containing ring compounds found in DNA and RNA, which include adenine and guanine.

gene.set.statistics.name: nucleoside metabolic process
gene.set.statistics.description: The chemical reactions and pathways involving a nucleoside, a nucleobase linked to either beta-D-ribofuranose (a ribonucleoside) or 2-deoxy-beta-D-ribofuranose, (a deoxyribonucleoside), e.g. adenosine, guanosine, inosine, cytidine, uridine and deoxyadenosine, deoxyguanosine, deoxycytidine and thymidine (= deoxythymidine).

gene.set.statistics.name: nucleotide metabolic process
gene.set.statistics.description: The chemical reactions and pathways involving a nucleotide, a nucleoside that is esterified with (ortho)phosphate or an oligophosphate at any hydroxyl group on the glycose moiety; may be mono-, di- or triphosphate; this definition includes cyclic nucleotides (nucleoside cyclic phosphates).

gene.set.statistics.name: nucleoside triphosphate biosynthetic process
gene.set.statistics.description: The chemical reactions and pathways resulting in the formation of a nucleoside triphosphate, a compound consisting of a nucleobase linked to a deoxyribose or ribose sugar esterified with triphosphate on the sugar.

gene.set.statistics.name: nucleoside triphosphate catabolic process
gene.set.statistics.description: The chemical reactions and pathways resulting in the breakdown of a nucleoside triphosphate, a compound consisting of a nucleobase linked to a deoxyribose or ribose sugar esterified with triphosphate on the sugar.

gene.set.statistics.name: ribonucleoside monophosphate biosynthetic process
gene.set.statistics.description: The chemical reactions and pathways resulting in the formation of a ribonucleoside monophosphate, a compound consisting of a nucleobase linked to a ribose sugar esterified with phosphate on the sugar.

gene.set.statistics.name: deoxyribonucleoside monophosphate biosynthetic process
gene.set.statistics.description: The chemical reactions and pathways resulting in the formation of a deoxyribonucleoside monophosphate, a compound consisting of a nucleobase linked to a deoxyribose sugar esterified with phosphate on the sugar.

gene.set.statistics.name: nucleotide biosynthetic process
gene.set.statistics.description: The chemical reactions and pathways resulting in the formation of nucleotides, any nucleoside that is esterified with (ortho)phosphate or an oligophosphate at any hydroxyl group on the glycose moiety; may be mono-, di- or triphosphate; this definition includes cyclic-nucleotides (nucleoside cyclic phosphates).

gene.set.statistics.name: purine ribonucleoside monophosphate biosynthetic process
gene.set.statistics.description: The chemical reactions and pathways resulting in the formation of purine ribonucleoside monophosphate, a compound consisting of a purine base linked to a ribose sugar esterified with phosphate on the sugar.

gene.set.statistics.name: pyrimidine ribonucleotide biosynthetic process
gene.set.statistics.description: The chemical reactions and pathways resulting in the formation of a pyrimidine ribonucleotide, a compound consisting of nucleoside (a pyrimidine base linked to a ribose sugar) esterified with a phosphate group at either the 3' or 5'-hydroxyl group of the sugar.

gene.set.statistics.name: isopentenyl diphosphate biosynthetic process
