gene.set.statistics.description: The chemical reactions and pathways resulting in the formation of isopentenyl diphosphate, an isomer of dimethylallyl diphosphate and the key precursor of all isoprenoids.

gene.set.statistics.name: 10-formyltetrahydrofolate biosynthetic process
gene.set.statistics.description: The chemical reactions and pathways resulting in the formation of 10-formyltetrahydrofolate, the formylated derivative of tetrahydrofolate.

gene.set.statistics.name: deoxyribonucleotide biosynthetic process
gene.set.statistics.description: The chemical reactions and pathways resulting in the formation of a deoxyribonucleotide, a compound consisting of deoxyribonucleoside (a base linked to a deoxyribose sugar) esterified with a phosphate group at either the 3' or 5'-hydroxyl group of the sugar.

gene.set.statistics.name: cellular response to starvation
gene.set.statistics.description: Any process that results in a change in state or activity of a cell (in terms of movement, secretion, enzyme production, gene expression, etc.) as a result of deprivation of nourishment.

gene.set.statistics.name: GDP-mannose biosynthetic process
gene.set.statistics.description: The chemical reactions and pathways resulting in the formation of GDP-mannose, a substance composed of mannose in glycosidic linkage with guanosine diphosphate.

gene.set.statistics.name: mRNA transcription
gene.set.statistics.description: The cellular synthesis of messenger RNA (mRNA) from a DNA template.

gene.set.statistics.name: rRNA transcription
gene.set.statistics.description: The synthesis of ribosomal RNA (rRNA), any RNA that forms part of the ribosomal structure, from a DNA template.

gene.set.statistics.name: protein secretion
gene.set.statistics.description: The controlled release of proteins from a cell.

gene.set.statistics.name: oligosaccharide metabolic process
gene.set.statistics.description: The chemical reactions and pathways involving oligosaccharides, molecules with between two and (about) 20 monosaccharide residues connected by glycosidic linkages.

gene.set.statistics.name: response to radiation
gene.set.statistics.description: Any process that results in a change in state or activity of a cell or an organism (in terms of movement, secretion, enzyme production, gene expression, etc.) as a result of an electromagnetic radiation stimulus. Electromagnetic radiation is a propagating wave in space with electric and magnetic components. These components oscillate at right angles to each other and to the direction of propagation.

gene.set.statistics.name: response to heat
gene.set.statistics.description: Any process that results in a change in state or activity of a cell or an organism (in terms of movement, secretion, enzyme production, gene expression, etc.) as a result of a heat stimulus, a temperature stimulus above the optimal temperature for that organism.

gene.set.statistics.name: response to cold
gene.set.statistics.description: Any process that results in a change in state or activity of a cell or an organism (in terms of movement, secretion, enzyme production, gene expression, etc.) as a result of a cold stimulus, a temperature stimulus below the optimal temperature for that organism.

gene.set.statistics.name: response to UV
gene.set.statistics.description: Any process that results in a change in state or activity of a cell or an organism (in terms of movement, secretion, enzyme production, gene expression, etc.) as a result of an ultraviolet radiation (UV light) stimulus. Ultraviolet radiation is electromagnetic radiation with a wavelength in the range of 10 to 380 nanometers.

gene.set.statistics.name: response to light stimulus
gene.set.statistics.description: Any process that results in a change in state or activity of a cell or an organism (in terms of movement, secretion, enzyme production, gene expression, etc.) as a result of a light stimulus, electromagnetic radiation of wavelengths classified as infrared, visible or ultraviolet light.

gene.set.statistics.name: NAD biosynthetic process
gene.set.statistics.description: The chemical reactions and pathways resulting in the formation of nicotinamide adenine dinucleotide, a coenzyme present in most living cells and derived from the B vitamin nicotinic acid; biosynthesis may be of either the oxidized form, NAD, or the reduced form, NADH.

gene.set.statistics.name: carnitine metabolic process
gene.set.statistics.description: The chemical reactions and pathways involving carnitine (hydroxy-trimethyl aminobutyric acid), a compound that participates in the transfer of acyl groups across the inner mitochondrial membrane.

gene.set.statistics.name: methylglyoxal metabolic process
gene.set.statistics.description: The chemical reactions and pathways involving methylglyoxal, CH3-CO-CHO, the aldehyde of pyruvic acid.

gene.set.statistics.name: fertilization
gene.set.statistics.description: The union of gametes of opposite sexes during the process of sexual reproduction to form a zygote. It involves the fusion of the gametic nuclei (karyogamy) and cytoplasm (plasmogamy).

gene.set.statistics.name: response to wounding
gene.set.statistics.description: Any process that results in a change in state or activity of a cell or an organism (in terms of movement, secretion, enzyme production, gene expression, etc.) as a result of a stimulus indicating damage to the organism.

gene.set.statistics.name: response to mechanical stimulus
gene.set.statistics.description: Any process that results in a change in state or activity of a cell or an organism (in terms of movement, secretion, enzyme production, gene expression, etc.) as a result of a mechanical stimulus.

gene.set.statistics.name: response to virus
gene.set.statistics.description: Any process that results in a change in state or activity of a cell or an organism (in terms of movement, secretion, enzyme production, gene expression, etc.) as a result of a stimulus from a virus.

gene.set.statistics.name: response to bacterium
gene.set.statistics.description: Any process that results in a change in state or activity of a cell or an organism (in terms of movement, secretion, enzyme production, gene expression, etc.) as a result of a stimulus from a bacterium.

gene.set.statistics.name: response to toxic substance
gene.set.statistics.description: Any process that results in a change in state or activity of a cell or an organism (in terms of movement, secretion, enzyme production, gene expression, etc.) as a result of a toxic stimulus.

gene.set.statistics.name: UV protection
gene.set.statistics.description: Any process in which an organism or cell protects itself from ultraviolet radiation (UV), which may also result in resistance to repeated exposure to UV.

gene.set.statistics.name: response to salt stress
gene.set.statistics.description: Any process that results in a change in state or activity of a cell or an organism (in terms of movement, secretion, enzyme production, gene expression, etc.) as a result of a stimulus indicating an increase or decrease in the concentration of salt (particularly but not exclusively sodium and chloride ions) in the environment.

gene.set.statistics.name: anatomical structure morphogenesis
gene.set.statistics.description: The process in which anatomical structures are generated and organized. Morphogenesis pertains to the creation of form.

gene.set.statistics.name: response to hormone
gene.set.statistics.description: Any process that results in a change in state or activity of a cell or an organism (in terms of movement, secretion, enzyme production, gene expression, etc.) as a result of a hormone stimulus.

gene.set.statistics.name: response to carbohydrate
gene.set.statistics.description: Any process that results in a change in state or activity of a cell or an organism (in terms of movement, secretion, enzyme production, gene expression, etc.) as a result of a carbohydrate stimulus.

gene.set.statistics.name: response to glucose
gene.set.statistics.description: Any process that results in a change in state or activity of a cell or an organism (in terms of movement, secretion, enzyme production, gene expression, etc.) as a result of a glucose stimulus.

gene.set.statistics.name: post-embryonic development
gene.set.statistics.description: The process whose specific outcome is the progression of the organism over time, from the completion of embryonic development to the mature structure. See embryonic development.

gene.set.statistics.name: embryo development ending in birth or egg hatching
gene.set.statistics.description: The process whose specific outcome is the progression of an embryo over time, from zygote formation until the end of the embryonic life stage. The end of the embryonic life stage is organism-specific and may be somewhat arbitrary; for mammals it is usually considered to be birth, for insects the hatching of the first instar larva from the eggshell.

gene.set.statistics.name: flavonoid metabolic process
gene.set.statistics.description: The chemical reactions and pathways involving flavonoids, a group of water-soluble phenolic derivatives containing a flavan skeleton including flavones, flavonols and flavanoids, and anthocyanins.

gene.set.statistics.name: abscission
gene.set.statistics.description: The controlled shedding of a body part.

gene.set.statistics.name: animal organ morphogenesis
gene.set.statistics.description: Morphogenesis of an animal organ. An organ is defined as a tissue or set of tissues that work together to perform a specific function or functions. Morphogenesis is the process in which anatomical structures are generated and organized. Organs are commonly observed as visibly distinct structures, but may also exist as loosely associated clusters of cells that work together to perform a specific function or functions.

gene.set.statistics.name: tissue development
gene.set.statistics.description: The process whose specific outcome is the progression of a tissue over time, from its formation to the mature structure.

gene.set.statistics.name: epidermal cell differentiation
gene.set.statistics.description: The process in which a relatively unspecialized cell acquires specialized features of an epidermal cell, any of the cells making up the epidermis.

gene.set.statistics.name: anterior/posterior pattern specification
gene.set.statistics.description: The regionalization process in which specific areas of cell differentiation are determined along the anterior-posterior axis. The anterior-posterior axis is defined by a line that runs from the head or mouth of an organism to the tail or opposite end of the organism.

gene.set.statistics.name: regulation of signal transduction
gene.set.statistics.description: Any process that modulates the frequency, rate or extent of signal transduction.

gene.set.statistics.name: positive regulation of signal transduction
gene.set.statistics.description: Any process that activates or increases the frequency, rate or extent of signal transduction.

gene.set.statistics.name: negative regulation of signal transduction
gene.set.statistics.description: Any process that stops, prevents, or reduces the frequency, rate or extent of signal transduction.

gene.set.statistics.name: cellular process
gene.set.statistics.description: Any process that is carried out at the cellular level, but not necessarily restricted to a single cell. For example, cell communication occurs among more than one cell, but occurs at the cellular level.

gene.set.statistics.name: response to extracellular stimulus
gene.set.statistics.description: Any process that results in a change in state or activity of a cell or an organism (in terms of movement, secretion, enzyme production, gene expression, etc.) as a result of an extracellular stimulus.

gene.set.statistics.name: cellular water homeostasis
gene.set.statistics.description: Any process involved in the maintenance of an internal steady state of water within a cell.

gene.set.statistics.name: wax biosynthetic process
gene.set.statistics.description: The chemical reactions and pathways resulting in the formation of wax, which includes C16 and C18 fatty acids.

gene.set.statistics.name: meiotic chromosome condensation
gene.set.statistics.description: Compaction of chromatin structure prior to meiosis in eukaryotic cells.

gene.set.statistics.name: response to organic substance
gene.set.statistics.description: Any process that results in a change in state or activity of a cell or an organism (in terms of movement, secretion, enzyme production, gene expression, etc.) as a result of an organic substance stimulus.

gene.set.statistics.name: response to inorganic substance
gene.set.statistics.description: Any process that results in a change in state or activity of a cell or an organism (in terms of movement, secretion, enzyme production, gene expression, etc.) as a result of an inorganic substance stimulus.

gene.set.statistics.name: response to metal ion
gene.set.statistics.description: Any process that results in a change in state or activity of a cell or an organism (in terms of movement, secretion, enzyme production, gene expression, etc.) as a result of a metal ion stimulus.

gene.set.statistics.name: response to iron(III) ion
gene.set.statistics.description: Any process that results in a change in state or activity of a cell or an organism (in terms of movement, secretion, enzyme production, gene expression, etc.) as a result of an iron(III) ion stimulus.

gene.set.statistics.name: response to zinc ion
gene.set.statistics.description: Any process that results in a change in state or activity of a cell or an organism (in terms of movement, secretion, enzyme production, gene expression, etc.) as a result of a zinc ion stimulus.

gene.set.statistics.name: response to aluminum ion
gene.set.statistics.description: Any process that results in a change in state or activity of a cell or an organism (in terms of movement, secretion, enzyme production, gene expression, etc.) as a result of an aluminum ion stimulus.

gene.set.statistics.name: response to mycotoxin
gene.set.statistics.description: Any process that results in a change in state or activity of a cell or an organism (in terms of movement, secretion, enzyme production, gene expression, etc.) as a result of a mycotoxin stimulus. A mycotoxin is a toxic chemical substance produced by fungi.

gene.set.statistics.name: phenylacetate catabolic process
gene.set.statistics.description: The chemical reactions and pathways resulting in the breakdown of phenylacetate.

gene.set.statistics.name: response to X-ray
gene.set.statistics.description: Any process that results in a change in state or activity of a cell or an organism (in terms of movement, secretion, enzyme production, gene expression, etc.) as a result of X-ray radiation. An X-ray is a form of electromagnetic radiation with a wavelength in the range of 10 nanometers to 100 picometers (corresponding to frequencies in the range 30 PHz to 3 EHz).

gene.set.statistics.name: response to ionizing radiation
gene.set.statistics.description: Any process that results in a change in state or activity of a cell or an organism (in terms of movement, secretion, enzyme production, gene expression, etc.) as a result of a ionizing radiation stimulus. Ionizing radiation is radiation with sufficient energy to remove electrons from atoms and may arise from spontaneous decay of unstable isotopes, resulting in alpha and beta particles and gamma rays. Ionizing radiation also includes X-rays.

gene.set.statistics.name: maintenance of DNA methylation
gene.set.statistics.description: Any process involved in maintaining the methylation state of a nucleotide sequence.

gene.set.statistics.name: response to UV-B
gene.set.statistics.description: Any process that results in a change in state or activity of a cell or an organism (in terms of movement, secretion, enzyme production, gene expression, etc.) as a result of a UV-B radiation stimulus. UV-B radiation (UV-B light) spans the wavelengths 280 to 315 nm.

gene.set.statistics.name: response to lithium ion
gene.set.statistics.description: Any process that results in a change in state or activity of a cell or an organism (in terms of movement, secretion, enzyme production, gene expression, etc.) as a result of a lithium (Li+) ion stimulus.

gene.set.statistics.name: response to organonitrogen compound
gene.set.statistics.description: Any process that results in a change in state or activity of a cell or an organism (in terms of movement, secretion, enzyme production, gene expression, etc.) as a result of an organonitrogen stimulus. An organonitrogen compound is formally a compound containing at least one carbon-nitrogen bond.

gene.set.statistics.name: establishment or maintenance of transmembrane electrochemical gradient
gene.set.statistics.description: The directed movement of ions to establish or maintain an electrochemical gradient across a membrane by means of some agent such as a transporter or pore.

gene.set.statistics.name: multicellular organism aging
gene.set.statistics.description: An aging process that has as participant a whole multicellular organism. Multicellular organism aging includes loss of functions such as resistance to disease, homeostasis, and fertility, as well as wear and tear. Multicellular organisms aging includes processes like cellular senescence and organ senescence, but is more inclusive. May precede death (GO:0016265) of an organism and may succeed developmental maturation (GO:0021700).

gene.set.statistics.name: SCF complex assembly
gene.set.statistics.description: The aggregation, arrangement and bonding together of a set of components to form the SKP1-Cullin/Cdc53-F-box protein ubiquitin ligase (SCF) complex.

gene.set.statistics.name: response to selenium ion
gene.set.statistics.description: Any process that results in a change in state or activity of a cell or an organism (in terms of movement, secretion, enzyme production, gene expression, etc.) as a result of a stimulus from selenium ion.

gene.set.statistics.name: detoxification of copper ion
gene.set.statistics.description: Any process that reduces or removes the toxicity of copper ion. These include transport of copper away from sensitive areas and to compartments or complexes whose purpose is sequestration of copper ion.

gene.set.statistics.name: response to lead ion
gene.set.statistics.description: Any process that results in a change in state or activity of a cell or an organism (in terms of movement, secretion, enzyme production, gene expression, etc.) as a result of a lead ion stimulus.

gene.set.statistics.name: regulation of hydrogen peroxide metabolic process
gene.set.statistics.description: Any process that modulates the frequency, rate or extent of the chemical reactions and pathways involving hydrogen peroxide.

gene.set.statistics.name: membrane invagination
gene.set.statistics.description: The infolding of a membrane.

gene.set.statistics.name: response to gamma radiation
gene.set.statistics.description: Any process that results in a change in state or activity of a cell or an organism (in terms of movement, secretion, enzyme production, gene expression, etc.) as a result of a gamma radiation stimulus. Gamma radiation is a form of electromagnetic radiation (EMR) or light emission of a specific frequency produced from sub-atomic particle interaction, such as electron-positron annihilation and radioactive decay. Gamma rays are generally characterized as EMR having the highest frequency and energy, and also the shortest wavelength, within the electromagnetic radiation spectrum.

gene.set.statistics.name: COP9 signalosome assembly
gene.set.statistics.description: The aggregation, arrangement and bonding together of a set of components to form a COP9 signalosome.

gene.set.statistics.name: regulation of G2/M transition of mitotic cell cycle
gene.set.statistics.description: Any signalling pathway that modulates the activity of a cell cycle cyclin-dependent protein kinase to modulate the switch from G2 phase to M phase of the mitotic cell cycle.

gene.set.statistics.name: histone monoubiquitination
gene.set.statistics.description: The modification of histones by addition of a single ubiquitin group.

gene.set.statistics.name: fatty acid omega-oxidation
gene.set.statistics.description: A fatty acid oxidation process in which the methyl group at the end of the fatty acid molecule (the omega carbon) is first oxidized to a hydroxyl group, then to an oxo group, and finally to a carboxyl group. The long chain dicarboxylates derived from omega-oxidation then enter the beta-oxidation pathway for further degradation.

gene.set.statistics.name: centriole-centriole cohesion
gene.set.statistics.description: The cell cycle process in which the two centrioles within a centrosome remain tightly paired.

gene.set.statistics.name: exit from mitosis
gene.set.statistics.description: The cell cycle transition where a cell leaves M phase and enters a new G1 phase. M phase is the part of the mitotic cell cycle during which mitosis and cytokinesis take place.

gene.set.statistics.name: positive regulation of heart rate
gene.set.statistics.description: Any process that activates or increases the frequency or rate of heart contraction.

gene.set.statistics.name: gene expression
gene.set.statistics.description: The process in which a gene's sequence is converted into a mature gene product or products (proteins or RNA). This includes the production of an RNA transcript as well as any processing to produce a mature RNA product or an mRNA or circRNA (for protein-coding genes) and the translation of that mRNA or circRNA into protein. Protein maturation is included when required to form an active form of a product from an inactive precursor form.

gene.set.statistics.name: regulation of gene expression
gene.set.statistics.description: Any process that modulates the frequency, rate or extent of gene expression. Gene expression is the process in which a gene's coding sequence is converted into a mature gene product or products (proteins or RNA). This includes the production of an RNA transcript as well as any processing to produce a mature RNA product or an mRNA or circRNA (for protein-coding genes) and the translation of that mRNA or circRNA into protein. Protein maturation is included when required to form an active form of a product from an inactive precursor form.

gene.set.statistics.name: regulation of signaling receptor activity
gene.set.statistics.description: Any process that modulates the frequency, rate or extent of a signaling receptor activity. Receptor activity is when a molecule combines with an extracellular or intracellular messenger to initiate a change in cell activity.

gene.set.statistics.name: regulation of gastrulation
gene.set.statistics.description: Any process that modulates the rate or extent of gastrulation. Gastrulation is the complex and coordinated series of cellular movements that occurs at the end of cleavage during embryonic development of most animals.

gene.set.statistics.name: regulation of epidermal cell division
gene.set.statistics.description: Any process that modulates the frequency, rate or extent of the physical partitioning and separation of an epidermal cell into daughter cells. An epidermal cell is any of the cells that make up the epidermis.

gene.set.statistics.name: proteasomal protein catabolic process
gene.set.statistics.description: The chemical reactions and pathways resulting in the breakdown of a protein or peptide by hydrolysis of its peptide bonds that is mediated by the proteasome.

gene.set.statistics.name: proteasomal ubiquitin-independent protein catabolic process
gene.set.statistics.description: The chemical reactions and pathways resulting in the breakdown of a protein or peptide by hydrolysis of its peptide bonds that is mediated by the proteasome but do not involve ubiquitin.

gene.set.statistics.name: RNA secondary structure unwinding
gene.set.statistics.description: The process in which a secondary structure of RNA are broken or 'melted'.

gene.set.statistics.name: regulation of autophagy
gene.set.statistics.description: Any process that modulates the frequency, rate or extent of autophagy. Autophagy is the process in which cells digest parts of their own cytoplasm.

gene.set.statistics.name: negative regulation of autophagy
gene.set.statistics.description: Any process that stops, prevents, or reduces the frequency, rate or extent of autophagy. Autophagy is the process in which cells digest parts of their own cytoplasm.

gene.set.statistics.name: positive regulation of autophagy
gene.set.statistics.description: Any process that activates, maintains or increases the rate of autophagy. Autophagy is the process in which cells digest parts of their own cytoplasm.

gene.set.statistics.name: positive regulation of calcium ion transport into cytosol
gene.set.statistics.description: Any process that increases the rate of the directed movement of calcium ions into the cytosol of a cell. The cytosol is that part of the cytoplasm that does not contain membranous or particulate subcellular components.

gene.set.statistics.name: regulation of cell cycle process
gene.set.statistics.description: Any process that modulates a cellular process that is involved in the progression of biochemical and morphological phases and events that occur in a cell during successive cell replication or nuclear replication events.

gene.set.statistics.name: regulation of double-strand break repair via homologous recombination
gene.set.statistics.description: Any process that modulates the frequency, rate or extent of the error-free repair of a double-strand break in DNA in which the broken DNA molecule is repaired using homologous sequences.

gene.set.statistics.name: miRNA metabolic process
gene.set.statistics.description: The chemical reactions and pathways involving miRNA, microRNA, a class of single-stranded RNA molecules of about 21-23 nucleotides in length, which regulates gene expression.

gene.set.statistics.name: miRNA catabolic process
gene.set.statistics.description: The chemical reactions and pathways resulting in the breakdown of miRNA, microRNA, a class of single-stranded RNA molecules of about 21-23 nucleotides in length, which regulates gene expression.

gene.set.statistics.name: regulation of lamellipodium assembly
gene.set.statistics.description: Any process that modulates the rate, frequency or extent of the formation of a lamellipodium, a thin sheetlike extension of the surface of a migrating cell.

gene.set.statistics.name: positive regulation of lamellipodium assembly
gene.set.statistics.description: Any process that increases the rate, frequency or extent of the formation of a lamellipodium, a thin sheetlike extension of the surface of a migrating cell.

gene.set.statistics.name: regulation of endothelial cell migration
gene.set.statistics.description: Any process that modulates the rate, frequency, or extent of the orderly movement of an endothelial cell into the extracellular matrix to form an endothelium.

gene.set.statistics.name: positive regulation of endothelial cell migration
gene.set.statistics.description: Any process that increases the rate, frequency, or extent of the orderly movement of an endothelial cell into the extracellular matrix to form an endothelium.

gene.set.statistics.name: regulation of cytoplasmic mRNA processing body assembly
gene.set.statistics.description: Any process that modulates the rate, frequency, or extent of the aggregation, arrangement and bonding together of proteins and RNA molecules to form a cytoplasmic mRNA processing body.

gene.set.statistics.name: positive regulation of cytoplasmic mRNA processing body assembly
gene.set.statistics.description: Any process that increases the rate, frequency, or extent of the aggregation, arrangement and bonding together of proteins and RNA molecules to form a cytoplasmic mRNA processing body.

gene.set.statistics.name: posttranscriptional regulation of gene expression
gene.set.statistics.description: Any process that modulates the frequency, rate or extent of gene expression after the production of an RNA transcript.

gene.set.statistics.name: positive regulation of cardiac muscle hypertrophy
gene.set.statistics.description: Any process that increases the rate, frequency or extent of the enlargement or overgrowth of all or part of the heart due to an increase in size (not length) of individual cardiac muscle fibers, without cell division.

gene.set.statistics.name: negative regulation of cardiac muscle hypertrophy
gene.set.statistics.description: Any process that decreases the rate, frequency or extent of the enlargement or overgrowth of all or part of the heart due to an increase in size (not length) of individual cardiac muscle fibers, without cell division.

gene.set.statistics.name: positive regulation of gene expression
gene.set.statistics.description: Any process that increases the frequency, rate or extent of gene expression. Gene expression is the process in which a gene's coding sequence is converted into a mature gene product or products (proteins or RNA). This includes the production of an RNA transcript as well as any processing to produce a mature RNA product or an mRNA or circRNA (for protein-coding genes) and the translation of that mRNA or circRNA into protein. Protein maturation is included when required to form an active form of a product from an inactive precursor form.

gene.set.statistics.name: negative regulation of gene expression
gene.set.statistics.description: Any process that decreases the frequency, rate or extent of gene expression. Gene expression is the process in which a gene's coding sequence is converted into a mature gene product or products (proteins or RNA). This includes the production of an RNA transcript as well as any processing to produce a mature RNA product or an mRNA or circRNA (for protein-coding genes) and the translation of that mRNA or circRNA into protein. Protein maturation is included when required to form an active form of a product from an inactive precursor form.

gene.set.statistics.name: regulation of epithelial cell migration
gene.set.statistics.description: Any process that modulates the frequency, rate or extent of epithelial cell migration.

gene.set.statistics.name: negative regulation of epithelial cell migration
gene.set.statistics.description: Any process that stops, prevents, or reduces the frequency, rate or extent of epithelial cell migration.

gene.set.statistics.name: positive regulation of epithelial cell migration
gene.set.statistics.description: Any process that activates or increases the frequency, rate or extent of epithelial cell migration.

gene.set.statistics.name: positive regulation of mitochondrial fusion
gene.set.statistics.description: Any process that increases the frequency, rate or extent of merging of two or more mitochondria within a cell to form a single compartment.

gene.set.statistics.name: negative regulation of mitochondrial fusion
gene.set.statistics.description: Any process that decreases the frequency, rate or extent of merging of two or more mitochondria within a cell to form a single compartment.

gene.set.statistics.name: negative regulation of platelet-derived growth factor receptor signaling pathway
gene.set.statistics.description: Any process that stops, prevents, or reduces the frequency, rate or extent of the platelet-derived growth factor receptor signaling pathway.

gene.set.statistics.name: cell communication by chemical coupling
gene.set.statistics.description: The process that mediates signaling interactions between one cell and another cell by the transfer of small, water-soluble molecules or metabolites between their adjacent cytoplasms via intercellular protein channels.

gene.set.statistics.name: cell communication by electrical coupling
gene.set.statistics.description: The process that mediates signaling interactions between one cell and another cell by transfer of current between their adjacent cytoplasms via intercellular protein channels.

gene.set.statistics.name: cardiac muscle cell apoptotic process
gene.set.statistics.description: A form of programmed cell death induced by external or internal signals that trigger the activity of proteolytic caspases, whose actions dismantle a cardiac muscle cell and result in its death. Cardiac muscle cells are striated muscle cells that are responsible for heart contraction.

gene.set.statistics.name: negative regulation of striated muscle cell apoptotic process
gene.set.statistics.description: Any process that decreases the rate or extent of striated muscle cell apoptotic process, a form of programmed cell death induced by external or internal signals that trigger the activity of proteolytic caspases whose actions dismantle a striated muscle cell and result in its death.

gene.set.statistics.name: positive regulation of cardiac muscle cell apoptotic process
gene.set.statistics.description: Any process that increases the rate or extent of cardiac cell apoptotic process, a form of programmed cell death induced by external or internal signals that trigger the activity of proteolytic caspases whose actions dismantle a cardiac muscle cell and result in its death.

gene.set.statistics.name: ectodermal cell differentiation
gene.set.statistics.description: The process in which relatively unspecialized cells acquire specialized structural and/or functional features of an ectodermal cell. Differentiation includes the processes involved in commitment of a cell to a specific fate.

gene.set.statistics.name: regulation of epithelial to mesenchymal transition
gene.set.statistics.description: Any process that modulates the rate, frequency, or extent of epithelial to mesenchymal transition. Epithelial to mesenchymal transition where an epithelial cell loses apical/basolateral polarity, severs intercellular adhesive junctions, degrades basement membrane components and becomes a migratory mesenchymal cell.

gene.set.statistics.name: positive regulation of epithelial to mesenchymal transition
gene.set.statistics.description: Any process that increases the rate, frequency, or extent of epithelial to mesenchymal transition. Epithelial to mesenchymal transition is where an epithelial cell loses apical/basolateral polarity, severs intercellular adhesive junctions, degrades basement membrane components and becomes a migratory mesenchymal cell.

gene.set.statistics.name: negative regulation of epithelial to mesenchymal transition
gene.set.statistics.description: Any process that decreases the rate, frequency, or extent of epithelial to mesenchymal transition. Epithelial to mesenchymal transition where an epithelial cell loses apical/basolateral polarity, severs intercellular adhesive junctions, degrades basement membrane components and becomes a migratory mesenchymal cell.

gene.set.statistics.name: negative regulation of hydrogen peroxide biosynthetic process
gene.set.statistics.description: Any process that decreases the rate, frequency or extent of hydrogen peroxide biosynthesis. The chemical reactions and pathways resulting in the formation of hydrogen peroxide (H2O2), a potentially harmful byproduct of aerobic cellular respiration which can cause damage to DNA.

gene.set.statistics.name: protein kinase A signaling
gene.set.statistics.description: A series of reactions, mediated by the intracellular serine/threonine kinase protein kinase A, which occurs as a result of a single trigger reaction or compound.

gene.set.statistics.name: regulation of protein kinase A signaling
gene.set.statistics.description: Any process that modulates the rate, frequency, or extent of protein kinase A signaling. PKA signaling is the series of reactions, mediated by the intracellular serine/threonine kinase protein kinase A, which occurs as a result of a single trigger reaction or compound.

gene.set.statistics.name: positive regulation of long-chain fatty acid import across plasma membrane
gene.set.statistics.description: Any process that increases the rate, frequency or extent of plasma membrane long-chain fatty acid transport. Plasma membrane long-chain fatty acid transport is the directed movement of long-chain fatty acids across the plasma membrane. A long-chain fatty acid is a fatty acid with a chain length between C13 and C22.

gene.set.statistics.name: positive regulation of plasminogen activation
gene.set.statistics.description: Any process that increases the rate, frequency or extent of plasminogen activation. Plasminogen activation is the process in which plasminogen is processed to plasmin.

gene.set.statistics.name: negative regulation of plasminogen activation
gene.set.statistics.description: Any process that decreases the rate, frequency or extent of plasminogen activation. Plasminogen activation is the process in which plasminogen is processed to plasmin.

gene.set.statistics.name: positive regulation of macrophage chemotaxis
gene.set.statistics.description: Any process that increases the rate, frequency or extent of macrophage chemotaxis. Macrophage chemotaxis is the movement of a macrophage in response to an external stimulus.

gene.set.statistics.name: fibroblast migration
gene.set.statistics.description: Cell migration that is accomplished by extension and retraction of a fibroblast pseudopodium. A fibroblast is a connective tissue cell which secretes an extracellular matrix rich in collagen and other macromolecules.

gene.set.statistics.name: regulation of fibroblast migration
gene.set.statistics.description: Any process that modulates the rate, frequency or extent of fibroblast cell migration. Fibroblast cell migration is accomplished by extension and retraction of a pseudopodium.

gene.set.statistics.name: negative regulation of fibroblast migration
gene.set.statistics.description: Any process that decreases the rate, frequency or extent of fibroblast cell migration. Fibroblast cell migration is accomplished by extension and retraction of a pseudopodium.

gene.set.statistics.name: positive regulation of sodium ion transport
gene.set.statistics.description: Any process that increases the frequency, rate or extent of the directed movement of sodium ions (Na+) into, out of or within a cell, or between cells, by means of some agent such as a transporter or pore.

gene.set.statistics.name: negative regulation of sodium ion transport
gene.set.statistics.description: Any process that decreases the frequency, rate or extent of the directed movement of sodium ions (Na+) into, out of or within a cell, or between cells, by means of some agent such as a transporter or pore.

gene.set.statistics.name: regulation of mRNA export from nucleus
gene.set.statistics.description: Any process that modulates the frequency, rate or extent of the directed movement of mRNA from the nucleus to the cytoplasm.

gene.set.statistics.name: positive regulation of peptidyl-threonine phosphorylation
gene.set.statistics.description: Any process that increases the frequency, rate or extent of peptidyl-threonine phosphorylation. Peptidyl-threonine phosphorylation is the phosphorylation of peptidyl-threonine to form peptidyl-O-phospho-L-threonine.

gene.set.statistics.name: negative regulation of peptidyl-threonine phosphorylation
gene.set.statistics.description: Any process that decreases the frequency, rate or extent of peptidyl-threonine phosphorylation. Peptidyl-threonine phosphorylation is the phosphorylation of peptidyl-threonine to form peptidyl-O-phospho-L-threonine.

gene.set.statistics.name: regulation of tumor necrosis factor-mediated signaling pathway
gene.set.statistics.description: Any process that modulates the rate or extent of the tumor necrosis factor-mediated signaling pathway. The tumor necrosis factor-mediated signaling pathway is the series of molecular signals generated as a consequence of tumor necrosis factor binding to a cell surface receptor.

gene.set.statistics.name: regulation of synaptic vesicle priming
gene.set.statistics.description: Any process that modulates the frequency, rate or extent of synaptic vesicle priming. Synaptic vesicle priming is the formation of SNARE-containing complexes, bringing synaptic vesicle membrane and plasma membranes into close proximity and thereby facilitating membrane fusion.

gene.set.statistics.name: regulation of cell-substrate adhesion
gene.set.statistics.description: Any process that modulates the frequency, rate or extent of cell-substrate adhesion. Cell-substrate adhesion is the attachment of a cell to the underlying substrate via adhesion molecules.

gene.set.statistics.name: positive regulation of cell-substrate adhesion
gene.set.statistics.description: Any process that increases the frequency, rate or extent of cell-substrate adhesion. Cell-substrate adhesion is the attachment of a cell to the underlying substrate via adhesion molecules.

gene.set.statistics.name: negative regulation of cell-substrate adhesion
gene.set.statistics.description: Any process that decreases the frequency, rate or extent of cell-substrate adhesion. Cell-substrate adhesion is the attachment of a cell to the underlying substrate via adhesion molecules.

gene.set.statistics.name: positive regulation of T cell chemotaxis
gene.set.statistics.description: Any process that increases the rate, frequency or extent of T cell chemotaxis. T cell chemotaxis is the directed movement of a T cell in response to an external stimulus.

gene.set.statistics.name: regulation of mitochondrion organization
gene.set.statistics.description: Any process that modulates the frequency, rate or extent of a process involved in the formation, arrangement of constituent parts, or disassembly of a mitochondrion.

gene.set.statistics.name: positive regulation of mitochondrion organization
gene.set.statistics.description: Any process that increases the frequency, rate or extent of a process involved in the formation, arrangement of constituent parts, or disassembly of a mitochondrion.

gene.set.statistics.name: regulation of centrosome duplication
gene.set.statistics.description: Any process that modulates the frequency, rate or extent of centrosome duplication. Centrosome duplication is the replication of a centrosome, a structure comprised of a pair of centrioles and peri-centriolar material from which a microtubule spindle apparatus is organized.

gene.set.statistics.name: positive regulation of centrosome duplication
gene.set.statistics.description: Any process that increases the frequency, rate or extent of centrosome duplication. Centrosome duplication is the replication of a centrosome, a structure comprised of a pair of centrioles and peri-centriolar material from which a microtubule spindle apparatus is organized.

gene.set.statistics.name: negative regulation of centrosome duplication
gene.set.statistics.description: Any process that decreases the frequency, rate or extent of centrosome duplication. Centrosome duplication is the replication of a centrosome, a structure comprised of a pair of centrioles and peri-centriolar material from which a microtubule spindle apparatus is organized.

gene.set.statistics.name: regulation of glucose transmembrane transport
gene.set.statistics.description: Any process that modulates the frequency, rate or extent of glucose transport across a membrane. Glucose transport is the directed movement of the hexose monosaccharide glucose into, out of or within a cell, or between cells, by means of some agent such as a transporter or pore.

gene.set.statistics.name: positive regulation of myotube differentiation
gene.set.statistics.description: Any process that activates, maintains or increases the frequency, rate or extent of myotube differentiation. Myotube differentiation is the process in which a relatively unspecialized cell acquires specialized features of a myotube cell. Myotubes are multinucleated cells that are formed when proliferating myoblasts exit the cell cycle, differentiate and fuse.

gene.set.statistics.name: negative regulation of myotube differentiation
gene.set.statistics.description: Any process that decreases the frequency, rate or extent of myotube differentiation. Myotube differentiation is the process in which a relatively unspecialized cell acquires specialized features of a myotube cell. Myotubes are multinucleated cells that are formed when proliferating myoblasts exit the cell cycle, differentiate and fuse.

gene.set.statistics.name: regulation of protein ADP-ribosylation
gene.set.statistics.description: Any process that modulates the frequency, rate or extent of protein ADP-ribosylation. Protein ADP-ribosylation is the transfer, from NAD, of ADP-ribose to protein amino acids.

gene.set.statistics.name: negative regulation of protein ADP-ribosylation
gene.set.statistics.description: Any process that decreases the frequency, rate or extent of protein ADP-ribosylation. Protein ADP-ribosylation is the transfer, from NAD, of ADP-ribose to protein amino acids.

gene.set.statistics.name: regulation of keratinocyte proliferation
gene.set.statistics.description: Any process that modulates the rate, frequency or extent of keratinocyte proliferation. Keratinocyte proliferation is the multiplication or reproduction of keratinocytes, resulting in the expansion of a cell population.

gene.set.statistics.name: negative regulation of keratinocyte proliferation
gene.set.statistics.description: Any process that decreases the rate, frequency or extent of keratinocyte proliferation. Keratinocyte proliferation is the multiplication or reproduction of keratinocytes, resulting in the expansion of a cell population.

gene.set.statistics.name: retina layer formation
gene.set.statistics.description: The process in which the vertebrate retina is organized into three laminae: the outer nuclear layer (ONL), which contains photoreceptor nuclei; the inner nuclear layer (INL), which contains amacrine, bipolar and horizontal cells; and the retinal ganglion cell (RGC) layer. Between the inner and outer nuclear layers, the outer plexiform layer (OPL) contains connections between the photoreceptors and bipolar and horizontal cells. The inner plexiform layer (IPL) is positioned between the INL and the ganglion cell layer and contains the dendrites of RGCs and processes of bipolar and amacrine cells. Spanning all layers of the retina are the radially oriented Mueller glia.

gene.set.statistics.name: positive regulation of pathway-restricted SMAD protein phosphorylation
gene.set.statistics.description: Any process that increases the rate, frequency or extent of pathway-restricted SMAD protein phosphorylation. Pathway-restricted SMAD proteins and common-partner SMAD proteins are involved in the transforming growth factor beta receptor signaling pathways.

gene.set.statistics.name: positive regulation of cholesterol efflux
gene.set.statistics.description: Any process that increases the frequency, rate or extent of cholesterol efflux. Cholesterol efflux is the directed movement of cholesterol, cholest-5-en-3-beta-ol, out of a cell or organelle.

gene.set.statistics.name: regulation of release of sequestered calcium ion into cytosol by sarcoplasmic reticulum
gene.set.statistics.description: Any process that modulates the rate, frequency or extent of release of sequestered calcium ion into cytosol by the sarcoplasmic reticulum, the process in which the release of sequestered calcium ion by sarcoplasmic reticulum into cytosol occurs via calcium release channels.

gene.set.statistics.name: regulation of cardiac muscle contraction by regulation of the release of sequestered calcium ion
gene.set.statistics.description: Any process that modulates the frequency, rate or extent of cardiac muscle contraction via the regulation of the release of sequestered calcium ion by sarcoplasmic reticulum into cytosol. The sarcoplasmic reticulum is the endoplasmic reticulum of striated muscle, specialised for the sequestration of calcium ions that are released upon receipt of a signal relayed by the T tubules from the neuromuscular junction.

gene.set.statistics.name: regulation of cardiac muscle contraction by calcium ion signaling
gene.set.statistics.description: Any process that modulates the frequency, rate or extent of cardiac muscle contraction by changing the calcium ion signals that trigger contraction.

gene.set.statistics.name: regulation of lipid storage
gene.set.statistics.description: Any process that modulates the rate, frequency or extent of lipid storage. Lipid storage is the accumulation and maintenance in cells or tissues of lipids, compounds soluble in organic solvents but insoluble or sparingly soluble in aqueous solvents. Lipid reserves can be accumulated during early developmental stages for mobilization and utilization at later stages of development.

gene.set.statistics.name: positive regulation of cholesterol storage
gene.set.statistics.description: Any process that increases the rate or extent of cholesterol storage. Cholesterol storage is the accumulation and maintenance in cells or tissues of cholesterol, cholest-5-en-3 beta-ol, the principal sterol of vertebrates and the precursor of many steroids, including bile acids and steroid hormones.

gene.set.statistics.name: negative regulation of mitochondrial membrane potential
gene.set.statistics.description: Any process that stops, prevents, or reduces the frequency, rate or extent of establishment or extent of a mitochondrial membrane potential, the electric potential existing across any mitochondrial membrane arising from charges in the membrane itself and from the charges present in the media on either side of the membrane.

gene.set.statistics.name: positive regulation of mitochondrial membrane potential
gene.set.statistics.description: Any process that activates or increases the frequency, rate or extent of establishment or extent of a mitochondrial membrane potential, the electric potential existing across any mitochondrial membrane arising from charges in the membrane itself and from the charges present in the media on either side of the membrane.

gene.set.statistics.name: positive regulation of necrotic cell death
gene.set.statistics.description: Any process that increases the rate, frequency or extent of necrotic cell death. Necrotic cell death is a cell death process that is morphologically characterized by a gain in cell volume (oncosis), swelling of organelles, plasma membrane rupture and subsequent loss of intracellular contents.

gene.set.statistics.name: regulation of cell death
gene.set.statistics.description: Any process that modulates the rate or frequency of cell death. Cell death is the specific activation or halting of processes within a cell so that its vital functions markedly cease, rather than simply deteriorating gradually over time, which culminates in cell death.

gene.set.statistics.name: positive regulation of cell death
gene.set.statistics.description: Any process that increases the rate or frequency of cell death. Cell death is the specific activation or halting of processes within a cell so that its vital functions markedly cease, rather than simply deteriorating gradually over time, which culminates in cell death.

gene.set.statistics.name: negative regulation of transcription by competitive promoter binding
gene.set.statistics.description: Any process that stops, prevents, or reduces the frequency, rate or extent of DNA-dependent transcription using a mechanism that involves direct competition for interaction with a promoter binding site.

gene.set.statistics.name: positive regulation of endopeptidase activity
gene.set.statistics.description: Any process that increases the frequency, rate or extent of endopeptidase activity, the endohydrolysis of peptide bonds within proteins.

gene.set.statistics.name: negative regulation of endopeptidase activity
gene.set.statistics.description: Any process that decreases the frequency, rate or extent of endopeptidase activity, the endohydrolysis of peptide bonds within proteins.

gene.set.statistics.name: positive regulation of peptidase activity
gene.set.statistics.description: Any process that increases the frequency, rate or extent of peptidase activity, the hydrolysis of peptide bonds within proteins.

gene.set.statistics.name: magnesium ion homeostasis
gene.set.statistics.description: Any process involved in the maintenance of an internal steady state of magnesium ions within an organism or cell.

gene.set.statistics.name: transport along microtubule
gene.set.statistics.description: The movement of organelles or other particles from one location in the cell to another along microtubules, driven by motor activity.

gene.set.statistics.name: positive regulation of G2/M transition of mitotic cell cycle
gene.set.statistics.description: Any signalling pathway that activates or increases the activity of a cell cycle cyclin-dependent protein kinase to modulate the switch from G2 phase to M phase of the mitotic cell cycle.

gene.set.statistics.name: negative regulation of G2/M transition of mitotic cell cycle
gene.set.statistics.description: Any signalling pathway that decreases or inhibits the activity of a cell cycle cyclin-dependent protein kinase to modulate the switch from G2 phase to M phase of the mitotic cell cycle.

gene.set.statistics.name: regulation of neuron projection development
gene.set.statistics.description: Any process that modulates the rate, frequency or extent of neuron projection development. Neuron projection development is the process whose specific outcome is the progression of a neuron projection over time, from its formation to the mature structure. A neuron projection is any process extending from a neural cell, such as axons or dendrites (collectively called neurites).

gene.set.statistics.name: positive regulation of neuron projection development
gene.set.statistics.description: Any process that increases the rate, frequency or extent of neuron projection development. Neuron projection development is the process whose specific outcome is the progression of a neuron projection over time, from its formation to the mature structure. A neuron projection is any process extending from a neural cell, such as axons or dendrites (collectively called neurites).

gene.set.statistics.name: negative regulation of neuron projection development
gene.set.statistics.description: Any process that decreases the rate, frequency or extent of neuron projection development. Neuron projection development is the process whose specific outcome is the progression of a neuron projection over time, from its formation to the mature structure. A neuron projection is any process extending from a neural cell, such as axons or dendrites (collectively called neurites).

gene.set.statistics.name: regulation of low-density lipoprotein particle clearance
gene.set.statistics.description: Any process that modulates the rate, frequency or extent of low-density lipoprotein particle clearance. Low-density lipoprotein particle clearance is the process in which a low-density lipoprotein particle is removed from the blood via receptor-mediated endocytosis and its constituent parts degraded.

gene.set.statistics.name: negative regulation of low-density lipoprotein particle clearance
gene.set.statistics.description: Any process that decreases the rate, frequency or extent of low-density lipoprotein particle clearance. Low-density lipoprotein particle clearance is the process in which a low-density lipoprotein particle is removed from the blood via receptor-mediated endocytosis and its constituent parts degraded.

gene.set.statistics.name: negative regulation of SMAD protein complex assembly
gene.set.statistics.description: Any process that decreases the rate, frequency, or extent of SMAD protein complex assembly. SMAD protein complex assembly is the aggregation, arrangement and bonding together of a set of components to form a protein complex that contains SMAD proteins.

gene.set.statistics.name: ubiquitin recycling
gene.set.statistics.description: Any process involved in the maintenance of an internal steady state of ubiquitin monomers and free ubiquitin chains at the level of the cell by recycling ubiquitin from proteasome-bound ubiquitinated intermediates.

gene.set.statistics.name: free ubiquitin chain polymerization
gene.set.statistics.description: The process of creating free ubiquitin chains, compounds composed of a large number of ubiquitin monomers. These chains are not conjugated to a protein.

gene.set.statistics.name: response to auditory stimulus
gene.set.statistics.description: Any process that results in a change in state or activity of a cell or an organism (in terms of movement, secretion, enzyme production, gene expression, etc.) as a result of an auditory stimulus.

gene.set.statistics.name: programmed cell death
gene.set.statistics.description: A process which begins when a cell receives an internal or external signal and activates a series of biochemical events (signaling pathway). The process ends with the death of the cell.

gene.set.statistics.name: astrocyte development
gene.set.statistics.description: The process aimed at the progression of an astrocyte over time, from initial commitment of the cell to a specific fate, to the fully functional differentiated cell. An astrocyte is the most abundant type of glial cell. Astrocytes provide support for neurons and regulate the environment in which they function.

gene.set.statistics.name: oligodendrocyte development
gene.set.statistics.description: The process aimed at the progression of an oligodendrocyte over time, from initial commitment of the cell to a specific fate, to the fully functional differentiated cell. An oligodendrocyte is a type of glial cell involved in myelinating the axons in the central nervous system.

gene.set.statistics.name: glial cell proliferation
gene.set.statistics.description: The multiplication or reproduction of glial cells by cell division, resulting in the expansion of their population. Glial cells exist throughout the nervous system, and include Schwann cells, astrocytes, and oligodendrocytes among others.

gene.set.statistics.name: notochord formation
gene.set.statistics.description: The formation of the notochord from the chordamesoderm. The notochord is composed of large cells packed within a firm connective tissue sheath and is found in all chordates at the ventral surface of the neural tube. In vertebrates, the notochord contributes to the vertebral column.

gene.set.statistics.name: neural crest formation
gene.set.statistics.description: The formation of the specialized region of ectoderm between the neural ectoderm (neural plate) and non-neural ectoderm. The neural crest gives rise to the neural crest cells that migrate away from this region as neural tube formation procedes.

gene.set.statistics.name: neural crest cell development
gene.set.statistics.description: The process aimed at the progression of a neural crest cell over time, from initial commitment of the cell to its specific fate, to the fully functional differentiated cell.

gene.set.statistics.name: Schwann cell differentiation
gene.set.statistics.description: The process in which a relatively unspecialized cell acquires the specialized features of a Schwann cell. Schwann cells are found in the peripheral nervous system, where they insulate neurons and axons, and regulate the environment in which neurons function.

gene.set.statistics.name: positive regulation of neuron maturation
gene.set.statistics.description: Any process that activates or increases the frequency, rate or extent of neuron maturation.

gene.set.statistics.name: regulation of dopamine secretion
gene.set.statistics.description: Any process that modulates the frequency, rate or extent of the regulated release of dopamine.

gene.set.statistics.name: phosphatidylinositol 3-kinase signaling
gene.set.statistics.description: A series of reactions within the signal-receiving cell, mediated by the intracellular phosphatidylinositol 3-kinase (PI3K). Many cell surface receptor linked signaling pathways signal through PI3K to regulate numerous cellular functions.

gene.set.statistics.name: regulation of phosphatidylinositol 3-kinase signaling
gene.set.statistics.description: Any process that modulates the frequency, rate or extent of signal transduction mediated by the phosphatidylinositol 3-kinase cascade.

gene.set.statistics.name: negative regulation of phosphatidylinositol 3-kinase signaling
gene.set.statistics.description: Any process that stops, prevents, or reduces the frequency, rate or extent of signal transduction mediated by the phosphatidylinositol 3-kinase cascade.

gene.set.statistics.name: positive regulation of phosphatidylinositol 3-kinase signaling
gene.set.statistics.description: Any process that activates or increases the frequency, rate or extent of signal transduction mediated by the phosphatidylinositol 3-kinase cascade.

gene.set.statistics.name: response to organic cyclic compound
gene.set.statistics.description: Any process that results in a change in state or activity of a cell or an organism (in terms of movement, secretion, enzyme production, gene expression, etc.) as a result of an organic cyclic compound stimulus.

gene.set.statistics.name: response to purine-containing compound
gene.set.statistics.description: Any process that results in a change in state or activity of a cell or an organism (in terms of movement, secretion, enzyme production, gene expression, etc.) as a result of a purine-containing compound stimulus.

gene.set.statistics.name: response to amine
gene.set.statistics.description: Any process that results in a change in state or activity of a cell or an organism (in terms of movement, secretion, enzyme production, gene expression, etc.) as a result of an amine stimulus. An amine is a compound formally derived from ammonia by replacing one, two or three hydrogen atoms by hydrocarbyl groups.

gene.set.statistics.name: regulation of skeletal muscle adaptation
gene.set.statistics.description: Any process in which skeletal muscle adapts, with consequent modifications to structural and/or functional phenotypes, in response to a stimulus. Stimuli include contractile activity, loading conditions, substrate supply, and environmental factors. These adaptive events occur in both muscle fibers and associated structures (motoneurons and capillaries), and they involve alterations in regulatory mechanisms, contractile properties and metabolic capacities.

gene.set.statistics.name: negative regulation of muscle atrophy
gene.set.statistics.description: Any process that stops, prevents, or reduces the frequency, rate, or extent of muscle atrophy.

gene.set.statistics.name: response to activity
gene.set.statistics.description: Any process that results in a change in state or activity of a cell or an organism (in terms of movement, secretion, enzyme production, gene expression, etc.) as a result of an activity stimulus.

gene.set.statistics.name: myoblast migration involved in skeletal muscle regeneration
gene.set.statistics.description: The process in which a myoblast migrates along an entire fiber to the site of injury. A myoblast is a mononucleate cell type that, by fusion with other myoblasts, gives rise to the myotubes that eventually develop into skeletal muscle fibers.

gene.set.statistics.name: response to muscle activity
gene.set.statistics.description: Any process that results in a change in state or activity of a cell or an organism (in terms of movement, secretion, enzyme production, gene expression, etc.) as a result of a muscle activity stimulus.

gene.set.statistics.name: transition between fast and slow fiber
gene.set.statistics.description: The process of conversion of fast-contracting muscle fibers to a slower character. This may involve slowing of contractile rate, slow myosin gene induction, increase in oxidative metabolic properties, altered electrophysiology and altered innervation. This process also regulates skeletal muscle adapatation.

gene.set.statistics.name: cardiac muscle hypertrophy in response to stress
gene.set.statistics.description: The physiological enlargement or overgrowth of all or part of the heart muscle due to an increase in size (not length) of individual cardiac muscle fibers, without cell division, as a result of a disturbance in organismal or cellular homeostasis.

gene.set.statistics.name: smooth muscle cell migration
gene.set.statistics.description: The orderly movement of a smooth muscle cell from one site to another, often during the development of a multicellular organism.

gene.set.statistics.name: positive regulation of smooth muscle cell migration
gene.set.statistics.description: Any process that activates, maintains or increases the frequency, rate or extent of smooth muscle cell migration.

gene.set.statistics.name: negative regulation of smooth muscle cell migration
gene.set.statistics.description: Any process that stops, prevents, or reduces the frequency, rate or extent of smooth muscle cell migration.

gene.set.statistics.name: heparan sulfate proteoglycan biosynthetic process
gene.set.statistics.description: The chemical reactions and pathways resulting in the formation of the heparan sulfate proteoglycan, a glycosaminoglycan with repeat unit consisting of alternating alpha-(1->4)-linked hexuronic acid and glucosamine residues; the former are a mixture of sulfated and nonsulfated D-glucuronic acid and L-iduronic acid; the L-iduronic acid is either sulfated or acetylated on its amino group as well as being sulfated on one of its hydroxyl groups; heparan sulfate chains are covalently linked to peptidyl-serine by a glycosidic attachment through the trisaccharide galactosyl-galactosyl-xylosyl to serine residues.

gene.set.statistics.name: protein transport
gene.set.statistics.description: The directed movement of proteins into, out of or within a cell, or between cells, by means of some agent such as a transporter or pore.

gene.set.statistics.name: carbon dioxide transport
gene.set.statistics.description: The directed movement of carbon dioxide (CO2) into, out of or within a cell, or between cells, by means of some agent such as a transporter or pore.

gene.set.statistics.name: magnesium ion transport
gene.set.statistics.description: The directed movement of magnesium (Mg) ions into, out of or within a cell, or between cells, by means of some agent such as a transporter or pore.

gene.set.statistics.name: ammonium transport
gene.set.statistics.description: The directed movement of ammonium into, out of or within a cell, or between cells, by means of some agent such as a transporter or pore. Ammonium is the cation NH4+ which is formed from N2 by root-nodule bacteria in leguminous plants and is an excretory product in ammonotelic animals.

gene.set.statistics.name: bicarbonate transport
gene.set.statistics.description: The directed movement of bicarbonate into, out of or within a cell, or between cells, by means of some agent such as a transporter or pore.

gene.set.statistics.name: thiosulfate transport
gene.set.statistics.description: The directed movement of thiosulfate into, out of or within a cell, or between cells, by means of some agent such as a transporter or pore.

gene.set.statistics.name: oxaloacetate transport
gene.set.statistics.description: The directed movement of oxaloacetate, the anion of oxobutanedioic acid, into, out of or within a cell, or between cells, by means of some agent such as a transporter or pore.

gene.set.statistics.name: alpha-ketoglutarate transport
gene.set.statistics.description: The directed movement of alpha-ketoglutarate into, out of or within a cell, or between cells, by means of some agent such as a transporter or pore.

gene.set.statistics.name: glycerol transport
gene.set.statistics.description: The directed movement of glycerol into, out of or within a cell, or between cells, by means of some agent such as a transporter or pore. Glycerol is 1,2,3-propanetriol, a sweet, hygroscopic, viscous liquid, widely distributed in nature as a constituent of many lipids.

gene.set.statistics.name: neutral amino acid transport
gene.set.statistics.description: The directed movement of neutral amino acids, amino acids with no net charge, into, out of or within a cell, or between cells, by means of some agent such as a transporter or pore.

gene.set.statistics.name: aspartate transmembrane transport
gene.set.statistics.description: The process in which aspartate is transported across a lipid bilayer, from one side of a membrane to the other.

gene.set.statistics.name: L-glutamate transmembrane transport
gene.set.statistics.description: The directed movement of L-glutamate across a membrane.

gene.set.statistics.name: leucine transport
gene.set.statistics.description: The directed movement of leucine, 2-amino-4-methylpentanoic acid, into, out of or within a cell, or between cells, by means of some agent such as a transporter or pore.

gene.set.statistics.name: phenylalanine transport
gene.set.statistics.description: The directed movement of phenylalanine, 2-amino-3-phenylpropanoic acid, into, out of or within a cell, or between cells, by means of some agent such as a transporter or pore.

gene.set.statistics.name: L-serine transport
gene.set.statistics.description: The directed movement of L-serine, the L-enantiomer of 2-amino-3-hydroxypropanoic acid, into, out of or within a cell, or between cells, by means of some agent such as a transporter or pore.

gene.set.statistics.name: tryptophan transport
gene.set.statistics.description: The directed movement of tryptophan, 2-amino-3-(1H-indol-3-yl)propanoic acid, into, out of or within a cell, or between cells, by means of some agent such as a transporter or pore.

gene.set.statistics.name: fatty acid transport
gene.set.statistics.description: The directed movement of fatty acids into, out of or within a cell, or between cells, by means of some agent such as a transporter or pore. Fatty acids are aliphatic monocarboxylic acids liberated from naturally occurring fats and oils by hydrolysis.

gene.set.statistics.name: long-chain fatty acid transport
gene.set.statistics.description: The directed movement of long-chain fatty acids into, out of or within a cell, or between cells, by means of some agent such as a transporter or pore. A long-chain fatty acid is a fatty acid with a chain length between C13 and C22.

gene.set.statistics.name: long-chain fatty acid import into peroxisome
gene.set.statistics.description: The directed movement of long-chain fatty acids into a peroxisome. A long-chain fatty acid is a fatty acid with a chain length between C13 and C22.

gene.set.statistics.name: long-chain fatty acid import across plasma membrane
gene.set.statistics.description: The directed movement of long-chain fatty acids from outside of a cell, across the plasma membrane and into the cytosol. A long-chain fatty acid is a fatty acid with a chain length between C13 and C22.

gene.set.statistics.name: phospholipid transport
gene.set.statistics.description: The directed movement of phospholipids into, out of or within a cell, or between cells, by means of some agent such as a transporter or pore. Phospholipids are any lipids containing phosphoric acid as a mono- or diester.

gene.set.statistics.name: sterol transport
gene.set.statistics.description: The directed movement of sterols into, out of or within a cell, or between cells, by means of some agent such as a transporter or pore. Sterols are steroids with one or more hydroxyl groups and a hydrocarbon side-chain in the molecule.

gene.set.statistics.name: coenzyme A metabolic process
gene.set.statistics.description: The chemical reactions and pathways involving coenzyme A, 3'-phosphoadenosine-(5')diphospho(4')pantatheine, an acyl carrier in many acylation and acyl-transfer reactions in which the intermediate is a thiol ester.

gene.set.statistics.name: coenzyme A biosynthetic process
gene.set.statistics.description: The chemical reactions and pathways resulting in the formation of coenzyme A, 3'-phosphoadenosine-(5')diphospho(4')pantatheine, an acyl carrier in many acylation and acyl-transfer reactions in which the intermediate is a thiol ester.

gene.set.statistics.name: nucleobase-containing small molecule interconversion
gene.set.statistics.description: The chemical reactions and pathways by which a nucleobase, nucleoside or nucleotide small molecule is synthesized from another nucleobase, nucleoside or nucleotide small molecule.

gene.set.statistics.name: diadenosine tetraphosphate biosynthetic process
gene.set.statistics.description: The chemical reactions and pathways resulting in the formation of diadenosine tetraphosphate, a derivative of the nucleoside adenosine with four phosphate groups attached.

gene.set.statistics.name: energy derivation by oxidation of organic compounds
gene.set.statistics.description: The chemical reactions and pathways by which a cell derives energy from organic compounds; results in the oxidation of the compounds from which energy is released.

gene.set.statistics.name: ATP synthesis coupled proton transport
gene.set.statistics.description: The transport of protons across a membrane to generate an electrochemical gradient (proton-motive force) that powers ATP synthesis.

gene.set.statistics.name: CDP-diacylglycerol biosynthetic process
gene.set.statistics.description: The chemical reactions and pathways resulting in the formation of CDP-diacylglycerol, CDP-1,2-diacylglycerol, a substance composed of diacylglycerol in glycosidic linkage with cytidine diphosphate.

gene.set.statistics.name: viral process
gene.set.statistics.description: A multi-organism process in which a virus is a participant. The other participant is the host. Includes infection of a host cell, replication of the viral genome, and assembly of progeny virus particles. In some cases the viral genetic material may integrate into the host genome and only subsequently, under particular circumstances, 'complete' its life cycle.

gene.set.statistics.name: lipid catabolic process
gene.set.statistics.description: The chemical reactions and pathways resulting in the breakdown of lipids, compounds soluble in an organic solvent but not, or sparingly, in an aqueous solvent.

gene.set.statistics.name: vesicle organization
gene.set.statistics.description: A process that is carried out at the cellular level which results in the assembly, arrangement of constituent parts, or disassembly of a vesicle.

gene.set.statistics.name: carbohydrate biosynthetic process
gene.set.statistics.description: The chemical reactions and pathways resulting in the formation of carbohydrates, any of a group of organic compounds based of the general formula Cx(H2O)y.

gene.set.statistics.name: Wnt signaling pathway
gene.set.statistics.description: The series of molecular signals initiated by binding of a Wnt protein to a frizzled family receptor on the surface of the target cell and ending with a change in cell state.

gene.set.statistics.name: rhodopsin mediated signaling pathway
gene.set.statistics.description: The series of molecular signals generated as a consequence of excitation of rhodopsin by a photon and the events that convert the absorbed photons into a cellular response.

gene.set.statistics.name: immunoglobulin mediated immune response
gene.set.statistics.description: An immune response mediated by immunoglobulins, whether cell-bound or in solution.

gene.set.statistics.name: RNA metabolic process
gene.set.statistics.description: The cellular chemical reactions and pathways involving RNA, ribonucleic acid, one of the two main type of nucleic acid, consisting of a long, unbranched macromolecule formed from ribonucleotides joined in 3',5'-phosphodiester linkage.

gene.set.statistics.name: mRNA metabolic process
gene.set.statistics.description: The chemical reactions and pathways involving mRNA, messenger RNA, which is responsible for carrying the coded genetic 'message', transcribed from DNA, to sites of protein assembly at the ribosomes.

gene.set.statistics.name: rRNA catabolic process
gene.set.statistics.description: The chemical reactions and pathways resulting in the breakdown of rRNA, ribosomal RNA, a structural constituent of ribosomes.

gene.set.statistics.name: snRNA catabolic process
gene.set.statistics.description: The chemical reactions and pathways resulting in the breakdown of snRNA, small nuclear RNA, low-molecular-mass RNA molecules found in the eukaryotic nucleus as components of the small nuclear ribonucleoprotein.

gene.set.statistics.name: tRNA catabolic process
gene.set.statistics.description: The chemical reactions and pathways resulting in the breakdown of tRNA, transfer RNA, a class of relatively small RNA molecules responsible for mediating the insertion of amino acids into the sequence of nascent polypeptide chains during protein synthesis.

gene.set.statistics.name: synaptic vesicle exocytosis
gene.set.statistics.description: Fusion of intracellular membrane-bounded vesicles with the pre-synaptic membrane of the neuronal cell resulting in release of neurotransmitter into the synaptic cleft.

gene.set.statistics.name: synaptic vesicle docking
gene.set.statistics.description: The initial (indirect) attachment of a synaptic vesicle membrane to the presynaptic active zone membrane, mediated by proteins protruding from the membrane and proteins of the presynaptic active zone cytoplasmic component.  Synaptic vesicle tethering is the first step in this process.

gene.set.statistics.name: synaptic vesicle priming
gene.set.statistics.description: A process that converts synaptic vesicles to a state of competence for calcium triggered fusion with the active zone membrane by bringing the two membranes into very close proximity. Priming typically (but not always) occurs after docking (Jahn and Fasshauer, 2012). Primed vesicles are also capable of spontaneously fusing with the active zone membrane.

gene.set.statistics.name: sterol metabolic process
gene.set.statistics.description: The chemical reactions and pathways involving sterols, steroids with one or more hydroxyl groups and a hydrocarbon side-chain in the molecule.

gene.set.statistics.name: sterol biosynthetic process
gene.set.statistics.description: The chemical reactions and pathways resulting in the formation of sterols, steroids with one or more hydroxyl groups and a hydrocarbon side-chain in the molecule.

gene.set.statistics.name: synaptic vesicle budding from presynaptic endocytic zone membrane
gene.set.statistics.description: Evagination of the presynaptic membrane, resulting in the formation of a new synaptic vesicle.

gene.set.statistics.name: synaptic vesicle maturation
gene.set.statistics.description: Steps required to form an initiated synaptic vesicle into a fully formed and transmissible synaptic vesicle.

gene.set.statistics.name: synaptic vesicle to endosome fusion
gene.set.statistics.description: Fusion of a synaptic vesicle with an endosome.

gene.set.statistics.name: synaptic vesicle uncoating
gene.set.statistics.description: The removal of the protein coat on a synaptic vesicle following the pinching step at the end of budding from the presynaptic membrane.

gene.set.statistics.name: vesicle-mediated transport
gene.set.statistics.description: A cellular transport process in which transported substances are moved in membrane-bounded vesicles; transported substances are enclosed in the vesicle lumen or located in the vesicle membrane. The process begins with a step that directs a substance to the forming vesicle, and includes vesicle budding and coating. Vesicles are then targeted to, and fuse with, an acceptor membrane.

gene.set.statistics.name: endosomal transport
