gene.set.statistics.description: The directed movement of substances mediated by an endosome, a membrane-bounded organelle that carries materials enclosed in the lumen or located in the endosomal membrane.

gene.set.statistics.name: regulation of striated muscle tissue development
gene.set.statistics.description: Any process that modulates the frequency, rate or extent of striated muscle development.

gene.set.statistics.name: iron-sulfur cluster assembly
gene.set.statistics.description: The incorporation of iron and exogenous sulfur into a metallo-sulfur cluster.

gene.set.statistics.name: telomere capping
gene.set.statistics.description: A process in which telomeres are protected from degradation and fusion, thereby ensuring chromosome stability by protecting the ends from both degradation and from being recognized as damaged DNA. May be mediated by specific single- or double-stranded telomeric DNA binding proteins.

gene.set.statistics.name: macroautophagy
gene.set.statistics.description: The major inducible pathway for the general turnover of cytoplasmic constituents in eukaryotic cells, it is also responsible for the degradation of active cytoplasmic enzymes and organelles during nutrient starvation. Macroautophagy involves the formation of double-membrane-bounded autophagosomes which enclose the cytoplasmic constituent targeted for degradation in a membrane-bounded structure.  Autophagosomes then fuse with a lysosome (or vacuole) releasing single-membrane-bounded autophagic bodies that are then degraded within the lysosome (or vacuole). Some types of macroautophagy, e.g. pexophagy, mitophagy, involve selective targeting of the targets to be degraded.

gene.set.statistics.name: positive regulation of macroautophagy
gene.set.statistics.description: Any process, such as recognition of nutrient depletion, that activates or increases the rate of macroautophagy to bring cytosolic macromolecules to the vacuole/lysosome for degradation.

gene.set.statistics.name: autophagosome membrane docking
gene.set.statistics.description: The initial attachment of an autophagosome membrane to a target membrane, mediated by proteins protruding from the membrane of the vesicle and the target membrane. Docking requires only that the two membranes come close enough for these proteins to interact and adhere.

gene.set.statistics.name: regulation of macroautophagy
gene.set.statistics.description: Any process that modulates the frequency, rate or extent of macroautophagy.

gene.set.statistics.name: negative regulation of macroautophagy
gene.set.statistics.description: Any process that stops, prevents, or reduces the frequency, rate or extent of macroautophagy.

gene.set.statistics.name: RNA interference
gene.set.statistics.description: The process in which double-stranded RNAs silence cognate genes. Involves posttranscriptional gene inactivation ('silencing') both of transgenes or dsRNA introduced into a germline, and of the host gene(s) homologous to the transgenes or dsRNA. This silencing is triggered by the introduction of transgenes or double-stranded RNA (dsRNA), and can occur through a specific decrease in the level of mRNA, or by negative regulation of translation, of both host genes and transgenes.

gene.set.statistics.name: selenocysteine metabolic process
gene.set.statistics.description: The chemical reactions and pathways involving selenocysteine, an essential component of glutathione peroxidase and some other proteins.

gene.set.statistics.name: gap junction assembly
gene.set.statistics.description: Assembly of gap junctions, which are found in most animal tissues, and serve as direct connections between the cytoplasms of adjacent cells. They provide open channels through the plasma membrane, allowing ions and small molecules (less than approximately a thousand daltons) to diffuse freely between neighboring cells, but preventing the passage of proteins and nucleic acids.

gene.set.statistics.name: phosphorylation
gene.set.statistics.description: The process of introducing a phosphate group into a molecule, usually with the formation of a phosphoric ester, a phosphoric anhydride or a phosphoric amide.

gene.set.statistics.name: dephosphorylation
gene.set.statistics.description: The process of removing one or more phosphoric (ester or anhydride) residues from a molecule.

gene.set.statistics.name: meiotic chromosome movement towards spindle pole
gene.set.statistics.description: The cell cycle process in which the directed movement of chromosomes from the center of the spindle towards the spindle poles takes place, mediated by the shortening of microtubules attached to the chromosomes. This occurs during meiosis.

gene.set.statistics.name: dendrite development
gene.set.statistics.description: The process whose specific outcome is the progression of the dendrite over time, from its formation to the mature structure.

gene.set.statistics.name: posttranscriptional gene silencing
gene.set.statistics.description: The inactivation of gene expression by a posttranscriptional mechanism.

gene.set.statistics.name: gene silencing
gene.set.statistics.description: Any process carried out at the cellular level that results in either long-term transcriptional repression via action on chromatin structure or RNA mediated, post-transcriptional repression of gene expression.

gene.set.statistics.name: regulation of embryonic cell shape
gene.set.statistics.description: Any process that modulates the surface configuration of an embryonic cell.

gene.set.statistics.name: cell migration
gene.set.statistics.description: The controlled self-propelled movement of a cell from one site to a destination guided by molecular cues. Cell migration is a central process in the development and maintenance of multicellular organisms.

gene.set.statistics.name: negative regulation of transcription by RNA polymerase I
gene.set.statistics.description: Any process that stops, prevents, or reduces the frequency, rate or extent of transcription mediated by RNA polymerase I.

gene.set.statistics.name: negative regulation of transcription by RNA polymerase III
gene.set.statistics.description: Any process that stops, prevents, or reduces the frequency, rate or extent of transcription mediated by RNA polymerase III.

gene.set.statistics.name: cytosolic transport
gene.set.statistics.description: The directed movement of substances or organelles within the cytosol.

gene.set.statistics.name: protein processing
gene.set.statistics.description: Any protein maturation process achieved by the cleavage of a peptide bond or bonds within a protein. Protein maturation is the process leading to the attainment of the full functional capacity of a protein.

gene.set.statistics.name: negative regulation of angiogenesis
gene.set.statistics.description: Any process that stops, prevents, or reduces the frequency, rate or extent of angiogenesis.

gene.set.statistics.name: protein autoprocessing
gene.set.statistics.description: Processing which a protein carries out itself. This involves actions such as the autolytic removal of residues to generate the mature form of the protein.

gene.set.statistics.name: base conversion or substitution editing
gene.set.statistics.description: Any base modification or substitution events that result in alterations in the coding potential or structural properties of RNAs as a result of changes in the base-pairing properties of the modified ribonucleoside(s).

gene.set.statistics.name: cytidine to uridine editing
gene.set.statistics.description: The conversion of a cytosine residue to uridine in an RNA molecule by deamination.

gene.set.statistics.name: peroxisome fission
gene.set.statistics.description: The division of a mature peroxisome within a cell to form two or more separate peroxisome compartments.

gene.set.statistics.name: protein ubiquitination
gene.set.statistics.description: The process in which one or more ubiquitin groups are added to a protein.

gene.set.statistics.name: histone methylation
gene.set.statistics.description: The modification of histones by addition of methyl groups.

gene.set.statistics.name: histone phosphorylation
gene.set.statistics.description: The modification of histones by addition of phosphate groups.

gene.set.statistics.name: histone acetylation
gene.set.statistics.description: The modification of a histone by the addition of an acetyl group.

gene.set.statistics.name: histone ubiquitination
gene.set.statistics.description: The modification of histones by addition of ubiquitin groups.

gene.set.statistics.name: histone deacetylation
gene.set.statistics.description: The modification of histones by removal of acetyl groups.

gene.set.statistics.name: histone dephosphorylation
gene.set.statistics.description: The modification of histones by removal of phosphate groups.

gene.set.statistics.name: protein deubiquitination
gene.set.statistics.description: The removal of one or more ubiquitin groups from a protein.

gene.set.statistics.name: nucleosome positioning
gene.set.statistics.description: Ordering of successions of nucleosomes into regular arrays so that nucleosomes are positioned at defined distances from one another.

gene.set.statistics.name: Rac protein signal transduction
gene.set.statistics.description: A series of molecular signals within the cell that are mediated by a member of the Rac family of proteins switching to a GTP-bound active state.

gene.set.statistics.name: protein sumoylation
gene.set.statistics.description: The process in which a SUMO protein (small ubiquitin-related modifier) is conjugated to a target protein via an isopeptide bond between the carboxy-terminus of SUMO with an epsilon-amino group of a lysine residue of the target protein.

gene.set.statistics.name: poly(A)+ mRNA export from nucleus
gene.set.statistics.description: The directed movement of poly(A)+ mRNA out of the nucleus into the cytoplasm.

gene.set.statistics.name: regulation of transforming growth factor beta receptor signaling pathway
gene.set.statistics.description: Any process that modulates the frequency, rate or extent of activity of any TGF-beta receptor signaling pathway.

gene.set.statistics.name: protein import
gene.set.statistics.description: The targeting and directed movement of proteins into a cell or organelle.  Not all import involves an initial targeting event.

gene.set.statistics.name: nucleologenesis
gene.set.statistics.description: A cellular process that results in the biosynthesis of constituent macromolecules, assembly, and arrangement of constituent parts of a nucleolus, a small, dense body one or more of which are present in the nucleus of eukaryotic cells.

gene.set.statistics.name: drug metabolic process
gene.set.statistics.description: The chemical reactions and pathways involving a drug, a substance used in the diagnosis, treatment or prevention of a disease; as used here antibiotic substances (see antibiotic metabolism) are considered to be drugs, even if not used in medical or veterinary practice.

gene.set.statistics.name: stem cell division
gene.set.statistics.description: The self-renewing division of a stem cell. A stem cell is an undifferentiated cell, in the embryo or adult, that can undergo unlimited division and give rise to one or several different cell types.

gene.set.statistics.name: negative regulation of translation
gene.set.statistics.description: Any process that stops, prevents, or reduces the frequency, rate or extent of the chemical reactions and pathways resulting in the formation of proteins by the translation of mRNA or circRNA.

gene.set.statistics.name: calcium-ion regulated exocytosis
gene.set.statistics.description: The release of intracellular molecules (e.g. hormones, matrix proteins) contained within a membrane-bounded vesicle by fusion of the vesicle with the plasma membrane of a cell, induced by a rise in cytosolic calcium-ion levels.

gene.set.statistics.name: regulation of exocytosis
gene.set.statistics.description: Any process that modulates the frequency, rate or extent of exocytosis.

gene.set.statistics.name: regulation of calcium ion-dependent exocytosis
gene.set.statistics.description: Any process that modulates the frequency, rate or extent of calcium ion-dependent exocytosis.

gene.set.statistics.name: peptidyl-lysine hydroxylation
gene.set.statistics.description: The hydroxylation of peptidyl-lysine to form peptidyl-hydroxylysine.

gene.set.statistics.name: N-terminal peptidyl-glycine N-myristoylation
gene.set.statistics.description: The myristoylation of the N-terminal glycine of proteins to form the derivative N-myristoyl-glycine.

gene.set.statistics.name: peptidyl-serine phosphorylation
gene.set.statistics.description: The phosphorylation of peptidyl-serine to form peptidyl-O-phospho-L-serine.

gene.set.statistics.name: peptidyl-threonine phosphorylation
gene.set.statistics.description: The phosphorylation of peptidyl-threonine to form peptidyl-O-phospho-L-threonine.

gene.set.statistics.name: peptidyl-tyrosine phosphorylation
gene.set.statistics.description: The phosphorylation of peptidyl-tyrosine to form peptidyl-O4'-phospho-L-tyrosine.

gene.set.statistics.name: peptidyl-cysteine S-nitrosylation
gene.set.statistics.description: The covalent addition of a nitric oxide (NO) group to the sulphur (S) atom of a cysteine residue in a protein, to form peptidyl-S-nitrosyl-L-cysteine.

gene.set.statistics.name: protein hydroxylation
gene.set.statistics.description: The addition of a hydroxy group to a protein amino acid.

gene.set.statistics.name: peptide cross-linking
gene.set.statistics.description: The formation of a covalent cross-link between or within protein chains.

gene.set.statistics.name: peptidyl-methionine modification
gene.set.statistics.description: The modification of peptidyl-methionine.

gene.set.statistics.name: peptidyl-arginine methylation
gene.set.statistics.description: The addition of a methyl group to an arginine residue in a protein.

gene.set.statistics.name: protein N-linked glycosylation via asparagine
gene.set.statistics.description: The glycosylation of protein via the N4 atom of peptidyl-asparagine forming N4-glycosyl-L-asparagine; the most common form is N-acetylglucosaminyl asparagine; N-acetylgalactosaminyl asparagine and N4 glucosyl asparagine also occur. This modification typically occurs in extracellular peptides with an N-X-(ST) motif. Partial modification has been observed to occur with cysteine, rather than serine or threonine, in the third position; secondary structure features are important, and proline in the second or fourth positions inhibits modification.

gene.set.statistics.name: protein palmitoylation
gene.set.statistics.description: The covalent attachment of a palmitoyl group to a protein.

gene.set.statistics.name: internal peptidyl-lysine acetylation
gene.set.statistics.description: The addition of an acetyl group to a non-terminal lysine residue in a protein.

gene.set.statistics.name: peptidyl-proline hydroxylation to 4-hydroxy-L-proline
gene.set.statistics.description: The modification of peptidyl-proline to form 4-hydroxy-L-proline; catalyzed by procollagen-proline,2-oxoglutarate-4-dioxygenase.

gene.set.statistics.name: nitrobenzene metabolic process
gene.set.statistics.description: The chemical reactions and pathways involving nitrobenzene (nitrobenzol), a derivative of benzene with an NO2 group attached to the ring. It is a yellow aromatic liquid used in perfumery and manufactured in large quantities in the preparation of aniline.

gene.set.statistics.name: release from viral latency
gene.set.statistics.description: The process by which a virus begins to replicate following a latency replication decision (switch).

gene.set.statistics.name: modulation by virus of host process
gene.set.statistics.description: The process in which a virus effects a change in the structure or processes of its host organism.

gene.set.statistics.name: modulation by virus of host cellular process
gene.set.statistics.description: The process in which a virus effects a change in the processes and activities of its host organism.

gene.set.statistics.name: viral life cycle
gene.set.statistics.description: A set of processes which all viruses follow to ensure survival; includes attachment and entry of the virus particle, decoding of genome information, translation of viral mRNA by host ribosomes, genome replication, and assembly and release of viral particles containing the genome.

gene.set.statistics.name: virion attachment to host cell
gene.set.statistics.description: The process by which a virion protein binds to molecules on the host cellular surface or host cell surface projection.

gene.set.statistics.name: fusion of virus membrane with host plasma membrane
gene.set.statistics.description: Fusion of a viral membrane with the host cell membrane during viral entry. Results in release of the virion contents into the cytoplasm.

gene.set.statistics.name: receptor-mediated endocytosis of virus by host cell
gene.set.statistics.description: Any receptor-mediated endocytosis that is involved in the uptake of a virus into a host cell; successive instances of virus endocytosis result in the accumulation of virus particles within the cell.

gene.set.statistics.name: virion assembly
gene.set.statistics.description: A late phase of the viral life cycle during which all the components necessary for the formation of a mature virion collect at a particular site in the cell and the basic structure of the virus particle is formed.

gene.set.statistics.name: viral RNA genome packaging
gene.set.statistics.description: The packaging of viral RNA (single-stranded or double-stranded) into a nucleocapsid.

gene.set.statistics.name: viral release from host cell
gene.set.statistics.description: The dissemination of mature viral particles from the host cell, e.g. by cell lysis or the budding of virus particles from the cell membrane.

gene.set.statistics.name: viral genome replication
gene.set.statistics.description: Any process involved directly in viral genome replication, including viral nucleotide metabolism.

gene.set.statistics.name: viral translation
gene.set.statistics.description: A process by which viral mRNA is translated into viral protein, using the host cellular machinery.

gene.set.statistics.name: viral protein processing
gene.set.statistics.description: Any protein maturation process achieved by the cleavage of a peptide bond or bonds within a viral protein.

gene.set.statistics.name: viral transcription
gene.set.statistics.description: The process by which a viral genome, or part of a viral genome, is transcribed within the host cell.

gene.set.statistics.name: regulation of lipid metabolic process
gene.set.statistics.description: Any process that modulates the frequency, rate or extent of the chemical reactions and pathways involving lipids.

gene.set.statistics.name: regulation of fatty acid metabolic process
gene.set.statistics.description: Any process that modulates the frequency, rate or extent of the chemical reactions and pathways involving fatty acids.

gene.set.statistics.name: cytokine-mediated signaling pathway
gene.set.statistics.description: A series of molecular signals initiated by the binding of a cytokine to a receptor on the surface of a cell, and ending with regulation of a downstream cellular process, e.g. transcription.

gene.set.statistics.name: regulation of metabolic process
gene.set.statistics.description: Any process that modulates the frequency, rate or extent of the chemical reactions and pathways within a cell or an organism.

gene.set.statistics.name: transmission of nerve impulse
gene.set.statistics.description: The neurological system process in which a signal is transmitted through the nervous system by a combination of action potential propagation and synaptic transmission.

gene.set.statistics.name: neuronal action potential
gene.set.statistics.description: An action potential that occurs in a neuron.

gene.set.statistics.name: sensory perception of pain
gene.set.statistics.description: The series of events required for an organism to receive a painful stimulus, convert it to a molecular signal, and recognize and characterize the signal. Pain is medically defined as the physical sensation of discomfort or distress caused by injury or illness, so can hence be described as a harmful stimulus which signals current (or impending) tissue damage. Pain may come from extremes of temperature, mechanical damage, electricity or from noxious chemical substances. This is a neurological process.

gene.set.statistics.name: citrulline biosynthetic process
gene.set.statistics.description: The chemical reactions and pathways resulting in the formation of citrulline, N5-carbamoyl-L-ornithine, an alpha amino acid not found in proteins.

gene.set.statistics.name: lactate biosynthetic process
gene.set.statistics.description: The chemical reactions and pathways resulting in the formation of lactate, the anion of lactic acid.

gene.set.statistics.name: carnitine metabolic process, CoA-linked
gene.set.statistics.description: The chemical reactions and pathways involving carnitine, where metabolism is linked to CoA.

gene.set.statistics.name: glucose 1-phosphate metabolic process
gene.set.statistics.description: The chemical reactions and pathways involving glucose 1-phosphate, a monophosphorylated derivative of glucose with the phosphate group attached to C-1.

gene.set.statistics.name: glycine betaine biosynthetic process from choline
gene.set.statistics.description: The chemical reactions and pathways resulting in the formation of betaine (N-trimethylglycine) from the oxidation of choline.

gene.set.statistics.name: pentose biosynthetic process
gene.set.statistics.description: The chemical reactions and pathways resulting in the formation of a pentose, any monosaccharide with a chain of five carbon atoms in the molecule.

gene.set.statistics.name: leukotriene biosynthetic process
gene.set.statistics.description: The chemical reactions and pathways resulting in the formation of leukotriene, a pharmacologically active substance derived from a polyunsaturated fatty acid, such as arachidonic acid.

gene.set.statistics.name: cyclooxygenase pathway
gene.set.statistics.description: The chemical reactions and pathways by which prostaglandins are formed from arachidonic acid, and in which prostaglandin-endoperoxide synthase (cyclooxygenase) catalyzes the committed step in the conversion of arachidonic acid to the prostaglandin-endoperoxides PGG2 and PGH2.

gene.set.statistics.name: galactose catabolic process
gene.set.statistics.description: The chemical reactions and pathways resulting in the breakdown of galactose, the aldohexose galacto-hexose.

gene.set.statistics.name: glucuronoside catabolic process
gene.set.statistics.description: The chemical reactions and pathways resulting in the breakdown of glucuronosides, compound composed of a hydroxy compound linked to a glucuronate residue.

gene.set.statistics.name: fatty acid oxidation
gene.set.statistics.description: The removal of one or more electrons from a fatty acid, with or without the concomitant removal of a proton or protons, by reaction with an electron-accepting substance, by addition of oxygen or by removal of hydrogen.

gene.set.statistics.name: removal of superoxide radicals
gene.set.statistics.description: Any process, acting at the cellular level, involved in removing superoxide radicals (O2-) from a cell or organism, e.g. by conversion to dioxygen (O2) and hydrogen peroxide (H2O2).

gene.set.statistics.name: triglyceride biosynthetic process
gene.set.statistics.description: The chemical reactions and pathways resulting in the formation of a triglyceride, any triester of glycerol.

gene.set.statistics.name: triglyceride catabolic process
gene.set.statistics.description: The chemical reactions and pathways resulting in the breakdown of a triglyceride, any triester of glycerol.

gene.set.statistics.name: tryptophan catabolic process to kynurenine
gene.set.statistics.description: The chemical reactions and pathways resulting in the breakdown of tryptophan into other compounds, including kynurenine.

gene.set.statistics.name: 4-hydroxyproline catabolic process
gene.set.statistics.description: The chemical reactions and pathways resulting in the breakdown of 4-hydroxyproline, C5H9NO3, a derivative of the amino acid proline.

gene.set.statistics.name: peptidyl-proline hydroxylation
gene.set.statistics.description: The hydroxylation of peptidyl-proline to form peptidyl-hydroxyproline.

gene.set.statistics.name: taurine metabolic process
gene.set.statistics.description: The chemical reactions and pathways involving taurine (2-aminoethanesulfonic acid), a sulphur-containing amino acid derivative important in the metabolism of fats.

gene.set.statistics.name: protein metabolic process
gene.set.statistics.description: The chemical reactions and pathways involving a protein. Includes protein modification.

gene.set.statistics.name: glycerol catabolic process
gene.set.statistics.description: The chemical reactions and pathways resulting in the breakdown of glycerol, 1,2,3-propanetriol, a sweet, hygroscopic, viscous liquid, widely distributed in nature as a constituent of many lipids.

gene.set.statistics.name: short-chain fatty acid catabolic process
gene.set.statistics.description: The chemical reactions and pathways resulting in the breakdown of fatty acids with a chain length of less than C6.

gene.set.statistics.name: glucuronate catabolic process to xylulose 5-phosphate
gene.set.statistics.description: The chemical reactions and pathways resulting in the breakdown of glucuronate into other compounds, including xylulose 5-phosphate.

gene.set.statistics.name: NAD metabolic process
gene.set.statistics.description: The chemical reactions and pathways involving nicotinamide adenine dinucleotide (NAD), a coenzyme present in most living cells and derived from the B vitamin nicotinic acid.

gene.set.statistics.name: cellular homeostasis
gene.set.statistics.description: Any process involved in the maintenance of an internal steady state at the level of the cell.

gene.set.statistics.name: antimicrobial humoral response
gene.set.statistics.description: An immune response against microbes mediated through a body fluid. Examples of this process are seen in the antimicrobial humoral response of Drosophila melanogaster and Mus musculus.

gene.set.statistics.name: carboxylic acid metabolic process
gene.set.statistics.description: The chemical reactions and pathways involving carboxylic acids, any organic acid containing one or more carboxyl (COOH) groups or anions (COO-).

gene.set.statistics.name: quinolinate biosynthetic process
gene.set.statistics.description: The chemical reactions and pathways resulting in the formation of quinolinate, the anion of quinolinic acid, also known as 2,3-pyridinedicarboxylic acid.

gene.set.statistics.name: stem cell population maintenance
gene.set.statistics.description: The process by which an organism or tissue maintains a population of stem cells of a single type.  This can be achieved by a number of mechanisms: stem cell asymmetric division maintains stem cell numbers; stem cell symmetric division increases them; maintenance of a stem cell niche maintains the conditions for commitment to the stem cell fate for some types of stem cell; stem cells may arise de novo from other cell types.

gene.set.statistics.name: L-ascorbic acid metabolic process
gene.set.statistics.description: The chemical reactions and pathways involving L-ascorbic acid, (2R)-2-[(1S)-1,2-dihydroxyethyl]-4-hydroxy-5-oxo-2,5-dihydrofuran-3-olate; L-ascorbic acid is vitamin C and has co-factor and anti-oxidant activities in many species.

gene.set.statistics.name: pyrimidine nucleobase biosynthetic process
gene.set.statistics.description: The chemical reactions and pathways resulting in the formation of pyrimidine nucleobases, 1,3-diazine, organic nitrogenous bases.

gene.set.statistics.name: cytosine metabolic process
gene.set.statistics.description: The chemical reactions and pathways involving cytosine, 4-amino-2-hydroxypyrimidine, a pyrimidine derivative that is one of the five main bases found in nucleic acids; it occurs widely in cytidine derivatives.

gene.set.statistics.name: antigen processing and presentation
gene.set.statistics.description: The process in which an antigen-presenting cell expresses antigen (peptide or lipid) on its cell surface in association with an MHC protein complex.

gene.set.statistics.name: antigen processing and presentation of exogenous peptide antigen via MHC class II
gene.set.statistics.description: The process in which an antigen-presenting cell expresses a peptide antigen of exogenous origin on its cell surface in association with an MHC class II protein complex. The peptide antigen is typically, but not always, processed from a whole protein.

gene.set.statistics.name: axonal transport of mitochondrion
gene.set.statistics.description: The directed movement of mitochondria along microtubules in nerve cell axons.

gene.set.statistics.name: lipid storage
gene.set.statistics.description: The accumulation and maintenance in cells or tissues of lipids, compounds soluble in organic solvents but insoluble or sparingly soluble in aqueous solvents. Lipid reserves can be accumulated during early developmental stages for mobilization and utilization at later stages of development.

gene.set.statistics.name: peptidyl-arginine methylation, to symmetrical-dimethyl arginine
gene.set.statistics.description: The process of methylation of peptidyl-arginine to form peptidyl-N(omega),N'(omega)-dimethyl-L-arginine.

gene.set.statistics.name: peptidyl-arginine methylation, to asymmetrical-dimethyl arginine
gene.set.statistics.description: The process of methylation of peptidyl-arginine to form peptidyl-N(omega),N(omega)-dimethyl-L-arginine.

gene.set.statistics.name: second-messenger-mediated signaling
gene.set.statistics.description: Any intracellular signal transduction in which the signal is passed on within the cell via a second messenger; a small molecule or ion that can be quickly generated or released from intracellular stores, and can diffuse within the cell. Second-messenger signaling includes production or release of the second messenger, and effectors downstream of the second messenger that further transmit the signal within the cell.

gene.set.statistics.name: cAMP-mediated signaling
gene.set.statistics.description: Any intracellular signal transduction in which the signal is passed on within the cell via cyclic AMP (cAMP). Includes production of cAMP, and downstream effectors that further transmit the signal within the cell.

gene.set.statistics.name: cGMP-mediated signaling
gene.set.statistics.description: Any intracellular signal transduction in which the signal is passed on within the cell via cyclic GMP (cGMP). Includes production of cGMP, and downstream effectors that further transmit the signal within the cell.

gene.set.statistics.name: modification-dependent protein catabolic process
gene.set.statistics.description: The chemical reactions and pathways resulting in the breakdown of a protein or peptide by hydrolysis of its peptide bonds, initiated by the covalent modification of the target protein.

gene.set.statistics.name: sexual reproduction
gene.set.statistics.description: A reproduction process that creates a new organism by combining the genetic material of two gametes, which may come from two organisms or from a single organism, in the case of self-fertilizing hermaphrodites, e.g. C. elegans, or self-fertilization in plants. It occurs both in eukaryotes and prokaryotes: in multicellular eukaryotic organisms, an individual is created anew; in prokaryotes, the initial cell has additional or transformed genetic material. In a process called genetic recombination, genetic material (DNA) originating from two gametes join up so that homologous sequences are aligned with each other, and this is followed by exchange of genetic information. After the new recombinant chromosome is formed, it is passed on to progeny.

gene.set.statistics.name: translesion synthesis
gene.set.statistics.description: The replication of damaged DNA by synthesis across a lesion in the template strand; a specialized DNA polymerase or replication complex inserts a defined nucleotide across from the lesion which allows DNA synthesis to continue beyond the lesion. This process can be mutagenic depending on the damaged nucleotide and the inserted nucleotide.

gene.set.statistics.name: spinal cord development
gene.set.statistics.description: The process whose specific outcome is the progression of the spinal cord over time, from its formation to the mature structure. The spinal cord primarily conducts sensory and motor nerve impulses between the brain and the peripheral nervous tissues.

gene.set.statistics.name: spinal cord motor neuron differentiation
gene.set.statistics.description: The process in which neuroepithelial cells in the ventral neural tube acquire specialized structural and/or functional features of motor neurons. Motor neurons innervate an effector (muscle or glandular) tissue and are responsible for transmission of motor impulses from the brain to the periphery. Differentiation includes the processes involved in commitment of a cell to a specific fate.

gene.set.statistics.name: corpus callosum morphogenesis
gene.set.statistics.description: The process in which the anatomical structures of the corpus callosum are generated and organized. The corpus callosum is a thick bundle of nerve fibers comprising a commissural plate connecting the two cerebral hemispheres. It consists of contralateral axon projections that provides communications between the right and left cerebral hemispheres.

gene.set.statistics.name: cerebellum development
gene.set.statistics.description: The process whose specific outcome is the progression of the cerebellum over time, from its formation to the mature structure. The cerebellum is the portion of the brain in the back of the head between the cerebrum and the pons. In mice, the cerebellum controls balance for walking and standing, modulates the force and range of movement and is involved in the learning of motor skills.

gene.set.statistics.name: optic nerve development
gene.set.statistics.description: The process whose specific outcome is the progression of the optic nerve over time, from its formation to the mature structure. The sensory optic nerve originates from the bipolar cells of the retina and conducts visual information to the brainstem. The optic nerve exits the back of the eye in the orbit, enters the optic canal, and enters the central nervous system at the optic chiasm (crossing) where the nerve fibers become the optic tract just prior to entering the hindbrain.

gene.set.statistics.name: lateral ventricle development
gene.set.statistics.description: The process whose specific outcome is the progression of the lateral ventricles over time, from the formation to the mature structure. The two lateral ventricles are a cavity in each of the cerebral hemispheres derived from the cavity of the embryonic neural tube. They are separated from each other by the septum pellucidum, and each communicates with the third ventricle by the foramen of Monro, through which also the choroid plexuses of the lateral ventricles become continuous with that of the third ventricle.

gene.set.statistics.name: cerebellar Purkinje cell layer development
gene.set.statistics.description: The process whose specific outcome is the progression of the cerebellar Purkinje cell layer over time, from its formation to the mature structure. The Purkinje cell layer lies just underneath the molecular layer of the cerebellar cortex. It contains the neuronal cell bodies of the Purkinje cells that are arranged side by side in a single layer. Candelabrum interneurons are vertically oriented between the Purkinje cells. Purkinje neurons are inhibitory and provide the output of the cerebellar cortex through axons that project into the white matter. Extensive dendritic trees from the Purkinje cells extend upward in a single plane into the molecular layer where they synapse with parallel fibers of granule cells.

gene.set.statistics.name: cerebellar Purkinje cell layer morphogenesis
gene.set.statistics.description: The process in which the anatomical structure of the cerebellar Purkinje cell layer is generated and organized. The Purkinje cell layer lies just underneath the molecular layer of the cerebellar cortex. It contains the neuronal cell bodies of the Purkinje cells that are arranged side by side in a single layer. Candelabrum interneurons are vertically oriented between the Purkinje cells. Purkinje neurons are inhibitory and provide the output of the cerebellar cortex through axons that project into the white matter. Extensive dendritic trees from the Purkinje cells extend upward in a single plane into the molecular layer where they synapse with parallel fibers of granule cells.

gene.set.statistics.name: cerebellar cortex development
gene.set.statistics.description: The process whose specific outcome is the progression of the cerebellar cortex over time, from its formation to the mature structure. The cerebellar cortex is a thin mantle of gray matter that covers the surface of each cerebral hemisphere. It has a characteristic morphology with convolutions (gyri) and crevices (sulci) that have specific functions. Six layers of nerve cells and the nerve pathways that connect them comprise the cerebellar cortex. Together, these regions are responsible for the processes of conscious thought, perception, emotion and memory as well as advanced motor function.

gene.set.statistics.name: cerebellar granule cell differentiation
gene.set.statistics.description: The process in which neuroblasts acquire specialized structural and/or functional features that characterize the mature cerebellar granule cell. Differentiation includes the processes involved in commitment of a neuroblast to a granule cell fate. A granule cell is a glutamatergic interneuron found in the cerebellar cortex.

gene.set.statistics.name: striatum development
gene.set.statistics.description: The progression of the striatum over time from its initial formation until its mature state. The striatum is a region of the forebrain consisting of the caudate nucleus, putamen and fundus striati.

gene.set.statistics.name: substantia nigra development
gene.set.statistics.description: The progression of the substantia nigra over time from its initial formation until its mature state. The substantia nigra is the layer of gray substance that separates the posterior parts of the cerebral peduncles (tegmentum mesencephali) from the anterior parts; it normally includes a posterior compact part with many pigmented cells (pars compacta) and an anterior reticular part whose cells contain little pigment (pars reticularis).

gene.set.statistics.name: hippocampus development
gene.set.statistics.description: The progression of the hippocampus over time from its initial formation until its mature state.

gene.set.statistics.name: orbitofrontal cortex development
gene.set.statistics.description: The progression of the orbitofrontal cortex over time from its initial formation until its mature state. The orbitofrontal cortex is a cerebral cortex region located in the frontal lobe.

gene.set.statistics.name: thalamus development
gene.set.statistics.description: The process in which the thalamus changes over time, from its initial formation to its mature state.

gene.set.statistics.name: cerebral cortex cell migration
gene.set.statistics.description: The orderly movement of cells from one site to another in the cerebral cortex.

gene.set.statistics.name: cerebral cortex radial glia guided migration
gene.set.statistics.description: The radial migration of neuronal or glial precursor cells along radial glial cells during the development of the cerebral cortex.

gene.set.statistics.name: nucleokinesis involved in cell motility in cerebral cortex radial glia guided migration
gene.set.statistics.description: The microtubule-mediated movement of the nucleus that is required for the movement of cells along radial glial fibers as a component of the process of cerebral cortex glial-mediated radial cell migration.

gene.set.statistics.name: layer formation in cerebral cortex
gene.set.statistics.description: The detachment of cells from radial glial fibers at the appropriate time when they cease to migrate and form distinct layer in the cerebral cortex.

gene.set.statistics.name: cell proliferation in forebrain
gene.set.statistics.description: The creation of greater cell numbers in the forebrain due to cell division of progenitor cells.

gene.set.statistics.name: hypothalamus development
gene.set.statistics.description: The progression of the hypothalamus region of the forebrain, from its initial formation to its mature state.

gene.set.statistics.name: pyramidal neuron development
gene.set.statistics.description: The progression of a pyramidal neuron from its initial formation to its mature state.

gene.set.statistics.name: cerebral cortex neuron differentiation
gene.set.statistics.description: The process in which a relatively unspecialized cell acquires specialized features of a neuron residing in the cerebral cortex.

gene.set.statistics.name: dorsal/ventral neural tube patterning
gene.set.statistics.description: The process in which the neural tube is regionalized in the dorsoventral axis.

gene.set.statistics.name: neural tube development
gene.set.statistics.description: The process whose specific outcome is the progression of the neural tube over time, from its formation to the mature structure. The mature structure of the neural tube exists when the tube has been segmented into the forebrain, midbrain, hindbrain and spinal cord regions. In addition neural crest has budded away from the epithelium.

gene.set.statistics.name: central nervous system projection neuron axonogenesis
gene.set.statistics.description: Generation of a long process of a CNS neuron, that carries efferent (outgoing) action potentials from the cell body towards target cells in a different central nervous system region.

gene.set.statistics.name: central nervous system neuron development
gene.set.statistics.description: The process whose specific outcome is the progression of a neuron whose cell body is located in the central nervous system, from initial commitment of the cell to a neuronal fate, to the fully functional differentiated neuron.

gene.set.statistics.name: central nervous system neuron axonogenesis
gene.set.statistics.description: Generation of a long process from a neuron whose cell body resides in the central nervous system. The process carries efferent (outgoing) action potentials from the cell body towards target cells.

gene.set.statistics.name: cerebral cortex development
gene.set.statistics.description: The progression of the cerebral cortex over time from its initial formation until its mature state. The cerebral cortex is the outer layered region of the telencephalon.

gene.set.statistics.name: neurogenesis
gene.set.statistics.description: Generation of cells within the nervous system.

gene.set.statistics.name: tangential migration from the subventricular zone to the olfactory bulb
gene.set.statistics.description: The migration of cells in the telencephalon from the subventricular zone to the olfactory bulb in which cells move orthogonally to the direction of radial migration and do not use radial glial cell processes as substrates for migration.

gene.set.statistics.name: regulation of rhodopsin mediated signaling pathway
gene.set.statistics.description: Any process that modulates the frequency, rate or extent of rhodopsin-mediated signaling.

gene.set.statistics.name: negative regulation of cell-cell adhesion
gene.set.statistics.description: Any process that stops, prevents or reduces the rate or extent of cell adhesion to another cell.

gene.set.statistics.name: protein maturation by protein folding
gene.set.statistics.description: The process of assisting in the covalent and noncovalent assembly of single chain polypeptides or multisubunit complexes into the correct tertiary structure that results in the attainment of the full functional capacity of a protein.

gene.set.statistics.name: regulation of cell morphogenesis
gene.set.statistics.description: Any process that modulates the frequency, rate or extent of cell morphogenesis. Cell morphogenesis is the developmental process in which the shape of a cell is generated and organized.

gene.set.statistics.name: gland morphogenesis
gene.set.statistics.description: The process in which the anatomical structures of a gland are generated and organized.

gene.set.statistics.name: membrane to membrane docking
gene.set.statistics.description: The initial attachment of a membrane to a target membrane, mediated by proteins protruding from the two membranes. Docking requires only that the membranes come close enough for the proteins to interact and adhere.

gene.set.statistics.name: protein to membrane docking
gene.set.statistics.description: The initial attachment of a protein to a target membrane, mediated by a proteins protruding from the target membrane. Docking requires only that the proteins come close enough to interact and adhere.

gene.set.statistics.name: extracellular matrix disassembly
gene.set.statistics.description: A process that results in the breakdown of the extracellular matrix.

gene.set.statistics.name: regulation of transmembrane transporter activity
gene.set.statistics.description: Any process that modulates the frequency, rate or extent of transmembrane transporter activity.

gene.set.statistics.name: electron transport chain
gene.set.statistics.description: A process in which a series of electron carriers operate together to transfer electrons from donors to any of several different terminal electron acceptors to generate a transmembrane electrochemical gradient.

gene.set.statistics.name: respiratory electron transport chain
gene.set.statistics.description: A process in which a series of electron carriers operate together to transfer electrons from donors such as NADH and FADH2 to any of several different terminal electron acceptors to generate a transmembrane electrochemical gradient.

gene.set.statistics.name: signal transduction involved in regulation of gene expression
gene.set.statistics.description: Any process that modulates the frequency, rate or extent of gene expression as a consequence of a process in which a signal is released and/or conveyed from one location to another.

gene.set.statistics.name: CD40 signaling pathway
gene.set.statistics.description: A series of molecular signals initiated by the binding of the cell surface receptor CD40 to one of its physiological ligands, and ending with regulation of a downstream cellular process, e.g. transcription.

gene.set.statistics.name: cellular potassium ion homeostasis
gene.set.statistics.description: Any process involved in the maintenance of an internal steady state of potassium ions at the level of a cell.

gene.set.statistics.name: establishment of cell polarity
gene.set.statistics.description: The specification and formation of anisotropic intracellular organization or cell growth patterns.

gene.set.statistics.name: maintenance of cell polarity
gene.set.statistics.description: The maintenance of established anisotropic intracellular organization or cell growth patterns.

gene.set.statistics.name: cell projection organization
gene.set.statistics.description: A process that is carried out at the cellular level which results in the assembly, arrangement of constituent parts, or disassembly of a prolongation or process extending from a cell, e.g. a flagellum or axon.

gene.set.statistics.name: cell projection assembly
gene.set.statistics.description: Formation of a prolongation or process extending from a cell, e.g. a flagellum or axon.

gene.set.statistics.name: lamellipodium assembly
gene.set.statistics.description: Formation of a lamellipodium, a thin sheetlike extension of the surface of a migrating cell.

gene.set.statistics.name: microvillus assembly
gene.set.statistics.description: Formation of a microvillus, a thin cylindrical membrane-covered projection on the surface of a cell.

gene.set.statistics.name: actin cytoskeleton organization
gene.set.statistics.description: A process that is carried out at the cellular level which results in the assembly, arrangement of constituent parts, or disassembly of cytoskeletal structures comprising actin filaments and their associated proteins.

gene.set.statistics.name: actin filament polymerization
gene.set.statistics.description: Assembly of actin filaments by the addition of actin monomers to a filament.

gene.set.statistics.name: actin filament depolymerization
gene.set.statistics.description: Disassembly of actin filaments by the removal of actin monomers from a filament.

gene.set.statistics.name: actin filament fragmentation
gene.set.statistics.description: The severing of actin filaments into numerous short fragments, usually mediated by actin severing proteins.

gene.set.statistics.name: actin filament-based movement
gene.set.statistics.description: Movement of organelles or other particles along actin filaments, or sliding of actin filaments past each other, mediated by motor proteins.

gene.set.statistics.name: muscle filament sliding
gene.set.statistics.description: The sliding of actin thin filaments and myosin thick filaments past each other in muscle contraction. This involves a process of interaction of myosin located on a thick filament with actin located on a thin filament. During this process ATP is split and forces are generated.

gene.set.statistics.name: vesicle transport along actin filament
gene.set.statistics.description: Movement of a vesicle along an actin filament, mediated by motor proteins.

gene.set.statistics.name: insulin secretion
gene.set.statistics.description: The regulated release of proinsulin from secretory granules accompanied by cleavage of proinsulin to form mature insulin. In vertebrates, insulin is secreted from B granules in the B cells of the vertebrate pancreas and from insulin-producing cells in insects.

gene.set.statistics.name: protein repair
gene.set.statistics.description: The process of restoring a protein to its original state after damage by such things as oxidation or spontaneous decomposition of residues.

gene.set.statistics.name: hemopoiesis
gene.set.statistics.description: The process whose specific outcome is the progression of the myeloid and lymphoid derived organ/tissue systems of the blood and other parts of the body over time, from formation to the mature structure. The site of hemopoiesis is variable during development, but occurs primarily in bone marrow or kidney in many adult vertebrates.

gene.set.statistics.name: myeloid cell differentiation
gene.set.statistics.description: The process in which a relatively unspecialized myeloid precursor cell acquires the specialized features of any cell of the myeloid leukocyte, megakaryocyte, thrombocyte, or erythrocyte lineages.

gene.set.statistics.name: regulation of endocytosis
gene.set.statistics.description: Any process that modulates the frequency, rate or extent of endocytosis.

gene.set.statistics.name: natural killer cell activation
gene.set.statistics.description: The change in morphology and behavior of a natural killer cell in response to a cytokine, chemokine, cellular ligand, or soluble factor.

gene.set.statistics.name: regulation of Wnt signaling pathway
gene.set.statistics.description: Any process that modulates the frequency, rate or extent of the activity of the Wnt signal transduction pathway.

gene.set.statistics.name: sphingolipid biosynthetic process
gene.set.statistics.description: The chemical reactions and pathways resulting in the formation of sphingolipids, any of a class of lipids containing the long-chain amine diol sphingosine or a closely related base (a sphingoid).

gene.set.statistics.name: sphingolipid catabolic process
gene.set.statistics.description: The chemical reactions and pathways resulting in the breakdown of sphingolipids, any of a class of lipids containing the long-chain amine diol sphingosine or a closely related base (a sphingoid).

gene.set.statistics.name: protein import into mitochondrial matrix
gene.set.statistics.description: The import of proteins across the outer and inner mitochondrial membranes into the matrix. Unfolded proteins enter the mitochondrial matrix with a chaperone protein; the information required to target the precursor protein from the cytosol to the mitochondrial matrix is contained within its N-terminal matrix-targeting sequence. Translocation of precursors to the matrix occurs at the rare sites where the outer and inner membranes are close together.

gene.set.statistics.name: cell differentiation
gene.set.statistics.description: The process in which relatively unspecialized cells, e.g. embryonic or regenerative cells, acquire specialized structural and/or functional features that characterize the cells, tissues, or organs of the mature organism or some other relatively stable phase of the organism's life history. Differentiation includes the processes involved in commitment of a cell to a specific fate and its subsequent development to the mature state.

gene.set.statistics.name: regulation of cell adhesion
gene.set.statistics.description: Any process that modulates the frequency, rate or extent of attachment of a cell to another cell or to the extracellular matrix.

gene.set.statistics.name: pancreatic juice secretion
gene.set.statistics.description: The regulated release of pancreatic juice by the exocrine pancreas into the upper part of the intestine. Pancreatic juice is slightly alkaline and contains numerous enzymes and inactive enzyme precursors including alpha-amylase, chymotrypsinogen, lipase, procarboxypeptidase, proelastase, prophospholipase A2, ribonuclease, and trypsinogen. Its high concentration of bicarbonate ions helps to neutralize the acid from the stomach.

gene.set.statistics.name: regulation of proteolysis
gene.set.statistics.description: Any process that modulates the frequency, rate or extent of the hydrolysis of a peptide bond or bonds within a protein.

gene.set.statistics.name: protein catabolic process
gene.set.statistics.description: The chemical reactions and pathways resulting in the breakdown of a protein by the destruction of the native, active configuration, with or without the hydrolysis of peptide bonds.

gene.set.statistics.name: platelet activation
gene.set.statistics.description: A series of progressive, overlapping events triggered by exposure of the platelets to subendothelial tissue. These events include shape change, adhesiveness, aggregation, and release reactions. When carried through to completion, these events lead to the formation of a stable hemostatic plug.

gene.set.statistics.name: regulation of DNA-dependent DNA replication initiation
gene.set.statistics.description: Any process that modulates the frequency, rate or extent of initiation of DNA-dependent DNA replication; the process in which DNA becomes competent to replicate. In eukaryotes, replication competence is established in early G1 and lost during the ensuing S phase.

gene.set.statistics.name: positive regulation of Wnt signaling pathway
gene.set.statistics.description: Any process that activates or increases the frequency, rate or extent of Wnt signal transduction.

gene.set.statistics.name: negative regulation of Wnt signaling pathway
gene.set.statistics.description: Any process that stops, prevents, or reduces the frequency, rate or extent of the Wnt signaling pathway.

gene.set.statistics.name: neuron differentiation
gene.set.statistics.description: The process in which a relatively unspecialized cell acquires specialized features of a neuron.

gene.set.statistics.name: B cell differentiation
gene.set.statistics.description: The process in which a precursor cell type acquires the specialized features of a B cell. A B cell is a lymphocyte of B lineage with the phenotype CD19-positive and capable of B cell mediated immunity.

gene.set.statistics.name: nitric oxide transport
gene.set.statistics.description: The directed movement of nitric oxide, nitrogen monoxide, into, out of or within a cell, or between cells, by means of some agent such as a transporter or pore.

gene.set.statistics.name: regulation of blood coagulation
gene.set.statistics.description: Any process that modulates the frequency, rate or extent of blood coagulation.

gene.set.statistics.name: positive regulation of blood coagulation
gene.set.statistics.description: Any process that activates or increases the frequency, rate or extent of blood coagulation.

gene.set.statistics.name: extracellular matrix organization
gene.set.statistics.description: A process that is carried out at the cellular level which results in the assembly, arrangement of constituent parts, or disassembly of an extracellular matrix.

gene.set.statistics.name: collagen fibril organization
gene.set.statistics.description: Any process that determines the size and arrangement of collagen fibrils within an extracellular matrix.

gene.set.statistics.name: heparan sulfate proteoglycan catabolic process
gene.set.statistics.description: The chemical reactions and pathways resulting in the breakdown of proteoglycan containing heparan sulfate, any member of a group of glycosaminoglycans that have repeat units consisting of alternating alpha-(1->4) linked hexuronic acid and glucosamine residues, the former being a mixture of sulfated and nonsulfated D-glucuronic and L-iduronic acids, and the latter being either sulfated or acetylated on its amino group as well as sulfated on one of its hydroxyl groups.

gene.set.statistics.name: chondroitin sulfate biosynthetic process
gene.set.statistics.description: The chemical reactions and pathways resulting in the formation of chondroitin sulfate, any member of a group of 10-60 kDa glycosaminoglycans, widely distributed in cartilage and other mammalian connective tissues, the repeat units of which consist of beta-(1,4)-linked D-glucuronyl beta-(1,3)-N-acetyl-D-galactosamine sulfate.

gene.set.statistics.name: keratinocyte differentiation
gene.set.statistics.description: The process in which a relatively unspecialized cell acquires specialized features of a keratinocyte.

gene.set.statistics.name: T cell differentiation
gene.set.statistics.description: The process in which a precursor cell type acquires characteristics of a more mature T-cell. A T cell is a type of lymphocyte whose definin characteristic is the expression of a T cell receptor complex.

gene.set.statistics.name: erythrocyte differentiation
gene.set.statistics.description: The process in which a myeloid precursor cell acquires specializes features of an erythrocyte.

gene.set.statistics.name: platelet formation
gene.set.statistics.description: The process in which platelets bud from long processes extended by megakaryocytes.

gene.set.statistics.name: neutrophil differentiation
gene.set.statistics.description: The process in which a myeloid precursor cell acquires the specialized features of a neutrophil.

gene.set.statistics.name: monocyte differentiation
gene.set.statistics.description: The process in which a relatively unspecialized myeloid precursor cell acquires the specialized features of a monocyte.

gene.set.statistics.name: macrophage differentiation
gene.set.statistics.description: The process in which a relatively unspecialized monocyte acquires the specialized features of a macrophage.

gene.set.statistics.name: male sex determination
gene.set.statistics.description: The specification of male sex of an individual organism.

gene.set.statistics.name: myofibril assembly
gene.set.statistics.description: Formation of myofibrils, the repeating units of striated muscle.

gene.set.statistics.name: skeletal muscle thin filament assembly
gene.set.statistics.description: The aggregation, arrangement and bonding together of proteins to form the actin-based thin filaments of myofibrils in skeletal muscle.

gene.set.statistics.name: autophagy of peroxisome
gene.set.statistics.description: The process in which peroxisomes are delivered to a type of vacuole and degraded in response to changing nutrient conditions.

gene.set.statistics.name: growth hormone secretion
gene.set.statistics.description: The regulated release of growth hormone from secretory granules into the blood.

gene.set.statistics.name: chromosome condensation
gene.set.statistics.description: The progressive compaction of dispersed interphase chromatin into threadlike chromosomes prior to mitotic or meiotic nuclear division, or during apoptosis, in eukaryotic cells.

gene.set.statistics.name: apoptotic chromosome condensation
gene.set.statistics.description: The compaction of chromatin during apoptosis.

gene.set.statistics.name: maintenance of gastrointestinal epithelium
gene.set.statistics.description: Protection of epithelial surfaces of the gastrointestinal tract from proteolytic and caustic digestive agents.

gene.set.statistics.name: bone mineralization
gene.set.statistics.description: The deposition of hydroxyapatite, a form of calcium phosphate with the formula Ca10(PO4)6(OH)2, in bone tissue.

gene.set.statistics.name: intestinal cholesterol absorption
gene.set.statistics.description: Uptake of cholesterol into the blood by absorption from the small intestine.

gene.set.statistics.name: cholesterol transport
gene.set.statistics.description: The directed movement of cholesterol, cholest-5-en-3-beta-ol, into, out of or within a cell, or between cells, by means of some agent such as a transporter or pore.

gene.set.statistics.name: positive regulation of cell growth
gene.set.statistics.description: Any process that activates or increases the frequency, rate, extent or direction of cell growth.

gene.set.statistics.name: negative regulation of cell growth
gene.set.statistics.description: Any process that stops, prevents, or reduces the frequency, rate, extent or direction of cell growth.

gene.set.statistics.name: osteoclast differentiation
gene.set.statistics.description: The process in which a relatively unspecialized monocyte acquires the specialized features of an osteoclast. An osteoclast is a specialized phagocytic cell associated with the absorption and removal of the mineralized matrix of bone tissue.

gene.set.statistics.name: flagellated sperm motility
gene.set.statistics.description: The directed, self-propelled movement of a cilium (aka flagellum) that contributes to the movement of a flagellated sperm.

gene.set.statistics.name: lung development
gene.set.statistics.description: The process whose specific outcome is the progression of the lung over time, from its formation to the mature structure. In all air-breathing vertebrates the lungs are developed from the ventral wall of the oesophagus as a pouch which divides into two sacs. In amphibians and many reptiles the lungs retain very nearly this primitive sac-like character, but in the higher forms the connection with the esophagus becomes elongated into the windpipe and the inner walls of the sacs become more and more divided, until, in the mammals, the air spaces become minutely divided into tubes ending in small air cells, in the walls of which the blood circulates in a fine network of capillaries. In mammals the lungs are more or less divided into lobes, and each lung occupies a separate cavity in the thorax.

gene.set.statistics.name: embryonic limb morphogenesis
gene.set.statistics.description: The process, occurring in the embryo, by which the anatomical structures of the limb are generated and organized. A limb is an appendage of an animal used for locomotion or grasping.

gene.set.statistics.name: DNA damage response, signal transduction by p53 class mediator
gene.set.statistics.description: A cascade of processes induced by the cell cycle regulator phosphoprotein p53, or an equivalent protein, in response to the detection of DNA damage.

gene.set.statistics.name: regulation of cell migration
gene.set.statistics.description: Any process that modulates the frequency, rate or extent of cell migration.

gene.set.statistics.name: positive regulation of cell migration
gene.set.statistics.description: Any process that activates or increases the frequency, rate or extent of cell migration.

gene.set.statistics.name: negative regulation of cell migration
gene.set.statistics.description: Any process that stops, prevents, or reduces the frequency, rate or extent of cell migration.

gene.set.statistics.name: fructose 1,6-bisphosphate metabolic process
gene.set.statistics.description: The chemical reactions and pathways involving fructose 1,6-bisphosphate, also known as FBP. The D enantiomer is a metabolic intermediate in glycolysis and gluconeogenesis.

gene.set.statistics.name: production of siRNA involved in RNA interference
gene.set.statistics.description: Cleavage of double-stranded RNA to form small interfering RNA molecules (siRNAs) of 21-23 nucleotides, in the context of RNA interference.

gene.set.statistics.name: targeting of mRNA for destruction involved in RNA interference
gene.set.statistics.description: The process in which small interfering RNAs target cognate mRNA molecules for degradation.

gene.set.statistics.name: sleep
gene.set.statistics.description: Any process in which an organism enters and maintains a periodic, readily reversible state of reduced awareness and metabolic activity. Usually accompanied by physical relaxation, the onset of sleep in humans and other mammals is marked by a change in the electrical activity of the brain.

gene.set.statistics.name: ubiquitin-dependent ERAD pathway
gene.set.statistics.description: The series of steps necessary to target endoplasmic reticulum (ER)-resident proteins for degradation by the cytoplasmic proteasome. Begins with recognition of the ER-resident protein, includes retrotranslocation (dislocation) of the protein from the ER to the cytosol, protein ubiquitination necessary for correct substrate transfer, transport of the protein to the proteasome, and ends with degradation of the protein by the cytoplasmic proteasome.

gene.set.statistics.name: regulation of complement activation
gene.set.statistics.description: Any process that modulates the frequency, rate or extent of complement activation.

gene.set.statistics.name: tRNA methylation
gene.set.statistics.description: The posttranscriptional addition of methyl groups to specific residues in a tRNA molecule.

gene.set.statistics.name: maturation of SSU-rRNA
gene.set.statistics.description: Any process involved in the maturation of a precursor Small SubUnit (SSU) ribosomal RNA (rRNA) molecule into a mature SSU-rRNA molecule.

gene.set.statistics.name: fatty acid elongation
gene.set.statistics.description: The elongation of a fatty acid chain by the sequential addition of two-carbon units.

gene.set.statistics.name: positive regulation of bone mineralization
gene.set.statistics.description: Any process that activates or increases the frequency, rate or extent of bone mineralization.

gene.set.statistics.name: BMP signaling pathway
gene.set.statistics.description: A series of molecular signals initiated by the binding of a member of the BMP (bone morphogenetic protein) family to a receptor on the surface of a target cell, and ending with regulation of a downstream cellular process, e.g. transcription.

gene.set.statistics.name: positive regulation of transforming growth factor beta receptor signaling pathway
gene.set.statistics.description: Any process that activates or increases the frequency, rate or extent of TGF-beta receptor signaling pathway activity.

gene.set.statistics.name: negative regulation of transforming growth factor beta receptor signaling pathway
gene.set.statistics.description: Any process that stops, prevents, or reduces the frequency, rate or extent of any TGF-beta receptor signaling pathway.

gene.set.statistics.name: positive regulation of BMP signaling pathway
gene.set.statistics.description: Any process that activates or increases the frequency, rate or extent of BMP signaling pathway activity.

gene.set.statistics.name: regulation of axon extension
gene.set.statistics.description: Any process that modulates the rate, direction or extent of axon extension.

gene.set.statistics.name: negative regulation of axon extension
gene.set.statistics.description: Any process that stops, prevents, or reduces the frequency, rate or extent of axon outgrowth.

gene.set.statistics.name: intracellular estrogen receptor signaling pathway
gene.set.statistics.description: Any series of molecular signals generated as a consequence of an intracellular estrogen receptor binding to one of its physiological ligands. The pathway begins with receptor-ligand binding, and ends with regulation of a downstream cellular process (e.g. transcription).

gene.set.statistics.name: androgen receptor signaling pathway
gene.set.statistics.description: Any series of molecular signals generated as a consequence of an androgen binding to its receptor.

gene.set.statistics.name: intracellular receptor signaling pathway
gene.set.statistics.description: Any series of molecular signals initiated by a ligand binding to an receptor located within a cell.

gene.set.statistics.name: male genitalia development
gene.set.statistics.description: The process whose specific outcome is the progression of the male genitalia over time, from its formation to the mature structure.

gene.set.statistics.name: collagen catabolic process
gene.set.statistics.description: The proteolytic chemical reactions and pathways resulting in the breakdown of collagen in the extracellular matrix, usually carried out by proteases secreted by nearby cells.

gene.set.statistics.name: PML body organization
gene.set.statistics.description: A process that is carried out at the cellular level which results in the assembly, arrangement of constituent parts, or disassembly of PML bodies, a class of nuclear body; they react against SP100 auto-antibodies (PML = promyelocytic leukemia).

gene.set.statistics.name: neutrophil chemotaxis
gene.set.statistics.description: The directed movement of a neutrophil cell, the most numerous polymorphonuclear leukocyte found in the blood, in response to an external stimulus, usually an infection or wounding.

gene.set.statistics.name: leukocyte chemotaxis
gene.set.statistics.description: The movement of a leukocyte in response to an external stimulus.

gene.set.statistics.name: cellular chloride ion homeostasis
gene.set.statistics.description: Any process involved in the maintenance of an internal steady state of chloride ions at the level of a cell.

gene.set.statistics.name: cytoskeleton-dependent intracellular transport
gene.set.statistics.description: The directed movement of substances along cytoskeletal fibers such as microfilaments or microtubules within a cell.

gene.set.statistics.name: regulation of actin filament polymerization
gene.set.statistics.description: Any process that modulates the frequency, rate or extent of the assembly of actin filaments by the addition of actin monomers to a filament.

gene.set.statistics.name: positive regulation of actin filament depolymerization
gene.set.statistics.description: Any process that activates or increases the frequency, rate or extent of actin depolymerization.

gene.set.statistics.name: negative regulation of actin filament polymerization
gene.set.statistics.description: Any process that stops, prevents, or reduces the frequency, rate or extent of actin polymerization.

gene.set.statistics.name: positive regulation of actin filament polymerization
gene.set.statistics.description: Any process that activates or increases the frequency, rate or extent of actin polymerization.

gene.set.statistics.name: prostate gland development
gene.set.statistics.description: The process whose specific outcome is the progression of the prostate gland over time, from its formation to the mature structure. The prostate gland is a partly muscular, partly glandular body that is situated near the base of the mammalian male urethra and secretes an alkaline viscid fluid which is a major constituent of the ejaculatory fluid.

gene.set.statistics.name: granulocyte differentiation
gene.set.statistics.description: The process in which a myeloid precursor cell acquires the specialized features of a granulocyte. Granulocytes are a class of leukocytes characterized by the presence of granules in their cytoplasm. These cells are active in allergic immune reactions such as arthritic inflammation and rashes. This class includes basophils, eosinophils and neutrophils.

gene.set.statistics.name: epithelial cell differentiation
gene.set.statistics.description: The process in which a relatively unspecialized cell acquires specialized features of an epithelial cell, any of the cells making up an epithelium.

gene.set.statistics.name: negative regulation of epithelial cell differentiation
gene.set.statistics.description: Any process that stops, prevents, or reduces the frequency, rate or extent of epithelial cell differentiation.

gene.set.statistics.name: cortical cytoskeleton organization
gene.set.statistics.description: A process that is carried out at the cellular level which results in the assembly, arrangement of constituent parts, or disassembly of cytoskeletal structures in the cell cortex, i.e. just beneath the plasma membrane.

gene.set.statistics.name: cortical actin cytoskeleton organization
gene.set.statistics.description: A process that is carried out at the cellular level which results in the assembly, arrangement of constituent parts, or disassembly of actin-based cytoskeletal structures in the cell cortex, i.e. just beneath the plasma membrane.

gene.set.statistics.name: thyroid gland development
gene.set.statistics.description: The process whose specific outcome is the progression of the thyroid gland over time, from its formation to the mature structure. The thyroid gland is an endoderm-derived gland that produces thyroid hormone.

gene.set.statistics.name: mammary gland development
gene.set.statistics.description: The process whose specific outcome is the progression of the mammary gland over time, from its formation to the mature structure. The mammary gland is a large compound sebaceous gland that in female mammals is modified to secrete milk. Its development starts with the formation of the mammary line and ends as the mature gland cycles between nursing and weaning stages.

gene.set.statistics.name: positive regulation of B cell proliferation
gene.set.statistics.description: Any process that activates or increases the rate or extent of B cell proliferation.

gene.set.statistics.name: forebrain development
gene.set.statistics.description: The process whose specific outcome is the progression of the forebrain over time, from its formation to the mature structure. The forebrain is the anterior of the three primary divisions of the developing chordate brain or the corresponding part of the adult brain (in vertebrates, includes especially the cerebral hemispheres, the thalamus, and the hypothalamus and especially in higher vertebrates is the main control center for sensory and associative information processing, visceral functions, and voluntary motor functions).

gene.set.statistics.name: midbrain development
gene.set.statistics.description: The process whose specific outcome is the progression of the midbrain over time, from its formation to the mature structure. The midbrain is the middle division of the three primary divisions of the developing chordate brain or the corresponding part of the adult brain (in vertebrates, includes a ventral part containing the cerebral peduncles and a dorsal tectum containing the corpora quadrigemina and that surrounds the aqueduct of Sylvius connecting the third and fourth ventricles).

gene.set.statistics.name: notochord development
gene.set.statistics.description: The process whose specific outcome is the progression of the notochord over time, from its formation to the mature structure. The notochord is a mesoderm-derived structure located ventral of the developing nerve cord. In vertebrates, the notochord serves as a core around which other mesodermal cells form the vertebrae. In the most primitive chordates, which lack vertebrae, the notochord persists as a substitute for a vertebral column.

gene.set.statistics.name: negative regulation of vascular endothelial growth factor receptor signaling pathway
gene.set.statistics.description: Any process that stops, prevents, or reduces the frequency, rate or extent of vascular endothelial growth factor receptor signaling pathway activity.

gene.set.statistics.name: positive regulation of vascular endothelial growth factor receptor signaling pathway
gene.set.statistics.description: Any process that activates or increases the frequency, rate or extent of vascular endothelial growth factor receptor signaling pathway activity.

gene.set.statistics.name: establishment or maintenance of actin cytoskeleton polarity
gene.set.statistics.description: Any cellular process that results in the specification, formation or maintenance of polarized actin-based cytoskeletal structures.

gene.set.statistics.name: establishment or maintenance of microtubule cytoskeleton polarity
gene.set.statistics.description: Any cellular process that results in the specification, formation or maintenance of polarized microtubule-based cytoskeletal structures.

gene.set.statistics.name: astral microtubule organization
gene.set.statistics.description: A process that is carried out at the cellular level which results in the assembly, arrangement of constituent parts, or disassembly of astral microtubules, any of the spindle microtubules that radiate in all directions from the spindle poles.

gene.set.statistics.name: endoplasmic reticulum unfolded protein response
gene.set.statistics.description: The series of molecular signals generated as a consequence of the presence of unfolded proteins in the endoplasmic reticulum (ER) or other ER-related stress; results in changes in the regulation of transcription and translation.

gene.set.statistics.name: retrograde protein transport, ER to cytosol
gene.set.statistics.description: The directed movement of unfolded or misfolded proteins from the endoplasmic reticulum to the cytosol through the translocon.

gene.set.statistics.name: response to caffeine
gene.set.statistics.description: Any process that results in a change in state or activity of a cell or an organism (in terms of movement, secretion, enzyme production, gene expression, etc.) as a result of a caffeine stimulus. Caffeine is an alkaloid found in numerous plant species, where it acts as a natural pesticide that paralyzes and kills certain insects feeding upon them.

gene.set.statistics.name: pancreas development
gene.set.statistics.description: The process whose specific outcome is the progression of the pancreas over time, from its formation to the mature structure. The pancreas is an endoderm derived structure that produces precursors of digestive enzymes and blood glucose regulating enzymes.

gene.set.statistics.name: endocrine pancreas development
gene.set.statistics.description: The process whose specific outcome is the progression of the endocrine pancreas over time, from its formation to the mature structure. The endocrine pancreas is made up of islet cells that produce insulin, glucagon and somatostatin.
