gene.set.statistics.description: The morphogenetic process that results in flattening of a cell as a consequence of its adhesion to a substrate.

gene.set.statistics.name: microtubule anchoring
gene.set.statistics.description: Any process in which a microtubule is maintained in a specific location in a cell.

gene.set.statistics.name: microtubule anchoring at centrosome
gene.set.statistics.description: Any process in which a microtubule is maintained in a specific location in a cell by attachment to a centrosome.

gene.set.statistics.name: small-subunit processome assembly
gene.set.statistics.description: The aggregation, arrangement and bonding together of proteins and RNA molecules to form a small-subunit processome.

gene.set.statistics.name: snRNA 3'-end processing
gene.set.statistics.description: Any process involved in forming the mature 3' end of an snRNA molecule.

gene.set.statistics.name: U4 snRNA 3'-end processing
gene.set.statistics.description: Any process involved in forming the mature 3' end of a U4 snRNA molecule.

gene.set.statistics.name: early endosome to Golgi transport
gene.set.statistics.description: The directed movement of substances from early endosomes to the Golgi.

gene.set.statistics.name: protein localization to kinetochore
gene.set.statistics.description: Any process in which a protein is transported to, or maintained at, the kinetochore.

gene.set.statistics.name: protein localization to nucleus
gene.set.statistics.description: A process in which a protein transports or maintains the localization of another protein to the nucleus.

gene.set.statistics.name: tooth mineralization
gene.set.statistics.description: The process in which calcium salts are deposited into calcareous tooth structures such as dental enamel, dentin and cementum.

gene.set.statistics.name: mitochondrial unfolded protein response
gene.set.statistics.description: The series of molecular signals generated as a consequence of the presence of unfolded proteins in the mitochondrial matrix; results in transcriptional upregulation of nuclear genes encoding mitochondrial stress proteins.

gene.set.statistics.name: mitochondrial respiratory chain complex III assembly
gene.set.statistics.description: The aggregation, arrangement and bonding together of a set of components to form the cytochrome bc(1) complex (also known as ubiquinol-cytochrome c reductase), in the mitochondrial inner membrane.

gene.set.statistics.name: cellular response to oxidative stress
gene.set.statistics.description: Any process that results in a change in state or activity of a cell (in terms of movement, secretion, enzyme production, gene expression, etc.) as a result of oxidative stress, a state often resulting from exposure to high levels of reactive oxygen species, e.g. superoxide anions, hydrogen peroxide (H2O2), and hydroxyl radicals.

gene.set.statistics.name: cellular response to heat
gene.set.statistics.description: Any process that results in a change in state or activity of a cell (in terms of movement, secretion, enzyme production, gene expression, etc.) as a result of a heat stimulus, a temperature stimulus above the optimal temperature for that organism.

gene.set.statistics.name: cellular protein localization
gene.set.statistics.description: Any process in which a protein is transported to, and/or maintained in, a specific location at the level of a cell. Localization at the cellular level encompasses movement within the cell, from within the cell to the cell surface, or from one location to another at the surface of a cell.

gene.set.statistics.name: cellular response to reactive oxygen species
gene.set.statistics.description: Any process that results in a change in state or activity of a cell (in terms of movement, secretion, enzyme production, gene expression, etc.) as a result of a reactive oxygen species stimulus. Reactive oxygen species include singlet oxygen, superoxide, and oxygen free radicals.

gene.set.statistics.name: cellular response to unfolded protein
gene.set.statistics.description: Any process that results in a change in state or activity of a cell (in terms of movement, secretion, enzyme production, gene expression, etc.) as a result of an unfolded protein stimulus.

gene.set.statistics.name: cellular protein-containing complex assembly
gene.set.statistics.description: The aggregation, arrangement and bonding together of a set of components to form a protein complex, occurring at the level of an individual cell.

gene.set.statistics.name: cellular protein-containing complex localization
gene.set.statistics.description: A protein complex localization process that takes place at the cellular level; as a result, a protein complex is transported to, or maintained in, a specific location within a cell.

gene.set.statistics.name: glutathione transport
gene.set.statistics.description: The directed movement of glutathione, the tripeptide glutamylcysteinylglycine, into, out of or within a cell, or between cells, by means of some agent such as a transporter or pore.

gene.set.statistics.name: cellular response to UV
gene.set.statistics.description: Any process that results in a change in state or activity of a cell (in terms of movement, secretion, enzyme production, gene expression, etc.) as a result of an ultraviolet radiation (UV light) stimulus. Ultraviolet radiation is electromagnetic radiation with a wavelength in the range of 10 to 380 nanometers.

gene.set.statistics.name: cellular macromolecule biosynthetic process
gene.set.statistics.description: The chemical reactions and pathways resulting in the formation of a macromolecule, any molecule of high relative molecular mass, the structure of which essentially comprises the multiple repetition of units derived, actually or conceptually, from molecules of low relative molecular mass, carried out by individual cells.

gene.set.statistics.name: regulation of ion transmembrane transport
gene.set.statistics.description: Any process that modulates the frequency, rate or extent of the directed movement of ions from one side of a membrane to the other.

gene.set.statistics.name: negative regulation of ion transmembrane transport
gene.set.statistics.description: Any process that stops, prevents, or reduces the frequency, rate or extent of the directed movement of ions from one side of a membrane to the other.

gene.set.statistics.name: positive regulation of ion transmembrane transport
gene.set.statistics.description: Any process that activates or increases the frequency, rate or extent of the directed movement of ions from one side of a membrane to the other.

gene.set.statistics.name: histone lysine methylation
gene.set.statistics.description: The modification of a histone by addition of one or more methyl groups to a lysine residue.

gene.set.statistics.name: histone arginine methylation
gene.set.statistics.description: The modification of a histone by addition of a methyl group to an arginine residue.

gene.set.statistics.name: protein folding in endoplasmic reticulum
gene.set.statistics.description: A protein folding process that takes place in the endoplasmic reticulum (ER). Secreted, plasma membrane and organelle proteins are folded in the ER, assisted by chaperones and foldases (protein disulphide isomerases), and additional factors required for optimal folding (ATP, Ca2+ and an oxidizing environment to allow disulfide bond formation).

gene.set.statistics.name: response to endoplasmic reticulum stress
gene.set.statistics.description: Any process that results in a change in state or activity of a cell (in terms of movement, secretion, enzyme production, gene expression, etc.) as a result of a stress acting at the endoplasmic reticulum. ER stress usually results from the accumulation of unfolded or misfolded proteins in the ER lumen.

gene.set.statistics.name: mitochondrial protein processing
gene.set.statistics.description: The peptide cleavage of mitochondrial proteins, including cleavage contributing to their import.

gene.set.statistics.name: somatic stem cell population maintenance
gene.set.statistics.description: Any process by which an organism retains a population of somatic stem cells, undifferentiated cells in the embryo or adult which can undergo unlimited division and give rise to cell types of the body other than those of the germ-line.

gene.set.statistics.name: regulation of Rac protein signal transduction
gene.set.statistics.description: Any process that modulates the frequency, rate or extent of Rac protein signal transduction.

gene.set.statistics.name: positive regulation of Rac protein signal transduction
gene.set.statistics.description: Any process that activates or increases the frequency, rate or extent of Rac protein signal transduction.

gene.set.statistics.name: regulation of Rho protein signal transduction
gene.set.statistics.description: Any process that modulates the frequency, rate or extent of Rho protein signal transduction.

gene.set.statistics.name: negative regulation of Rho protein signal transduction
gene.set.statistics.description: Any process that stops, prevents, or reduces the frequency, rate or extent of Rho protein signal transduction.

gene.set.statistics.name: positive regulation of Rho protein signal transduction
gene.set.statistics.description: Any process that activates or increases the frequency, rate or extent of Rho protein signal transduction.

gene.set.statistics.name: regulation of histone acetylation
gene.set.statistics.description: Any process that modulates the frequency, rate or extent of the addition of an acetyl group to a histone protein.

gene.set.statistics.name: positive regulation of histone acetylation
gene.set.statistics.description: Any process that activates or increases the frequency, rate or extent of the addition of an acetyl group to a histone protein.

gene.set.statistics.name: negative regulation of histone acetylation
gene.set.statistics.description: Any process that stops, prevents, or reduces the frequency, rate or extent of the addition of an acetyl group to a histone protein.

gene.set.statistics.name: establishment of apical/basal cell polarity
gene.set.statistics.description: The specification and formation of the polarity of a cell along its apical/basal axis.

gene.set.statistics.name: response to nicotine
gene.set.statistics.description: Any process that results in a change in state or activity of a cell or an organism (in terms of movement, secretion, enzyme production, gene expression, etc.) as a result of a nicotine stimulus.

gene.set.statistics.name: embryonic forelimb morphogenesis
gene.set.statistics.description: The process, occurring in the embryo, by which the anatomical structures of the forelimb are generated and organized. The forelimbs are the front limbs of an animal, e.g. the arms of a human.

gene.set.statistics.name: tube formation
gene.set.statistics.description: Creation of the central hole of a tube in an anatomical structure through which gases and/or liquids flow.

gene.set.statistics.name: post-embryonic hemopoiesis
gene.set.statistics.description: The stages of blood cell formation that take place after completion of embryonic development.

gene.set.statistics.name: social behavior
gene.set.statistics.description: Behavior directed towards society, or taking place between members of the same species. Occurs predominantly, or only, in individuals that are part of a group.

gene.set.statistics.name: gene silencing by miRNA
gene.set.statistics.description: Downregulation of gene expression through the action of microRNAs (miRNAs), endogenous 21-24 nucleotide small RNAs processed from stem-loop RNA precursors (pre-miRNAs). Once incorporated into a RNA-induced silencing complex (RISC), miRNAs can downregulate gene expression by either of two posttranscriptional mechanisms: endolytic cleavage of the RNA (often mRNA) or mRNA translational repression, usually accompanied by poly-A tail shortening and subsequent degradation of the mRNA.

gene.set.statistics.name: ectopic germ cell programmed cell death
gene.set.statistics.description: Programmed cell death of an errant germ line cell that is outside the normal migratory path or ectopic to the gonad. This is an important mechanism of regulating germ cell survival within the embryo.

gene.set.statistics.name: synaptic transmission, glutamatergic
gene.set.statistics.description: The vesicular release of glutamate from a presynapse, across a chemical synapse, the subsequent activation of glutamate receptors at the postsynapse of a target cell (neuron, muscle, or secretory cell) and the effects of this activation on the postsynaptic membrane potential and ionic composition of the postsynaptic cytosol. This process encompasses both spontaneous and evoked release of neurotransmitter and all parts of synaptic vesicle exocytosis. Evoked transmission starts with the arrival of an action potential at the presynapse.

gene.set.statistics.name: multicellular organism growth
gene.set.statistics.description: The increase in size or mass of an entire multicellular organism, as opposed to cell growth.

gene.set.statistics.name: organ growth
gene.set.statistics.description: The increase in size or mass of an organ. Organs are commonly observed as visibly distinct structures, but may also exist as loosely associated clusters of cells that function together as to perform a specific function.

gene.set.statistics.name: miRNA mediated inhibition of translation
gene.set.statistics.description: The process in which microRNAs (miRNAs) block the translation of target mRNAs into proteins. Once incorporated into a RNA-induced silencing complex (RISC), a miRNA will typically mediate repression of translation if the miRNA imperfectly base-pairs with the 3' untranslated regions of target mRNAs.

gene.set.statistics.name: miRNA loading onto RISC involved in gene silencing by miRNA
gene.set.statistics.description: The transfer of a microRNA (miRNA) strand from a miRNA:miRNA duplex onto the RNA-initiated silencing complex (RISC).

gene.set.statistics.name: pre-miRNA export from nucleus
gene.set.statistics.description: Transport of pre-microRNAs (pre-miRNAs) from the nucleus to the cytoplasm. Pre-miRNAs are a ~60-70 nucleotide stem loop intermediate in miRNA production, produced by the nuclear cleavage of a primary miRNA (pri-mRNA) transcript. Pre-miRNAs are transported from the nucleus to the cytoplasm where further cleavage occurs to produce a mature miRNA product.

gene.set.statistics.name: positive regulation of protein dephosphorylation
gene.set.statistics.description: Any process that activates or increases the frequency, rate or extent of removal of phosphate groups from a protein.

gene.set.statistics.name: negative regulation of protein dephosphorylation
gene.set.statistics.description: Any process the stops, prevents, or reduces the frequency, rate or extent of removal of phosphate groups from a protein.

gene.set.statistics.name: wound healing, spreading of epidermal cells
gene.set.statistics.description: The migration of an epidermal cell along or through a wound gap that contributes to the reestablishment of a continuous epidermis.

gene.set.statistics.name: hippo signaling
gene.set.statistics.description: The series of molecular signals mediated by the serine/threonine kinase Hippo or one of its orthologs. In Drosophila, Hippo in complex with the scaffold protein Salvador (Sav), phosphorylates and activates Warts (Wts), which in turn phosphorylates and inactivates the Yorkie (Yki) transcriptional activator. The core fly components hippo, sav, wts and mats are conserved in mammals as STK4/3 (MST1/2), SAV1/WW45, LATS1/2 and MOB1.

gene.set.statistics.name: peptidyl-tyrosine dephosphorylation
gene.set.statistics.description: The removal of phosphoric residues from peptidyl-O-phospho-tyrosine to form peptidyl-tyrosine.

gene.set.statistics.name: long-chain fatty-acyl-CoA metabolic process
gene.set.statistics.description: The chemical reactions and pathways involving long-chain fatty-acyl-CoAs, any derivative of coenzyme A in which the sulfhydryl group is in a thioester linkage with a long-chain fatty-acyl group. Long-chain fatty-acyl-CoAs have chain lengths of C13 or more.

gene.set.statistics.name: long-chain fatty-acyl-CoA biosynthetic process
gene.set.statistics.description: The chemical reactions and pathways resulting in the formation of a long-chain fatty-acyl-CoA any derivative of coenzyme A in which the sulfhydryl group is in a thioester linkage with a long-chain fatty-acyl group. Long-chain fatty-acyl-CoAs have chain lengths of C13 or more.

gene.set.statistics.name: protein localization to microtubule
gene.set.statistics.description: A process in which a protein is transported to, or maintained at, a microtubule.

gene.set.statistics.name: Roundabout signaling pathway
gene.set.statistics.description: A series of molecular signals initiated by the binding of a SLIT protein to a Roundabout (ROBO) family receptor on the surface of a target cell, and ending with regulation of a downstream cellular process, e.g. transcription.

gene.set.statistics.name: protein localization to synapse
gene.set.statistics.description: Any process in which a protein is transported to, and/or maintained at the synapse, the junction between a nerve fiber of one neuron and another neuron or muscle fiber or glial cell.

gene.set.statistics.name: phosphate ion transmembrane transport
gene.set.statistics.description: The process in which a phosphate is transported across a membrane.

gene.set.statistics.name: maintenance of protein localization in endoplasmic reticulum
gene.set.statistics.description: Any process in which a protein is maintained in the endoplasmic reticulum and prevented from moving elsewhere. These include sequestration within the endoplasmic reticulum, protein stabilization to prevent transport elsewhere and the active retrieval of proteins that escape the endoplasmic reticulum.

gene.set.statistics.name: response to interferon-alpha
gene.set.statistics.description: Any process that results in a change in state or activity of a cell or an organism (in terms of movement, secretion, enzyme production, gene expression, etc.) as a result of an interferon-alpha stimulus. Interferon-alpha is a type I interferon.

gene.set.statistics.name: response to interferon-beta
gene.set.statistics.description: Any process that results in a change in state or activity of a cell or an organism (in terms of movement, secretion, enzyme production, gene expression, etc.) as a result of an interferon-beta stimulus. Interferon-beta is a type I interferon.

gene.set.statistics.name: cellular response to interferon-alpha
gene.set.statistics.description: Any process that results in a change in state or activity of a cell (in terms of movement, secretion, enzyme production, gene expression, etc.) as a result of an interferon-alpha stimulus. Interferon-alpha is a type I interferon.

gene.set.statistics.name: cellular response to interferon-beta
gene.set.statistics.description: Any process that results in a change in state or activity of a cell (in terms of movement, secretion, enzyme production, gene expression, etc.) as a result of an interferon-beta stimulus. Interferon-beta is a type I interferon.

gene.set.statistics.name: vesicle cargo loading
gene.set.statistics.description: The formation of a macromolecular complex between the coat proteins and proteins and/or lipoproteins that are going to be transported by a vesicle.

gene.set.statistics.name: SNARE complex assembly
gene.set.statistics.description: The aggregation, arrangement and bonding together of a set of components to form a SNARE complex, a protein complex involved in membrane fusion; a stable ternary complex consisting of a four-helix bundle, usually formed from one R-SNARE and three Q-SNAREs with an ionic layer sandwiched between hydrophobic layers.

gene.set.statistics.name: SNARE complex disassembly
gene.set.statistics.description: The disaggregation of the SNARE protein complex into its constituent components. The SNARE complex is a protein complex involved in membrane fusion; a stable ternary complex consisting of a four-helix bundle, usually formed from one R-SNARE and three Q-SNAREs with an ionic layer sandwiched between hydrophobic layers.

gene.set.statistics.name: histone H2A monoubiquitination
gene.set.statistics.description: The modification of histone H2A by addition of a single ubiquitin group.

gene.set.statistics.name: monoubiquitinated protein deubiquitination
gene.set.statistics.description: The removal of the ubiquitin group from a monoubiquitinated protein.

gene.set.statistics.name: regulation of SNARE complex assembly
gene.set.statistics.description: Any process that modulates the frequency, rate or extent of assembly of the SNARE complex. The SNARE complex is a protein complex involved in membrane fusion; a stable ternary complex consisting of a four-helix bundle, usually formed from one R-SNARE and three Q-SNAREs with an ionic layer sandwiched between hydrophobic layers.

gene.set.statistics.name: oxidative single-stranded RNA demethylation
gene.set.statistics.description: Removal of the methyl group from one or more nucleotides within a single-stranded RNA molecule involving the oxidation (i.e. electron loss) of one or more atoms.

gene.set.statistics.name: intracellular signal transduction
gene.set.statistics.description: The process in which a signal is passed on to downstream components within the cell, which become activated themselves to further propagate the signal and finally trigger a change in the function or state of the cell.

gene.set.statistics.name: negative regulation of chromatin binding
gene.set.statistics.description: Any process that stops or reduces the frequency, rate or extent of chromatin binding. Chromatin binding is the selective interaction with chromatin, the network of fibers of DNA, protein, and sometimes RNA, that make up the chromosomes of the eukaryotic nucleus during interphase.

gene.set.statistics.name: positive regulation of chromatin binding
gene.set.statistics.description: Any process that increases the frequency, rate or extent of chromatin binding. Chromatin binding is the selective interaction with chromatin, the network of fibers of DNA, protein, and sometimes RNA, that make up the chromosomes of the eukaryotic nucleus during interphase.

gene.set.statistics.name: calcium-mediated signaling using intracellular calcium source
gene.set.statistics.description: A series of molecular signals in which a cell uses calcium ions released from an intracellular store to convert a signal into a response.

gene.set.statistics.name: purinergic nucleotide receptor signaling pathway
gene.set.statistics.description: The series of molecular signals generated as a consequence of a receptor binding to an extracellular purine nucleotide to initiate a change in cell activity.

gene.set.statistics.name: histone H2B conserved C-terminal lysine deubiquitination
gene.set.statistics.description: A histone deubiquitination process in which a ubiquitin monomer is removed from a conserved lysine residue in the C-terminus of histone H2B. The conserved lysine residue is K119 in fission yeast, K123 in budding yeast, or K120 in mammals.

gene.set.statistics.name: stress granule disassembly
gene.set.statistics.description: The disaggregation of a stress granule into its constituent protein and RNA parts.

gene.set.statistics.name: maintenance of blood-brain barrier
gene.set.statistics.description: Maintaining the structure and function of the blood-brain barrier, thus ensuring specific regulated transport of substances (e.g. macromolecules, small molecules, ions) into the brain, and out of the brain into the blood circulation.

gene.set.statistics.name: entry of bacterium into host cell
gene.set.statistics.description: The process in which a bacterium enters a host cell. The host is defined as the larger of the organisms involved in a symbiotic interaction.

gene.set.statistics.name: TRIF-dependent toll-like receptor signaling pathway
gene.set.statistics.description: Any series of molecular signals generated as a consequence of binding to a toll-like receptor where the TRIF adaptor mediates transduction of the signal. Toll-like receptors directly bind pattern motifs from a variety of microbial sources to initiate innate immune response.

gene.set.statistics.name: cellular response to drug
gene.set.statistics.description: Any process that results in a change in state or activity of a cell (in terms of movement, secretion, enzyme production, gene expression, etc.) as a result of a drug stimulus. A drug is a substance used in the diagnosis, treatment or prevention of a disease.

gene.set.statistics.name: mitochondrial protein catabolic process
gene.set.statistics.description: The chemical reactions and pathways resulting in the breakdown of a mitochondrial protein. This process is necessary to maintain the healthy state of mitochondria and is thought to occur via the induction of an intramitochondrial lysosome-like organelle that acts to eliminate the damaged oxidised mitochondrial proteins without destroying the mitochondrial structure.

gene.set.statistics.name: CD4-positive, alpha-beta T cell activation
gene.set.statistics.description: The change in morphology and behavior of a CD4-positive, alpha-beta T cell resulting from exposure to a mitogen, cytokine, chemokine, cellular ligand, or an antigen for which it is specific.

gene.set.statistics.name: T-helper 1 cell activation
gene.set.statistics.description: The change in morphology and behavior of a T-helper 1 cell resulting from exposure to a mitogen, cytokine, chemokine, cellular ligand, or an antigen for which it is specific.

gene.set.statistics.name: interleukin-12-mediated signaling pathway
gene.set.statistics.description: A series of molecular signals initiated by the binding of interleukin-12 to a receptor on the surface of a cell, and ending with regulation of a downstream cellular process, e.g. transcription.

gene.set.statistics.name: interleukin-15-mediated signaling pathway
gene.set.statistics.description: A series of molecular signals initiated by the binding of interleukin-15 to a receptor on the surface of a cell, and ending with regulation of a downstream cellular process, e.g. transcription.

gene.set.statistics.name: sodium ion transmembrane transport
gene.set.statistics.description: A process in which a sodium ion is transported from one side of a membrane to the other by means of some agent such as a transporter or pore.

gene.set.statistics.name: response to hepatocyte growth factor
gene.set.statistics.description: Any process that results in a change in state or activity of a cell or an organism (in terms of movement, secretion, enzyme production, gene expression, etc.) as a result of a hepatocyte growth factor stimulus.

gene.set.statistics.name: cellular response to hepatocyte growth factor stimulus
gene.set.statistics.description: Any process that results in a change in state or activity of a cell (in terms of movement, secretion, enzyme production, gene expression, etc.) as a result of a hepatocyte growth factor stimulus.

gene.set.statistics.name: intraciliary transport involved in cilium assembly
gene.set.statistics.description: The bidirectional movement of large protein complexes along microtubules within a cilium that contributes to cilium assembly.

gene.set.statistics.name: endothelial cell chemotaxis
gene.set.statistics.description: The directed movement of an endothelial cell guided by a specific chemical concentration gradient. Movement may be towards a higher concentration (positive chemotaxis) or towards a lower concentration (negative chemotaxis).

gene.set.statistics.name: insulin secretion involved in cellular response to glucose stimulus
gene.set.statistics.description: The regulated release of proinsulin from secretory granules (B granules) in the B cells of the pancreas; accompanied by cleavage of proinsulin to form mature insulin, in response to a glucose stimulus.

gene.set.statistics.name: positive regulation of insulin secretion involved in cellular response to glucose stimulus
gene.set.statistics.description: Any process that increases the frequency, rate or extent of the regulated release of insulin that contributes to the response of a cell to glucose.

gene.set.statistics.name: positive regulation of mitochondrial membrane permeability
gene.set.statistics.description: Any process that increases the frequency, rate or extent of the passage or uptake of molecules by the mitochondrial membrane.

gene.set.statistics.name: negative regulation of mitochondrial membrane permeability
gene.set.statistics.description: Any process that decreases the frequency, rate or extent of the passage or uptake of molecules by the mitochondrial membrane.

gene.set.statistics.name: positive regulation of urine volume
gene.set.statistics.description: Any process that increases the amount of urine excreted from the body over a unit of time.

gene.set.statistics.name: positive regulation of renal sodium excretion
gene.set.statistics.description: Any process that increases the amount of sodium excreted in urine over a unit of time.

gene.set.statistics.name: protein K11-linked deubiquitination
gene.set.statistics.description: A protein deubiquitination process in which a K11-linked ubiquitin chain, i.e. a polymer of ubiquitin formed by linkages between lysine residues at position 11 of the ubiquitin monomers, is removed from a protein.

gene.set.statistics.name: nail development
gene.set.statistics.description: The process whose specific outcome is the progression of a nail over time, from its formation to the mature structure. A nail is a horn-like envelope covering the outer end of a finger or toe, and consists of the nail plate, the nail matrix and the nail bed below it, and the grooves surrounding it.

gene.set.statistics.name: response to isolation stress
gene.set.statistics.description: Any process that results in a change in state or activity of a cell or an organism (in terms of movement, secretion, enzyme production, gene expression, etc.) as a result of a lack of contact with other members of the same species.

gene.set.statistics.name: response to immobilization stress
gene.set.statistics.description: Any process that results in a change in state or activity of a cell or an organism (in terms of movement, secretion, enzyme production, gene expression, etc.) as a result of being rendered immobile.

gene.set.statistics.name: aorta development
gene.set.statistics.description: The progression of the aorta over time, from its initial formation to the mature structure. An aorta is an artery that carries blood from the heart to other parts of the body.

gene.set.statistics.name: skeletal muscle cell differentiation
gene.set.statistics.description: The process in which a relatively unspecialized cell acquires specialized features of a skeletal muscle cell, a somatic cell located in skeletal muscle.

gene.set.statistics.name: cellular response to vascular endothelial growth factor stimulus
gene.set.statistics.description: Any process that results in a change in state or activity of a cell (in terms of movement, secretion, enzyme production, gene expression, etc.) as a result of a vascular endothelial growth factor stimulus.

gene.set.statistics.name: cardiolipin acyl-chain remodeling
gene.set.statistics.description: Remodeling the acyl chains of premature (de novo synthesized) cardiolipin (1,3-bis(3-phosphatidyl)glycerol), through sequential deacylation and re-acylation reactions, to generate mature cardiolipin containing high-levels of unsaturated fatty acids.

gene.set.statistics.name: peptidyl-threonine dephosphorylation
gene.set.statistics.description: The removal of phosphoric residues from peptidyl-O-phospho-L-threonine to form peptidyl-threonine.

gene.set.statistics.name: aggrephagy
gene.set.statistics.description: Selective degradation of protein aggregates by macroautophagy.

gene.set.statistics.name: endodermal cell differentiation
gene.set.statistics.description: The process in which a relatively unspecialized cell acquires the specialized features of an endoderm cell, a cell of the inner of the three germ layers of the embryo.

gene.set.statistics.name: response to muscle stretch
gene.set.statistics.description: Any process that results in a change in state or activity of a cell or an organism (in terms of movement, secretion, enzyme production, gene expression, etc.) as a result of a myofibril being extended beyond its slack length.

gene.set.statistics.name: tetrahydrofolate interconversion
gene.set.statistics.description: The chemical reactions and pathways by which one-carbon (C1) units are transferred between tetrahydrofolate molecules, to synthesise other tetrahydrofolate molecules.

gene.set.statistics.name: positive regulation of transcription from RNA polymerase II promoter in response to stress
gene.set.statistics.description: Any process that increases the frequency, rate or extent of transcription from an RNA polymerase II promoter as a result of a stimulus indicating the organism is under stress. The stress is usually, but not necessarily, exogenous (e.g. temperature, humidity, ionizing radiation).

gene.set.statistics.name: protein localization to endosome
gene.set.statistics.description: A process in which a protein is transported to, or maintained in, a location within an endosome.

gene.set.statistics.name: cellular response to interleukin-3
gene.set.statistics.description: Any process that results in a change in state or activity of a cell (in terms of movement, secretion, enzyme production, gene expression, etc.) as a result of an interleukin-3 stimulus.

gene.set.statistics.name: osteoclast development
gene.set.statistics.description: The process whose specific outcome is the progression of a osteoclast from its formation to the mature structure. Cell development does not include the steps involved in committing a cell to a specific fate. An osteoclast is a specialized phagocytic cell associated with the absorption and removal of the mineralized matrix of bone tissue.

gene.set.statistics.name: cleavage furrow formation
gene.set.statistics.description: Generation of the cleavage furrow, a shallow groove in the cell surface near the old metaphase plate that marks the site of cytokinesis. This process includes the recruitment and localized activation of signals such as RhoA at the site of the future furrow to ensure that furrowing initiates at the correct site in the cell.

gene.set.statistics.name: alpha-linolenic acid metabolic process
gene.set.statistics.description: The chemical reactions and pathways involving alpha-linolenic acid, an unsaturated omega-6 fatty acid that has the molecular formula C18H32O2.

gene.set.statistics.name: medium-chain fatty-acyl-CoA catabolic process
gene.set.statistics.description: The chemical reactions and pathways resulting in the breakdown of medium-chain fatty-acyl-CoAs, any derivative of coenzyme A in which the sulfhydryl group is in a thioester linkage with a medium-chain fatty-acyl group. A medium-chain fatty acid is a fatty acid with a chain length of between C6 and C12.

gene.set.statistics.name: cellular response to platelet-derived growth factor stimulus
gene.set.statistics.description: Any process that results in a change in state or activity of a cell (in terms of movement, secretion, enzyme production, gene expression, etc.) as a result of a platelet-derived growth factor stimulus.

gene.set.statistics.name: phosphatidylglycerol acyl-chain remodeling
gene.set.statistics.description: Remodeling the acyl chains of phosphatidylglycerol, through sequential deacylation and re-acylation reactions, to generate phosphatidylglycerol containing different types of fatty acid acyl chains.

gene.set.statistics.name: phosphatidylcholine acyl-chain remodeling
gene.set.statistics.description: Remodeling the acyl chains of phosphatidylcholine, through sequential deacylation and re-acylation reactions, to generate phosphatidylcholine containing different types of fatty acid acyl chains.

gene.set.statistics.name: outer dynein arm assembly
gene.set.statistics.description: The aggregation, arrangement and bonding together of a set of components to form an axonemal dynein outer arm, an outer arm structure present on the outer doublet microtubules of ciliary and flagellar axonemes.

gene.set.statistics.name: inner dynein arm assembly
gene.set.statistics.description: The aggregation, arrangement and bonding together of a set of components to form an axonemal dynein inner arm, an inner arm structure present on the outer doublet microtubules of ciliary and flagellar axonemes.

gene.set.statistics.name: protein localization to nuclear inner membrane
gene.set.statistics.description: A process in which a protein is transported to, or maintained in, a location within the nuclear inner membrane.

gene.set.statistics.name: multivesicular body assembly
gene.set.statistics.description: The aggregation, arrangement and bonding together of a set of components to form a multivesicular body, a type of late endosome in which regions of the limiting endosomal membrane invaginate to form internal vesicles; membrane proteins that enter the internal vesicles are sequestered from the cytoplasm.

gene.set.statistics.name: cellular response to increased oxygen levels
gene.set.statistics.description: Any process that results in a change in state or activity of a cell (in terms of movement, secretion, enzyme production, gene expression, etc.) as a result of a stimulus reflecting an increase in the level of oxygen.

gene.set.statistics.name: interstrand cross-link repair
gene.set.statistics.description: Removal of a DNA interstrand crosslink (a covalent attachment of DNA bases on opposite strands of the DNA) and restoration of the DNA. DNA interstrand crosslinks occur when both strands of duplex DNA are covalently tethered together (e.g. by an exogenous or endogenous agent), thus preventing the strand unwinding necessary for essential DNA functions such as transcription and replication.

gene.set.statistics.name: vascular endothelial growth factor receptor-2 signaling pathway
gene.set.statistics.description: Any series of molecular signals initiated by the binding of an extracellular ligand to a vascular endothelial growth factor receptor-2 (VEGFR-2) located on the surface of the receiving cell, and ending with regulation of a downstream cellular process, e.g. transcription.

gene.set.statistics.name: dendritic cell migration
gene.set.statistics.description: The movement of a dendritic cell within or between different tissues and organs of the body.

gene.set.statistics.name: post-anal tail morphogenesis
gene.set.statistics.description: The process in which a post-anal tail is generated and organized. A post-anal tail is a muscular region of the body that extends posterior to the anus. The post-anal tail may aid locomotion and balance.

gene.set.statistics.name: sodium ion export across plasma membrane
gene.set.statistics.description: The directed movement of sodium ions from inside of a cell, across the plasma membrane and into the extracellular region.

gene.set.statistics.name: pre-replicative complex assembly
gene.set.statistics.description: The aggregation, arrangement and bonding together of a set of components to form the pre-replicative complex, a protein-DNA complex that forms at the origin of replication during the initial step of DNA replication and allows the origin to become competent, or 'licensed', for replication.

gene.set.statistics.name: tRNA stabilization
gene.set.statistics.description: Prevention of degradation of tRNA molecules.

gene.set.statistics.name: calcium import into the mitochondrion
gene.set.statistics.description: A process in which a calcium ion (Ca2+) is transported from the cytosol into the mitochondrial matrix.

gene.set.statistics.name: synaptic vesicle recycling via endosome
gene.set.statistics.description: Synaptic vesicle recycling where vesicles endocytosed via clathrin-coated pits re-acidify and refill with neurotransmitters after passing through an endosomal intermediate.

gene.set.statistics.name: neuron death in response to oxidative stress
gene.set.statistics.description: Any biological process that results in permanent cessation of all vital functions of a neuron upon exposure to an oxidative stress stimulus.

gene.set.statistics.name: positive regulation of translation in response to endoplasmic reticulum stress
gene.set.statistics.description: Any process that activates, or increases the frequency, rate or extent of translation as a result of endoplasmic reticulum stress.

gene.set.statistics.name: IRE1-mediated unfolded protein response
gene.set.statistics.description: A series of molecular signals mediated by the endoplasmic reticulum stress sensor IRE1 (Inositol-requiring transmembrane kinase/endonuclease). Begins with activation of IRE1 in response to endoplasmic reticulum (ER) stress, and ends with regulation of a downstream cellular process, e.g. transcription. One target of activated IRE1 is the transcription factor HAC1 in yeast, or XBP1 in mammals; IRE1 cleaves an intron of a mRNA coding for HAC1/XBP1 to generate an activated HAC1/XBP1 transcription factor, which controls the up regulation of UPR-related genes. At least in mammals, IRE1 can also signal through additional intracellular pathways including JNK and NF-kappaB.

gene.set.statistics.name: PERK-mediated unfolded protein response
gene.set.statistics.description: A series of molecular signals mediated by the endoplasmic reticulum membrane stress sensor PERK (PKR-like ER kinase). Begins with activation of PERK in response to endoplasmic reticulum (ER) stress and ends with regulation of a downstream cellular process, e.g. transcription. The main substrate of PERK is the translation initiation factor eIF2alpha. Serine-phosphorylation of eIF2alpha by PERK inactivates eIF2alpha and inhibits general protein translation. In addition, eIF2alpha phosphorylation preferentially increases the translation of selective mRNAs such as ATF4 (activating transcription factor 4), which up regulates a subset of UPR genes required to restore folding capacity.

gene.set.statistics.name: ATF6-mediated unfolded protein response
gene.set.statistics.description: A series of molecular signals mediated by the endoplasmic reticulum membrane stress sensor ATF6 (activating transcription factor 6). Begins with activation of ATF6 in response to endoplasmic reticulum (ER) stress, and ends with regulation of a downstream cellular process, e.g. transcription. Under conditions of endoplasmic reticulum stress, ATF6 translocates to the Golgi where it is processed by proteases to release a cytoplasmic domain (ATF6f), which operates as a transcriptional activator of many genes required to restore folding capacity.

gene.set.statistics.name: ERAD pathway
gene.set.statistics.description: The protein catabolic pathway which targets endoplasmic reticulum (ER)-resident proteins for degradation by the cytoplasmic proteasome. It begins with recognition of the ER-resident protein, includes retrotranslocation (dislocation) of the protein from the ER to the cytosol, protein modifications necessary for correct substrate transfer (e.g. ubiquitination), transport of the protein to the proteasome, and ends with degradation of the protein by the cytoplasmic proteasome.

gene.set.statistics.name: insulin receptor internalization
gene.set.statistics.description: A receptor-mediated endocytosis process that results in the movement of an insulin receptor from the plasma membrane to the inside of the cell.

gene.set.statistics.name: reelin-mediated signaling pathway
gene.set.statistics.description: A series of molecular signals initiated by the binding of reelin (a secreted glycoprotein) to a receptor on the surface of a target cell, and ending with regulation of a downstream cellular process, e.g. transcription.

gene.set.statistics.name: apolipoprotein A-I-mediated signaling pathway
gene.set.statistics.description: A series of molecular signals initiated by the binding of apolipoprotein A-I to a receptor on the surface of a cell, and ending with regulation of a downstream cellular process, e.g. transcription.

gene.set.statistics.name: positive regulation of endothelial cell chemotaxis by VEGF-activated vascular endothelial growth factor receptor signaling pathway
gene.set.statistics.description: A series of molecular signals initiated by the binding of a vascular endothelial growth factor (VEGF) to a VEGFR on the surface of a cell, which activates or increases the frequency, rate or extent of endothelial cell chemotaxis.

gene.set.statistics.name: NIK/NF-kappaB signaling
gene.set.statistics.description: The process in which a signal is passed on to downstream components within the cell through the NIK-dependent processing and activation of NF-KappaB. Begins with activation of the NF-KappaB-inducing kinase (NIK), which in turn phosphorylates and activates IkappaB kinase alpha (IKKalpha). IKKalpha phosphorylates the NF-Kappa B2 protein (p100) leading to p100 processing and release of an active NF-KappaB (p52).

gene.set.statistics.name: collagen-activated tyrosine kinase receptor signaling pathway
gene.set.statistics.description: A series of molecular signals initiated by the binding of collagen to a receptor on the surface of the target cell where the receptor possesses tyrosine kinase activity. The pathway ends with regulation of a downstream cellular process, e.g. transcription.

gene.set.statistics.name: positive regulation of cell migration by vascular endothelial growth factor signaling pathway
gene.set.statistics.description: A series of molecular signals initiated by the binding of a vascular endothelial growth factor (VEGF) to a receptor on the surface of a cell, which activates or increases the frequency, rate or extent of the orderly movement of a cell from one site to another.

gene.set.statistics.name: nodal signaling pathway
gene.set.statistics.description: A series of molecular signals initiated by the binding of a nodal protein to an activin receptor on the surface of a target cell, and ending with regulation of a downstream cellular process, e.g. transcription.

gene.set.statistics.name: Fc-epsilon receptor signaling pathway
gene.set.statistics.description: A series of molecular signals initiated by the binding of the Fc portion of immunoglobulin E (IgE) to an Fc-epsilon receptor on the surface of a signal-receiving cell, and ending with regulation of a downstream cellular process, e.g. transcription. The Fc portion of an immunoglobulin is its C-terminal constant region.

gene.set.statistics.name: Fc-gamma receptor signaling pathway involved in phagocytosis
gene.set.statistics.description: An Fc-gamma receptor signaling pathway that contributes to the endocytic engulfment of external particulate material by phagocytes.

gene.set.statistics.name: interleukin-7-mediated signaling pathway
gene.set.statistics.description: A series of molecular signals initiated by the binding of interleukin-7 to a receptor on the surface of a cell, and ending with regulation of a downstream cellular process, e.g. transcription.

gene.set.statistics.name: interleukin-9-mediated signaling pathway
gene.set.statistics.description: A series of molecular signals initiated by the binding of interleukin-9 to a receptor on the surface of a cell, and ending with regulation of a downstream cellular process, e.g. transcription.

gene.set.statistics.name: interleukin-21-mediated signaling pathway
gene.set.statistics.description: A series of molecular signals initiated by the binding of interleukin-21 to a receptor on the surface of a cell, and ending with regulation of a downstream cellular process, e.g. transcription.

gene.set.statistics.name: chemokine (C-C motif) ligand 21 signaling pathway
gene.set.statistics.description: A series of molecular signals initiated by the binding of the C-C chemokine CCL21 to a receptor on the surface of a cell, and ending with regulation of a downstream cellular process, e.g. transcription.

gene.set.statistics.name: ERBB signaling pathway
gene.set.statistics.description: A series of molecular signals initiated by binding of a ligand to a member of the ERBB family of receptor tyrosine kinases on the surface of a cell, and ending with regulation of a downstream cellular process, e.g. transcription.

gene.set.statistics.name: ERBB2 signaling pathway
gene.set.statistics.description: A series of molecular signals initiated by binding of a ligand to a member of the ERBB family of receptors on the surface of a cell, where the signal is transmitted by ERBB2. The pathway ends with regulation of a downstream cellular process, e.g. transcription. ERBB2 receptors are themselves unable to bind to ligands, but act as a signal-amplifying tyrosine kinase within a heterodimeric pair.

gene.set.statistics.name: interleukin-23-mediated signaling pathway
gene.set.statistics.description: A series of molecular signals initiated by the binding of interleukin-23 to a receptor on the surface of a cell, and ending with regulation of a downstream cellular process, e.g. transcription.

gene.set.statistics.name: thrombopoietin-mediated signaling pathway
gene.set.statistics.description: A series of molecular signals initiated by the binding of a thrombopoietin to the thrombopoietin receptor on the surface of a cell, and ending with regulation of a downstream cellular process, e.g. transcription.

gene.set.statistics.name: angiotensin-activated signaling pathway
gene.set.statistics.description: The series of molecular signals generated as a consequence of angiotensin II binding to an angiotensin receptor on the surface of the cell, and proceeding with the activated receptor transmitting the signal to a heterotrimeric G-protein complex to initiate a change in cell activity. Ends with regulation of a downstream cellular process, e.g. transcription.

gene.set.statistics.name: nerve growth factor signaling pathway
gene.set.statistics.description: A series of molecular signals initiated by the binding of nerve growth factor (NGF) to a receptor on the surface of the target cell, and ending with regulation of a downstream cellular process, e.g. transcription.

gene.set.statistics.name: TORC1 signaling
gene.set.statistics.description: A series of intracellular molecular signals mediated by TORC1; TOR (target of rapamycin) in complex with at least Raptor (regulatory-associated protein of TOR), or orthologs of, and other signaling components.

gene.set.statistics.name: TORC2 signaling
gene.set.statistics.description: A series of intracellular molecular signals mediated by TORC2; TOR (rapamycin-insensitive companion of TOR) in complex with at least Rictor (regulatory-associated protein of TOR), or orthologs of, and other signaling components.

gene.set.statistics.name: induction by virus of host autophagy
gene.set.statistics.description: Any process in which a virus activates or increases the frequency, rate or extent of autophagy in the host.

gene.set.statistics.name: RIG-I signaling pathway
gene.set.statistics.description: Any series of molecular signals generated as a consequence of the cytoplasmic pattern recognition receptor (PRR) RIG-1 (also known as DDX58) binding to viral RNA. RIG-I detects RNA synthesized during active viral replication and triggers a signaling pathway to protect the host against viral infection, for example by inducing the expression of antiviral cytokines.

gene.set.statistics.name: negative regulation of MDA-5 signaling pathway
gene.set.statistics.description: Any process that stops, prevents, or reduces the frequency, rate or extent of the series of molecular signals generated as a consequence of the cytoplasmic pattern recognition receptor (PRR) MDA-5 (also known as IFIH1) binding to viral RNA.

gene.set.statistics.name: negative regulation of RIG-I signaling pathway
gene.set.statistics.description: Any process that stops, prevents, or reduces the frequency, rate or extent of the series of molecular signals generated as a consequence of the cytoplasmic pattern recognition receptor (PRR) RIG-1 (also known as DDX58) binding to viral RNA.

gene.set.statistics.name: viral RNA genome replication
gene.set.statistics.description: The replication of a viral RNA genome.

gene.set.statistics.name: viral budding via host ESCRT complex
gene.set.statistics.description: Viral budding which uses a host ESCRT protein complex, or complexes, to mediate the budding process.

gene.set.statistics.name: establishment of mitotic spindle localization
gene.set.statistics.description: The cell cycle process in which the directed movement of the mitotic spindle to a specific location in the cell occurs.

gene.set.statistics.name: regulation of growth
gene.set.statistics.description: Any process that modulates the frequency, rate or extent of the growth of all or part of an organism so that it occurs at its proper speed, either globally or in a specific part of the organism's development.

gene.set.statistics.name: locomotion
gene.set.statistics.description: Self-propelled movement of a cell or organism from one location to another.

gene.set.statistics.name: regulation of multicellular organism growth
gene.set.statistics.description: Any process that modulates the frequency, rate or extent of growth of the body of an organism so that it reaches its usual body size.

gene.set.statistics.name: embryonic cleavage
gene.set.statistics.description: The first few specialized divisions of an activated animal egg.

gene.set.statistics.name: positive regulation of multicellular organism growth
gene.set.statistics.description: Any process that activates or increases the frequency, rate or extent of growth of an organism to reach its usual body size.

gene.set.statistics.name: positive regulation of embryonic development
gene.set.statistics.description: Any process that activates or increases the frequency, rate or extent of embryonic development.

gene.set.statistics.name: regulation of meiotic nuclear division
gene.set.statistics.description: Any process that modulates the frequency, rate or extent of meiotic nuclear division, the process in which the nucleus of a diploid cell divides twice forming four haploid cells, one or more of which usually function as gametes.

gene.set.statistics.name: regulation of gene expression, epigenetic
gene.set.statistics.description: Any process that modulates the frequency, rate or extent of gene expression; the process is mitotically or meiotically heritable, or is stably self-propagated in the cytoplasm of a resting cell, and does not entail a change in DNA sequence.

gene.set.statistics.name: negative regulation of fibroblast growth factor receptor signaling pathway
gene.set.statistics.description: Any process that stops, prevents, or reduces the frequency, rate or extent of fibroblast growth factor receptor signaling pathway activity.

gene.set.statistics.name: protein refolding
gene.set.statistics.description: The process carried out by a cell that restores the biological activity of an unfolded or misfolded protein, using helper proteins such as chaperones.

gene.set.statistics.name: epithelial fluid transport
gene.set.statistics.description: The directed movement of fluid across epithelia.

gene.set.statistics.name: negative regulation of epidermal growth factor receptor signaling pathway
gene.set.statistics.description: Any process that stops, prevents, or reduces the frequency, rate or extent of epidermal growth factor receptor signaling pathway activity.

gene.set.statistics.name: wound healing
gene.set.statistics.description: The series of events that restore integrity to a damaged tissue, following an injury.

gene.set.statistics.name: gliogenesis
gene.set.statistics.description: The process that results in the generation of glial cells. This includes the production of glial progenitors and their differentiation into mature glia.

gene.set.statistics.name: T cell proliferation
gene.set.statistics.description: The expansion of a T cell population by cell division. Follows T cell activation.

gene.set.statistics.name: B cell proliferation
gene.set.statistics.description: The expansion of a B cell population by cell division. Follows B cell activation.

gene.set.statistics.name: positive regulation of T cell proliferation
gene.set.statistics.description: Any process that activates or increases the rate or extent of T cell proliferation.

gene.set.statistics.name: positive regulation of activated T cell proliferation
gene.set.statistics.description: Any process that activates or increases the rate or extent of activated T cell proliferation.

gene.set.statistics.name: T cell activation
gene.set.statistics.description: The change in morphology and behavior of a mature or immature T cell resulting from exposure to a mitogen, cytokine, chemokine, cellular ligand, or an antigen for which it is specific.

gene.set.statistics.name: B cell activation
gene.set.statistics.description: The change in morphology and behavior of a mature or immature B cell resulting from exposure to a mitogen, cytokine, chemokine, cellular ligand, or an antigen for which it is specific.

gene.set.statistics.name: endothelial cell activation
gene.set.statistics.description: The change in morphology and behavior of an endothelial cell resulting from exposure to a cytokine, chemokine, cellular ligand, or soluble factor.

gene.set.statistics.name: neutrophil activation
gene.set.statistics.description: The change in morphology and behavior of a neutrophil resulting from exposure to a cytokine, chemokine, cellular ligand, or soluble factor.

gene.set.statistics.name: regulation of cell population proliferation
gene.set.statistics.description: Any process that modulates the frequency, rate or extent of cell proliferation.

gene.set.statistics.name: regulation of T cell proliferation
gene.set.statistics.description: Any process that modulates the frequency, rate or extent of T cell proliferation.

gene.set.statistics.name: negative regulation of T cell proliferation
gene.set.statistics.description: Any process that stops, prevents or reduces the rate or extent of T cell proliferation.

gene.set.statistics.name: neurotransmitter catabolic process
gene.set.statistics.description: The chemical reactions and pathways resulting in the breakdown of any of a group of substances that are released on excitation from the axon terminal of a presynaptic neuron of the central or peripheral nervous system and travel across the synaptic cleft to either excite or inhibit the target cell.

gene.set.statistics.name: neurotransmitter biosynthetic process
gene.set.statistics.description: The chemical reactions and pathways resulting in the formation of any of a group of substances that are released on excitation from the axon terminal of a presynaptic neuron of the central or peripheral nervous system and travel across the synaptic cleft to either excite or inhibit the target cell.

gene.set.statistics.name: retrograde transport, endosome to Golgi
gene.set.statistics.description: The directed movement of membrane-bounded vesicles from endosomes back to the trans-Golgi network where they are recycled for further rounds of transport.

gene.set.statistics.name: cellular response to glucose starvation
gene.set.statistics.description: Any process that results in a change in state or activity of a cell (in terms of movement, secretion, enzyme production, gene expression, etc.) as a result of deprivation of glucose.

gene.set.statistics.name: lipoprotein catabolic process
gene.set.statistics.description: The chemical reactions and pathways resulting in the breakdown of any conjugated, water-soluble protein in which the covalently attached nonprotein group consists of a lipid or lipids.

gene.set.statistics.name: heme catabolic process
gene.set.statistics.description: The chemical reactions and pathways resulting in the breakdown of heme, any compound of iron complexed in a porphyrin (tetrapyrrole) ring.

gene.set.statistics.name: regulation of protein catabolic process
gene.set.statistics.description: Any process that modulates the frequency, rate or extent of the chemical reactions and pathways resulting in the breakdown of a protein by the destruction of the native, active configuration, with or without the hydrolysis of peptide bonds.

gene.set.statistics.name: negative regulation of protein catabolic process
gene.set.statistics.description: Any process that stops, prevents, or reduces the frequency, rate or extent of the chemical reactions and pathways resulting in the breakdown of a protein by the destruction of the native, active configuration, with or without the hydrolysis of peptide bonds.

gene.set.statistics.name: xenobiotic catabolic process
gene.set.statistics.description: The chemical reactions and pathways resulting in the breakdown of a xenobiotic compound, a compound foreign to living organisms. Used of chemical compounds, e.g. a xenobiotic chemical, such as a pesticide.

gene.set.statistics.name: cellular ketone metabolic process
gene.set.statistics.description: The chemical reactions and pathways involving any of a class of organic compounds that contain the carbonyl group, CO, and in which the carbonyl group is bonded only to carbon atoms, as carried out by individual cells. The general formula for a ketone is RCOR, where R and R are alkyl or aryl groups.

gene.set.statistics.name: response to cocaine
gene.set.statistics.description: Any process that results in a change in state or activity of a cell or an organism (in terms of movement, secretion, enzyme production, gene expression, etc.) as a result of a cocaine stimulus. Cocaine is a crystalline alkaloid obtained from the leaves of the coca plant.

gene.set.statistics.name: establishment of planar polarity of embryonic epithelium
gene.set.statistics.description: Coordinated organization of groups of cells in the plane of an embryonic epithelium, such that they all orient to similar coordinates.

gene.set.statistics.name: ribosome biogenesis
gene.set.statistics.description: A cellular process that results in the biosynthesis of constituent macromolecules, assembly, and arrangement of constituent parts of ribosome subunits; includes transport to the sites of protein synthesis.

gene.set.statistics.name: ribosome assembly
gene.set.statistics.description: The aggregation, arrangement and bonding together of the mature ribosome and of its subunits.

gene.set.statistics.name: mature ribosome assembly
gene.set.statistics.description: The aggregation, arrangement and bonding together of the large and small ribosomal subunits into a functional ribosome.

gene.set.statistics.name: peptidyl-aspartic acid hydroxylation
gene.set.statistics.description: The hydroxylation of peptidyl-aspartic acid to form peptidyl-hydroxyaspartic acid.

gene.set.statistics.name: natural killer cell mediated cytotoxicity
gene.set.statistics.description: The directed killing of a target cell by a natural killer cell through the release of granules containing cytotoxic mediators or through the engagement of death receptors.

gene.set.statistics.name: ribosomal large subunit biogenesis
gene.set.statistics.description: A cellular process that results in the biosynthesis of constituent macromolecules, assembly, and arrangement of constituent parts of a large ribosomal subunit; includes transport to the sites of protein synthesis.

gene.set.statistics.name: ribosomal small subunit biogenesis
gene.set.statistics.description: A cellular process that results in the biosynthesis of constituent macromolecules, assembly, and arrangement of constituent parts of a small ribosomal subunit; includes transport to the sites of protein synthesis.

gene.set.statistics.name: error-prone translesion synthesis
gene.set.statistics.description: The conversion of DNA-damage induced single-stranded gaps into large molecular weight DNA after replication by using a specialized DNA polymerase or replication complex to insert a defined nucleotide across the lesion. This process does not remove the replication-blocking lesions and causes an increase in the endogenous mutation level. For example, in E. coli, a low fidelity DNA polymerase, pol V, copies lesions that block replication fork progress. This produces mutations specifically targeted to DNA template damage sites, but it can also produce mutations at undamaged sites.

gene.set.statistics.name: purine nucleoside metabolic process
gene.set.statistics.description: The chemical reactions and pathways involving one of a family of organic molecules consisting of a purine base covalently bonded to a sugar ribose (a ribonucleoside) or deoxyribose (a deoxyribonucleoside).

gene.set.statistics.name: regulation of fatty acid biosynthetic process
gene.set.statistics.description: Any process that modulates the frequency, rate or extent of the chemical reactions and pathways resulting in the formation of fatty acids, any of the aliphatic monocarboxylic acids that can be liberated by hydrolysis from naturally occurring fats and oils.

gene.set.statistics.name: regulation of protein import into nucleus
gene.set.statistics.description: Any process that modulates the frequency, rate or extent of movement of proteins from the cytoplasm to the nucleus.

gene.set.statistics.name: positive regulation of protein import into nucleus
gene.set.statistics.description: Any process that activates or increases the frequency, rate or extent of movement of proteins from the cytoplasm into the nucleus.

gene.set.statistics.name: negative regulation of protein import into nucleus
gene.set.statistics.description: Any process that stops, prevents, or reduces the frequency, rate or extent of the movement of proteins from the cytoplasm into the nucleus.

gene.set.statistics.name: vasoconstriction
gene.set.statistics.description: A decrease in the diameter of blood vessels, especially arteries, due to constriction of smooth muscle cells that line the vessels, and usually causing an increase in blood pressure.

gene.set.statistics.name: vasodilation
gene.set.statistics.description: An increase in the internal diameter of blood vessels, especially arterioles or capillaries, due to relaxation of smooth muscle cells that line the vessels, and usually resulting in a decrease in blood pressure.

gene.set.statistics.name: regulation of phosphorylation
gene.set.statistics.description: Any process that modulates the frequency, rate or extent of addition of phosphate groups into a molecule.

gene.set.statistics.name: negative regulation of phosphorylation
gene.set.statistics.description: Any process that stops, prevents or decreases the rate of addition of phosphate groups to a molecule.

gene.set.statistics.name: positive regulation of phosphorylation
gene.set.statistics.description: Any process that activates or increases the frequency, rate or extent of addition of phosphate groups to a molecule.

gene.set.statistics.name: keratan sulfate catabolic process
gene.set.statistics.description: The chemical reactions and pathways resulting in the breakdown of keratan sulfate, a glycosaminoglycan with repeat units consisting of beta-1,4-linked D-galactopyranosyl-beta-(1,4)-N-acetyl-D-glucosamine 6-sulfate and with variable amounts of fucose, sialic acid and mannose units; keratan sulfate chains are covalently linked by a glycosidic attachment through the trisaccharide galactosyl-galactosyl-xylose to peptidyl-threonine or serine residues.

gene.set.statistics.name: vitamin K metabolic process
gene.set.statistics.description: The chemical reactions and pathways involving any of the forms of vitamin K, quinone-derived vitamins which are involved in the synthesis of blood-clotting factors in mammals. Vitamin K substances share a methylated naphthoquinone ring structure and vary in the aliphatic side chains attached to the molecule.

gene.set.statistics.name: regulation of membrane potential
gene.set.statistics.description: Any process that modulates the establishment or extent of a membrane potential, the electric potential existing across any membrane arising from charges in the membrane itself and from the charges present in the media on either side of the membrane.

gene.set.statistics.name: cristae formation
gene.set.statistics.description: The assembly of cristae, the inwards folds of the inner mitochondrial membrane.

gene.set.statistics.name: dopamine metabolic process
gene.set.statistics.description: The chemical reactions and pathways involving dopamine, a catecholamine neurotransmitter and a metabolic precursor of noradrenaline and adrenaline.

gene.set.statistics.name: dopamine catabolic process
gene.set.statistics.description: The chemical reactions and pathways resulting in the breakdown of dopamine, a catecholamine neurotransmitter and a metabolic precursor of noradrenaline and adrenaline.

gene.set.statistics.name: choline catabolic process
gene.set.statistics.description: The chemical reactions and pathways resulting in the breakdown of choline (2-hydroxyethyltrimethylammonium), an amino alcohol that occurs widely in living organisms as a constituent of certain types of phospholipids and in the neurotransmitter acetylcholine.

gene.set.statistics.name: hormone metabolic process
gene.set.statistics.description: The chemical reactions and pathways involving any hormone, naturally occurring substances secreted by specialized cells that affects the metabolism or behavior of other cells possessing functional receptors for the hormone.

gene.set.statistics.name: arginine biosynthetic process via ornithine
gene.set.statistics.description: The chemical reactions and pathways resulting in the formation of arginine (2-amino-5-guanidinopentanoic acid) via the intermediate compound ornithine.

gene.set.statistics.name: eye photoreceptor cell development
gene.set.statistics.description: Development of a photoreceptor, a sensory cell in the eye that reacts to the presence of light. They usually contain a pigment that undergoes a chemical change when light is absorbed, thus stimulating a nerve.

gene.set.statistics.name: inner ear morphogenesis
gene.set.statistics.description: The process in which the anatomical structures of the inner ear are generated and organized. The inner ear is the structure in vertebrates that contains the organs of balance and hearing. It consists of soft hollow sensory structures (the membranous labyrinth) containing fluid (endolymph) surrounded by fluid (perilymph) and encased in a bony cavity (the bony labyrinth). It consists of two chambers, the sacculus and utriculus, from which arise the cochlea and semicircular canals respectively.

gene.set.statistics.name: outer ear morphogenesis
gene.set.statistics.description: The process in which the anatomical structures of the outer ear are generated and organized. The outer ear is the part of the ear external to the tympanum (eardrum). It consists of a tube (the external auditory meatus) that directs sound waves on to the tympanum, and may also include the external pinna, which extends beyond the skull.

gene.set.statistics.name: middle ear morphogenesis
gene.set.statistics.description: The process in which the anatomical structures of the middle ear are generated and organized. The middle ear is the air-filled cavity within the skull of vertebrates that lies between the outer ear and the inner ear. It is linked to the pharynx (and therefore to outside air) via the Eustachian tube and in mammals contains the three ear ossicles, which transmit auditory vibrations from the outer ear (via the tympanum) to the inner ear (via the oval window).

gene.set.statistics.name: odontogenesis of dentin-containing tooth
gene.set.statistics.description: The process whose specific outcome is the progression of a dentin-containing tooth over time, from its formation to the mature structure. A dentin-containing tooth is a hard, bony organ borne on the jaw or other bone of a vertebrate, and is composed mainly of dentin, a dense calcified substance, covered by a layer of enamel.

gene.set.statistics.name: odontogenesis
gene.set.statistics.description: The process whose specific outcome is the progression of a tooth or teeth over time, from formation to the mature structure(s). A tooth is any hard bony, calcareous, or chitinous organ found in the mouth or pharynx of an animal and used in procuring or masticating food.

gene.set.statistics.name: inner ear auditory receptor cell differentiation
gene.set.statistics.description: The process in which a relatively unspecialized inner cell acquires specialized features of an auditory hair cell.

gene.set.statistics.name: response to drug
gene.set.statistics.description: Any process that results in a change in state or activity of a cell or an organism (in terms of movement, secretion, enzyme production, gene expression, etc.) as a result of a drug stimulus. A drug is a substance used in the diagnosis, treatment or prevention of a disease.

gene.set.statistics.name: positive regulation of tyrosine phosphorylation of STAT protein
gene.set.statistics.description: Any process that activates or increases the frequency, rate or extent of the introduction of a phosphate group to a tyrosine residue of a STAT (Signal Transducer and Activator of Transcription) protein.

gene.set.statistics.name: negative regulation of tyrosine phosphorylation of STAT protein
gene.set.statistics.description: Any process that stops, prevents, or reduces the frequency, rate or extent of the introduction of a phosphate group to a tyrosine residue of a STAT (Signal Transducer and Activator of Transcription) protein.

gene.set.statistics.name: response to hydrogen peroxide
gene.set.statistics.description: Any process that results in a change in state or activity of a cell or an organism (in terms of movement, secretion, enzyme production, gene expression, etc.) as a result of a hydrogen peroxide (H2O2) stimulus.

gene.set.statistics.name: myelination
gene.set.statistics.description: The process in which myelin sheaths are formed and maintained around neurons. Oligodendrocytes in the brain and spinal cord and Schwann cells in the peripheral nervous system wrap axons with compact layers of their plasma membrane. Adjacent myelin segments are separated by a non-myelinated stretch of axon called a node of Ranvier.

gene.set.statistics.name: retinol metabolic process
gene.set.statistics.description: The chemical reactions and pathways involving retinol, one of the three compounds that makes up vitamin A.

gene.set.statistics.name: retinoic acid metabolic process
gene.set.statistics.description: The chemical reactions and pathways involving retinoic acid, one of the three components that makes up vitamin A.

gene.set.statistics.name: retinal metabolic process
gene.set.statistics.description: The chemical reactions and pathways involving retinal, a compound that plays an important role in the visual process in most vertebrates. In the retina, retinal combines with opsins to form visual pigments. Retinal is one of the forms of vitamin A.

gene.set.statistics.name: glucose homeostasis
gene.set.statistics.description: Any process involved in the maintenance of an internal steady state of glucose within an organism or cell.

gene.set.statistics.name: response to starvation
gene.set.statistics.description: Any process that results in a change in state or activity of a cell or an organism (in terms of movement, secretion, enzyme production, gene expression, etc.) as a result of a starvation stimulus, deprivation of nourishment.

gene.set.statistics.name: cholesterol homeostasis
gene.set.statistics.description: Any process involved in the maintenance of an internal steady state of cholesterol within an organism or cell.

gene.set.statistics.name: muscle cell differentiation
gene.set.statistics.description: The process in which a relatively unspecialized cell acquires specialized features of a muscle cell.

gene.set.statistics.name: follicle-stimulating hormone signaling pathway
gene.set.statistics.description: The series of molecular signals mediated by follicle-stimulating hormone.

gene.set.statistics.name: fibrinolysis
gene.set.statistics.description: A process that solubilizes fibrin in the bloodstream of a multicellular organism, chiefly by the proteolytic action of plasmin.

gene.set.statistics.name: D-xylose metabolic process
gene.set.statistics.description: The chemical reactions and pathways involving D-xylose, a naturally occurring plant polysaccharide.

gene.set.statistics.name: embryonic digit morphogenesis
gene.set.statistics.description: The process, occurring in the embryo, by which the anatomical structures of the digit are generated and organized. A digit is one of the terminal divisions of an appendage, such as a finger or toe.

gene.set.statistics.name: defense response to bacterium
gene.set.statistics.description: Reactions triggered in response to the presence of a bacterium that act to protect the cell or organism.

gene.set.statistics.name: hydrogen peroxide metabolic process
gene.set.statistics.description: The chemical reactions and pathways involving hydrogen peroxide (H2O2), a potentially harmful byproduct of aerobic cellular respiration which can cause damage to DNA.

gene.set.statistics.name: hydrogen peroxide catabolic process
gene.set.statistics.description: The chemical reactions and pathways resulting in the breakdown of hydrogen peroxide (H2O2).

gene.set.statistics.name: regulation of circadian rhythm
gene.set.statistics.description: Any process that modulates the frequency, rate or extent of a circadian rhythm. A circadian rhythm is a biological process in an organism that recurs with a regularity of approximately 24 hours.

gene.set.statistics.name: positive regulation of circadian rhythm
gene.set.statistics.description: Any process that activates or increases the frequency, rate or extent of a circadian rhythm behavior.

gene.set.statistics.name: negative regulation of circadian rhythm
gene.set.statistics.description: Any process that stops, prevents, or reduces the frequency, rate or extent of a circadian rhythm behavior.

gene.set.statistics.name: eating behavior
gene.set.statistics.description: The specific behavior of an organism relating to the intake of food, any substance (usually solid) that can be metabolized by an organism to give energy and build tissue.

gene.set.statistics.name: long-chain fatty acid biosynthetic process
gene.set.statistics.description: The chemical reactions and pathways resulting in the formation of long-chain fatty acids, any fatty acid with a chain length between C13 and C22.

gene.set.statistics.name: very long-chain fatty acid catabolic process
gene.set.statistics.description: The chemical reactions and pathways resulting in the breakdown of a fatty acid which has a chain length greater than C22.

gene.set.statistics.name: very long-chain fatty acid biosynthetic process
gene.set.statistics.description: The chemical reactions and pathways resulting in the formation of a fatty acid which has a chain length greater than C22.

gene.set.statistics.name: nucleosome mobilization
gene.set.statistics.description: The movement of nucleosomes along a DNA fragment.

gene.set.statistics.name: DNA damage response, detection of DNA damage
gene.set.statistics.description: The series of events required to receive a stimulus indicating DNA damage has occurred and convert it to a molecular signal.

gene.set.statistics.name: signal transduction in response to DNA damage
