gene.set.statistics.description: A cascade of processes induced by the detection of DNA damage within a cell.

gene.set.statistics.name: intrinsic apoptotic signaling pathway in response to DNA damage by p53 class mediator
gene.set.statistics.description: A series of molecular signals in which an intracellular signal is conveyed to trigger the apoptotic death of a cell. The pathway is induced by the cell cycle regulator phosphoprotein p53, or an equivalent protein, in response to the detection of DNA damage, and ends when the execution phase of apoptosis is triggered.

gene.set.statistics.name: mitochondrial ATP synthesis coupled electron transport
gene.set.statistics.description: The transfer of electrons through a series of electron donors and acceptors, generating energy that is ultimately used for synthesis of ATP, as it occurs in the mitochondrial inner membrane or chloroplast thylakoid membrane.

gene.set.statistics.name: mitochondrial ATP synthesis coupled proton transport
gene.set.statistics.description: The transport of protons across a mitochondrial membrane to generate an electrochemical gradient (proton-motive force) that powers ATP synthesis.

gene.set.statistics.name: mRNA transcription by RNA polymerase II
gene.set.statistics.description: The cellular synthesis of messenger RNA (mRNA) from a DNA template by RNA polymerase II, originating at an RNA polymerase II promoter.

gene.set.statistics.name: nucleolar large rRNA transcription by RNA polymerase I
gene.set.statistics.description: The synthesis of the large ribosomal RNA (rRNA) transcript which encodes several rRNAs, e.g. in mammals 28S, 18S and 5.8S, from a nuclear DNA template transcribed by RNA polymerase I.

gene.set.statistics.name: 5S class rRNA transcription by RNA polymerase III
gene.set.statistics.description: The synthesis of 5S ribosomal RNA (rRNA), or an equivalent rRNA, from a DNA template by RNA polymerase III (Pol III), originating at a type 1 RNA polymerase III promoter.

gene.set.statistics.name: snRNA transcription by RNA polymerase II
gene.set.statistics.description: The synthesis of small nuclear RNA (snRNA) from a DNA template by RNA Polymerase II (Pol II), originating at a Pol II promoter.

gene.set.statistics.name: snRNA transcription by RNA polymerase III
gene.set.statistics.description: The synthesis of small nuclear RNA (snRNA) from a DNA template by RNA Polymerase III (Pol III), originating at a Pol III promoter.

gene.set.statistics.name: tRNA transcription by RNA polymerase III
gene.set.statistics.description: The synthesis of transfer RNA (tRNA) from a DNA template by RNA polymerase III (Pol III), originating at a Pol III promoter.

gene.set.statistics.name: xenobiotic transport
gene.set.statistics.description: The directed movement of a xenobiotic, a compound foreign to living organisms, into, out of or within a cell, or between cells, by means of some agent such as a transporter or pore.

gene.set.statistics.name: glucocorticoid receptor signaling pathway
gene.set.statistics.description: Any series of molecular signals generated as a consequence of a glucocorticoid binding to its receptor.

gene.set.statistics.name: D-serine transport
gene.set.statistics.description: The directed movement of D-serine, the D-enantiomer of 2-amino-3-hydroxypropanoic acid, into, out of or within a cell, or between cells, by means of some agent such as a transporter or pore.

gene.set.statistics.name: regulation of apoptotic process
gene.set.statistics.description: Any process that modulates the occurrence or rate of cell death by apoptotic process.

gene.set.statistics.name: amyloid precursor protein catabolic process
gene.set.statistics.description: The chemical reactions and pathways resulting in the breakdown of amyloid precursor protein (APP), the precursor of amyloid-beta, a glycoprotein associated with Alzheimer's disease.

gene.set.statistics.name: sequestering of actin monomers
gene.set.statistics.description: The selective interaction of actin monomers with specific molecules that inhibit their polymerization by preventing their access to other monomers.

gene.set.statistics.name: negative regulation of Golgi to plasma membrane protein transport
gene.set.statistics.description: Any process that stops, prevents, or reduces the frequency, rate or extent of the transport of proteins from the Golgi to the plasma membrane.

gene.set.statistics.name: positive regulation of Golgi to plasma membrane protein transport
gene.set.statistics.description: Any process that activates or increases the frequency, rate or extent of the transport of proteins from the Golgi to the plasma membrane.

gene.set.statistics.name: Golgi to plasma membrane protein transport
gene.set.statistics.description: The directed movement of proteins from the Golgi to the plasma membrane in transport vesicles that move from the trans-Golgi network to the plasma membrane.

gene.set.statistics.name: camera-type eye development
gene.set.statistics.description: The process whose specific outcome is the progression of the camera-type eye over time, from its formation to the mature structure. The camera-type eye is an organ of sight that receives light through an aperture and focuses it through a lens, projecting it on a photoreceptor field.

gene.set.statistics.name: myeloid dendritic cell differentiation
gene.set.statistics.description: The process in which a monocyte acquires the specialized features of a dendritic cell, an immunocompetent cell of the lymphoid and hemopoietic systems and skin.

gene.set.statistics.name: T cell homeostasis
gene.set.statistics.description: The process of regulating the proliferation and elimination of T cells such that the total number of T cells within a whole or part of an organism is stable over time in the absence of an outside stimulus.

gene.set.statistics.name: regulation of macrophage activation
gene.set.statistics.description: Any process that modulates the frequency or rate of macrophage activation.

gene.set.statistics.name: positive regulation of macrophage activation
gene.set.statistics.description: Any process that stimulates, induces or increases the rate of macrophage activation.

gene.set.statistics.name: tRNA aminoacylation
gene.set.statistics.description: The chemical reactions and pathways by which the various amino acids become bonded to their corresponding tRNAs. The most common route for synthesis of aminoacyl tRNA is by the formation of an ester bond between the 3'-hydroxyl group of the most 3' adenosine of the tRNA and the alpha carboxylic acid  group of an amino acid, usually catalyzed by the cognate aminoacyl-tRNA ligase. A given aminoacyl-tRNA ligase aminoacylates all species of an isoaccepting group of tRNA molecules.

gene.set.statistics.name: ATP-dependent chromatin remodeling
gene.set.statistics.description: Dynamic structural changes to eukaryotic chromatin that require energy from the hydrolysis of ATP, ranging from local changes necessary for transcriptional regulation to global changes necessary for chromosome segregation, mediated by ATP-dependent chromatin-remodelling factors.

gene.set.statistics.name: DNA methylation involved in embryo development
gene.set.statistics.description: The covalent transfer of a methyl group to C-5 of cytosine that contributes to the epigenetic regulation of embryonic gene expression.

gene.set.statistics.name: positive regulation of apoptotic process
gene.set.statistics.description: Any process that activates or increases the frequency, rate or extent of cell death by apoptotic process.

gene.set.statistics.name: negative regulation of apoptotic process
gene.set.statistics.description: Any process that stops, prevents, or reduces the frequency, rate or extent of cell death by apoptotic process.

gene.set.statistics.name: negative regulation of programmed cell death
gene.set.statistics.description: Any process that stops, prevents, or reduces the frequency, rate or extent of programmed cell death, cell death resulting from activation of endogenous cellular processes.

gene.set.statistics.name: positive regulation of catalytic activity
gene.set.statistics.description: Any process that activates or increases the activity of an enzyme.

gene.set.statistics.name: negative regulation of catalytic activity
gene.set.statistics.description: Any process that stops or reduces the activity of an enzyme.

gene.set.statistics.name: regulation of GTPase activity
gene.set.statistics.description: Any process that modulates the rate of GTP hydrolysis by a GTPase.

gene.set.statistics.name: pyrimidine nucleoside salvage
gene.set.statistics.description: Any process that generates a pyrimidine nucleoside, one of a family of organic molecules consisting of a pyrimidine base covalently bonded to a sugar ribose, from derivatives of it, without de novo synthesis.

gene.set.statistics.name: purine-containing compound salvage
gene.set.statistics.description: Any process that generates a purine-containing compound, any nucleobase, nucleoside, nucleotide or nucleic acid that contains a purine base, from derivatives of them without de novo synthesis.

gene.set.statistics.name: hypoxanthine salvage
gene.set.statistics.description: Any process that generates hypoxanthine, 6-hydroxy purine, from derivatives of it without de novo synthesis.

gene.set.statistics.name: receptor clustering
gene.set.statistics.description: The receptor metabolic process that results in grouping of a set of receptors at a cellular location, often to amplify the sensitivity of a signaling response.

gene.set.statistics.name: negative regulation of vascular permeability
gene.set.statistics.description: Any process that reduces the extent to which blood vessels can be pervaded by fluid.

gene.set.statistics.name: regulation of I-kappaB kinase/NF-kappaB signaling
gene.set.statistics.description: Any process that modulates I-kappaB kinase/NF-kappaB signaling.

gene.set.statistics.name: positive regulation of I-kappaB kinase/NF-kappaB signaling
gene.set.statistics.description: Any process that activates or increases the frequency, rate or extent of I-kappaB kinase/NF-kappaB signaling.

gene.set.statistics.name: negative regulation of I-kappaB kinase/NF-kappaB signaling
gene.set.statistics.description: Any process that stops, prevents, or reduces the frequency, rate or extent of -kappaB kinase/NF-kappaB signaling.

gene.set.statistics.name: surfactant homeostasis
gene.set.statistics.description: Any process involved in the maintenance of a steady-state level of the surface-active lipoprotein mixture which coats the alveoli.

gene.set.statistics.name: stress fiber assembly
gene.set.statistics.description: The aggregation, arrangement and bonding together of a set of components to form a stress fiber. A stress fiber is a contractile actin filament bundle that consists of short actin filaments with alternating polarity.

gene.set.statistics.name: entrainment of circadian clock by photoperiod
gene.set.statistics.description: The synchronization of a circadian rhythm to photoperiod, the intermittent cycle of light (day) and dark (night).

gene.set.statistics.name: negative regulation of cysteine-type endopeptidase activity involved in apoptotic process
gene.set.statistics.description: Any process that stops, prevents, or reduces the frequency, rate or extent of a cysteine-type endopeptidase activity involved in the apoptotic process.

gene.set.statistics.name: proteasome-mediated ubiquitin-dependent protein catabolic process
gene.set.statistics.description: The chemical reactions and pathways resulting in the breakdown of a protein or peptide by hydrolysis of its peptide bonds, initiated by the covalent attachment of ubiquitin, and mediated by the proteasome.

gene.set.statistics.name: ubiquitin-dependent protein catabolic process via the multivesicular body sorting pathway
gene.set.statistics.description: The chemical reactions and pathways resulting in the breakdown of a protein or peptide covalently tagged with ubiquitin, via the multivesicular body (MVB) sorting pathway; ubiquitin-tagged proteins are sorted into MVBs, and delivered to a lysosome/vacuole for degradation.

gene.set.statistics.name: peptide catabolic process
gene.set.statistics.description: The chemical reactions and pathways resulting in the breakdown of peptides, compounds of 2 or more (but usually less than 100) amino acids where the alpha carboxyl group of one is bound to the alpha amino group of another.

gene.set.statistics.name: response to amino acid
gene.set.statistics.description: Any process that results in a change in state or activity of a cell or an organism (in terms of movement, secretion, enzyme production, gene expression, etc.) as a result of an amino acid stimulus. An amino acid is a carboxylic acids containing one or more amino groups.

gene.set.statistics.name: proteasome assembly
gene.set.statistics.description: The aggregation, arrangement and bonding together of a mature, active proteasome complex.

gene.set.statistics.name: regulation of protein-containing complex assembly
gene.set.statistics.description: Any process that modulates the frequency, rate or extent of protein complex assembly.

gene.set.statistics.name: positive regulation of potassium ion transport
gene.set.statistics.description: Any process that activates or increases the frequency, rate or extent of the directed movement of potassium ions (K+) into, out of or within a cell, or between cells, by means of some agent such as a transporter or pore.

gene.set.statistics.name: anoikis
gene.set.statistics.description: Apoptosis triggered by inadequate or inappropriate adherence to substrate e.g. after disruption of the interactions between normal epithelial cells and the extracellular matrix.

gene.set.statistics.name: apoptotic cell clearance
gene.set.statistics.description: The recognition and removal of an apoptotic cell by a neighboring cell or by a phagocyte.

gene.set.statistics.name: response to morphine
gene.set.statistics.description: Any process that results in a change in state or activity of a cell or an organism (in terms of movement, secretion, enzyme production, gene expression, etc.) as a result of a morphine stimulus. Morphine is an opioid alkaloid, isolated from opium, with a complex ring structure.

gene.set.statistics.name: response to alkaloid
gene.set.statistics.description: Any process that results in a change in state or activity of a cell or an organism (in terms of movement, secretion, enzyme production, gene expression, etc.) as a result of an alkaloid stimulus. Alkaloids are a large group of nitrogenous substances found in naturally in plants, many of which have extracts that are pharmacologically active.

gene.set.statistics.name: positive regulation of cysteine-type endopeptidase activity involved in apoptotic process
gene.set.statistics.description: Any process that activates or increases the activity of a cysteine-type endopeptidase involved in the apoptotic process.

gene.set.statistics.name: apical junction assembly
gene.set.statistics.description: The formation of an apical junction, a functional unit located near the cell apex at the points of contact between epithelial cells composed of the tight junction, the zonula adherens junction and the desmosomes, by the aggregation, arrangement and bonding together of its constituents.

gene.set.statistics.name: mast cell degranulation
gene.set.statistics.description: The regulated exocytosis of secretory granules containing preformed mediators such as histamine, serotonin, and neutral proteases by a mast cell.

gene.set.statistics.name: regulation of mast cell degranulation
gene.set.statistics.description: Any process that modulates the frequency, rate, or extent of mast cell degranulation.

gene.set.statistics.name: positive regulation of mast cell degranulation
gene.set.statistics.description: Any process that activates or increases the frequency, rate or extent of mast cell degranulation.

gene.set.statistics.name: eosinophil degranulation
gene.set.statistics.description: The regulated exocytosis of secretory granules containing preformed mediators such as major basic protein, eosinophil peroxidase, and eosinophil cationic protein by an eosinophil.

gene.set.statistics.name: positive regulation of eosinophil degranulation
gene.set.statistics.description: Any process that activates or increases the frequency, rate or extent of eosinophil degranulation.

gene.set.statistics.name: neutrophil degranulation
gene.set.statistics.description: The regulated exocytosis of secretory granules containing preformed mediators such as proteases, lipases, and inflammatory mediators by a neutrophil.

gene.set.statistics.name: natural killer cell degranulation
gene.set.statistics.description: The regulated exocytosis of secretory granules containing preformed mediators such as perforin and granzymes by a natural killer cell.

gene.set.statistics.name: response to exogenous dsRNA
gene.set.statistics.description: Any process that results in a change in state or activity of a cell or an organism (in terms of movement, secretion, enzyme production, gene expression, etc.) as a result of an exogenous double-stranded RNA stimulus.

gene.set.statistics.name: protein unfolding
gene.set.statistics.description: The process of assisting in the disassembly of non-covalent linkages in a protein or protein aggregate, often where the proteins are in a non-functional or denatured state.

gene.set.statistics.name: beta selection
gene.set.statistics.description: The process in which successful recombination of a T cell receptor beta chain into a translatable protein coding sequence leads to rescue from apoptosis and subsequent proliferation of an immature T cell.

gene.set.statistics.name: negative regulation of CD4-positive, alpha-beta T cell differentiation
gene.set.statistics.description: Any process that stops, prevents, or reduces the frequency, rate, or extent of CD4-positive, alpha-beta T cell differentiation.

gene.set.statistics.name: positive regulation of DNA binding
gene.set.statistics.description: Any process that increases the frequency, rate or extent of DNA binding. DNA binding is any process in which a gene product interacts selectively with DNA (deoxyribonucleic acid).

gene.set.statistics.name: negative regulation of DNA binding
gene.set.statistics.description: Any process that stops or reduces the frequency, rate or extent of DNA binding. DNA binding is any process in which a gene product interacts selectively with DNA (deoxyribonucleic acid).

gene.set.statistics.name: regulation of protein binding
gene.set.statistics.description: Any process that modulates the frequency, rate or extent of protein binding.

gene.set.statistics.name: skeletal muscle tissue regeneration
gene.set.statistics.description: The regrowth of skeletal muscle tissue to repair injured or damaged muscle fibers in the postnatal stage.

gene.set.statistics.name: regulation of MAP kinase activity
gene.set.statistics.description: Any process that modulates the frequency, rate or extent of MAP kinase activity.

gene.set.statistics.name: positive regulation of MAP kinase activity
gene.set.statistics.description: Any process that activates or increases the frequency, rate or extent of MAP kinase activity.

gene.set.statistics.name: negative regulation of MAP kinase activity
gene.set.statistics.description: Any process that stops, prevents, or reduces the frequency, rate or extent of MAP kinase activity.

gene.set.statistics.name: regulation of MAPK cascade
gene.set.statistics.description: Any process that modulates the frequency, rate or extent of signal transduction mediated by the MAP kinase (MAPK) cascade.

gene.set.statistics.name: negative regulation of MAPK cascade
gene.set.statistics.description: Any process that stops, prevents, or reduces the frequency, rate or extent of signal transduction mediated by the MAPKKK cascade.

gene.set.statistics.name: positive regulation of MAPK cascade
gene.set.statistics.description: Any process that activates or increases the frequency, rate or extent of signal transduction mediated by the MAPK cascade.

gene.set.statistics.name: negative regulation of DNA-binding transcription factor activity
gene.set.statistics.description: Any process that stops, prevents, or reduces the frequency, rate or extent of the activity of a transcription factor, any factor involved in the initiation or regulation of transcription.

gene.set.statistics.name: response to peptide hormone
gene.set.statistics.description: Any process that results in a change in state or activity of a cell or an organism (in terms of movement, secretion, enzyme production, gene expression, etc.) as a result of a peptide hormone stimulus. A peptide hormone is any of a class of peptides that are secreted into the blood stream and have endocrine functions in living animals.

gene.set.statistics.name: regulation of pentose-phosphate shunt
gene.set.statistics.description: Any process that modulates the frequency, rate or extent of the pentose-phosphate shunt, the process in which glucose is oxidized, coupled to NADPH synthesis.

gene.set.statistics.name: regulation of cellular respiration
gene.set.statistics.description: Any process that modulates the frequency, rate or extent of cellular respiration, the enzymatic release of energy from organic compounds.

gene.set.statistics.name: regulation of ATPase activity
gene.set.statistics.description: Any process that modulates the rate of ATP hydrolysis by an ATPase.

gene.set.statistics.name: pigmentation
gene.set.statistics.description: The accumulation of pigment in an organism, tissue or cell, either by increased deposition or by increased number of cells.

gene.set.statistics.name: regulation of RNA splicing
gene.set.statistics.description: Any process that modulates the frequency, rate or extent of RNA splicing, the process of removing sections of the primary RNA transcript to remove sequences not present in the mature form of the RNA and joining the remaining sections to form the mature form of the RNA.

gene.set.statistics.name: histone exchange
gene.set.statistics.description: The replacement, within chromatin, of resident histones or histone subunits with alternative, sometimes variant, histones or subunits.

gene.set.statistics.name: regulation of mRNA stability
gene.set.statistics.description: Any process that modulates the propensity of mRNA molecules to degradation. Includes processes that both stabilize and destabilize mRNAs.

gene.set.statistics.name: protein kinase B signaling
gene.set.statistics.description: A series of reactions, mediated by the intracellular serine/threonine kinase protein kinase B (also called AKT), which occurs as a result of a single trigger reaction or compound.

gene.set.statistics.name: mitochondrial DNA repair
gene.set.statistics.description: The process of restoring mitochondrial DNA after damage.

gene.set.statistics.name: positive regulation of JUN kinase activity
gene.set.statistics.description: Any process that activates or increases the frequency, rate or extent of JUN kinase activity.

gene.set.statistics.name: negative regulation of JUN kinase activity
gene.set.statistics.description: Any process that stops, prevents, or reduces the frequency, rate or extent of JUN kinase activity.

gene.set.statistics.name: positive regulation of DNA damage response, signal transduction by p53 class mediator
gene.set.statistics.description: Any process that activates, maintains or increases the rate of the cascade of processes induced by the cell cycle regulator phosphoprotein p53, or an equivalent protein, in response to the detection of DNA damage.

gene.set.statistics.name: regulation of neuron apoptotic process
gene.set.statistics.description: Any process that modulates the occurrence or rate of cell death by apoptotic process in neurons.

gene.set.statistics.name: negative regulation of neuron apoptotic process
gene.set.statistics.description: Any process that stops, prevents, or reduces the frequency, rate or extent of cell death by apoptotic process in neurons.

gene.set.statistics.name: positive regulation of neuron apoptotic process
gene.set.statistics.description: Any process that activates or increases the frequency, rate or extent of cell death of neurons by apoptotic process.

gene.set.statistics.name: blood vessel endothelial cell migration
gene.set.statistics.description: The orderly movement of an endothelial cell into the extracellular matrix in order to form new blood vessels during angiogenesis.

gene.set.statistics.name: regulation of blood vessel endothelial cell migration
gene.set.statistics.description: Any process that modulates the frequency, rate or extent of the migration of the endothelial cells of blood vessels.

gene.set.statistics.name: positive regulation of blood vessel endothelial cell migration
gene.set.statistics.description: Any process that activates or increases the frequency, rate or extent of the migration of the endothelial cells of blood vessels.

gene.set.statistics.name: negative regulation of blood vessel endothelial cell migration
gene.set.statistics.description: Any process that stops, prevents, or reduces the frequency, rate or extent of the migration of the endothelial cells of blood vessels.

gene.set.statistics.name: endothelial cell migration
gene.set.statistics.description: The orderly movement of an endothelial cell into the extracellular matrix to form an endothelium.

gene.set.statistics.name: positive regulation of GTPase activity
gene.set.statistics.description: Any process that activates or increases the activity of a GTPase.

gene.set.statistics.name: positive regulation of phosphatidylinositol 3-kinase activity
gene.set.statistics.description: Any process that activates or increases the frequency, rate or extent of phosphatidylinositol 3-kinase activity.

gene.set.statistics.name: positive regulation of insulin-like growth factor receptor signaling pathway
gene.set.statistics.description: Any process that increases the frequency, rate or extent of insulin-like growth factor receptor signaling.

gene.set.statistics.name: skin development
gene.set.statistics.description: The process whose specific outcome is the progression of the skin over time, from its formation to the mature structure. The skin is the external membranous integument of an animal. In vertebrates the skin generally consists of two layers, an outer nonsensitive and nonvascular epidermis (cuticle or skarfskin) composed of cells which are constantly growing and multiplying in the deeper, and being thrown off in the superficial layers, as well as an inner vascular dermis (cutis, corium or true skin) composed mostly of connective tissue.

gene.set.statistics.name: skin morphogenesis
gene.set.statistics.description: The process in which the anatomical structures of the skin are generated and organized. The skin is the external membranous integument of an animal. In vertebrates the skin generally consists of two layers, an outer nonsensitive and nonvascular epidermis (cuticle or skarfskin) composed of cells which are constantly growing and multiplying in the deeper, and being thrown off in the superficial layers, as well as an inner, sensitive and vascular dermis (cutis, corium or true skin) composed mostly of connective tissue.

gene.set.statistics.name: regulation of carbohydrate utilization
gene.set.statistics.description: Any process that modulates the frequency, rate or extent of carbohydrate utilization.

gene.set.statistics.name: regulation of DNA-templated transcription in response to stress
gene.set.statistics.description: Modulation of the frequency, rate or extent of transcription from a DNA template as a result of a stimulus indicating the organism is under stress. The stress is usually, but not necessarily, exogenous (e.g. temperature, humidity, ionizing radiation).

gene.set.statistics.name: cortical microtubule organization
gene.set.statistics.description: A process that is carried out at the cellular level which results in the assembly, arrangement of constituent parts, or disassembly of structures formed of microtubules and associated proteins in the cell cortex, i.e. just beneath the plasma membrane of a cell.

gene.set.statistics.name: response to estrogen
gene.set.statistics.description: Any process that results in a change in state or activity of a cell or an organism (in terms of movement, secretion, enzyme production, gene expression, etc.) as a result of stimulus by an estrogen, C18 steroid hormones that can stimulate the development of female sexual characteristics.

gene.set.statistics.name: linoleic acid metabolic process
gene.set.statistics.description: The chemical reactions and pathways involving linoleic acid, an unsaturated omega-6 fatty acid that has the molecular formula C18H32O2.

gene.set.statistics.name: engulfment of apoptotic cell
gene.set.statistics.description: The removal of the apoptotic cell by phagocytosis, by a neighboring cell or by a phagocyte.

gene.set.statistics.name: mitochondrial fragmentation involved in apoptotic process
gene.set.statistics.description: The change in the morphology of the mitochondria in an apoptotic cell from a highly branched network to a fragmented vesicular form.

gene.set.statistics.name: regulation of phosphoprotein phosphatase activity
gene.set.statistics.description: Any process that modulates the frequency, rate or extent of phosphoprotein phosphatase activity, the catalysis of the hydrolysis of phosphate from a phosphoprotein.

gene.set.statistics.name: post-translational protein modification
gene.set.statistics.description: The process of covalently altering one or more amino acids in a protein after the protein has been completely translated and released from the ribosome.

gene.set.statistics.name: reverse cholesterol transport
gene.set.statistics.description: The directed movement of peripheral cell cholesterol, cholest-5-en-3-beta-ol, towards the liver for catabolism.

gene.set.statistics.name: negative regulation by host of viral transcription
gene.set.statistics.description: Any process in which a host organism stops, prevents, or reduces the frequency, rate or extent of viral transcription.

gene.set.statistics.name: positive regulation by host of viral transcription
gene.set.statistics.description: Any process in which a host organism activates or increases the frequency, rate or extent of viral transcription, the synthesis of either RNA on a template of DNA or DNA on a template of RNA.

gene.set.statistics.name: exonucleolytic catabolism of deadenylated mRNA
gene.set.statistics.description: The chemical reactions and pathways resulting in the breakdown of the transcript body of a nuclear-transcribed mRNA that occurs when the ends are not protected by the 3'-poly(A) tail.

gene.set.statistics.name: regulation of cAMP-mediated signaling
gene.set.statistics.description: Any process which modulates the frequency, rate or extent of cAMP-mediated signaling, a series of molecular signals in which a cell uses cyclic AMP to convert an extracellular signal into a response.

gene.set.statistics.name: histone H3 acetylation
gene.set.statistics.description: The modification of histone H3 by the addition of an acetyl group.

gene.set.statistics.name: histone H4 acetylation
gene.set.statistics.description: The modification of histone H4 by the addition of an acetyl group.

gene.set.statistics.name: histone H2A acetylation
gene.set.statistics.description: The modification of histone H2A by the addition of an acetyl group.

gene.set.statistics.name: histone H4-K5 acetylation
gene.set.statistics.description: The modification of histone H4 by the addition of an acetyl group to a lysine residue at position 5 of the histone.

gene.set.statistics.name: histone H4-K8 acetylation
gene.set.statistics.description: The modification of histone H4 by the addition of an acetyl group to a lysine residue at position 8 of the histone.

gene.set.statistics.name: histone H4-K16 acetylation
gene.set.statistics.description: The modification of histone H4 by the addition of an acetyl group to a lysine residue at position 16 of the histone.

gene.set.statistics.name: histone H4-R3 methylation
gene.set.statistics.description: The modification of histone H4 by addition of a methyl group to arginine at position 3 of the histone.

gene.set.statistics.name: modulation by symbiont of host process
gene.set.statistics.description: The process in which a symbiont organism effects a change in the structure or processes of its host organism.

gene.set.statistics.name: hypomethylation of CpG island
gene.set.statistics.description: An decrease in the epigenetic methylation of cytosine and adenosine residues in a CpG island in DNA. CpG islands are genomic regions that contain a high frequency of the CG dinucleotide and are often associated with the transcription start site of genes.

gene.set.statistics.name: regulation of DNA methylation
gene.set.statistics.description: Any process that modulates the frequency, rate or extent of the covalent transfer of a methyl group to either N-6 of adenine or C-5 or N-4 of cytosine.

gene.set.statistics.name: regulation of anion transport
gene.set.statistics.description: Any process that modulates the frequency, rate or extent of the directed movement of anions, atoms or small molecules with a net negative charge into, out of or within a cell, or between cells, by means of some agent such as a transporter or pore.

gene.set.statistics.name: 'de novo' UMP biosynthetic process
gene.set.statistics.description: The chemical reactions and pathways resulting in the formation of UMP, uridine monophosphate, starting with the synthesis of (S)-dihydroorotate from bicarbonate; UMP biosynthesis may either occur via reduction by quinone, NAD(+) or oxygen.

gene.set.statistics.name: UMP salvage
gene.set.statistics.description: Any process which produces UMP, uridine monophosphate, from derivatives of it (e.g. cytidine, uridine, cytosine) without de novo synthesis.

gene.set.statistics.name: AMP salvage
gene.set.statistics.description: The chemical reactions and pathways resulting in the formation of adenosine monophosphate (AMP) from derivatives of it (either adenine, ADP or adenosine 3',5'-bisphosphate) without de novo synthesis.

gene.set.statistics.name: 'de novo' CTP biosynthetic process
gene.set.statistics.description: The chemical reactions and pathways resulting in the formation of cytidine 5'-triphosphate (CTP) from simpler components.

gene.set.statistics.name: cellular protein catabolic process
gene.set.statistics.description: The chemical reactions and pathways resulting in the breakdown of a protein by individual cells.

gene.set.statistics.name: cellular carbohydrate metabolic process
gene.set.statistics.description: The chemical reactions and pathways involving carbohydrates, any of a group of organic compounds based of the general formula Cx(H2O)y, as carried out by individual cells.

gene.set.statistics.name: cellular protein metabolic process
gene.set.statistics.description: The chemical reactions and pathways involving a specific protein, rather than of proteins in general, occurring at the level of an individual cell. Includes cellular protein modification.

gene.set.statistics.name: wound healing, spreading of cells
gene.set.statistics.description: The migration of a cell along or through a wound gap that contributes to the reestablishment of a continuous surface.

gene.set.statistics.name: cellular response to leptin stimulus
gene.set.statistics.description: Any process that results in a change in state or activity of a cell (in terms of movement, secretion, enzyme production, gene expression, etc.) as a result of a leptin stimulus. Leptin is a hormone manufactured primarily in the adipocytes of white adipose tissue, and the level of circulating leptin is directly proportional to the total amount of fat in the body. It plays a key role in regulating energy intake and energy expenditure, including appetite and metabolism.

gene.set.statistics.name: response to leptin
gene.set.statistics.description: Any process that results in a change in state or activity of a cell or an organism (in terms of movement, secretion, enzyme production, gene expression, etc.) as a result of a leptin stimulus. Leptin is a hormone manufactured primarily in the adipocytes of white adipose tissue, and the level of circulating leptin is directly proportional to the total amount of fat in the body. It plays a key role in regulating energy intake and energy expenditure, including appetite and metabolism].

gene.set.statistics.name: cell-cell adhesion mediated by cadherin
gene.set.statistics.description: The attachment of one cell to another cell via a cadherin, transmembrane proteins having repeating extracellular calcium ion binding domains.

gene.set.statistics.name: cellular response to fibroblast growth factor stimulus
gene.set.statistics.description: Any process that results in a change in state or activity of a cell (in terms of movement, secretion, enzyme production, gene expression, etc.) as a result of an fibroblast growth factor stimulus.

gene.set.statistics.name: macropinocytosis
gene.set.statistics.description: An endocytosis process that results in the uptake of liquid material by cells from their external environment by the 'ruffling' of the cell membrane to form heterogeneously sized intracellular vesicles called macropinosomes, which can be up to 5 micrometers in size.

gene.set.statistics.name: glucose import in response to insulin stimulus
gene.set.statistics.description: The directed movement of the hexose monosaccharide glucose into a cell as a result of an insulin stimulus.

gene.set.statistics.name: negative regulation of protein kinase activity by regulation of protein phosphorylation
gene.set.statistics.description: The stopping, prevention, or reduction in frequency, rate or extent of protein kinase activity as a result of regulating the phosphorylation status of that protein kinase.

gene.set.statistics.name: adhesion of symbiont to host
gene.set.statistics.description: The attachment of a symbiont to its host via adhesion molecules, general stickiness etc., either directly or indirectly. The host is defined as the larger of the organisms involved in a symbiotic interaction.

gene.set.statistics.name: entry into host
gene.set.statistics.description: Entry of a symbiont into the body, tissues, or cells of a host organism as part of the symbiont life cycle. The host is defined as the larger of the organisms involved in a symbiotic interaction.

gene.set.statistics.name: regulation of mitochondrial mRNA stability
gene.set.statistics.description: Any process that modulates the propensity of mitochondrial mRNA molecules to degradation. Includes processes that both stabilize and destabilize mitochondrial mRNAs.

gene.set.statistics.name: long-chain fatty acid import into cell
gene.set.statistics.description: The directed movement of a long-chain fatty acid from outside of a cell into a cell. This may occur via transport across the plasma membrane or via endocytosis. A long-chain fatty acid is a fatty acid with a chain length between C13 and C22.

gene.set.statistics.name: [2Fe-2S] cluster assembly
gene.set.statistics.description: The incorporation of two iron atoms and two sulfur atoms into an iron-sulfur cluster.

gene.set.statistics.name: daunorubicin metabolic process
gene.set.statistics.description: The chemical reactions and pathways involving daunorubicin, a chemotherapeutic of the anthracycline family that is given as a treatment for some types of cancer.

gene.set.statistics.name: tooth eruption
gene.set.statistics.description: The tooth development process in which the teeth enter the mouth and become visible.

gene.set.statistics.name: cell cycle phase transition
gene.set.statistics.description: The cell cycle process by which a cell commits to entering the next cell cycle phase.

gene.set.statistics.name: cilium organization
gene.set.statistics.description: A process that is carried out at the cellular level which results in the assembly, arrangement of constituent parts, or disassembly of a cilium, a specialized eukaryotic organelle that consists of a filiform extrusion of the cell surface. Each cilium is bounded by an extrusion of the cytoplasmic membrane, and contains a regular longitudinal array of microtubules, anchored basally in a centriole.

gene.set.statistics.name: positive regulation by host of viral release from host cell
gene.set.statistics.description: A process in which a host organism activates or increases the frequency, rate or extent of the release of a virus with which it is infected, from its cells.

gene.set.statistics.name: positive regulation by host of viral process
gene.set.statistics.description: A process in which a host organism activates or increases the frequency, rate or extent of the release of a process being mediated by a virus with which it is infected.

gene.set.statistics.name: G-quadruplex DNA unwinding
gene.set.statistics.description: The process by which G-quadruplex (also known as G4) DNA, which is a four-stranded DNA structure held together by guanine base pairing, is unwound or 'melted'.

gene.set.statistics.name: negative regulation by host of viral genome replication
gene.set.statistics.description: A process in which a host organism stops, prevents or reduces the frequency, rate or extent of viral genome replication.

gene.set.statistics.name: positive regulation by host of viral genome replication
gene.set.statistics.description: A process in which a host organism activates or increases the frequency, rate or extent of  viral genome replication.

gene.set.statistics.name: modulation by host of viral RNA genome replication
gene.set.statistics.description: A process in which a host organism modulates the frequency, rate or extent of viral RNA genome replication.

gene.set.statistics.name: estrous cycle
gene.set.statistics.description: A type of ovulation cycle, which occurs in most mammalian therian females, where the endometrium is resorbed if pregnancy does not occur.

gene.set.statistics.name: DNA deamination
gene.set.statistics.description: The removal of an amino group from a nucleotide base in DNA. An example is the deamination of cytosine to produce uracil.

gene.set.statistics.name: depurination
gene.set.statistics.description: The disruption of the bond between the sugar in the backbone and the A or G base, causing the base to be removed and leaving a depurinated sugar.

gene.set.statistics.name: actin nucleation
gene.set.statistics.description: The initial step in the formation of an actin filament, in which actin monomers combine to form a new filament. Nucleation is slow relative to the subsequent addition of more monomers to extend the filament.

gene.set.statistics.name: negative regulation of nitric oxide biosynthetic process
gene.set.statistics.description: Any process that stops, prevents, or reduces the frequency, rate or extent of the chemical reactions and pathways resulting in the formation of nitric oxide.

gene.set.statistics.name: early endosome to late endosome transport
gene.set.statistics.description: The directed movement of substances, in membrane-bounded vesicles, from the early sorting endosomes to the late sorting endosomes; transport occurs along microtubules and can be experimentally blocked with microtubule-depolymerizing drugs.

gene.set.statistics.name: protein insertion into mitochondrial inner membrane
gene.set.statistics.description: The processes mediating the insertion of proteins into the mitochondrial inner membrane. Mitochondrial inner membrane proteins can get inserted from the cytosol, by crossing the outer membrane and being guided by an inner membrane translocase complex into their final destination in the inner membrane. Some proteins present in the intermembrane space can get inserted into the inner mitochondrial membrane. Finally, some proteins are inserted into the inner membrane from the matrix side of the membrane.

gene.set.statistics.name: protein insertion into mitochondrial outer membrane
gene.set.statistics.description: The process comprising the insertion of proteins from outside the organelle into the mitochondrial outer membrane, mediated by large outer membrane translocase complexes.

gene.set.statistics.name: protein import into mitochondrial intermembrane space
gene.set.statistics.description: The import of proteins into the space between the inner and outer mitochondrial membranes.

gene.set.statistics.name: protein import into peroxisome membrane
gene.set.statistics.description: The targeting of proteins into the peroxisomal membrane. The process is not well understood, but both signals and mechanism differ from those involved in peroxisomal matrix protein import.

gene.set.statistics.name: protein targeting to ER
gene.set.statistics.description: The process of directing proteins towards the endoplasmic reticulum (ER) using signals contained within the protein. One common mechanism uses a 16- to 30-residue signal sequence, typically located at the N-terminus of the protein and containing positively charged amino acids followed by a continuous stretch of hydrophobic residues, which directs the ribosome to the ER membrane and initiates transport of the growing polypeptide across the ER membrane.

gene.set.statistics.name: protein insertion into ER membrane
gene.set.statistics.description: The process that results in incorporation of a protein into an endoplasmic reticulum (ER) membrane. It depends on specific topogenic sequences of amino acids that ensure that a protein acquires the proper orientation during its insertion into the ER membrane.

gene.set.statistics.name: protein retention in Golgi apparatus
gene.set.statistics.description: The retention of proteins within the Golgi apparatus. Golgi-localized carbohydrate-modifying enzymes have a short N-terminal domain that faces the cytosol, a single transmembrane alpha helix, and a large C-terminal domain that faces the Golgi lumen and that contains the catalytic site. How the membrane-spanning alpha helix in a Golgi enzyme causes its localization and prevents its movement to the plasma membrane is not known.

gene.set.statistics.name: constitutive secretory pathway
gene.set.statistics.description: A process of exocytosis found in all eukaryotic cells, in which transport vesicles destined for the plasma membrane leave the trans-Golgi network in a steady stream. Upon exocytosis, the membrane proteins and lipids in these vesicles provide new components for the plasma membrane, and the soluble proteins inside the vesicles are released into the extracellular space.

gene.set.statistics.name: regulated exocytosis
gene.set.statistics.description: A process of exocytosis in which soluble proteins and other substances are initially stored in secretory vesicles for later release. It is found mainly in cells that are specialized for secreting products such as hormones, neurotransmitters, or digestive enzymes rapidly on demand.

gene.set.statistics.name: transcytosis
gene.set.statistics.description: The directed movement of endocytosed material through the cell and its exocytosis from the plasma membrane at the opposite side.

gene.set.statistics.name: T-helper 1 cell differentiation
gene.set.statistics.description: The process in which a relatively unspecialized T cell acquires the specialized features of a T-helper 1 (Th1) cell. A Th1 cell is a CD4-positive, alpha-beta T cell that has the phenotype T-bet-positive and produces interferon-gamma.

gene.set.statistics.name: regulation of viral genome replication
gene.set.statistics.description: Any process that modulates the frequency, rate or extent of viral genome replication.

gene.set.statistics.name: positive regulation of viral genome replication
gene.set.statistics.description: Any process that activates or increases the frequency, rate or extent of viral genome replication.

gene.set.statistics.name: negative regulation of viral genome replication
gene.set.statistics.description: Any process that stops, prevents, or reduces the frequency, rate or extent of viral genome replication.

gene.set.statistics.name: innate immune response
gene.set.statistics.description: Innate immune responses are defense responses mediated by germline encoded components that directly recognize components of potential pathogens.

gene.set.statistics.name: regulation of innate immune response
gene.set.statistics.description: Any process that modulates the frequency, rate or extent of the innate immune response, the organism's first line of defense against infection.

gene.set.statistics.name: positive regulation of innate immune response
gene.set.statistics.description: Any process that activates or increases the frequency, rate or extent of the innate immune response, the organism's first line of defense against infection.

gene.set.statistics.name: intermediate filament cytoskeleton organization
gene.set.statistics.description: A process that is carried out at the cellular level which results in the assembly, arrangement of constituent parts, or disassembly of cytoskeletal structures comprising intermediate filaments and their associated proteins.

gene.set.statistics.name: intermediate filament organization
gene.set.statistics.description: Control of the spatial distribution of intermediate filaments; includes organizing filaments into meshworks, bundles, or other structures, as by cross-linking.

gene.set.statistics.name: intermediate filament bundle assembly
gene.set.statistics.description: The formation of the bundles of intermediate filaments. Intermediate filament-associated proteins (IFAPs) cross-link intermediate filaments with one another, forming a bundle or a network, and with other cell structures, including the plasma membrane. The organization of intermediate filaments and their supportive function in various cells types depends in large part on their linkage to other cell structures via IFAPs.

gene.set.statistics.name: protein neddylation
gene.set.statistics.description: Covalent attachment of the ubiquitin-like protein NEDD8 (RUB1) to another protein.

gene.set.statistics.name: meiotic chromosome segregation
gene.set.statistics.description: The process in which genetic material, in the form of chromosomes, is organized into specific structures and then physically separated and apportioned to two or more sets during M phase of the meiotic cell cycle.

gene.set.statistics.name: cell fate commitment
gene.set.statistics.description: The commitment of cells to specific cell fates and their capacity to differentiate into particular kinds of cells. Positional information is established through protein signals that emanate from a localized source within a cell (the initial one-cell zygote) or within a developmental field.

gene.set.statistics.name: apical protein localization
gene.set.statistics.description: Any process in which a protein is transported to, or maintained in, apical regions of the cell.

gene.set.statistics.name: establishment of protein localization
gene.set.statistics.description: The directed movement of a protein to a specific location.

gene.set.statistics.name: isotype switching
gene.set.statistics.description: The switching of activated B cells from IgM biosynthesis to biosynthesis of other isotypes of immunoglobulin, accomplished through a recombination process involving an intrachromosomal deletion involving switch regions that reside 5' of each constant region gene segment in the immunoglobulin heavy chain locus.

gene.set.statistics.name: establishment or maintenance of epithelial cell apical/basal polarity
gene.set.statistics.description: Any cellular process that results in the specification, formation or maintenance of the apicobasal polarity of an epithelial cell.

gene.set.statistics.name: establishment of epithelial cell apical/basal polarity
gene.set.statistics.description: The specification and formation of the apicobasal polarity of an epithelial cell.

gene.set.statistics.name: maintenance of epithelial cell apical/basal polarity
gene.set.statistics.description: The maintenance of the apicobasal polarity of an epithelial cell.

gene.set.statistics.name: establishment of neuroblast polarity
gene.set.statistics.description: The specification and formation of the apicobasal polarity of a neuroblast cell, a progenitor of the central nervous system.

gene.set.statistics.name: sarcomere organization
gene.set.statistics.description: The myofibril assembly process that results in the organization of muscle actomyosin into sarcomeres. The sarcomere is the repeating unit of a myofibril in a muscle cell, composed of an array of overlapping thick and thin filaments between two adjacent Z discs.

gene.set.statistics.name: cell-cell junction organization
gene.set.statistics.description: A process that is carried out at the cellular level which results in the assembly, arrangement of constituent parts, or disassembly of a cell-cell junction. A cell-cell junction is a specialized region of connection between two cells.

gene.set.statistics.name: mRNA cis splicing, via spliceosome
gene.set.statistics.description: The joining together, after removal of an intervening sequence composed of one or more introns, of two segments of the same RNA molecule via spliceosomal catalysis to produce an mRNA composed only of exon sequences that all came from the same primary transcript.

gene.set.statistics.name: leukocyte activation
gene.set.statistics.description: A change in morphology and behavior of a leukocyte resulting from exposure to a specific antigen, mitogen, cytokine, cellular ligand, or soluble factor.

gene.set.statistics.name: carnitine biosynthetic process
gene.set.statistics.description: The chemical reactions and pathways resulting in the formation of carnitine (hydroxy-trimethyl aminobutyric acid), a compound that participates in the transfer of acyl groups across the inner mitochondrial membrane.

gene.set.statistics.name: cellular respiration
gene.set.statistics.description: The enzymatic release of energy from inorganic and organic compounds (especially carbohydrates and fats) which either requires oxygen (aerobic respiration) or does not (anaerobic respiration).

gene.set.statistics.name: positive regulation of MHC class I biosynthetic process
gene.set.statistics.description: Any process that activates or increases the frequency, rate or extent of the chemical reactions and pathways resulting in the formation of MHC class I.

gene.set.statistics.name: regulation of nitric oxide biosynthetic process
gene.set.statistics.description: Any process that modulates the frequency, rate or extent of the chemical reactions and pathways resulting in the formation of nitric oxide.

gene.set.statistics.name: positive regulation of nitric oxide biosynthetic process
gene.set.statistics.description: Any process that activates or increases the frequency, rate or extent of the chemical reactions and pathways resulting in the formation of nitric oxide.

gene.set.statistics.name: myoblast differentiation
gene.set.statistics.description: The process in which a relatively unspecialized cell acquires specialized features of a myoblast. A myoblast is a mononucleate cell type that, by fusion with other myoblasts, gives rise to the myotubes that eventually develop into striated muscle fibers.

gene.set.statistics.name: endothelial cell differentiation
gene.set.statistics.description: The process in which a mesodermal, bone marrow or neural crest cell acquires specialized features of an endothelial cell, a thin flattened cell. A layer of such cells lines the inside surfaces of body cavities, blood vessels, and lymph vessels, making up the endothelium.

gene.set.statistics.name: bone resorption
gene.set.statistics.description: The process in which specialized cells known as osteoclasts degrade the organic and inorganic portions of bone, and endocytose and transport the degradation products.

gene.set.statistics.name: cell redox homeostasis
gene.set.statistics.description: Any process that maintains the redox environment of a cell or compartment within a cell.

gene.set.statistics.name: response to ethanol
gene.set.statistics.description: Any process that results in a change in state or activity of a cell or an organism (in terms of movement, secretion, enzyme production, gene expression, etc.) as a result of an ethanol stimulus.

gene.set.statistics.name: photoreceptor cell maintenance
gene.set.statistics.description: Any process preventing the degeneration of the photoreceptor, a specialized cell type that is sensitive to light.

gene.set.statistics.name: mast cell activation

gene.set.statistics.name: positive regulation of dopamine metabolic process
gene.set.statistics.description: Any process that activates or increases the frequency, rate or extent of the chemical reactions and pathways involving dopamine.

gene.set.statistics.name: positive regulation of striated muscle contraction
gene.set.statistics.description: Any process that activates or increases the frequency, rate or extent of striated muscle contraction.

gene.set.statistics.name: regulation of embryonic development
gene.set.statistics.description: Any process that modulates the frequency, rate or extent of embryonic development.

gene.set.statistics.name: negative regulation of activated T cell proliferation
gene.set.statistics.description: Any process that stops, prevents or reduces the rate or extent of activated T cell proliferation.

gene.set.statistics.name: AMP metabolic process
gene.set.statistics.description: The chemical reactions and pathways involving AMP, adenosine monophosphate.

gene.set.statistics.name: ATP metabolic process
gene.set.statistics.description: The chemical reactions and pathways involving ATP, adenosine triphosphate, a universally important coenzyme and enzyme regulator.

gene.set.statistics.name: GMP metabolic process
gene.set.statistics.description: The chemical reactions and pathways involving GMP, guanosine monophosphate.

gene.set.statistics.name: GMP catabolic process
gene.set.statistics.description: The chemical reactions and pathways resulting in the breakdown of GMP, guanosine monophosphate.

gene.set.statistics.name: GTP metabolic process
gene.set.statistics.description: The chemical reactions and pathways involving GTP, guanosine triphosphate.

gene.set.statistics.name: IMP metabolic process
gene.set.statistics.description: The chemical reactions and pathways involving IMP, inosine monophosphate.

gene.set.statistics.name: cAMP metabolic process
gene.set.statistics.description: The chemical reactions and pathways involving the nucleotide cAMP (cyclic AMP, adenosine 3',5'-cyclophosphate).

gene.set.statistics.name: pyrimidine nucleoside biosynthetic process
gene.set.statistics.description: The chemical reactions and pathways resulting in the formation of one of a family of organic molecules consisting of a pyrimidine base covalently bonded to a sugar ribose (a ribonucleoside) or deoxyribose (a deoxyribonucleoside).

gene.set.statistics.name: pyrimidine nucleoside catabolic process
gene.set.statistics.description: The chemical reactions and pathways resulting in the breakdown of one of a family of organic molecules consisting of a pyrimidine base covalently bonded to a sugar ribose (a ribonucleoside) or deoxyribose (a deoxyribonucleoside).

gene.set.statistics.name: tetrahydrobiopterin metabolic process
gene.set.statistics.description: The chemical reactions and pathways involving tetrahydrobiopterin, the reduced form of biopterin (2-amino-4-hydroxy-6-(1,2-dihydroxypropyl)-pteridine). It functions as a hydroxylation coenzyme, e.g. in the conversion of phenylalanine to tyrosine.

gene.set.statistics.name: glyceraldehyde-3-phosphate biosynthetic process
gene.set.statistics.description: The chemical reactions and pathways resulting in the formation of glyceraldehyde-3-phosphate, an important intermediate in glycolysis.

gene.set.statistics.name: D-gluconate catabolic process
gene.set.statistics.description: The chemical reactions and pathways resulting in the breakdown of D-gluconate, the anion of D-gluconic acid, the aldonic acid derived from glucose.

gene.set.statistics.name: nitric oxide metabolic process
gene.set.statistics.description: The chemical reactions and pathways involving nitric oxide, nitrogen monoxide (NO), a colorless gas only slightly soluble in water.

gene.set.statistics.name: aflatoxin metabolic process
gene.set.statistics.description: The chemical reactions and pathways involving aflatoxin, a fungal metabolite found as a contaminant in moldy grains that induces liver cancer. Aflatoxin induces a G to T transversion at codon 249 of p53, leading to its inactivation. Aflatoxin is converted to a chemical carcinogen by P450.

gene.set.statistics.name: formaldehyde catabolic process
gene.set.statistics.description: The chemical reactions and pathways resulting in the breakdown of formaldehyde (methanal, H2C=O), the simplest aldehyde.

gene.set.statistics.name: phosphocreatine biosynthetic process
gene.set.statistics.description: The chemical reactions and pathways resulting in the formation of phosphocreatine, a phosphagen of creatine which is synthesized and broken down by creatine phosphokinase.

gene.set.statistics.name: negative regulation of fatty acid oxidation
gene.set.statistics.description: Any process that stops, prevents, or reduces the frequency, rate or extent of fatty acid oxidation.

gene.set.statistics.name: regulation of glucose import
gene.set.statistics.description: Any process that modulates the frequency, rate or extent of the import of the hexose monosaccharide glucose into a cell or organelle.

gene.set.statistics.name: regulation of JNK cascade
gene.set.statistics.description: Any process that modulates the frequency, rate or extent of signal transduction mediated by the JNK cascade.

gene.set.statistics.name: negative regulation of JNK cascade
gene.set.statistics.description: Any process that stops, prevents, or reduces the frequency, rate or extent of signal transduction mediated by the JNK cascade.

gene.set.statistics.name: positive regulation of JNK cascade
gene.set.statistics.description: Any process that activates or increases the frequency, rate or extent of signal transduction mediated by the JNK cascade.

gene.set.statistics.name: acetyl-CoA catabolic process
gene.set.statistics.description: The chemical reactions and pathways resulting in the breakdown of acetyl-CoA, a derivative of coenzyme A in which the sulfhydryl group is acetylated.

gene.set.statistics.name: ribose phosphate biosynthetic process
gene.set.statistics.description: The chemical reactions and pathways resulting in the formation of ribose phosphate, any phosphorylated ribose sugar.

gene.set.statistics.name: negative regulation of receptor signaling pathway via JAK-STAT
gene.set.statistics.description: Any process that stops, prevents, or reduces the frequency, rate or extent of a receptor signaling pathway via JAK-STAT.

gene.set.statistics.name: positive regulation of receptor signaling pathway via JAK-STAT
gene.set.statistics.description: Any process that activates or increases the frequency, rate or extent of the JAK-STAT signaling pathway activity.

gene.set.statistics.name: dihydrofolate metabolic process
gene.set.statistics.description: The chemical reactions and pathways involving dihydrofolate, the dihydroxylated derivative of folate.

gene.set.statistics.name: acylglycerol catabolic process
gene.set.statistics.description: The chemical reactions and pathways resulting in the breakdown of acylglycerol, any mono-, di- or triester of glycerol with (one or more) fatty acids.

gene.set.statistics.name: platelet activating factor metabolic process
gene.set.statistics.description: The chemical reactions and pathways involving platelet activating factor, 1-O-alkyl-2-acetyl-sn-glycerol 3-phosphocholine, where alkyl = hexadecyl or octadecyl. Platelet activating factor is an inflammatory mediator released from a variety of cells in response to various stimuli.

gene.set.statistics.name: glycerophospholipid biosynthetic process
gene.set.statistics.description: The chemical reactions and pathways resulting in the formation of glycerophospholipids, any derivative of glycerophosphate that contains at least one O-acyl, O-alkyl, or O-alkenyl group attached to the glycerol residue.

gene.set.statistics.name: glycerophospholipid catabolic process
gene.set.statistics.description: The chemical reactions and pathways resulting in the breakdown of glycerophospholipids, any derivative of glycerophosphate that contains at least one O-acyl, O-alkyl, or O-alkenyl group attached to the glycerol residue.

gene.set.statistics.name: glyoxylate metabolic process
gene.set.statistics.description: The chemical reactions and pathways involving glyoxylate, the anion of glyoxylic acid, HOC-COOH.

gene.set.statistics.name: ceramide biosynthetic process
gene.set.statistics.description: The chemical reactions and pathways resulting in the formation of ceramides, any N-acylated sphingoid.

gene.set.statistics.name: regulation of Ras protein signal transduction
gene.set.statistics.description: Any process that modulates the frequency, rate or extent of Ras protein signal transduction.

gene.set.statistics.name: positive regulation of Ras protein signal transduction
gene.set.statistics.description: Any process that activates or increases the frequency, rate or extent of Ras protein signal transduction.

gene.set.statistics.name: negative regulation of Ras protein signal transduction
gene.set.statistics.description: Any process that stops, prevents, or reduces the frequency, rate or extent of Ras protein signal transduction.

gene.set.statistics.name: regulation of viral entry into host cell
gene.set.statistics.description: Any process that modulates the frequency, rate or extent of the viral entry into the host cell.

gene.set.statistics.name: negative regulation of viral entry into host cell
gene.set.statistics.description: Any process that stops, prevents, or reduces the frequency, rate or extent of the entry of viral entry into a host cell.

gene.set.statistics.name: positive regulation of viral entry into host cell
gene.set.statistics.description: Any process that activates or increases the frequency, rate or extent of the introduction of viral entry into the host cell.

gene.set.statistics.name: regulation of centriole replication
gene.set.statistics.description: Any process that modulates the frequency, rate or extent of the formation of a daughter centriole of an existing centriole.

gene.set.statistics.name: negative regulation of centriole replication
gene.set.statistics.description: Any process that stops, prevents, or reduces the frequency, rate or extent of centriole replication.

gene.set.statistics.name: positive regulation of centriole replication
gene.set.statistics.description: Any process that activates or increases the frequency, rate or extent of centriole replication.

gene.set.statistics.name: positive regulation of mitotic centrosome separation
gene.set.statistics.description: Any process that activates or increases the frequency, rate or extent of centrosome separation.

gene.set.statistics.name: positive regulation of organ growth
gene.set.statistics.description: Any process that activates or increases the frequency, rate or extent of growth of an organ of an organism.

gene.set.statistics.name: regulation of insulin receptor signaling pathway
gene.set.statistics.description: Any process that modulates the frequency, rate or extent of insulin receptor signaling.

gene.set.statistics.name: negative regulation of insulin receptor signaling pathway
gene.set.statistics.description: Any process that stops, prevents, or reduces the frequency, rate or extent of insulin receptor signaling.

gene.set.statistics.name: positive regulation of insulin receptor signaling pathway
gene.set.statistics.description: Any process that increases the frequency, rate or extent of insulin receptor signaling.

gene.set.statistics.name: alpha-beta T cell differentiation
gene.set.statistics.description: The process in which a precursor cell type acquires the specialized features of an alpha-beta T cell. An alpha-beta T cell is a T cell that expresses an alpha-beta T cell receptor complex.

gene.set.statistics.name: positive regulation of alpha-beta T cell differentiation
gene.set.statistics.description: Any process that activates or increases the frequency, rate or extent of alpha-beta T cell differentiation.

gene.set.statistics.name: lymphocyte proliferation
gene.set.statistics.description: The expansion of a lymphocyte population by cell division.

gene.set.statistics.name: tetrahydrofolate metabolic process
gene.set.statistics.description: The chemical reactions and pathways involving tetrahydrofolate, 5,6,7,8-tetrahydrofolic acid, a folate derivative bearing additional hydrogens on the pterin group.

gene.set.statistics.name: tetrahydrofolate biosynthetic process
gene.set.statistics.description: The chemical reactions and pathways resulting in the formation of tetrahydrofolate, 5,6,7,8-tetrahydrofolic acid, a folate derivative bearing additional hydrogens on the pterin group.

gene.set.statistics.name: folic acid metabolic process
gene.set.statistics.description: The chemical reactions and pathways involving folic acid, pteroylglutamic acid. Folic acid is widely distributed as a member of the vitamin B complex and is essential for the synthesis of purine and pyrimidines.

gene.set.statistics.name: retinal cell programmed cell death
gene.set.statistics.description: Programmed cell death that occurs in the developing retina.

gene.set.statistics.name: negative regulation of insulin secretion
gene.set.statistics.description: Any process that stops, prevents, or reduces the frequency, rate or extent of the regulated release of insulin.

gene.set.statistics.name: response to antibiotic
gene.set.statistics.description: Any process that results in a change in state or activity of a cell or an organism (in terms of movement, secretion, enzyme production, gene expression, etc.) as a result of an antibiotic stimulus. An antibiotic is a chemical substance produced by a microorganism which has the capacity to inhibit the growth of or to kill other microorganisms.

gene.set.statistics.name: response to arsenic-containing substance
gene.set.statistics.description: Any process that results in a change in state or activity of a cell or an organism (in terms of movement, secretion, enzyme production, gene expression, etc.) as a result of an arsenic stimulus from compounds containing arsenic, including arsenates, arsenites, and arsenides.

gene.set.statistics.name: response to cadmium ion
gene.set.statistics.description: Any process that results in a change in state or activity of a cell or an organism (in terms of movement, secretion, enzyme production, gene expression, etc.) as a result of a cadmium (Cd) ion stimulus.

gene.set.statistics.name: response to copper ion
gene.set.statistics.description: Any process that results in a change in state or activity of a cell or an organism (in terms of movement, secretion, enzyme production, gene expression, etc.) as a result of a copper ion stimulus.

gene.set.statistics.name: response to mercury ion
gene.set.statistics.description: Any process that results in a change in state or activity of a cell or an organism (in terms of movement, secretion, enzyme production, gene expression, etc.) as a result of a mercury ion stimulus.

gene.set.statistics.name: decidualization
gene.set.statistics.description: The cellular and vascular changes occurring in the endometrium of the pregnant uterus just after the onset of blastocyst implantation. This process involves the proliferation and differentiation of the fibroblast-like endometrial stromal cells into large, polyploid decidual cells that eventually form the maternal component of the placenta.

gene.set.statistics.name: GDP metabolic process
gene.set.statistics.description: The chemical reactions and pathways involving GDP, guanosine 5'-diphosphate.

gene.set.statistics.name: muscle cell cellular homeostasis
gene.set.statistics.description: The cellular homeostatic process that preserves a muscle cell in a stable functional or structural state.

gene.set.statistics.name: viral entry into host cell
gene.set.statistics.description: The process that occurs after viral attachment by which a virus, or viral nucleic acid, breaches the plasma membrane or cell envelope and enters the host cell. The process ends when the viral nucleic acid is released into the host cell cytoplasm.

gene.set.statistics.name: positive regulation by virus of viral protein levels in host cell
gene.set.statistics.description: Any process where the infecting virus increases the levels of viral proteins in a cell.

gene.set.statistics.name: viral budding
gene.set.statistics.description: A viral process by which enveloped viruses acquire a host-derived membrane enriched in viral proteins to form their external envelope. The process starts when nucleocapsids, assembled or in the process of being built, induce formation of a membrane curvature in the host plasma or organelle membrane and wrap up in the forming bud. The process ends when the bud is eventually pinched off by membrane scission to release the enveloped particle into the lumenal or extracellular space.

gene.set.statistics.name: viral budding from plasma membrane
gene.set.statistics.description: A viral budding that starts with formation of a membrane curvature in the host plasma membrane.

gene.set.statistics.name: protein autophosphorylation
gene.set.statistics.description: The phosphorylation by a protein of one or more of its own amino acid residues (cis-autophosphorylation), or residues on an identical protein (trans-autophosphorylation).

gene.set.statistics.name: modification by virus of host mRNA processing
gene.set.statistics.description: Any viral process that interferes with the processing of mRNA in the host cell.

gene.set.statistics.name: viral mRNA export from host cell nucleus
gene.set.statistics.description: The directed movement of intronless viral mRNA from the host nucleus to the cytoplasm for translation.

gene.set.statistics.name: microtubule polymerization
gene.set.statistics.description: The addition of tubulin heterodimers to one or both ends of a microtubule.

gene.set.statistics.name: regulation of nucleocytoplasmic transport
gene.set.statistics.description: Any process that modulates the frequency, rate or extent of the directed movement of substances between the nucleus and the cytoplasm.

gene.set.statistics.name: regulation of protein export from nucleus
gene.set.statistics.description: Any process that modulates the frequency, rate or extent of the directed movement of proteins from the nucleus to the cytoplasm.

gene.set.statistics.name: negative regulation of protein export from nucleus
gene.set.statistics.description: Any process that stops, prevents, or reduces the frequency, rate or extent of the directed movement of proteins from the nucleus into the cytoplasm.

gene.set.statistics.name: positive regulation of protein export from nucleus
gene.set.statistics.description: Any process that activates or increases the frequency, rate or extent of directed movement of proteins from the nucleus into the cytoplasm.

gene.set.statistics.name: positive regulation of RNA export from nucleus
gene.set.statistics.description: Any process that activates or increases the frequency, rate or extent of directed movement of RNA from the nucleus into the cytoplasm.

gene.set.statistics.name: lipid phosphorylation
gene.set.statistics.description: The process of introducing one or more phosphate groups into a lipid, any member of a group of substances soluble in lipid solvents but only sparingly soluble in aqueous solvents.

gene.set.statistics.name: carbohydrate phosphorylation
gene.set.statistics.description: The process of introducing a phosphate group into a carbohydrate, any organic compound based on the general formula Cx(H2O)y.

gene.set.statistics.name: phospholipid dephosphorylation
gene.set.statistics.description: The process of removing one or more phosphate groups from a phosphorylated lipid, any member of a group of substances soluble in lipid solvents but only sparingly soluble in aqueous solvents.

gene.set.statistics.name: filopodium assembly
gene.set.statistics.description: The assembly of a filopodium, a thin, stiff protrusion extended by the leading edge of a motile cell such as a crawling fibroblast or amoeba, or an axonal growth cone.

gene.set.statistics.name: bone remodeling
gene.set.statistics.description: The continuous turnover of bone matrix and mineral that involves first, an increase in resorption (osteoclastic activity) and later, reactive bone formation (osteoblastic activity). The process of bone remodeling takes place in the adult skeleton at discrete foci. The process ensures the mechanical integrity of the skeleton throughout life and plays an important role in calcium homeostasis. An imbalance in the regulation of bone resorption and bone formation results in many of the metabolic bone diseases, such as osteoporosis.

gene.set.statistics.name: phosphatidylinositol phosphate biosynthetic process
gene.set.statistics.description: The chemical reactions and pathways resulting in the formation of phosphatidylinositol phosphate.

gene.set.statistics.name: inositol phosphate dephosphorylation
gene.set.statistics.description: The process of removing a phosphate group from any mono- or polyphosphorylated inositol.

gene.set.statistics.name: positive regulation of saliva secretion
gene.set.statistics.description: Any process that activates or increases the frequency, rate or extent of the regulated release of saliva.

gene.set.statistics.name: positive regulation of lipid biosynthetic process
gene.set.statistics.description: Any process that activates or increases the frequency, rate or extent of the chemical reactions and pathways resulting in the formation of lipids.

gene.set.statistics.name: regulation of mitochondrial membrane permeability
gene.set.statistics.description: Any process that modulates the frequency, rate or extent of the passage or uptake of molecules by the mitochondrial membrane.

gene.set.statistics.name: intracellular transport
gene.set.statistics.description: The directed movement of substances within a cell.

gene.set.statistics.name: regulation of neurotransmitter secretion
gene.set.statistics.description: Any process that modulates the frequency, rate or extent of the regulated release of a neurotransmitter from a cell.

gene.set.statistics.name: pore complex assembly
gene.set.statistics.description: The aggregation, arrangement and bonding together of a set of components to form a pore complex. A pore complex is a small opening in a membrane that allows the passage of liquids and/or gases.

gene.set.statistics.name: nucleoside monophosphate phosphorylation
gene.set.statistics.description: The process of introducing one or more phosphate groups into a nucleoside monophosphate to produce a polyphosphorylated nucleoside.

gene.set.statistics.name: hydroxylysine biosynthetic process
gene.set.statistics.description: The chemical reactions and pathways resulting in the formation of hydroxylysine (5-hydroxy-2,6-diaminohexanoic acid), a chiral alpha-amino acid.

gene.set.statistics.name: fatty-acyl-CoA biosynthetic process
