gene.set.statistics.description: The chemical reactions and pathways resulting in the formation of a fatty-acyl-CoA, any derivative of coenzyme A in which the sulfhydryl group is in thiolester linkage with a fatty-acyl group.

gene.set.statistics.name: ketone body biosynthetic process
gene.set.statistics.description: The chemical reactions and pathways resulting in the formation of ketone bodies, any one of the three substances: acetoacetate, D-3-hydroxybutyrate (beta-hydroxybutyrate) or acetone. Biosynthesis involves the formation of hydroxymethylglutaryl-CoA, which is cleaved to acetate and acetyl-CoA.

gene.set.statistics.name: ketone body catabolic process
gene.set.statistics.description: The chemical reactions and pathways resulting in the breakdown of ketone bodies, any one of the three substances: acetoacetate, D-3-hydroxybutyrate (beta-hydroxybutyrate) or acetone. Ketone bodies can be used as an energy source as an alternative to glucose. Utilization of ketone bodies in peripheral tissues involves conversion of acetoacetate to acetoacetyl-CoA, which is then converted to two molecules of acetyl-CoA.

gene.set.statistics.name: positive regulation of hemoglobin biosynthetic process
gene.set.statistics.description: Any process that activates or increases the frequency, rate or extent of the chemical reactions and pathways resulting in the formation of hemoglobin, an oxygen carrying, conjugated protein containing four heme groups and globin.

gene.set.statistics.name: vesicle transport along microtubule
gene.set.statistics.description: The directed movement of a vesicle along a microtubule, mediated by motor proteins. This process begins with the attachment of a vesicle to a microtubule, and ends when the vesicle reaches its final destination.

gene.set.statistics.name: mitochondrion transport along microtubule
gene.set.statistics.description: The directed movement of a mitochondrion along a microtubule, mediated by motor proteins.

gene.set.statistics.name: platelet-derived growth factor receptor signaling pathway
gene.set.statistics.description: The series of molecular signals generated as a consequence of a platelet-derived growth factor receptor binding to one of its physiological ligands.

gene.set.statistics.name: insulin-like growth factor receptor signaling pathway
gene.set.statistics.description: The series of molecular signals generated as a consequence of the insulin-like growth factor receptor binding to one of its physiological ligands.

gene.set.statistics.name: vascular endothelial growth factor receptor signaling pathway
gene.set.statistics.description: Any series of molecular signals initiated by the binding of an extracellular ligand to a vascular endothelial growth factor receptor (VEGFR) located on the surface of the receiving cell, and ending with regulation of a downstream cellular process, e.g. transcription.

gene.set.statistics.name: neurotrophin TRK receptor signaling pathway
gene.set.statistics.description: A series of molecular signals initiated by the binding of a neurotrophin to a receptor on the surface of the target cell where the receptor possesses tyrosine kinase activity, and ending with regulation of a downstream cellular process, e.g. transcription.

gene.set.statistics.name: hepatocyte growth factor receptor signaling pathway
gene.set.statistics.description: The series of molecular signals generated as a consequence of the hepatocyte growth factor receptor binding to one of its physiological ligands.

gene.set.statistics.name: ephrin receptor signaling pathway
gene.set.statistics.description: The series of molecular signals generated as a consequence of an ephrin receptor binding to an ephrin.

gene.set.statistics.name: phosphatidylinositol-mediated signaling
gene.set.statistics.description: A series of molecular signals in which a cell uses a phosphatidylinositol-mediated signaling to convert a signal into a response. Phosphatidylinositols include phosphatidylinositol (PtdIns) and its phosphorylated derivatives.

gene.set.statistics.name: inositol phosphate-mediated signaling
gene.set.statistics.description: Any intracellular signal transduction in which the signal is passed on within the cell via an inositol phosphate. Includes production of the inositol phosphate, and downstream effectors that further transmit the signal within the cell. Inositol phosphates are a group of mono- to poly-phosphorylated inositols, and include inositol monophosphate (IP), inositol trisphosphate (IP3), inositol pentakisphosphate (IP5) and inositol hexaphosphate (IP6).

gene.set.statistics.name: regulation of mRNA splicing, via spliceosome
gene.set.statistics.description: Any process that modulates the frequency, rate or extent of mRNA splicing via a spliceosomal mechanism.

gene.set.statistics.name: negative regulation of mRNA splicing, via spliceosome
gene.set.statistics.description: Any process that stops, prevents or reduces the rate or extent of mRNA splicing via a spliceosomal mechanism.

gene.set.statistics.name: positive regulation of mRNA splicing, via spliceosome
gene.set.statistics.description: Any process that activates or increases the rate or extent of mRNA splicing via a spliceosomal mechanism.

gene.set.statistics.name: focal adhesion assembly
gene.set.statistics.description: The aggregation and bonding together of a set of components to form a focal adhesion, a complex of intracellular signaling and structural proteins that provides a structural link between the internal actin cytoskeleton and the ECM, and also function as a locus of signal transduction activity.

gene.set.statistics.name: positive regulation of fibroblast proliferation
gene.set.statistics.description: Any process that activates or increases the frequency, rate or extent of multiplication or reproduction of fibroblast cells.

gene.set.statistics.name: negative regulation of fibroblast proliferation
gene.set.statistics.description: Any process that stops, prevents, or reduces the frequency, rate or extent of multiplication or reproduction of fibroblast cells.

gene.set.statistics.name: regulation of synaptic plasticity
gene.set.statistics.description: A process that modulates synaptic plasticity, the ability of synapses to change as circumstances require. They may alter function, such as increasing or decreasing their sensitivity, or they may increase or decrease in actual numbers.

gene.set.statistics.name: regulation of short-term neuronal synaptic plasticity
gene.set.statistics.description: A process that modulates short-term neuronal synaptic plasticity, the ability of neuronal synapses to change in the short-term as circumstances require. Short-term neuronal synaptic plasticity generally involves increasing or decreasing synaptic sensitivity.

gene.set.statistics.name: Golgi vesicle transport
gene.set.statistics.description: The directed movement of substances into, out of or within the Golgi apparatus, mediated by vesicles.

gene.set.statistics.name: Golgi vesicle budding
gene.set.statistics.description: The evagination of the Golgi membrane, resulting in formation of a vesicle.

gene.set.statistics.name: COPII vesicle coating
gene.set.statistics.description: The addition of COPII proteins and adaptor proteins to ER membranes during the formation of transport vesicles, forming a vesicle coat.

gene.set.statistics.name: Golgi vesicle docking
gene.set.statistics.description: The initial attachment of a Golgi transport vesicle membrane to a target membrane, mediated by proteins protruding from the membrane of the Golgi vesicle and the target membrane.

gene.set.statistics.name: plasma membrane to endosome transport
gene.set.statistics.description: Transport of a vesicle from the plasma membrane to the endosome.

gene.set.statistics.name: negative regulation of DNA recombination at telomere
gene.set.statistics.description: Any process that stops, prevents, or reduces the frequency, rate or extent of genetic recombination within the telomere.

gene.set.statistics.name: sperm capacitation
gene.set.statistics.description: A process required for sperm to reach fertilization competence. Sperm undergo an incompletely understood series of morphological and molecular maturational processes, termed capacitation, involving, among other processes, protein tyrosine phosphorylation and increased intracellular calcium.

gene.set.statistics.name: eosinophil chemotaxis
gene.set.statistics.description: The movement of an eosinophil in response to an external stimulus.

gene.set.statistics.name: macrophage chemotaxis
gene.set.statistics.description: The movement of a macrophage in response to an external stimulus.

gene.set.statistics.name: snoRNA localization
gene.set.statistics.description: Any process in which small nucleolar RNA is transported to, or maintained in, a specific location.

gene.set.statistics.name: mRNA stabilization
gene.set.statistics.description: Prevention of degradation of mRNA molecules. In the absence of compensating changes in other processes, the slowing of mRNA degradation can result in an overall increase in the population of active mRNA molecules.

gene.set.statistics.name: positive regulation of receptor-mediated endocytosis
gene.set.statistics.description: Any process that activates or increases the frequency, rate or extent of receptor mediated endocytosis, the uptake of external materials by cells, utilizing receptors to ensure specificity of transport.

gene.set.statistics.name: negative regulation of receptor-mediated endocytosis
gene.set.statistics.description: Any process that stops, prevents, or reduces the frequency, rate or extent of receptor mediated endocytosis, the uptake of external materials by cells, utilizing receptors to ensure specificity of transport.

gene.set.statistics.name: response to pain
gene.set.statistics.description: Any process that results in a change in state or activity of a cell or an organism (in terms of movement, secretion, enzyme production, gene expression, etc.) as a result of a pain stimulus. Pain stimuli cause activation of nociceptors, peripheral receptors for pain, include receptors which are sensitive to painful mechanical stimuli, extreme heat or cold, and chemical stimuli.

gene.set.statistics.name: clathrin coat assembly
gene.set.statistics.description: The process that results in the assembly of clathrin triskelia into the ordered structure known as a clathrin cage.

gene.set.statistics.name: vesicle docking
gene.set.statistics.description: The initial attachment of a transport vesicle membrane to the target membrane, mediated by proteins protruding from the membrane of the vesicle and the target membrane. Docking requires only that the two membranes come close enough for these proteins to interact and adhere.

gene.set.statistics.name: vesicle fusion with Golgi apparatus
gene.set.statistics.description: The joining of the lipid bilayer membrane around a vesicle to the lipid bilayer membrane around the Golgi.

gene.set.statistics.name: organelle fusion
gene.set.statistics.description: The creation of a single organelle from two or more organelles.

gene.set.statistics.name: intracellular distribution of mitochondria
gene.set.statistics.description: Any process that establishes the spatial arrangement of mitochondria within the cell.

gene.set.statistics.name: axial mesoderm development
gene.set.statistics.description: The process whose specific outcome is the progression of the axial mesoderm over time, from its formation to the mature structure. The axial mesoderm includes the prechordal mesoderm and the chordamesoderm. It gives rise to the prechordal plate and to the notochord.

gene.set.statistics.name: paraxial mesoderm development
gene.set.statistics.description: The process whose specific outcome is the progression of the paraxial mesoderm over time, from its formation to the mature structure. The paraxial mesoderm is the mesoderm located bilaterally adjacent to the notochord and neural tube.

gene.set.statistics.name: lateral mesoderm development
gene.set.statistics.description: The process whose specific outcome is the progression of the lateral mesoderm over time, from its formation to the mature structure.

gene.set.statistics.name: retinoic acid receptor signaling pathway
gene.set.statistics.description: The series of molecular signals generated as a consequence of a retinoic acid receptor binding to one of its physiological ligands.

gene.set.statistics.name: positive regulation of retinoic acid receptor signaling pathway
gene.set.statistics.description: Any process that activates or increases the frequency, rate or extent of retinoic acid receptor signaling pathway activity.

gene.set.statistics.name: negative regulation of retinoic acid receptor signaling pathway
gene.set.statistics.description: Any process that stops, prevents, or reduces the frequency, rate or extent of retinoic acid receptor signaling pathway activity.

gene.set.statistics.name: oogenesis
gene.set.statistics.description: The complete process of formation and maturation of an ovum or female gamete from a primordial female germ cell. Examples of this process are found in Mus musculus and Drosophila melanogaster.

gene.set.statistics.name: synaptic vesicle endocytosis
gene.set.statistics.description: A vesicle-mediated transport process, in which the synaptic vesicle membrane constituents are retrieved from the presynaptic membrane on the axon terminal after neurotransmitter secretion by exocytosis. Synaptic vesicle endocytosis can occur via clathrin-dependent and clathrin-independent mechanisms.

gene.set.statistics.name: synaptic vesicle transport
gene.set.statistics.description: The directed movement of synaptic vesicles.

gene.set.statistics.name: rhythmic process
gene.set.statistics.description: Any process pertinent to the generation and maintenance of rhythms in the physiology of an organism.

gene.set.statistics.name: spermatid differentiation
gene.set.statistics.description: The process whose specific outcome is the progression of a spermatid over time, from initial commitment of the cell to a specific fate, to the fully functional differentiated cell.

gene.set.statistics.name: positive regulation of viral process
gene.set.statistics.description: Any process that activates or increases the frequency, rate or extent of a multi-organism process in which a virus is a participant.

gene.set.statistics.name: spleen development
gene.set.statistics.description: The process whose specific outcome is the progression of the spleen over time, from its formation to the mature structure. The spleen is a large vascular lymphatic organ composed of white and red pulp, involved both in hemopoietic and immune system functions.

gene.set.statistics.name: thymus development
gene.set.statistics.description: The process whose specific outcome is the progression of the thymus over time, from its formation to the mature structure. The thymus is a symmetric bi-lobed organ involved primarily in the differentiation of immature to mature T cells, with unique vascular, nervous, epithelial, and lymphoid cell components.

gene.set.statistics.name: bone marrow development
gene.set.statistics.description: The process whose specific outcome is the progression of the bone marrow over time, from its formation to the mature structure.

gene.set.statistics.name: response to steroid hormone
gene.set.statistics.description: Any process that results in a change in state or activity of a cell or an organism (in terms of movement, secretion, enzyme production, gene expression, etc.) as a result of a steroid hormone stimulus.

gene.set.statistics.name: digestive tract morphogenesis
gene.set.statistics.description: The process in which the anatomical structures of the digestive tract are generated and organized. The digestive tract is the anatomical structure through which food passes and is processed.

gene.set.statistics.name: positive regulation of pinocytosis
gene.set.statistics.description: Any process that activates, maintains or increases the rate of pinocytosis. Pinocytosis is the process in which cells take in liquid material from their external environment; literally 'cell drinking'. Liquid is enclosed in vesicles, formed by invagination of the plasma membrane. These vesicles then move into the cell and pass their contents to endosomes.

gene.set.statistics.name: negative regulation of pinocytosis
gene.set.statistics.description: Any process that stops, prevents, or reduces the frequency, rate or extent of pinocytosis. Pinocytosis is the process in which cells take in liquid material from their external environment; literally 'cell drinking'. Liquid is enclosed in vesicles, formed by invagination of the plasma membrane. These vesicles then move into the cell and pass their contents to endosomes.

gene.set.statistics.name: embryonic organ development
gene.set.statistics.description: Development, taking place during the embryonic phase, of a tissue or tissues that work together to perform a specific function or functions. Development pertains to the process whose specific outcome is the progression of a structure over time, from its formation to the mature structure. Organs are commonly observed as visibly distinct structures, but may also exist as loosely associated clusters of cells that work together to perform a specific function or functions.

gene.set.statistics.name: developmental growth
gene.set.statistics.description: The increase in size or mass of an entire organism, a part of an organism or a cell, where the increase in size or mass has the specific outcome of the progression of the organism over time from one condition to another.

gene.set.statistics.name: embryonic foregut morphogenesis
gene.set.statistics.description: The process in which the anatomical structures of the foregut are generated and organized, during the embryonic phase.

gene.set.statistics.name: positive regulation of developmental growth
gene.set.statistics.description: Any process that activates, maintains or increases the rate of developmental growth.

gene.set.statistics.name: negative regulation of skeletal muscle tissue development
gene.set.statistics.description: Any process that stops, prevents, or reduces the frequency, rate or extent of skeletal muscle tissue development.

gene.set.statistics.name: anatomical structure formation involved in morphogenesis
gene.set.statistics.description: The developmental process pertaining to the initial formation of an anatomical structure from unspecified parts. This process begins with the specific processes that contribute to the appearance of the discrete structure and ends when the structural rudiment is recognizable. An anatomical structure is any biological entity that occupies space and is distinguished from its surroundings. Anatomical structures can be macroscopic such as a carpel, or microscopic such as an acrosome.

gene.set.statistics.name: regulation of smooth muscle cell proliferation
gene.set.statistics.description: Any process that modulates the frequency, rate or extent of smooth muscle cell proliferation.

gene.set.statistics.name: positive regulation of smooth muscle cell proliferation
gene.set.statistics.description: Any process that activates or increases the rate or extent of smooth muscle cell proliferation.

gene.set.statistics.name: negative regulation of smooth muscle cell proliferation
gene.set.statistics.description: Any process that stops, prevents or reduces the rate or extent of smooth muscle cell proliferation.

gene.set.statistics.name: neuron fate determination
gene.set.statistics.description: The process in which a cell becomes capable of differentiating autonomously into a neuron regardless of its environment; upon determination, the cell fate cannot be reversed.

gene.set.statistics.name: neuron fate specification
gene.set.statistics.description: The process in which a cell becomes capable of differentiating autonomously into a neuron in an environment that is neutral with respect to the developmental pathway. Upon specification, the cell fate can be reversed.

gene.set.statistics.name: neuron development
gene.set.statistics.description: The process whose specific outcome is the progression of a neuron over time, from initial commitment of the cell to a specific fate, to the fully functional differentiated cell.

gene.set.statistics.name: positive regulation of collateral sprouting
gene.set.statistics.description: Any process that activates or increases the frequency, rate or extent of collateral sprouting.

gene.set.statistics.name: axon extension
gene.set.statistics.description: Long distance growth of a single axon process involved in cellular development.

gene.set.statistics.name: response to axon injury
gene.set.statistics.description: Any process that results in a change in state or activity of a cell or an organism (in terms of movement, secretion, enzyme production, gene expression, etc.) as a result of an axon injury stimulus.

gene.set.statistics.name: generation of neurons
gene.set.statistics.description: The process in which nerve cells are generated. This includes the production of neuroblasts and their differentiation into neurons.

gene.set.statistics.name: embryonic cranial skeleton morphogenesis
gene.set.statistics.description: The process in which the anatomical structures of the cranial skeleton are generated and organized during the embryonic phase.

gene.set.statistics.name: embryonic neurocranium morphogenesis
gene.set.statistics.description: The process in which the anatomical structures of the neurocranium are generated and organized during the embryonic phase. The neurocranium is the portion of the vertebrate skull surrounding the brain.

gene.set.statistics.name: embryonic viscerocranium morphogenesis
gene.set.statistics.description: The process in which the anatomical structures of the viscerocranium are generated and organized during the embryonic phase. The viscerocranium is the part of the skull comprising the facial bones.

gene.set.statistics.name: skeletal system morphogenesis
gene.set.statistics.description: The process in which the anatomical structures of the skeleton are generated and organized.

gene.set.statistics.name: embryonic skeletal system development
gene.set.statistics.description: The process, occurring during the embryonic phase, whose specific outcome is the progression of the skeleton over time, from its formation to the mature structure.

gene.set.statistics.name: astrocyte differentiation
gene.set.statistics.description: The process in which a relatively unspecialized cell acquires the specialized features of an astrocyte. An astrocyte is the most abundant type of glial cell. Astrocytes provide support for neurons and regulate the environment in which they function.

gene.set.statistics.name: oligodendrocyte differentiation
gene.set.statistics.description: The process in which a relatively unspecialized cell acquires the specialized features of an oligodendrocyte. An oligodendrocyte is a type of glial cell involved in myelinating the axons of neurons in the central nervous system.

gene.set.statistics.name: positive regulation of astrocyte differentiation
gene.set.statistics.description: Any process that activates or increases the frequency, rate or extent of astrocyte differentiation.

gene.set.statistics.name: regulation of oligodendrocyte differentiation
gene.set.statistics.description: Any process that modulates the frequency, rate or extent of oligodendrocyte differentiation.

gene.set.statistics.name: positive regulation of oligodendrocyte differentiation
gene.set.statistics.description: Any process that activates or increases the frequency, rate or extent of oligodendrocyte differentiation.

gene.set.statistics.name: epidermis morphogenesis
gene.set.statistics.description: The process in which the anatomical structures of the epidermis are generated and organized. The epidermis is the outer epithelial layer of an animal, it may be a single layer that produces an extracellular material (e.g. the cuticle of arthropods) or a complex stratified squamous epithelium, as in the case of many vertebrate species.

gene.set.statistics.name: cardiac muscle tissue development
gene.set.statistics.description: The process whose specific outcome is the progression of cardiac muscle over time, from its formation to the mature structure.

gene.set.statistics.name: skeletal muscle fiber development
gene.set.statistics.description: The process whose specific outcome is the progression of the skeletal muscle fiber over time, from its formation to the mature structure. Muscle fibers are formed by the maturation of myotubes. They can be classed as slow, intermediate/fast or fast.

gene.set.statistics.name: positive regulation of skeletal muscle fiber development
gene.set.statistics.description: Any process that activates, maintains or increases the rate of skeletal muscle fiber development. Muscle fibers are formed by the maturation of myotubes. They can be classed as slow, intermediate/fast or fast.

gene.set.statistics.name: smooth muscle tissue development
gene.set.statistics.description: The process whose specific outcome is the progression of smooth muscle over time, from its formation to the mature structure.

gene.set.statistics.name: branching morphogenesis of an epithelial tube
gene.set.statistics.description: The process in which the anatomical structures of branches in an epithelial tube are generated and organized. A tube is a long hollow cylinder.

gene.set.statistics.name: maintenance of presynaptic active zone structure
gene.set.statistics.description: A process which maintains the organization and the arrangement of proteins at the active zone to ensure the fusion and docking of vesicles and the release of neurotransmitters.

gene.set.statistics.name: neuron projection morphogenesis
gene.set.statistics.description: The process in which the anatomical structures of a neuron projection are generated and organized. A neuron projection is any process extending from a neural cell, such as axons or dendrites.

gene.set.statistics.name: dendrite morphogenesis
gene.set.statistics.description: The process in which the anatomical structures of a dendrite are generated and organized.

gene.set.statistics.name: regulation of dendrite morphogenesis
gene.set.statistics.description: Any process that modulates the frequency, rate or extent of dendrite morphogenesis.

gene.set.statistics.name: hair follicle maturation
gene.set.statistics.description: A developmental process, independent of morphogenetic (shape) change, that is required for a hair follicle to attain its fully functional state.

gene.set.statistics.name: erythrocyte development
gene.set.statistics.description: The process whose specific outcome is the progression of an erythrocyte over time, from its formation to the mature structure.

gene.set.statistics.name: forebrain morphogenesis
gene.set.statistics.description: The process in which the anatomical structures of the forebrain are generated and organized. The forebrain is the anterior of the three primary divisions of the developing chordate brain or the corresponding part of the adult brain (in vertebrates, includes especially the cerebral hemispheres, the thalamus, and the hypothalamus and especially in higher vertebrates is the main control center for sensory and associative information processing, visceral functions, and voluntary motor functions).

gene.set.statistics.name: brain morphogenesis
gene.set.statistics.description: The process in which the anatomical structures of the brain are generated and organized. The brain is one of the two components of the central nervous system and is the center of thought and emotion. It is responsible for the coordination and control of bodily activities and the interpretation of information from the senses (sight, hearing, smell, etc.).

gene.set.statistics.name: anatomical structure development
gene.set.statistics.description: The biological process whose specific outcome is the progression of an anatomical structure from an initial condition to its mature state. This process begins with the formation of the structure and ends with the mature structure, whatever form that may be including its natural destruction. An anatomical structure is any biological entity that occupies space and is distinguished from its surroundings. Anatomical structures can be macroscopic such as a carpel, or microscopic such as an acrosome.

gene.set.statistics.name: stem cell differentiation
gene.set.statistics.description: The process in which a relatively unspecialized cell acquires specialized features of a stem cell. A stem cell is a cell that retains the ability to divide and proliferate throughout life to provide progenitor cells that can differentiate into specialized cells.

gene.set.statistics.name: cell motility
gene.set.statistics.description: Any process involved in the controlled self-propelled movement of a cell that results in translocation of the cell from one place to another.

gene.set.statistics.name: homeostasis of number of cells
gene.set.statistics.description: Any biological process involved in the maintenance of the steady-state number of cells within a population of cells.

gene.set.statistics.name: homeostasis of number of cells within a tissue
gene.set.statistics.description: Any biological process involved in the maintenance of the steady-state number of cells within a population of cells in a tissue.

gene.set.statistics.name: 3'-phosphoadenosine 5'-phosphosulfate metabolic process
gene.set.statistics.description: The chemical reactions and pathways involving 3'-phosphoadenosine 5'-phosphosulfate, a naturally occurring mixed anhydride. It is an intermediate in the formation of a variety of sulfo compounds in biological systems.

gene.set.statistics.name: 3'-phosphoadenosine 5'-phosphosulfate biosynthetic process
gene.set.statistics.description: The chemical reactions and pathways resulting in the formation of 3'-phosphoadenosine 5'-phosphosulfate, a naturally occurring mixed anhydride. It is an intermediate in the formation of a variety of sulfo compounds in biological systems.

gene.set.statistics.name: positive regulation of viral transcription
gene.set.statistics.description: Any process that activates or increases the frequency, rate or extent of viral transcription.

gene.set.statistics.name: arachidonic acid secretion
gene.set.statistics.description: The controlled release of arachidonic acid from a cell or a tissue.

gene.set.statistics.name: RNA transport
gene.set.statistics.description: The directed movement of RNA, ribonucleic acids, into, out of or within a cell, or between cells, by means of some agent such as a transporter or pore.

gene.set.statistics.name: homocysteine metabolic process
gene.set.statistics.description: The chemical reactions and pathways involving homocysteine, the amino acid alpha-amino-gamma-mercaptobutanoic acid. Homocysteine is an important intermediate in the metabolic reactions of its S-methyl derivative, methionine.

gene.set.statistics.name: epithelial cell proliferation
gene.set.statistics.description: The multiplication or reproduction of epithelial cells, resulting in the expansion of a cell population. Epithelial cells make up the epithelium, the covering of internal and external surfaces of the body, including the lining of vessels and other small cavities. It consists of cells joined by small amounts of cementing substances.

gene.set.statistics.name: regulation of epithelial cell proliferation
gene.set.statistics.description: Any process that modulates the frequency, rate or extent of epithelial cell proliferation.

gene.set.statistics.name: positive regulation of epithelial cell proliferation
gene.set.statistics.description: Any process that activates or increases the rate or extent of epithelial cell proliferation.

gene.set.statistics.name: negative regulation of epithelial cell proliferation
gene.set.statistics.description: Any process that stops, prevents or reduces the rate or extent of epithelial cell proliferation.

gene.set.statistics.name: regulation of mRNA processing
gene.set.statistics.description: Any process that modulates the frequency, rate or extent of mRNA processing, those processes involved in the conversion of a primary mRNA transcript into a mature mRNA prior to its translation into polypeptide.

gene.set.statistics.name: negative regulation of defense response to virus
gene.set.statistics.description: Any process that stops, prevents or reduces the rate or extent of antiviral mechanisms, thereby facilitating viral replication.

gene.set.statistics.name: regulation of defense response to virus by virus
gene.set.statistics.description: Any viral process that modulates the frequency, rate, or extent of the antiviral response of the host cell or organism.

gene.set.statistics.name: regulation of defense response to virus by host
gene.set.statistics.description: Any host process that modulates the frequency, rate, or extent of the antiviral response of a host cell or organism.

gene.set.statistics.name: regulation of protein secretion
gene.set.statistics.description: Any process that modulates the frequency, rate or extent of the controlled release of a protein from a cell.

gene.set.statistics.name: negative regulation of protein secretion
gene.set.statistics.description: Any process that stops, prevents, or reduces the frequency, rate or extent of the controlled release of a protein from a cell.

gene.set.statistics.name: positive regulation of protein secretion
gene.set.statistics.description: Any process that activates or increases the frequency, rate or extent of the controlled release of a protein from a cell.

gene.set.statistics.name: regulation of inflammatory response
gene.set.statistics.description: Any process that modulates the frequency, rate or extent of the inflammatory response, the immediate defensive reaction (by vertebrate tissue) to infection or injury caused by chemical or physical agents.

gene.set.statistics.name: negative regulation of inflammatory response
gene.set.statistics.description: Any process that stops, prevents, or reduces the frequency, rate or extent of the inflammatory response.

gene.set.statistics.name: positive regulation of inflammatory response
gene.set.statistics.description: Any process that activates or increases the frequency, rate or extent of the inflammatory response.

gene.set.statistics.name: positive regulation of peptidyl-tyrosine phosphorylation
gene.set.statistics.description: Any process that activates or increases the frequency, rate or extent of the phosphorylation of peptidyl-tyrosine.

gene.set.statistics.name: negative regulation of phagocytosis
gene.set.statistics.description: Any process that stops, prevents, or reduces the frequency, rate or extent of phagocytosis.

gene.set.statistics.name: positive regulation of phagocytosis
gene.set.statistics.description: Any process that activates or increases the frequency, rate or extent of phagocytosis.

gene.set.statistics.name: regulation of neurogenesis
gene.set.statistics.description: Any process that modulates the frequency, rate or extent of neurogenesis, the generation of cells in the nervous system.

gene.set.statistics.name: negative regulation of neurogenesis
gene.set.statistics.description: Any process that stops, prevents, or reduces the frequency, rate or extent of neurogenesis, the generation of cells within the nervous system.

gene.set.statistics.name: positive regulation of neurogenesis
gene.set.statistics.description: Any process that activates or increases the frequency, rate or extent of neurogenesis, the generation of cells within the nervous system.

gene.set.statistics.name: regulation of axonogenesis
gene.set.statistics.description: Any process that modulates the frequency, rate or extent of axonogenesis, the generation of an axon, the long process of a neuron.

gene.set.statistics.name: negative regulation of axonogenesis
gene.set.statistics.description: Any process that stops, prevents, or reduces the frequency, rate or extent of axonogenesis.

gene.set.statistics.name: positive regulation of axonogenesis
gene.set.statistics.description: Any process that activates or increases the frequency, rate or extent of axonogenesis.

gene.set.statistics.name: regulation of dendrite development
gene.set.statistics.description: Any process that modulates the frequency, rate or extent of dendrite development.

gene.set.statistics.name: negative regulation of dendrite morphogenesis
gene.set.statistics.description: Any process that stops, prevents, or reduces the frequency, rate or extent of dendrite morphogenesis.

gene.set.statistics.name: positive regulation of dendrite morphogenesis
gene.set.statistics.description: Any process that activates or increases the frequency, rate or extent of dendrite morphogenesis.

gene.set.statistics.name: regulation of immune response
gene.set.statistics.description: Any process that modulates the frequency, rate or extent of the immune response, the immunological reaction of an organism to an immunogenic stimulus.

gene.set.statistics.name: regulation of catalytic activity
gene.set.statistics.description: Any process that modulates the activity of an enzyme.

gene.set.statistics.name: regulation of cellular process
gene.set.statistics.description: Any process that modulates the frequency, rate or extent of a cellular process, any of those that are carried out at the cellular level, but are not necessarily restricted to a single cell. For example, cell communication occurs among more than one cell, but occurs at the cellular level.

gene.set.statistics.name: regulation of insulin secretion
gene.set.statistics.description: Any process that modulates the frequency, rate or extent of the regulated release of insulin.

gene.set.statistics.name: ion homeostasis
gene.set.statistics.description: Any process involved in the maintenance of an internal steady state of ions within an organism or cell.

gene.set.statistics.name: regulation of synapse structure or activity
gene.set.statistics.description: Any process that modulates the physical form or the activity of a synapse, the junction between a neuron and a target (neuron, muscle, or secretory cell).

gene.set.statistics.name: modulation of chemical synaptic transmission
gene.set.statistics.description: Any process that modulates the frequency or amplitude of synaptic transmission, the process of communication from a neuron to a target (neuron, muscle, or secretory cell) across a synapse.  Amplitude, in this case, refers to the change in postsynaptic membrane potential due to a single instance of synaptic transmission.

gene.set.statistics.name: negative regulation of synaptic transmission
gene.set.statistics.description: Any process that stops, prevents, or reduces the frequency, rate or extent of synaptic transmission, the process of communication from a neuron to a target (neuron, muscle, or secretory cell) across a synapse.

gene.set.statistics.name: regulation of synapse organization
gene.set.statistics.description: Any process that modulates the physical form of a synapse, the junction between a neuron and a target (neuron, muscle, or secretory cell).

gene.set.statistics.name: synapse organization
gene.set.statistics.description: A process that is carried out at the cellular level which results in the assembly, arrangement of constituent parts, or disassembly of a synapse, the junction between a neuron and a target (neuron, muscle, or secretory cell).

gene.set.statistics.name: regulation of steroid biosynthetic process
gene.set.statistics.description: Any process that modulates the frequency, rate or extent of the chemical reactions and pathways resulting in the formation of steroids, compounds with a 1,2,cyclopentanoperhydrophenanthrene nucleus.

gene.set.statistics.name: protein stabilization
gene.set.statistics.description: Any process involved in maintaining the structure and integrity of a protein and preventing it from degradation or aggregation.

gene.set.statistics.name: defense response to Gram-negative bacterium
gene.set.statistics.description: Reactions triggered in response to the presence of a Gram-negative bacterium that act to protect the cell or organism.

gene.set.statistics.name: defense response to Gram-positive bacterium
gene.set.statistics.description: Reactions triggered in response to the presence of a Gram-positive bacterium that act to protect the cell or organism.

gene.set.statistics.name: defense response to fungus
gene.set.statistics.description: Reactions triggered in response to the presence of a fungus that act to protect the cell or organism.

gene.set.statistics.name: progesterone receptor signaling pathway
gene.set.statistics.description: Any series of molecular signals generated as a consequence of a progesterone binding to its receptor.

gene.set.statistics.name: antigen receptor-mediated signaling pathway
gene.set.statistics.description: A series of molecular signals initiated by the cross-linking of an antigen receptor on a B or T cell.

gene.set.statistics.name: T cell receptor signaling pathway
gene.set.statistics.description: A series of molecular signals initiated by the cross-linking of an antigen receptor on a T cell.

gene.set.statistics.name: B cell receptor signaling pathway
gene.set.statistics.description: A series of molecular signals initiated by the cross-linking of an antigen receptor on a B cell.

gene.set.statistics.name: negative regulation of T cell receptor signaling pathway
gene.set.statistics.description: Any process that stops, prevents, or reduces the frequency, rate or extent of signaling pathways initiated by the cross-linking of an antigen receptor on a T cell.

gene.set.statistics.name: positive regulation of T cell receptor signaling pathway
gene.set.statistics.description: Any process that activates or increases the frequency, rate or extent of signaling pathways initiated by the cross-linking of an antigen receptor on a T cell.

gene.set.statistics.name: positive regulation of T cell activation
gene.set.statistics.description: Any process that activates or increases the frequency, rate or extent of T cell activation.

gene.set.statistics.name: positive regulation of B cell activation
gene.set.statistics.description: Any process that activates or increases the frequency, rate or extent of B cell activation.

gene.set.statistics.name: white fat cell differentiation
gene.set.statistics.description: The process in which a relatively unspecialized cell acquires specialized features of a white adipocyte, an animal connective tissue cell involved in energy storage. White adipocytes have cytoplasmic lipids arranged in a unique vacuole.

gene.set.statistics.name: brown fat cell differentiation
gene.set.statistics.description: The process in which a relatively unspecialized cell acquires specialized features of a brown adipocyte, an animal connective tissue cell involved in adaptive thermogenesis. Brown adipocytes contain multiple small droplets of triglycerides and a high number of mitochondria.

gene.set.statistics.name: nervous system process
gene.set.statistics.description: A organ system process carried out by any of the organs or tissues of neurological system.

gene.set.statistics.name: voluntary musculoskeletal movement
gene.set.statistics.description: The movement of an organism or part of an organism using mechanoreceptors, the nervous system, striated muscle and/or the skeletal system that can be controlled at will.

gene.set.statistics.name: neuromuscular process controlling balance
gene.set.statistics.description: Any process that an organism uses to control its balance, the orientation of the organism (or the head of the organism) in relation to the source of gravity. In humans and animals, balance is perceived through visual cues, the labyrinth system of the inner ears and information from skin pressure receptors and muscle and joint receptors.

gene.set.statistics.name: cognition
gene.set.statistics.description: The operation of the mind by which an organism becomes aware of objects of thought or perception; it includes the mental activities associated with thinking, learning, and memory.

gene.set.statistics.name: multicellular organismal water homeostasis
gene.set.statistics.description: Any process involved in the maintenance of an internal steady state of water within a tissue, organ, or a multicellular organism.

gene.set.statistics.name: intestinal absorption
gene.set.statistics.description: Any process in which nutrients are taken up from the contents of the intestine.

gene.set.statistics.name: response to stimulus
gene.set.statistics.description: Any process that results in a change in state or activity of a cell or an organism (in terms of movement, secretion, enzyme production, gene expression, etc.) as a result of a stimulus. The process begins with detection of the stimulus and ends with a change in state or activity or the cell or organism.

gene.set.statistics.name: leukocyte migration
gene.set.statistics.description: The movement of a leukocyte within or between different tissues and organs of the body.

gene.set.statistics.name: leukocyte tethering or rolling
gene.set.statistics.description: Transient adhesive interactions between leukocytes and endothelial cells lining blood vessels. Carbohydrates on circulating leukocytes bind selectins on the vessel wall causing the leukocytes to slow down and roll along the inner surface of the vessel wall. During this rolling motion, transitory bonds are formed and broken between selectins and their ligands. Typically the first step in cellular extravasation (the movement of leukocytes out of the circulatory system, towards the site of tissue damage or infection).

gene.set.statistics.name: neuromuscular process
gene.set.statistics.description: Any process pertaining to the functions of the nervous and muscular systems of an organism.

gene.set.statistics.name: sensory perception of taste
gene.set.statistics.description: The series of events required for an organism to receive a gustatory stimulus, convert it to a molecular signal, and recognize and characterize the signal. Gustation involves the direct detection of chemical composition, usually through contact with chemoreceptor cells. This is a neurological process.

gene.set.statistics.name: sensory perception of bitter taste
gene.set.statistics.description: The series of events required to receive a bitter taste stimulus, convert it to a molecular signal, and recognize and characterize the signal. This is a neurological process.

gene.set.statistics.name: sensory perception of sweet taste
gene.set.statistics.description: The series of events required to receive a sweet taste stimulus, convert it to a molecular signal, and recognize and characterize the signal. This is a neurological process.

gene.set.statistics.name: sensory perception of umami taste
gene.set.statistics.description: The series of events required to receive an umami taste stimulus, convert it to a molecular signal, and recognize and characterize the signal. Umami taste is the savory taste of meats and other foods that are rich in glutamates. This is a neurological process.

gene.set.statistics.name: positive chemotaxis
gene.set.statistics.description: The directed movement of a motile cell or organism towards a higher concentration of a chemical.

gene.set.statistics.name: negative chemotaxis
gene.set.statistics.description: The directed movement of a motile cell or organism towards a lower concentration of a chemical.

gene.set.statistics.name: regulation of chemotaxis
gene.set.statistics.description: Any process that modulates the frequency, rate or extent of the directed movement of a motile cell or organism in response to a specific chemical concentration gradient.

gene.set.statistics.name: positive regulation of chemotaxis
gene.set.statistics.description: Any process that activates or increases the frequency, rate or extent of the directed movement of a motile cell or organism in response to a specific chemical concentration gradient.

gene.set.statistics.name: detection of mechanical stimulus
gene.set.statistics.description: The series of events by which a mechanical stimulus is received and converted into a molecular signal.

gene.set.statistics.name: regulation of nitric-oxide synthase activity
gene.set.statistics.description: Any process that modulates the activity of the enzyme nitric-oxide synthase.

gene.set.statistics.name: positive regulation of nitric-oxide synthase activity
gene.set.statistics.description: Any process that activates or increases the activity of the enzyme nitric-oxide synthase.

gene.set.statistics.name: negative regulation of nitric-oxide synthase activity
gene.set.statistics.description: Any process that stops or reduces the activity of the enzyme nitric-oxide synthase.

gene.set.statistics.name: microtubule sliding
gene.set.statistics.description: The movement of one microtubule along another microtubule.

gene.set.statistics.name: microtubule severing
gene.set.statistics.description: The process in which a microtubule is broken down into smaller segments. Severing enzymes remove dimers from the middle of the filament to create new ends, unlike depolymerizing kinesins that use ATP to uncap microtubules at their ends.

gene.set.statistics.name: actin filament severing
gene.set.statistics.description: The process in which an actin filament is broken down into smaller filaments.

gene.set.statistics.name: barbed-end actin filament capping
gene.set.statistics.description: The binding of a protein or protein complex to the barbed (or plus) end of an actin filament, thus preventing the addition, exchange or removal of further actin subunits.

gene.set.statistics.name: actin filament bundle assembly
gene.set.statistics.description: The assembly of actin filament bundles; actin filaments are on the same axis but may be oriented with the same or opposite polarities and may be packed with different levels of tightness.

gene.set.statistics.name: mRNA transport
gene.set.statistics.description: The directed movement of mRNA, messenger ribonucleic acid, into, out of or within a cell, or between cells, by means of some agent such as a transporter or pore.

gene.set.statistics.name: positive regulation of secretion
gene.set.statistics.description: Any process that activates or increases the frequency, rate or extent of the controlled release of a substance from a cell or a tissue.

gene.set.statistics.name: negative regulation of transport
gene.set.statistics.description: Any process that stops, prevents, or reduces the frequency, rate or extent of the directed movement of substances (such as macromolecules, small molecules, ions) into, out of or within a cell, or between cells, by means of some agent such as a transporter or pore.

gene.set.statistics.name: regulation of small GTPase mediated signal transduction
gene.set.statistics.description: Any process that modulates the frequency, rate or extent of small GTPase mediated signal transduction.

gene.set.statistics.name: negative regulation of small GTPase mediated signal transduction
gene.set.statistics.description: Any process that stops, prevents, or reduces the frequency, rate or extent of small GTPase mediated signal transduction.

gene.set.statistics.name: nuclear membrane disassembly
gene.set.statistics.description: The controlled breakdown of the nuclear membranes, for example during  cellular division.

gene.set.statistics.name: 'de novo' posttranslational protein folding
gene.set.statistics.description: The process of assisting in the correct noncovalent folding of newly formed polypeptides or folding intermediates of polypeptides that have exited the ribosome and/or have been stabilized and transferred by other chaperone proteins. This process could involve several cycles of ATP hydrolysis.

gene.set.statistics.name: chaperone cofactor-dependent protein refolding
gene.set.statistics.description: The process of assisting in the correct posttranslational noncovalent assembly of proteins, which is dependent on additional protein cofactors. This process occurs over one or several cycles of nucleotide hydrolysis-dependent binding and release.

gene.set.statistics.name: regulation of DNA-binding transcription factor activity
gene.set.statistics.description: Any process that modulates the frequency, rate or extent of the activity of a transcription factor, any factor involved in the initiation or regulation of transcription.

gene.set.statistics.name: positive regulation of DNA-binding transcription factor activity
gene.set.statistics.description: Any process that activates or increases the frequency, rate or extent of activity of a transcription factor, any factor involved in the initiation or regulation of transcription.

gene.set.statistics.name: positive regulation of NF-kappaB transcription factor activity
gene.set.statistics.description: Any process that activates or increases the frequency, rate or extent of activity of the transcription factor NF-kappaB.

gene.set.statistics.name: regulation of binding
gene.set.statistics.description: Any process that modulates the frequency, rate or extent of binding, the selective interaction of a molecule with one or more specific sites on another molecule.

gene.set.statistics.name: positive regulation of binding
gene.set.statistics.description: Any process that activates or increases the rate or extent of binding, the selective interaction of a molecule with one or more specific sites on another molecule.

gene.set.statistics.name: positive regulation of DNA ligation
gene.set.statistics.description: Any process that activates or increases the frequency, rate or extent of DNA ligation, the re-formation of a broken phosphodiester bond in the DNA backbone, carried out by DNA ligase.

gene.set.statistics.name: RNA polymerase II preinitiation complex assembly
gene.set.statistics.description: The aggregation, arrangement and bonding together of proteins on an RNA polymerase II promoter DNA to form the transcriptional preinitiation complex (PIC), the formation of which is a prerequisite for transcription by RNA polymerase.

gene.set.statistics.name: negative regulation of actin nucleation
gene.set.statistics.description: Any process that stops, prevents, or reduces the frequency, rate or extent of actin nucleation, the initial step in the formation of an actin filament in which actin monomers combine to form a new filament.

gene.set.statistics.name: positive regulation of actin nucleation
gene.set.statistics.description: Any process that activates or increases the frequency, rate or extent of actin nucleation, the initial step in the formation of an actin filament in which actin monomers combine to form a new filament.

gene.set.statistics.name: chaperone-mediated protein complex assembly
gene.set.statistics.description: The aggregation, arrangement and bonding together of a set of components to form a protein complex, mediated by chaperone molecules that do not form part of the finished complex.

gene.set.statistics.name: positive regulation of NK T cell activation
gene.set.statistics.description: Any process that activates or increases the frequency, rate or extent of natural killer T cell activation.

gene.set.statistics.name: striated muscle cell differentiation
gene.set.statistics.description: The process in which a relatively unspecialized cell acquires specialized features of a striated muscle cell; striated muscle fibers are divided by transverse bands into striations, and cardiac and voluntary muscle are types of striated muscle.

gene.set.statistics.name: regulation of muscle cell differentiation
gene.set.statistics.description: Any process that modulates the frequency, rate or extent of muscle cell differentiation.

gene.set.statistics.name: negative regulation of muscle cell differentiation
gene.set.statistics.description: Any process that stops, prevents, or reduces the frequency, rate or extent of muscle cell differentiation.

gene.set.statistics.name: positive regulation of muscle cell differentiation
gene.set.statistics.description: Any process that activates or increases the frequency, rate or extent of muscle cell differentiation.

gene.set.statistics.name: negative regulation of striated muscle cell differentiation
gene.set.statistics.description: Any process that stops, prevents, or reduces the frequency, rate or extent of striated muscle cell differentiation.

gene.set.statistics.name: glucose 6-phosphate metabolic process
gene.set.statistics.description: The chemical reactions and pathways involving glucose 6-phosphate, a monophosphorylated derivative of glucose with the phosphate group attached to C-6.

gene.set.statistics.name: nuclear export
gene.set.statistics.description: The directed movement of substances out of the nucleus.

gene.set.statistics.name: import into nucleus
gene.set.statistics.description: The directed movement of substances into the nucleus.

gene.set.statistics.name: sequestering of calcium ion
gene.set.statistics.description: The process of binding or confining calcium ions such that they are separated from other components of a biological system.

gene.set.statistics.name: release of sequestered calcium ion into cytosol
gene.set.statistics.description: The process in which calcium ions sequestered in the endoplasmic reticulum, Golgi apparatus or mitochondria are released into the cytosolic compartment.

gene.set.statistics.name: cartilage development
gene.set.statistics.description: The process whose specific outcome is the progression of a cartilage element over time, from its formation to the mature structure. Cartilage elements are skeletal elements that consist of connective tissue dominated by extracellular matrix containing collagen type II and large amounts of proteoglycan, particularly chondroitin sulfate.

gene.set.statistics.name: cytoplasmic sequestering of protein
gene.set.statistics.description: The selective interaction of a protein with specific molecules in the cytoplasm, thereby inhibiting its transport into other areas of the cell.

gene.set.statistics.name: regulation of protein transport
gene.set.statistics.description: Any process that modulates the frequency, rate or extent of the directed movement of a protein into, out of or within a cell, or between cells, by means of some agent such as a transporter or pore.

gene.set.statistics.name: negative regulation of protein transport
gene.set.statistics.description: Any process that stops, prevents, or reduces the frequency, rate or extent of the directed movement of a protein into, out of or within a cell, or between cells, by means of some agent such as a transporter or pore.

gene.set.statistics.name: spindle assembly
gene.set.statistics.description: The aggregation, arrangement and bonding together of a set of components to form the spindle, the array of microtubules and associated molecules that serves to move duplicated chromosomes apart.

gene.set.statistics.name: mitotic spindle disassembly
gene.set.statistics.description: The controlled breakdown of the spindle during a mitotic cell cycle.

gene.set.statistics.name: positive regulation of protein metabolic process
gene.set.statistics.description: Any process that activates or increases the frequency, rate or extent of the chemical reactions and pathways involving a protein.

gene.set.statistics.name: negative regulation of protein metabolic process
gene.set.statistics.description: Any process that stops, prevents, or reduces the frequency, rate or extent of chemical reactions and pathways involving a protein.

gene.set.statistics.name: regulation of RNA metabolic process
gene.set.statistics.description: Any process that modulates the frequency, rate or extent of the chemical reactions and pathways involving RNA.

gene.set.statistics.name: protein polymerization
gene.set.statistics.description: The process of creating protein polymers, compounds composed of a large number of component monomers; polymeric proteins may be made up of different or identical monomers. Polymerization occurs by the addition of extra monomers to an existing poly- or oligomeric protein.

gene.set.statistics.name: protein complex oligomerization
gene.set.statistics.description: The process of creating protein oligomers, compounds composed of a small number, usually between three and ten, of component monomers; protein oligomers may be composed of different or identical monomers. Oligomers may be formed by the polymerization of a number of monomers or the depolymerization of a large protein polymer.

gene.set.statistics.name: protein homooligomerization
gene.set.statistics.description: The process of creating protein oligomers, compounds composed of a small number, usually between three and ten, of identical component monomers. Oligomers may be formed by the polymerization of a number of monomers or the depolymerization of a large protein polymer.

gene.set.statistics.name: protein tetramerization
gene.set.statistics.description: The formation of a protein tetramer, a macromolecular structure consisting of four noncovalently associated identical or nonidentical subunits.

gene.set.statistics.name: negative regulation of cellular component movement
gene.set.statistics.description: Any process that stops, prevents, or reduces the frequency, rate or extent of the movement of a cellular component.

gene.set.statistics.name: positive regulation of cellular component movement
gene.set.statistics.description: Any process that activates or increases the frequency, rate or extent of the movement of a cellular component.

gene.set.statistics.name: chromosome organization
gene.set.statistics.description: A process that is carried out at the cellular level that results in the assembly, arrangement of constituent parts, or disassembly of chromosomes, structures composed of a very long molecule of DNA and associated proteins that carries hereditary information. This term covers covalent modifications at the molecular level as well as spatial relationships among the major components of a chromosome.

gene.set.statistics.name: regulation of release of sequestered calcium ion into cytosol
gene.set.statistics.description: Any process that modulates the frequency, rate or extent of the release into the cytosolic compartment of calcium ions sequestered in the endoplasmic reticulum or mitochondria.

gene.set.statistics.name: negative regulation of release of sequestered calcium ion into cytosol
gene.set.statistics.description: Any process that stops, prevents, or reduces the frequency, rate or extent of the release into the cytosolic compartment of calcium ions sequestered in the endoplasmic reticulum or mitochondria.

gene.set.statistics.name: positive regulation of release of sequestered calcium ion into cytosol
gene.set.statistics.description: Any process that activates or increases the frequency, rate or extent of the release into the cytosolic compartment of calcium ions sequestered in the endoplasmic reticulum or mitochondria.

gene.set.statistics.name: protein homotetramerization
gene.set.statistics.description: The formation of a protein homotetramer, a macromolecular structure consisting of four noncovalently associated identical subunits.

gene.set.statistics.name: protein heterotetramerization
gene.set.statistics.description: The formation of a protein heterotetramer, a macromolecular structure consisting of four noncovalently associated subunits, of which not all are identical.

gene.set.statistics.name: protein heterooligomerization
gene.set.statistics.description: The process of creating protein oligomers, compounds composed of a small number, usually between three and ten, of component monomers that are not all identical. Oligomers may be formed by the polymerization of a number of monomers or the depolymerization of a large protein polymer.

gene.set.statistics.name: nuclear pore complex assembly
gene.set.statistics.description: The aggregation, arrangement and bonding together of a set of components to form a nuclear pore complex.

gene.set.statistics.name: establishment of spindle localization
gene.set.statistics.description: The directed movement of the spindle to a specific location in the cell.

gene.set.statistics.name: establishment of spindle orientation
gene.set.statistics.description: Any process that set the alignment of spindle relative to other cellular structures.

gene.set.statistics.name: establishment of meiotic spindle localization
gene.set.statistics.description: The cell cycle process in which the directed movement of the meiotic spindle to a specific location in the cell occurs.

gene.set.statistics.name: centrosome duplication
gene.set.statistics.description: The replication of a centrosome, a structure comprised of a pair of centrioles and peri-centriolar material from which a microtubule spindle apparatus is organized.

gene.set.statistics.name: cell division
gene.set.statistics.description: The process resulting in division and partitioning of components of a cell to form more cells; may or may not be accompanied by the physical separation of a cell into distinct, individually membrane-bounded daughter cells.

gene.set.statistics.name: regulation of cell division
gene.set.statistics.description: Any process that modulates the frequency, rate or extent of the physical partitioning and separation of a cell into daughter cells.

gene.set.statistics.name: attachment of mitotic spindle microtubules to kinetochore
gene.set.statistics.description: The cell cycle process in which spindle microtubules become physically associated with the proteins making up the kinetochore complex as part of mitotic metaphase plate congression.

gene.set.statistics.name: meiotic cell cycle
gene.set.statistics.description: Progression through the phases of the meiotic cell cycle, in which canonically a cell replicates to produce four offspring with half the chromosomal content of the progenitor cell via two nuclear divisions.

gene.set.statistics.name: positive regulation of cyclic-nucleotide phosphodiesterase activity
gene.set.statistics.description: Any process that activates or increases the frequency, rate or extent of cyclic nucleotide phosphodiesterase activity, the catalysis of the reaction: nucleotide 3',5'-cyclic phosphate + H2O = nucleotide 5'-phosphate.

gene.set.statistics.name: negative regulation of cyclic-nucleotide phosphodiesterase activity
gene.set.statistics.description: Any process that stops or reduces the rate of cyclic nucleotide phosphodiesterase activity, the catalysis of the reaction: nucleotide 3',5'-cyclic phosphate + H2O = nucleotide 5'-phosphate.

gene.set.statistics.name: kinetochore organization
gene.set.statistics.description: A process that is carried out at the cellular level which results in the assembly, arrangement of constituent parts, or disassembly of the kinetochore, a multisubunit complex that is located at the centromeric region of DNA and provides an attachment point for the spindle microtubules.

gene.set.statistics.name: response to glucocorticoid
gene.set.statistics.description: Any process that results in a change in state or activity of a cell or an organism (in terms of movement, secretion, enzyme production, gene expression, etc.) as a result of a glucocorticoid stimulus. Glucocorticoids are hormonal C21 corticosteroids synthesized from cholesterol with the ability to bind with the cortisol receptor and trigger similar effects. Glucocorticoids act primarily on carbohydrate and protein metabolism, and have anti-inflammatory effects.

gene.set.statistics.name: positive regulation of neurotrophin TRK receptor signaling pathway
gene.set.statistics.description: Any process that activates or increases the frequency, rate or extent of the neurotrophin TRK receptor signaling pathway.

gene.set.statistics.name: neuron apoptotic process
gene.set.statistics.description: Any apoptotic process in a neuron, the basic cellular unit of nervous tissue. Each neuron consists of a body, an axon, and dendrites. Their purpose is to receive, conduct, and transmit impulses in the nervous system.

gene.set.statistics.name: stress-activated MAPK cascade
gene.set.statistics.description: A series of molecular signals in which a stress-activated MAP kinase cascade relays one or more of the signals; MAP kinase cascades involve at least three protein kinase activities and culminate in the phosphorylation and activation of a MAP kinase.

gene.set.statistics.name: response to nitrosative stress
gene.set.statistics.description: Any process that results in a change in state or activity of a cell or an organism (in terms of movement, secretion, enzyme production, gene expression, etc.) as a result of a nitrosative stress stimulus. Nitrosative stress is a state often resulting from exposure to high levels of nitric oxide (NO) or the highly reactive oxidant peroxynitrite, which is produced following interaction of NO with superoxide anions.

gene.set.statistics.name: response to corticosterone
gene.set.statistics.description: Any process that results in a change in state or activity of a cell or an organism (in terms of movement, secretion, enzyme production, gene expression, etc.) as a result of a corticosterone stimulus. Corticosterone is a 21 carbon steroid hormone of the corticosteroid type, produced in the cortex of the adrenal glands. In many species, corticosterone is the principal glucocorticoid, involved in regulation of fuel metabolism, immune reactions, and stress responses.

gene.set.statistics.name: response to cortisol
gene.set.statistics.description: Any process that results in a change in state or activity of a cell or an organism (in terms of movement, secretion, enzyme production, gene expression, etc.) as a result of a cortisol stimulus. Cortisol is the major natural glucocorticoid synthesized in the zona fasciculata of the adrenal cortex; it affects the metabolism of glucose, protein, and fats and has appreciable mineralocorticoid activity. It also regulates the immune system and affects many other functions.

gene.set.statistics.name: positive regulation of ubiquitin-protein transferase activity
gene.set.statistics.description: Any process that activates, maintains or increases the rate of ubiquitin transferase activity.

gene.set.statistics.name: negative regulation of ubiquitin-protein transferase activity
gene.set.statistics.description: Any process that stops, prevents, or reduces the frequency, rate or extent of ubiquitin transferase activity.

gene.set.statistics.name: negative regulation of meiotic cell cycle
gene.set.statistics.description: Any process that stops, prevents or reduces the rate or extent of progression through the meiotic cell cycle.

gene.set.statistics.name: regulation of intracellular pH
gene.set.statistics.description: Any process that modulates the internal pH of a cell, measured by the concentration of the hydrogen ion.

gene.set.statistics.name: maintenance of protein location in nucleus
gene.set.statistics.description: Any process in which a protein is maintained in the nucleus and prevented from moving elsewhere. These include sequestration within the nucleus, protein stabilization to prevent transport elsewhere and the active retrieval of proteins that escape the nucleus.

gene.set.statistics.name: regulation of cytosolic calcium ion concentration
gene.set.statistics.description: Any process involved in the maintenance of an internal steady state of calcium ions within the cytosol of a cell or between the cytosol and its surroundings.

gene.set.statistics.name: negative regulation of cytosolic calcium ion concentration
gene.set.statistics.description: Any process that decreases the concentration of calcium ions in the cytosol.

gene.set.statistics.name: regulation of filopodium assembly
gene.set.statistics.description: Any process that modulates the frequency, rate or extent of the assembly of a filopodium, a thin, stiff protrusion extended by the leading edge of a motile cell such as a crawling fibroblast or amoeba, or an axonal growth cone.

gene.set.statistics.name: negative regulation of filopodium assembly
gene.set.statistics.description: Any process that stops, prevents, or reduces the frequency, rate or extent of the assembly of a filopodium, a thin, stiff protrusion extended by the leading edge of a motile cell such as a crawling fibroblast or amoeba, or an axonal growth cone.

gene.set.statistics.name: positive regulation of filopodium assembly
gene.set.statistics.description: Any process that activates or increases the frequency, rate or extent of the assembly of a filopodium, a thin, stiff protrusion extended by the leading edge of a motile cell such as a crawling fibroblast or amoeba, or an axonal growth cone.

gene.set.statistics.name: regulation of stress fiber assembly
gene.set.statistics.description: Any process that modulates the frequency, rate or extent of the assembly of a stress fiber, a bundle of microfilaments and other proteins found in fibroblasts.

gene.set.statistics.name: regulation of cytoskeleton organization
gene.set.statistics.description: Any process that modulates the frequency, rate or extent of the formation, arrangement of constituent parts, or disassembly of cytoskeletal structures.

gene.set.statistics.name: positive regulation of cytoskeleton organization
gene.set.statistics.description: Any process that activates or increases the frequency, rate or extent of the formation, arrangement of constituent parts, or disassembly of cytoskeletal structures.

gene.set.statistics.name: positive regulation of stress fiber assembly
gene.set.statistics.description: Any process that activates or increases the frequency, rate or extent of the assembly of a stress fiber, a bundle of microfilaments and other proteins found in fibroblasts.

gene.set.statistics.name: negative regulation of stress fiber assembly
gene.set.statistics.description: Any process that stops, prevents, or reduces the frequency, rate or extent of the assembly a stress fiber, a bundle of microfilaments and other proteins found in fibroblasts.

gene.set.statistics.name: positive regulation of keratinocyte migration
gene.set.statistics.description: Any process that activates or increases the frequency, rate or extent of keratinocyte migration.

gene.set.statistics.name: mitochondrial calcium ion homeostasis
gene.set.statistics.description: Any process involved in the maintenance of an internal steady state of calcium ions within the cytoplasm of a cell or between mitochondria and their surroundings.

gene.set.statistics.name: positive regulation of mitochondrial calcium ion concentration
gene.set.statistics.description: Any process that increases the concentration of calcium ions in mitochondria.

gene.set.statistics.name: positive regulation of histone H3-K4 methylation
gene.set.statistics.description: Any process that activates or increases the frequency, rate or extent of the covalent addition of a methyl group to the lysine at position 4 of histone H3.

gene.set.statistics.name: negative regulation of histone H3-K4 methylation
gene.set.statistics.description: Any process that stops, prevents, or reduces the frequency, rate or extent of the covalent addition of a methyl group to the lysine at position 4 of histone H3.

gene.set.statistics.name: negative regulation of histone H3-K9 methylation
gene.set.statistics.description: Any process that stops, prevents, or reduces the frequency, rate or extent of the covalent addition of a methyl group to the lysine at position 9 of histone H3.

gene.set.statistics.name: positive regulation of histone H3-K9 methylation
gene.set.statistics.description: Any process that activates or increases the frequency, rate or extent of the covalent addition of a methyl group to the lysine at position 9 of histone H3.

gene.set.statistics.name: dopamine uptake involved in synaptic transmission
gene.set.statistics.description: The directed movement of dopamine into a presynaptic neuron or glial cell. In this context, dopamine is a catecholamine neurotransmitter and a metabolic precursor of noradrenaline and adrenaline.

gene.set.statistics.name: response to cAMP
gene.set.statistics.description: Any process that results in a change in state or activity of a cell or an organism (in terms of movement, secretion, enzyme production, gene expression, etc.) as a result of a cAMP (cyclic AMP, adenosine 3',5'-cyclophosphate) stimulus.

gene.set.statistics.name: response to calcium ion
gene.set.statistics.description: Any process that results in a change in state or activity of a cell or an organism (in terms of movement, secretion, enzyme production, gene expression, etc.) as a result of a calcium ion stimulus.

gene.set.statistics.name: response to methylmercury
gene.set.statistics.description: Any process that results in a change in state or activity of a cell or an organism (in terms of movement, secretion, enzyme production, gene expression, etc.) as a result of a methylmercury stimulus.

gene.set.statistics.name: response to electrical stimulus
gene.set.statistics.description: Any process that results in a change in state or activity of a cell or an organism (in terms of movement, secretion, enzyme production, gene expression, etc.) as a result of an electrical stimulus.

gene.set.statistics.name: proteolysis involved in cellular protein catabolic process
gene.set.statistics.description: The hydrolysis of a peptide bond or bonds within a protein as part of the chemical reactions and pathways resulting in the breakdown of a protein by individual cells.

gene.set.statistics.name: protein maturation
gene.set.statistics.description: Any process leading to the attainment of the full functional capacity of a protein.

gene.set.statistics.name: defense response to virus
gene.set.statistics.description: Reactions triggered in response to the presence of a virus that act to protect the cell or organism.

gene.set.statistics.name: regulation of norepinephrine uptake
gene.set.statistics.description: Any process that modulates the frequency, rate or extent of the directed movement of the neurotransmitter norepinephrine into a cell.

gene.set.statistics.name: actin filament network formation
gene.set.statistics.description: The assembly of a network of actin filaments; actin filaments on different axes and with differing orientations are crosslinked together to form a mesh of filaments.

gene.set.statistics.name: organelle localization
gene.set.statistics.description: Any process in which an organelle is transported to, and/or maintained in, a specific location.

gene.set.statistics.name: centrosome localization
gene.set.statistics.description: Any process in which a centrosome is transported to, and/or maintained in, a specific location within the cell.

gene.set.statistics.name: nucleus localization
gene.set.statistics.description: Any process in which the nucleus is transported to, and/or maintained in, a specific location within the cell.

gene.set.statistics.name: spindle localization
gene.set.statistics.description: Any process in which is the spindle is transported to, and/or maintained in, a specific location.

gene.set.statistics.name: establishment of centrosome localization
gene.set.statistics.description: The directed movement of the centrosome to a specific location.

gene.set.statistics.name: maintenance of centrosome location
gene.set.statistics.description: Any process in which a centrosome is maintained in a specific location within a cell and prevented from moving elsewhere.

gene.set.statistics.name: localization within membrane
