gene.set.statistics.description: Any process in which a substance or cellular entity, such as a protein complex or organelle, is transported to, and/or maintained in, a specific location within a membrane.

gene.set.statistics.name: establishment of Golgi localization
gene.set.statistics.description: The directed movement of the Golgi to a specific location.

gene.set.statistics.name: actin filament capping
gene.set.statistics.description: The binding of a protein or protein complex to the end of an actin filament, thus preventing the addition, exchange or removal of further actin subunits.

gene.set.statistics.name: pointed-end actin filament capping
gene.set.statistics.description: The binding of a protein or protein complex to the pointed (or minus) end of an actin filament, thus preventing the addition, exchange or removal of further actin subunits.

gene.set.statistics.name: biological process involved in interaction with symbiont
gene.set.statistics.description: An interaction between two organisms living together in more or less intimate association. The term symbiont is used for the smaller (macro) of the two members of a symbiosis; the various forms of symbiosis include parasitism, commensalism and mutualism.

gene.set.statistics.name: regulation of cell cycle
gene.set.statistics.description: Any process that modulates the rate or extent of progression through the cell cycle.

gene.set.statistics.name: actin crosslink formation
gene.set.statistics.description: The process in which two or more actin filaments are connected together by proteins that act as crosslinks between the filaments. The crosslinked filaments may be on the same or differing axes.

gene.set.statistics.name: positive regulation of nitric-oxide synthase biosynthetic process
gene.set.statistics.description: Any process that activates or increases the frequency, rate or extent of the chemical reactions and pathways resulting in the formation of a nitric oxide synthase enzyme.

gene.set.statistics.name: response to redox state
gene.set.statistics.description: Any process that results in a change in state or activity of a cell or an organism (in terms of movement, secretion, enzyme production, gene expression, etc.) as a result of a stimulus indicating redox state. Redox state refers to the balance of oxidized versus reduced forms of electron donors and acceptors in an organelle, cell or organ; plastoquinone, glutathione (GSH/GSSG), and nicotinamide nucleotides (NAD+/NADH and NADP+/NADPH) are among the most important.

gene.set.statistics.name: positive regulation of cell division
gene.set.statistics.description: Any process that activates or increases the frequency, rate or extent of cell division.

gene.set.statistics.name: negative regulation of cell division
gene.set.statistics.description: Any process that stops, prevents, or reduces the frequency, rate or extent of cell division.

gene.set.statistics.name: response to misfolded protein
gene.set.statistics.description: Any process that results in a change in state or activity of a cell or an organism (in terms of movement, secretion, enzyme production, gene expression, etc.) as a result of a misfolded protein stimulus.

gene.set.statistics.name: medium-chain fatty acid catabolic process
gene.set.statistics.description: The chemical reactions and pathways resulting in the breakdown of any fatty acid with a chain length of between C6 and C12.

gene.set.statistics.name: positive regulation of hair follicle development
gene.set.statistics.description: Any process that activates or increases the frequency, rate or extent of hair follicle development.

gene.set.statistics.name: positive regulation of synapse structural plasticity
gene.set.statistics.description: Any process that activates, maintains or increases the frequency, rate or extent of synaptic structural plasticity.

gene.set.statistics.name: protein autoubiquitination
gene.set.statistics.description: The ubiquitination by a protein of one or more of its own amino acid residues, or residues on an identical protein. Ubiquitination occurs on the lysine residue by formation of an isopeptide crosslink.

gene.set.statistics.name: killing by host of symbiont cells
gene.set.statistics.description: Any process mediated by an organism that results in the death of cells in the symbiont organism. The symbiont is defined as the smaller of the organisms involved in a symbiotic interaction.

gene.set.statistics.name: regulation of mitochondrial membrane potential
gene.set.statistics.description: Any process that modulates the establishment or extent of the mitochondrial membrane potential, the electric potential existing across the mitochondrial membrane arising from charges in the membrane itself and from the charges present in the media on either side of the membrane.

gene.set.statistics.name: regulation of focal adhesion assembly
gene.set.statistics.description: Any process that modulates the frequency, rate or extent of focal adhesion formation, the establishment and maturation of focal adhesions.

gene.set.statistics.name: positive regulation of focal adhesion assembly
gene.set.statistics.description: Any process that activates or increases the frequency, rate or extent of focal adhesion assembly, the establishment and maturation of focal adhesions.

gene.set.statistics.name: negative regulation of focal adhesion assembly
gene.set.statistics.description: Any process that stops, prevents, or reduces the frequency, rate or extent of focal adhesion assembly, the establishment and maturation of focal adhesions.

gene.set.statistics.name: positive regulation of protein kinase B signaling
gene.set.statistics.description: Any process that activates or increases the frequency, rate or extent of protein kinase B signaling, a series of reactions mediated by the intracellular serine/threonine kinase protein kinase B.

gene.set.statistics.name: negative regulation of protein kinase B signaling
gene.set.statistics.description: Any process that stops, prevents, or reduces the frequency, rate or extent of protein kinase B signaling, a series of reactions mediated by the intracellular serine/threonine kinase protein kinase B.

gene.set.statistics.name: membrane depolarization
gene.set.statistics.description: The process in which membrane potential decreases with respect to its steady-state potential, usually from negative potential to a more positive potential. For example, the initial depolarization during the rising phase of an action potential is in the direction from the negative steady-state resting potential towards the positive membrane potential that will be the peak of the action potential.

gene.set.statistics.name: regulation of mitochondrial depolarization
gene.set.statistics.description: Any process that modulates the frequency, rate or extent of the change in the membrane potential of the mitochondria from negative to positive.

gene.set.statistics.name: positive regulation of mitochondrial depolarization
gene.set.statistics.description: Any process that activates, maintains or increases the frequency, rate or extent of the change in the membrane potential of the mitochondria from negative to positive.

gene.set.statistics.name: regulation of calcium ion transport
gene.set.statistics.description: Any process that modulates the frequency, rate or extent of the directed movement of calcium ions into, out of or within a cell, or between cells, by means of some agent such as a transporter or pore.

gene.set.statistics.name: positive regulation of calcium ion transport
gene.set.statistics.description: Any process that activates or increases the frequency, rate or extent of the directed movement of calcium ions into, out of or within a cell, or between cells, by means of some agent such as a transporter or pore.

gene.set.statistics.name: regulation of sensory perception of pain
gene.set.statistics.description: Any process that modulates the frequency, rate or extent of the sensory perception of pain, the series of events required for an organism to receive a painful stimulus, convert it to a molecular signal, and recognize and characterize the signal.

gene.set.statistics.name: synaptic transmission, GABAergic
gene.set.statistics.description: The vesicular release of  gamma-aminobutyric acid (GABA). from a presynapse, across a chemical synapse, the subsequent activation of GABA receptors at the postsynapse of a target cell (neuron, muscle, or secretory cell) and the effects of this activation on the postsynaptic membrane potential and ionic composition of the postsynaptic cytosol. This process encompasses both spontaneous and evoked release of neurotransmitter and all parts of synaptic vesicle exocytosis. Evoked transmission starts with the arrival of an action potential at the presynapse.

gene.set.statistics.name: positive regulation of synapse assembly
gene.set.statistics.description: Any process that activates, maintains or increases the frequency, rate or extent of synapse assembly, the aggregation, arrangement and bonding together of a set of components to form a synapse.

gene.set.statistics.name: positive regulation of synaptic transmission, glutamatergic
gene.set.statistics.description: Any process that activates, maintains or increases the frequency, rate or extent of glutamatergic synaptic transmission, the process of communication from a neuron to another neuron across a synapse using the neurotransmitter glutamate.

gene.set.statistics.name: positive regulation of telomerase activity
gene.set.statistics.description: Any process that activates or increases the frequency, rate or extent of telomerase activity, the catalysis of the reaction: deoxynucleoside triphosphate + DNA(n) = diphosphate + DNA(n+1).

gene.set.statistics.name: regulation of chromosome segregation
gene.set.statistics.description: Any process that modulates the frequency, rate or extent of chromosome segregation, the process in which genetic material, in the form of chromosomes, is organized and then physically separated and apportioned to two or more sets.

gene.set.statistics.name: positive regulation of chromosome segregation
gene.set.statistics.description: Any process that activates or increases the frequency, rate or extent of chromosome segregation, the process in which genetic material, in the form of chromosomes, is organized and then physically separated and apportioned to two or more sets.

gene.set.statistics.name: positive regulation of attachment of spindle microtubules to kinetochore
gene.set.statistics.description: Any process that activates or increases the frequency, rate or extent of the attachment of spindle microtubules to the kinetochore.

gene.set.statistics.name: regulation of attachment of spindle microtubules to kinetochore
gene.set.statistics.description: Any process that modulates the frequency, rate or extent of the attachment of spindle microtubules to the kinetochore.

gene.set.statistics.name: negative regulation by host of symbiont molecular function
gene.set.statistics.description: Any process in which an organism stops, prevents, or reduces the frequency, rate or extent of the functional activity of symbiont proteins. The symbiont is defined as the smaller of the organisms involved in a symbiotic interaction.

gene.set.statistics.name: regulation of endopeptidase activity
gene.set.statistics.description: Any process that modulates the frequency, rate or extent of endopeptidase activity, the endohydrolysis of peptide bonds within proteins.

gene.set.statistics.name: monoacylglycerol catabolic process
gene.set.statistics.description: The chemical reactions and pathways resulting in the breakdown of monoacylglycerol, any ester of glycerol in which any one of its hydroxyl groups has been acylated with a fatty acid, the other being non-esterified.

gene.set.statistics.name: cellular glucuronidation
gene.set.statistics.description: The modification of an organic chemical by the conjugation of glucuronic acid. The substances resulting from glucuronidation are known as glucuronosides (or glucuronides) and are often much more water-soluble than the non-glucuronic acid-containing precursor.

gene.set.statistics.name: cardiac muscle cell differentiation
gene.set.statistics.description: The process in which a cardiac muscle precursor cell acquires specialized features of a cardiac muscle cell. Cardiac muscle cells are striated muscle cells that are responsible for heart contraction.

gene.set.statistics.name: ventricular cardiac muscle tissue morphogenesis
gene.set.statistics.description: The process in which the anatomical structures of cardiac ventricle muscle is generated and organized.

gene.set.statistics.name: cardiac muscle cell development
gene.set.statistics.description: The process whose specific outcome is the progression of a cardiac muscle cell over time, from its formation to the mature state.

gene.set.statistics.name: ventricular cardiac muscle cell development
gene.set.statistics.description: The process whose specific outcome is the progression of a ventricular cardiac muscle cell over time, from its formation to the mature state. Cardiac muscle cells are striated muscle cells that are responsible for heart contraction. The ventricle is the part of the heart that pumps blood out of the organ.

gene.set.statistics.name: metal ion homeostasis
gene.set.statistics.description: Any process involved in the maintenance of an internal steady state of metal ions within an organism or cell.

gene.set.statistics.name: iron ion homeostasis
gene.set.statistics.description: Any process involved in the maintenance of an internal steady state of iron ions within an organism or cell.

gene.set.statistics.name: calcium ion homeostasis
gene.set.statistics.description: Any process involved in the maintenance of an internal steady state of calcium ions within an organism or cell.

gene.set.statistics.name: anion homeostasis
gene.set.statistics.description: Any process involved in the maintenance of an internal steady state of anions within an organism or cell.

gene.set.statistics.name: transmembrane transport
gene.set.statistics.description: The process in which a solute is transported across a lipid bilayer, from one side of a membrane to the other.

gene.set.statistics.name: lipid homeostasis
gene.set.statistics.description: Any process involved in the maintenance of an internal steady state of lipid within an organism or cell.

gene.set.statistics.name: fatty acid homeostasis
gene.set.statistics.description: Any process involved in the maintenance of an internal steady state of fatty acid within an organism or cell.

gene.set.statistics.name: sterol homeostasis
gene.set.statistics.description: Any process involved in the maintenance of an internal steady state of sterol within an organism or cell.

gene.set.statistics.name: response to hyperoxia
gene.set.statistics.description: Any process that results in a change in state or activity of a cell or an organism (in terms of movement, secretion, enzyme production, gene expression, etc.) as a result of a stimulus indicating increased oxygen tension.

gene.set.statistics.name: regulation of cardiac muscle contraction
gene.set.statistics.description: Any process that modulates the frequency, rate or extent of cardiac muscle contraction.

gene.set.statistics.name: relaxation of cardiac muscle
gene.set.statistics.description: The process in which the extent of cardiac muscle contraction is reduced.

gene.set.statistics.name: L-proline biosynthetic process
gene.set.statistics.description: The chemical reactions and pathways resulting in the formation of L-proline, an L-enantiomer of a chiral, cyclic, nonessential alpha-amino acid found in peptide linkage in proteins.

gene.set.statistics.name: Sertoli cell development
gene.set.statistics.description: The process whose specific outcome is the progression of a Sertoli cell over time, from its formation to the mature structure. Cell development does not include the steps involved in committing a cell to a Sertoli cell fate.

gene.set.statistics.name: Sertoli cell proliferation
gene.set.statistics.description: The multiplication or reproduction of Sertoli cells, resulting in the expansion of the Sertoli cell population. A Sertoli cell is a supporting cell projecting inward from the basement membrane of seminiferous tubules.

gene.set.statistics.name: radial glial cell differentiation
gene.set.statistics.description: The process in which neuroepithelial cells of the neural tube give rise to radial glial cells, specialized bipotential progenitors cells of the brain. Differentiation includes the processes involved in commitment of a cell to a specific fate.

gene.set.statistics.name: Bergmann glial cell differentiation
gene.set.statistics.description: The process in which neuroepithelial cells of the neural tube give rise to Brgmann glial cells, specialized bipotential progenitors cells of the cerebellum. Differentiation includes the processes involved in commitment of a cell to a specific fate.

gene.set.statistics.name: roof of mouth development
gene.set.statistics.description: The biological process whose specific outcome is the progression of the roof of the mouth from an initial condition to its mature state. This process begins with the formation of the structure and ends with the mature structure. The roof of the mouth is the partition that separates the nasal and oral cavities.

gene.set.statistics.name: cardiac muscle cell proliferation
gene.set.statistics.description: The expansion of a cardiac muscle cell population by cell division.

gene.set.statistics.name: pericardium development
gene.set.statistics.description: The process whose specific outcome is the progression of the pericardium over time, from its formation to the mature structure. The pericardium is a double-walled sac that contains the heart and the roots of the aorta, vena cava and the pulmonary artery.

gene.set.statistics.name: retina development in camera-type eye
gene.set.statistics.description: The process whose specific outcome is the progression of the retina over time, from its formation to the mature structure. The retina is the innermost layer or coating at the back of the eyeball, which is sensitive to light and in which the optic nerve terminates.

gene.set.statistics.name: positive regulation of cardiac muscle cell proliferation
gene.set.statistics.description: Any process that activates or increases the frequency, rate or extent of cardiac muscle cell proliferation.

gene.set.statistics.name: heart contraction
gene.set.statistics.description: The multicellular organismal process in which the heart decreases in volume in a characteristic way to propel blood through the body.

gene.set.statistics.name: cardiac muscle contraction
gene.set.statistics.description: Muscle contraction of cardiac muscle tissue.

gene.set.statistics.name: positive regulation of protein glycosylation
gene.set.statistics.description: Any process that activates or increases the frequency, rate or extent of the glycosylation of one or more amino acid residues within a protein. Protein glycosylation is the addition of a carbohydrate or carbohydrate derivative unit to a protein amino acid, e.g. the addition of glycan chains to proteins.

gene.set.statistics.name: mammary gland involution
gene.set.statistics.description: The tissue remodeling that removes differentiated mammary epithelia during weaning.

gene.set.statistics.name: positive regulation of apoptotic process involved in mammary gland involution
gene.set.statistics.description: Any process that activates or increases the frequency, rate or extent of cell death by apoptotic process of mammary epithelial cells during mammary gland involution.

gene.set.statistics.name: vagina development
gene.set.statistics.description: The reproductive developmental process whose specific outcome is the progression of the vagina over time, from its formation to the mature structure.

gene.set.statistics.name: canonical Wnt signaling pathway
gene.set.statistics.description: The series of molecular signals initiated by binding of a Wnt protein to a frizzled family receptor on the surface of the target cell, followed by propagation of the signal via beta-catenin, and ending with a change in transcription of target genes. In this pathway, the activated receptor signals via downstream effectors that result in the inhibition of beta-catenin phosphorylation, thereby preventing degradation of beta-catenin. Stabilized beta-catenin can then accumulate and travel to the nucleus to trigger changes in transcription of target genes.

gene.set.statistics.name: Wnt signaling pathway, planar cell polarity pathway
gene.set.statistics.description: The series of molecular signals initiated by binding of a Wnt protein to a receptor on the surface of the target cell where activated receptors signal via downstream effectors including C-Jun N-terminal kinase (JNK) to modulate cytoskeletal elements and control cell polarity.

gene.set.statistics.name: synapse maturation
gene.set.statistics.description: The process that organizes a synapse so that it attains its fully functional state. Synaptic maturation plays a critical role in the establishment of effective synaptic connections in early development.

gene.set.statistics.name: regulation of postsynaptic membrane potential
gene.set.statistics.description: Any process that modulates the potential difference across a post-synaptic membrane.

gene.set.statistics.name: excitatory postsynaptic potential
gene.set.statistics.description: A process that leads to a temporary increase in postsynaptic potential due to the flow of positively charged ions into the postsynaptic cell. The flow of ions that causes an EPSP is an excitatory postsynaptic current (EPSC) and makes it easier for the neuron to fire an action potential.

gene.set.statistics.name: membrane hyperpolarization
gene.set.statistics.description: The process in which membrane potential increases with respect to its steady-state potential, usually from negative potential to a more negative potential. For example, during the repolarization phase of an action potential the membrane potential often becomes more negative or hyperpolarized before returning to the steady-state resting potential.

gene.set.statistics.name: auditory receptor cell stereocilium organization
gene.set.statistics.description: A process that is carried out at the cellular level which results in the assembly, arrangement of constituent parts, or disassembly of a stereocilium. A stereocilium is an actin-based protrusion from the apical surface of auditory hair cells.

gene.set.statistics.name: auditory receptor cell development
gene.set.statistics.description: The process whose specific outcome is the progression of an auditory receptor cell over time, from its formation to the mature structure. Cell development does not include the steps involved in committing a cell to a specific fate.

gene.set.statistics.name: maternal process involved in female pregnancy
gene.set.statistics.description: A reproductive process occurring in the mother that allows an embryo or fetus to develop within it.

gene.set.statistics.name: positive regulation of dopamine receptor signaling pathway
gene.set.statistics.description: Any process that activates or increases the frequency, rate or extent of the dopamine receptor protein signaling pathway. A dopamine receptor signaling pathway is the series of molecular signals generated as a consequence of a dopamine receptor binding to one of its physiological ligands.

gene.set.statistics.name: negative regulation of lipase activity
gene.set.statistics.description: Any process that decreases the frequency, rate or extent of lipase activity, the hydrolysis of a lipid or phospholipid.

gene.set.statistics.name: positive regulation of nuclear-transcribed mRNA poly(A) tail shortening
gene.set.statistics.description: Any process that increases the frequency, rate or extent of poly(A) tail shortening of a nuclear-transcribed mRNA. Poly(A) tail shortening is the decrease in length of the poly(A) tail of an mRNA from full length to an oligo(A) length.

gene.set.statistics.name: definitive hemopoiesis
gene.set.statistics.description: A second wave of blood cell production that, in vertebrates, generates long-term hemopoietic stem cells that continously provide erythroid, myeloid and lymphoid lineages throughout adulthood.

gene.set.statistics.name: hematopoietic stem cell differentiation
gene.set.statistics.description: The process in which a relatively unspecialized cell acquires specialized features of a hematopoietic stem cell. A stem cell is a cell that retains the ability to divide and proliferate throughout life to provide progenitor cells that can differentiate into specialized cells.

gene.set.statistics.name: regulation of mitotic spindle organization
gene.set.statistics.description: Any process that modulates the rate, frequency or extent of the assembly, arrangement of constituent parts, or disassembly of the microtubule spindle during a mitotic cell cycle.

gene.set.statistics.name: contact inhibition
gene.set.statistics.description: The series of events in which information about the density of cells in a population is received by direct cell-cell contact and is converted into a molecular signal, resulting in the cessation of cell growth or proliferation.

gene.set.statistics.name: positive regulation of glial cell proliferation
gene.set.statistics.description: Any process that activates or increases the rate or extent of glial cell proliferation.

gene.set.statistics.name: negative regulation of glial cell proliferation
gene.set.statistics.description: Any process that stops or decreases the rate or extent of glial cell proliferation.

gene.set.statistics.name: regulation of feeding behavior
gene.set.statistics.description: Any process that modulates the rate, frequency or extent of the behavior associated with the intake of food.

gene.set.statistics.name: regulation of transcription initiation from RNA polymerase II promoter
gene.set.statistics.description: Any process that modulates the rate, frequency or extent of a process involved in starting transcription from an RNA polymerase II promoter.

gene.set.statistics.name: positive regulation of transcription initiation from RNA polymerase II promoter
gene.set.statistics.description: Any process that increases the rate, frequency or extent of a process involved in starting transcription from an RNA polymerase II promoter.

gene.set.statistics.name: negative regulation of respiratory burst involved in inflammatory response
gene.set.statistics.description: Any process that decreases the rate, frequency or extent of a phase of elevated metabolic activity, during which oxygen consumption increases made as a defense response ; this leads to the production, by an NADH dependent system, of hydrogen peroxide (H2O2), superoxide anions and hydroxyl radicals.

gene.set.statistics.name: cilium assembly
gene.set.statistics.description: The assembly of a cilium, a specialized eukaryotic organelle that consists of a filiform extrusion of the cell surface. Each cilium is bounded by an extrusion of the cytoplasmic membrane, and contains a regular longitudinal array of microtubules, anchored basally in a centriole.

gene.set.statistics.name: long-term synaptic potentiation
gene.set.statistics.description: A process that modulates synaptic plasticity such that synapses are changed resulting in the increase in the rate, or frequency of synaptic transmission at the synapse.

gene.set.statistics.name: regulation of membrane repolarization
gene.set.statistics.description: Any process that modulates the establishment or extent of a membrane potential in the polarizing direction towards the resting potential, usually from positive to negative.

gene.set.statistics.name: regulation of ventricular cardiac muscle cell membrane repolarization
gene.set.statistics.description: Any process that modulates the establishment or extent of a membrane potential in the polarizing direction towards the resting potential in a ventricular cardiomyocyte.

gene.set.statistics.name: regulation of ryanodine-sensitive calcium-release channel activity
gene.set.statistics.description: Any process that modulates the activity of a ryanodine-sensitive calcium-release channel. The ryanodine-sensitive calcium-release channel catalyzes the transmembrane transfer of a calcium ion by a channel that opens when a ryanodine class ligand has been bound by the channel complex or one of its constituent parts.

gene.set.statistics.name: negative regulation of ryanodine-sensitive calcium-release channel activity
gene.set.statistics.description: Any process that decreases the activity of a ryanodine-sensitive calcium-release channel. The ryanodine-sensitive calcium-release channel catalyzes the transmembrane transfer of a calcium ion by a channel that opens when a ryanodine class ligand has been bound by the channel complex or one of its constituent parts.

gene.set.statistics.name: positive regulation of ryanodine-sensitive calcium-release channel activity
gene.set.statistics.description: Any process that increases the activity of a ryanodine-sensitive calcium-release channel. The ryanodine-sensitive calcium-release channel catalyzes the transmembrane transfer of a calcium ion by a channel that opens when a ryanodine class ligand has been bound by the channel complex or one of its constituent parts.

gene.set.statistics.name: face development
gene.set.statistics.description: The biological process whose specific outcome is the progression of a face from an initial condition to its mature state. The face is the ventral division of the head.

gene.set.statistics.name: face morphogenesis
gene.set.statistics.description: The process in which the anatomical structures of the face are generated and organized. The face is the ventral division of the head.

gene.set.statistics.name: cell chemotaxis
gene.set.statistics.description: The directed movement of a motile cell guided by a specific chemical concentration gradient. Movement may be towards a higher concentration (positive chemotaxis) or towards a lower concentration (negative chemotaxis).

gene.set.statistics.name: interferon-gamma-mediated signaling pathway
gene.set.statistics.description: A series of molecular signals initiated by the binding of interferon-gamma to a receptor on the surface of a cell, and ending with regulation of a downstream cellular process, e.g. transcription. Interferon gamma is the only member of the type II interferon found so far.

gene.set.statistics.name: regulation of interferon-gamma-mediated signaling pathway
gene.set.statistics.description: Any process that modulates the rate, frequency or extent of the series of molecular events generated as a consequence of interferon-gamma binding to a cell surface receptor.

gene.set.statistics.name: type I interferon signaling pathway
gene.set.statistics.description: A series of molecular signals initiated by the binding of a type I interferon to a receptor on the surface of a cell, and ending with regulation of a downstream cellular process, e.g. transcription. Type I interferons include the interferon-alpha, beta, delta, episilon, zeta, kappa, tau, and omega gene families.

gene.set.statistics.name: regulation of type I interferon-mediated signaling pathway
gene.set.statistics.description: Any process that modulates the rate, frequency or extent of a type I interferon-mediated signaling pathway. A type I interferon-mediated signaling pathway is the series of molecular events generated as a consequence of a type I interferon binding to a cell surface receptor.

gene.set.statistics.name: negative regulation of type I interferon-mediated signaling pathway
gene.set.statistics.description: Any process that decreases the rate, frequency or extent of a type I interferon-mediated signaling pathway. A type I interferon-mediated signaling pathway is the series of molecular events generated as a consequence of a type I interferon binding to a cell surface receptor.

gene.set.statistics.name: positive regulation of type I interferon-mediated signaling pathway
gene.set.statistics.description: Any process that increases the rate, frequency or extent of a type I interferon-mediated signaling pathway. A type I interferon-mediated signaling pathway is the series of molecular events generated as a consequence of a type I interferon binding to a cell surface receptor.

gene.set.statistics.name: bone trabecula formation
gene.set.statistics.description: The process of creating a trabecula in the bone. A trabecula is a tissue element in the form of a small beam, strut or rod.

gene.set.statistics.name: heart trabecula formation
gene.set.statistics.description: The process of creating a trabecula in the heart. A trabecula is a tissue element in the form of a small beam, strut or rod.

gene.set.statistics.name: bone development
gene.set.statistics.description: The process whose specific outcome is the progression of bone over time, from its formation to the mature structure. Bone is the hard skeletal connective tissue consisting of both mineral and cellular components.

gene.set.statistics.name: cell adhesion molecule production
gene.set.statistics.description: The appearance of a cell adhesion molecule due to biosynthesis or secretion.

gene.set.statistics.name: regulation of Fc receptor mediated stimulatory signaling pathway
gene.set.statistics.description: Any process that modulates the rate, frequency or extent of the Fc receptor mediated stimulatory signaling pathway. The Fc receptor mediated stimulatory signaling pathway is a series of molecular signals generated as a consequence of a the binding of the Fc portion of an immunoglobulin by an Fc receptor capable of activating or perpetuating an immune response. The Fc portion of an immunoglobulin is its C-terminal constant region.

gene.set.statistics.name: regulation of ventricular cardiac muscle cell membrane depolarization
gene.set.statistics.description: Any process that modulates the establishment or extent of a membrane potential in the depolarizing direction away from the resting potential in a ventricular cardiomyocyte.

gene.set.statistics.name: regulation of SMAD protein signal transduction
gene.set.statistics.description: Any process that modulates the rate, frequency or extent of SMAD protein signal transduction. Pathway-restricted SMAD proteins and common-partner SMAD proteins are involved in the transforming growth factor beta receptor signaling pathways.

gene.set.statistics.name: positive regulation of SMAD protein signal transduction
gene.set.statistics.description: Any process that increases the rate, frequency or extent of SMAD protein signal transduction. Pathway-restricted SMAD proteins and common-partner SMAD proteins are involved in the transforming growth factor beta receptor signaling pathways.

gene.set.statistics.name: SMAD protein signal transduction
gene.set.statistics.description: The cascade of processes by which a signal interacts with a receptor, causing a change in the activity of a SMAD protein, and ultimately effecting a change in the functioning of the cell.

gene.set.statistics.name: growth hormone receptor signaling pathway
gene.set.statistics.description: The series of molecular signals generated as a consequence of growth hormone receptor binding to its physiological ligand.

gene.set.statistics.name: growth hormone receptor signaling pathway via JAK-STAT
gene.set.statistics.description: The process in which STAT proteins (Signal Transducers and Activators of Transcription) are activated by members of the JAK (janus activated kinase) family of tyrosine kinases, following the binding of physiological ligands to the growth hormone receptor. Once activated, STATs dimerize and translocate to the nucleus and modulate the expression of target genes.

gene.set.statistics.name: calcium ion transport into cytosol
gene.set.statistics.description: The directed movement of calcium ions (Ca2+) into the cytosol.

gene.set.statistics.name: ventricular septum morphogenesis
gene.set.statistics.description: The developmental process in which a ventricular septum is generated and organized. A ventricular septum is an anatomical structure that separates the lower chambers (ventricles) of the heart from one another.

gene.set.statistics.name: response to growth hormone
gene.set.statistics.description: Any process that results in a change in state or activity of a cell or an organism (in terms of movement, secretion, enzyme production, gene expression, etc.) as a result of a growth hormone stimulus. Growth hormone is a peptide hormone that binds to the growth hormone receptor and stimulates growth.

gene.set.statistics.name: lung morphogenesis
gene.set.statistics.description: The process in which the anatomical structures of the lung are generated and organized.

gene.set.statistics.name: lung saccule development
gene.set.statistics.description: The biological process whose specific outcome is the progression of a lung saccule from an initial condition to its mature state. The lung saccule is the primitive gas exchange portion of the lung composed of type I and type II cells.

gene.set.statistics.name: trachea formation
gene.set.statistics.description: The process pertaining to the initial formation of a trachea from unspecified parts. The process begins with the specific processes that contribute to the appearance of the discrete structure and ends when the trachea is recognizable. The trachea is the portion of the airway that attaches to the bronchi as it branches.

gene.set.statistics.name: epithelial tube branching involved in lung morphogenesis
gene.set.statistics.description: The process in which a highly ordered sequence of patterning events generates the branched epithelial tubes of the lung, consisting of reiterated combinations of bud outgrowth, elongation, and dichotomous subdivision of terminal units.

gene.set.statistics.name: branching involved in mammary gland duct morphogenesis
gene.set.statistics.description: The process in which the branching structure of the mammary gland duct is generated and organized. The mammary gland is a large compound sebaceous gland that in female mammals is modified to secrete milk.

gene.set.statistics.name: bud elongation involved in lung branching
gene.set.statistics.description: The process in which a bud in the lung grows out from the point where it is formed.

gene.set.statistics.name: acrosomal vesicle exocytosis
gene.set.statistics.description: The calcium ion regulated exocytosis which results in fusion of the acrosomal vesicle with the plasma membrane of the sperm as part of the acrosome reaction.

gene.set.statistics.name: lung epithelial cell differentiation
gene.set.statistics.description: The process in which a relatively unspecialized cell acquires specialized features of an epithelial cell that contributes to the epithelium of the lung.

gene.set.statistics.name: positive regulation of epithelial cell proliferation involved in lung morphogenesis
gene.set.statistics.description: Any process that increases the rate or frequency of epithelial cell proliferation that results in the lung attaining its shape.

gene.set.statistics.name: type II pneumocyte differentiation
gene.set.statistics.description: The process in which a relatively unspecialized cell acquires specialized features of a type II pneumocyte. A type II pneumocyte is a surfactant secreting cell that contains abundant cytoplasm containing numerous lipid-rich multilamellar bodies.

gene.set.statistics.name: secretory columnal luminar epithelial cell differentiation involved in prostate glandular acinus development
gene.set.statistics.description: The process in which a relatively unspecialized epithelial cell acquires specialized features of a secretory columnal luminar epithelial cell of the prostate.

gene.set.statistics.name: muscle tissue development
gene.set.statistics.description: The progression of muscle tissue over time, from its initial formation to its mature state. Muscle tissue is a contractile tissue made up of actin and myosin fibers.

gene.set.statistics.name: skeletal muscle organ development
gene.set.statistics.description: The progression of a skeletal muscle organ over time from its initial formation to its mature state. A skeletal muscle organ includes the skeletal muscle tissue and its associated connective tissue.

gene.set.statistics.name: diaphragm development
gene.set.statistics.description: The progression of the diaphragm over time from its initial formation to the mature structure. The diaphragm is a skeletal muscle that is responsible for contraction and expansion of the lungs.

gene.set.statistics.name: regulation of necroptotic process
gene.set.statistics.description: Any process that modulates the rate, frequency or extent of a necroptotic process, a necrotic cell death process that results from the activation of endogenous cellular processes, such as signaling involving death domain receptors or Toll-like receptors.

gene.set.statistics.name: negative regulation of necroptotic process
gene.set.statistics.description: Any process that decreases the rate, frequency or extent of a necroptotic process, a necrotic cell death process that results from the activation of endogenous cellular processes, such as signaling involving death domain receptors or Toll-like receptors.

gene.set.statistics.name: negative regulation of cell death
gene.set.statistics.description: Any process that decreases the rate or frequency of cell death. Cell death is the specific activation or halting of processes within a cell so that its vital functions markedly cease, rather than simply deteriorating gradually over time, which culminates in cell death.

gene.set.statistics.name: apoptotic process involved in morphogenesis
gene.set.statistics.description: Any apoptotic process that contributes to the shaping of an anatomical structure.

gene.set.statistics.name: adipose tissue development
gene.set.statistics.description: The process whose specific outcome is the progression of adipose tissue over time, from its formation to the mature structure. Adipose tissue is specialized tissue that is used to store fat.

gene.set.statistics.name: regulation of ER to Golgi vesicle-mediated transport
gene.set.statistics.description: Any process that modulates the rate, frequency, or extent of ER to Golgi vesicle-mediated transport, the directed movement of substances from the endoplasmic reticulum (ER) to the Golgi, mediated by COP II vesicles. Small COP II coated vesicles form from the ER and then fuse directly with the cis-Golgi. Larger structures are transported along microtubules to the cis-Golgi.

gene.set.statistics.name: embryonic placenta morphogenesis
gene.set.statistics.description: The process in which the embryonic placenta is generated and organized.

gene.set.statistics.name: branching involved in labyrinthine layer morphogenesis
gene.set.statistics.description: The process in which the branches of the fetal placental villi are generated and organized. The villous part of the placenta is called the labyrinth layer.

gene.set.statistics.name: placenta blood vessel development
gene.set.statistics.description: The process whose specific outcome is the progression of a blood vessel of the placenta over time, from its formation to the mature structure.

gene.set.statistics.name: labyrinthine layer blood vessel development
gene.set.statistics.description: The process whose specific outcome is the progression of a blood vessel of the labyrinthine layer of the placenta over time, from its formation to the mature structure. The embryonic vessels grow through the layer to come in close contact with the maternal blood supply.

gene.set.statistics.name: prostate gland epithelium morphogenesis
gene.set.statistics.description: The process in which the anatomical structures of epithelia of the prostate gland are generated and organized. An epithelium consists of closely packed cells arranged in one or more layers, that covers the outer surfaces of the body or lines any internal cavity or tube.

gene.set.statistics.name: prostate gland stromal morphogenesis
gene.set.statistics.description: The process in which the prostate gland stroma is generated and organized. The prostate gland stroma is made up of the mesenchymal or fibroblast cells of the prostate gland.

gene.set.statistics.name: epithelial cell maturation involved in prostate gland development
gene.set.statistics.description: The developmental process, independent of morphogenetic (shape) change, that is required for an epithelial cell of the prostate gland to attain its fully functional state. An epithelial cell is a cell usually found in a two-dimensional sheet with a free surface.

gene.set.statistics.name: mammary gland branching involved in thelarche
gene.set.statistics.description: The process in which the branching structure of the mammary gland duct is generated and organized during the period of sexual maturity in mammals. The mammary gland is a large compound sebaceous gland that in female mammals is modified to secrete milk.

gene.set.statistics.name: mammary gland alveolus development
gene.set.statistics.description: The progression of the mammary gland alveolus over time, from its formation to its mature state. The mammary gland alveolus is a sac-like structure that is found in the mature gland.

gene.set.statistics.name: positive regulation of response to cytokine stimulus
gene.set.statistics.description: Any process that increases the rate, frequency, or extent of a response to cytokine stimulus.

gene.set.statistics.name: regulation of androgen receptor signaling pathway
gene.set.statistics.description: Any process that modulates the rate, frequency, or extent of the androgen receptor signaling pathway.

gene.set.statistics.name: negative regulation of androgen receptor signaling pathway
gene.set.statistics.description: Any process that decreases the rate, frequency, or extent of the androgen receptor signaling pathway.

gene.set.statistics.name: negative regulation of epithelial cell proliferation involved in prostate gland development
gene.set.statistics.description: Any process that decreases the rate, frequency or extent of epithelial cell proliferation that contributes to the progression of the prostate gland over time.

gene.set.statistics.name: hair follicle placode formation
gene.set.statistics.description: The developmental process in which a hair placode forms. An hair follicle placode is a thickening of the ectoderm that will give rise to the hair follicle bud.

gene.set.statistics.name: regulation of canonical Wnt signaling pathway
gene.set.statistics.description: Any process that modulates the rate, frequency, or extent of the Wnt signaling pathway through beta-catenin, the series of molecular signals initiated by binding of a Wnt protein to a frizzled family receptor on the surface of the target cell, followed by propagation of the signal via beta-catenin, and ending with a change in transcription of target genes.

gene.set.statistics.name: regulation of gene silencing by miRNA
gene.set.statistics.description: Any process that modulates the rate, frequency, or extent of the downregulation of gene expression through the action of microRNAs (miRNAs), endogenous 21-24 nucleotide small RNAs processed from stem-loop RNA precursors (pre-miRNAs). Once incorporated into a RNA-induced silencing complex (RISC), miRNAs can downregulate gene expression by either of two posttranscriptional mechanisms: RNA (often mRNA) cleavage or mRNA translational repression.

gene.set.statistics.name: negative regulation of gene silencing by miRNA
gene.set.statistics.description: Any process that decreases the rate, frequency, or extent of gene silencing by miRNA.

gene.set.statistics.name: regulation of gene silencing
gene.set.statistics.description: Any process that modulates the rate, frequency, or extent of gene silencing, the transcriptional or post-transcriptional process carried out at the cellular level that results in long-term gene inactivation.

gene.set.statistics.name: coronary vasculature development
gene.set.statistics.description: The process whose specific outcome is the progression of the blood vessels of the heart over time, from its formation to the mature structure.

gene.set.statistics.name: lipid tube assembly
gene.set.statistics.description: The aggregation, arrangement and bonding together of a set of macromolecules to form a macromolecular complex that contains a tube of lipid surrounded by a protein coat involved in membrane shaping of vesicle membranes as they fuse or undergo fission.

gene.set.statistics.name: dendritic spine development
gene.set.statistics.description: The process whose specific outcome is the progression of the dendritic spine over time, from its formation to the mature structure. A dendritic spine is a protrusion from a dendrite and a specialized subcellular compartment involved in synaptic transmission.

gene.set.statistics.name: dendritic spine morphogenesis
gene.set.statistics.description: The process in which the anatomical structures of a dendritic spine are generated and organized. A dendritic spine is a protrusion from a dendrite and a specialized subcellular compartment involved in synaptic transmission.

gene.set.statistics.name: regulation of dendritic spine development
gene.set.statistics.description: Any process that modulates the rate, frequency, or extent of dendritic spine development, the process whose specific outcome is the progression of the dendritic spine over time, from its formation to the mature structure.

gene.set.statistics.name: positive regulation of dendritic spine development
gene.set.statistics.description: Any process that increases the rate, frequency, or extent of dendritic spine development, the process whose specific outcome is the progression of the dendritic spine over time, from its formation to the mature structure.

gene.set.statistics.name: regulation of dendritic spine morphogenesis
gene.set.statistics.description: Any process that modulates the rate, frequency, or extent of dendritic spine morphogenesis, the process in which the anatomical structures of a dendritic spine are generated and organized. A dendritic spine is a protrusion from a dendrite and a specialized subcellular compartment involved in synaptic transmission.

gene.set.statistics.name: positive regulation of dendritic spine morphogenesis
gene.set.statistics.description: Any process that increases the rate, frequency, or extent of dendritic spine morphogenesis, the process in which the anatomical structures of a dendritic spine are generated and organized. A dendritic spine is a protrusion from a dendrite and a specialized subcellular compartment involved in synaptic transmission.

gene.set.statistics.name: positive regulation of mRNA catabolic process
gene.set.statistics.description: Any process that increases the rate, frequency, or extent of a mRNA catabolic process, the chemical reactions and pathways resulting in the breakdown of RNA, ribonucleic acid, one of the two main type of nucleic acid, consisting of a long, unbranched macromolecule formed from ribonucleotides joined in 3',5'-phosphodiester linkage.

gene.set.statistics.name: membrane organization
gene.set.statistics.description: A process which results in the assembly, arrangement of constituent parts, or disassembly of a membrane. A membrane is a double layer of lipid molecules that encloses all cells, and, in eukaryotes, many organelles; may be a single or double lipid bilayer; also includes associated proteins.

gene.set.statistics.name: membrane fusion
gene.set.statistics.description: The membrane organization process that joins two lipid bilayers to form a single membrane.

gene.set.statistics.name: cardiac muscle tissue regeneration
gene.set.statistics.description: The regrowth of cardiac muscle tissue to repair injured or damaged muscle fibers in the postnatal stage.

gene.set.statistics.name: establishment of endothelial barrier
gene.set.statistics.description: The establishment of a barrier between endothelial cell layers, such as those in the brain, lung or intestine, to exert specific and selective control over the passage of water and solutes, thus allowing formation and maintenance of compartments that differ in fluid and solute composition.

gene.set.statistics.name: eyelid development in camera-type eye
gene.set.statistics.description: The progression of the eyelid in a camera-type eye from its formation to the mature state. The eyelid is a membranous cover that helps protect and lubricate the eye.

gene.set.statistics.name: olfactory bulb mitral cell layer development
gene.set.statistics.description: The progression of the olfactory bulb mitral cell layer over time from its initial formation until its mature state. The mitral cell layer is composed of pyramidal neurons whose cell bodies are located between the granule cell layer and the plexiform layer.

gene.set.statistics.name: regulation of wound healing
gene.set.statistics.description: Any process that modulates the rate, frequency, or extent of the series of events that restore integrity to a damaged tissue, following an injury.

gene.set.statistics.name: negative regulation of wound healing
gene.set.statistics.description: Any process that decreases the rate, frequency, or extent of the series of events that restore integrity to a damaged tissue, following an injury.

gene.set.statistics.name: cell growth involved in cardiac muscle cell development
gene.set.statistics.description: The growth of a cardiac muscle cell, where growth contributes to the progression of the cell over time from its initial formation to its mature state.

gene.set.statistics.name: positive regulation of cell growth involved in cardiac muscle cell development
gene.set.statistics.description: Any process that increases the rate, frequency, or extent of the growth of a cardiac muscle cell, where growth contributes to the progression of the cell over time from its initial formation to its mature state.

gene.set.statistics.name: somite development
gene.set.statistics.description: The progression of a somite from its initial formation to the mature structure. Somites are mesodermal clusters that are arranged segmentally along the anterior posterior axis of an embryo.

gene.set.statistics.name: muscle structure development
gene.set.statistics.description: The progression of a muscle structure over time, from its formation to its mature state. Muscle structures are contractile cells, tissues or organs that are found in multicellular organisms.

gene.set.statistics.name: chaperone-mediated protein folding
gene.set.statistics.description: The process of inhibiting aggregation and assisting in the covalent and noncovalent assembly of single chain polypeptides or multisubunit complexes into the correct tertiary structure that is dependent on interaction with a chaperone.

gene.set.statistics.name: negative regulation of protein refolding
gene.set.statistics.description: Any process that decreases the rate, frequency, or extent of protein refolding. Protein refolding is the process carried out by a cell that restores the biological activity of an unfolded or misfolded protein, using helper proteins such as chaperones.

gene.set.statistics.name: negative regulation of histone H3-K27 methylation
gene.set.statistics.description: Any process that decreases the rate, frequency, or extent of histone H3-K27 methylation. Histone H3-K27 methylation is the modification of histone H3 by addition of a methyl group to lysine at position 27 of the histone.

gene.set.statistics.name: positive regulation of histone H3-K27 methylation
gene.set.statistics.description: Any process that increases the rate, frequency, or extent of histone H3-K27 methylation. Histone H3-K27 methylation is the modification of histone H3 by addition of a methyl group to lysine at position 27 of the histone.

gene.set.statistics.name: positive regulation of protein tyrosine kinase activity
gene.set.statistics.description: Any process that increases the rate, frequency, or extent of protein tyrosine kinase activity.

gene.set.statistics.name: negative regulation of protein tyrosine kinase activity
gene.set.statistics.description: Any process that decreases the rate, frequency, or extent of protein tyrosine kinase activity.

gene.set.statistics.name: regulation of proteasomal protein catabolic process
gene.set.statistics.description: Any process that modulates the rate, frequency, or extent of the chemical reactions and pathways resulting in the breakdown of a protein or peptide by hydrolysis of its peptide bonds that is mediated by the proteasome.

gene.set.statistics.name: mRNA destabilization
gene.set.statistics.description: Any process that decreases the stability of an mRNA molecule, making it more vulnerable to degradative processes. Messenger RNA is the intermediate molecule between DNA and protein. It includes UTR and coding sequences. It does not contain introns.

gene.set.statistics.name: 3'-UTR-mediated mRNA destabilization
gene.set.statistics.description: An mRNA destabilization process in which one or more RNA-binding proteins associate with the 3'-untranslated region (UTR) of an mRNA.

gene.set.statistics.name: negative regulation of insulin secretion involved in cellular response to glucose stimulus
gene.set.statistics.description: Any process that decreases the frequency, rate or extent of the regulated release of insulin that contributes to the response of a cell to glucose.

gene.set.statistics.name: fungiform papilla formation
gene.set.statistics.description: The developmental process pertaining to the initial formation of a spongiform papilla from unspecified parts. The fungiform papilla is a mushroom-shaped papilla of the tongue.

gene.set.statistics.name: retina vasculature morphogenesis in camera-type eye
gene.set.statistics.description: The process in which the vasculature of the retina is generated and organized.

gene.set.statistics.name: cardiac neural crest cell development involved in heart development
gene.set.statistics.description: The process aimed at the progression of a cardiac neural crest cell over time, from initial commitment of the cell to its specific fate, to the fully functional differentiated cell that contributes to the development of the heart.

gene.set.statistics.name: renal tubule development
gene.set.statistics.description: The progression of the renal tubule over time from its formation to the mature form. A renal tubule is a tube that filters, re-absorbs and secretes substances to rid an organism of waste and to play a role in fluid homeostasis.

gene.set.statistics.name: neural precursor cell proliferation
gene.set.statistics.description: The multiplication or reproduction of neural precursor cells, resulting in the expansion of a cell population. A neural precursor cell is either a nervous system stem cell or a nervous system progenitor cell.

gene.set.statistics.name: regulation of transcription from RNA polymerase II promoter in response to hypoxia
gene.set.statistics.description: Any process that modulates the frequency, rate or extent of transcription from an RNA polymerase II promoter as a result of a hypoxia stimulus.

gene.set.statistics.name: establishment of skin barrier
gene.set.statistics.description: Establishment of the epithelial barrier, the functional barrier in the skin that limits its permeability.

gene.set.statistics.name: protein localization to lysosome
gene.set.statistics.description: A process in which a protein is transported to, or maintained in, a location within a lysosome.

gene.set.statistics.name: hematopoietic stem cell homeostasis
gene.set.statistics.description: Any biological process involved in the maintenance of the steady-state number of hematopoietic stem cells within a population of cells.

gene.set.statistics.name: protein localization to cilium
gene.set.statistics.description: A process in which a protein is transported to, or maintained in, a location within a cilium.

gene.set.statistics.name: microglial cell proliferation
gene.set.statistics.description: The expansion of a microglial cell population by cell division.

gene.set.statistics.name: axon development
gene.set.statistics.description: The progression of an axon over time. Covers axonogenesis (de novo generation of an axon) and axon regeneration (regrowth), as well as processes pertaining to the progression of the axon over time (fasciculation and defasciculation).

gene.set.statistics.name: canonical glycolysis
gene.set.statistics.description: The glycolytic process that begins with the conversion of glucose to glucose-6-phosphate by glucokinase activity. Glycolytic processes are the  chemical reactions and pathways resulting in the breakdown of a carbohydrate into pyruvate, with the concomitant production of a small amount of ATP.

gene.set.statistics.name: fructose catabolic process to hydroxyacetone phosphate and glyceraldehyde-3-phosphate
gene.set.statistics.description: The chemical reactions and pathways resulting in the breakdown of fructose that results in the formation of dihydroxyacetone phosphate and glyceraldehyde-3-phosphate.

gene.set.statistics.name: regulation of protein complex stability
gene.set.statistics.description: Any process that affects the structure and integrity of a protein complex by altering the likelihood of its assembly or disassembly.

gene.set.statistics.name: cytoskeleton-dependent cytokinesis
gene.set.statistics.description: A cytokinesis that involves the function of a set of proteins that are part of the microfilament or microtubule cytoskeleton.

gene.set.statistics.name: chaperone-mediated autophagy
gene.set.statistics.description: The autophagy process which begins when chaperones and co-chaperones recognize a target motif and unfold the substrate protein. The proteins are then transported to the lysosome where they are degraded.

gene.set.statistics.name: reticulophagy
gene.set.statistics.description: The selective autohagy process in which parts of the endoplasmic reticulum are loaded into autophagosomes, delivered to the vacuole, and degraded in response to changing cellular conditions.

gene.set.statistics.name: lipophagy
gene.set.statistics.description: The selective autophagy process in which lipid droplets are delivered to the vacuole and degraded in response to changing cellular conditions.

gene.set.statistics.name: mitochondrial acetyl-CoA biosynthetic process from pyruvate
gene.set.statistics.description: The chemical reactions and pathways resulting in the formation of acetyl-CoA from pyruvate in the mitochondrion. The process begins with the transport of pyruvate from the cytosol to the mitochondrion where it is subsequently decarboxylated to form acetyl-CoA.

gene.set.statistics.name: late endosomal microautophagy
gene.set.statistics.description: The autophagy process by which cytosolic proteins targeted for degradation are tagged with a chaperone and are directly transferred into and degraded in a late endosomal compartment.

gene.set.statistics.name: protein targeting to lysosome involved in chaperone-mediated autophagy
gene.set.statistics.description: The targeting of a protein to the lysosome process in which an input protein binds to a chaperone and subsequently to a lysosomal receptor.

gene.set.statistics.name: endoplasmic reticulum-plasma membrane tethering
gene.set.statistics.description: The attachment of an endoplasmic reticulum membrane to the plasma membrane via molecular tethers.

gene.set.statistics.name: antimicrobial humoral immune response mediated by antimicrobial peptide
gene.set.statistics.description: An immune response against microbes mediated by anti-microbial peptides in body fluid.

gene.set.statistics.name: autophagosome-lysosome fusion
gene.set.statistics.description: The process in which autophagosomes, double-membraned vesicles containing cytoplasmic material, fuse with a vacuole (yeast) or lysosome (e.g. mammals and insects). In the case of yeast, inner membrane-bounded structures (autophagic bodies) appear in the vacuole. Fusion provides an acidic environment and digestive function to the interior of the autophagosome.

gene.set.statistics.name: negative regulation of protein K48-linked ubiquitination
gene.set.statistics.description: Any process that stops, prevents or reduces the frequency, rate or extent of K48-linked ubiquitination, a protein ubiquitination process in which a polymer of ubiquitin, formed by linkages between lysine residues at position 48 of the ubiquitin monomers, is added to a protein. K48-linked ubiquitination targets the substrate protein for degradation.

gene.set.statistics.name: establishment of protein localization to plasma membrane
gene.set.statistics.description: The directed movement of a protein to a specific location in a plasma membrane.

gene.set.statistics.name: midbody abscission
gene.set.statistics.description: The process by which the midbody, the cytoplasmic bridge that connects the two prospective daughter cells, is severed at the end of mitotic cytokinesis, resulting in two separate daughter cells.

gene.set.statistics.name: secondary palate development
gene.set.statistics.description: The biological process whose specific outcome is the progression of the secondary palate from an initial condition to its mature state. This process begins with the formation of the structure and ends with the mature structure. The secondary palate is the part of the palate formed from the fusion of the two palatine shelves, extensions of the maxillary prominences.

gene.set.statistics.name: positive regulation of stress granule assembly
gene.set.statistics.description: Any process that starts or increases the rate, frequency or extent of stress-granule assembly, the aggregation, arrangement and bonding together of proteins and RNA molecules to form a stress granule.

gene.set.statistics.name: R-loop disassembly
gene.set.statistics.description: A DNA metabolic process that results in the disassembly of R-loops. R-loops are three-stranded nucleic acid structures consisitng of an RNA:DNA heteroduplex and a looped-out non-template strand. Aberrant formation and persistence of R-loops block transcription elongation and cause DNA damage. Mechanisms that resolve R-loops are essential for genome stability.

gene.set.statistics.name: protein-containing complex assembly
gene.set.statistics.description: The aggregation, arrangement and bonding together of a set of macromolecules to form a protein-containing complex.

gene.set.statistics.name: neuron cellular homeostasis
gene.set.statistics.description: The cellular homeostatic process that preserves a neuron in a stable, differentiated functional and structural state.

gene.set.statistics.name: intrinsic apoptotic signaling pathway in response to endoplasmic reticulum stress
gene.set.statistics.description: A series of molecular signals in which an intracellular signal is conveyed to trigger the apoptotic death of a cell. The pathway is induced in response to a stimulus indicating endoplasmic reticulum (ER) stress, and ends when the execution phase of apoptosis is triggered. ER stress usually results from the accumulation of unfolded or misfolded proteins in the ER lumen.

gene.set.statistics.name: protein initiator methionine removal
gene.set.statistics.description: The protein modification process in which the translation-initiating methionine or formylmethionine residue is removed from a protein.

gene.set.statistics.name: glycosylation
gene.set.statistics.description: The covalent attachment and further modification of carbohydrate residues to a substrate molecule.

gene.set.statistics.name: positive regulation of glucagon secretion
gene.set.statistics.description: Any process that activates or increases the frequency, rate or extent of the regulated release of glucagon.

gene.set.statistics.name: interleukin-6-mediated signaling pathway
gene.set.statistics.description: A series of molecular signals initiated by the binding of interleukin-6 to a receptor on the surface of a cell, and ending with regulation of a downstream cellular process, e.g. transcription.

gene.set.statistics.name: interleukin-27-mediated signaling pathway
gene.set.statistics.description: A series of molecular signals initiated by the binding of interleukin-27 to a receptor on the surface of a cell, and ending with regulation of a downstream cellular process, e.g. transcription.

gene.set.statistics.name: mitochondrial translational elongation
gene.set.statistics.description: The successive addition of amino acid residues to a nascent polypeptide chain during protein biosynthesis in a mitochondrion.

gene.set.statistics.name: mitochondrial translational termination
gene.set.statistics.description: The process resulting in the release of a polypeptide chain from the ribosome in a mitochondrion, usually in response to a termination codon (note that mitochondria use variants of the universal genetic code that differ between different taxa).

gene.set.statistics.name: regulation of mitochondrial translation
gene.set.statistics.description: Any process that modulates the frequency, rate or extent of the chemical reactions and pathways resulting in the formation of proteins by the translation of mRNA in a mitochondrion.

gene.set.statistics.name: positive regulation of mitochondrial translation
gene.set.statistics.description: Any process that activates or increases the frequency, rate or extent of the chemical reactions and pathways resulting in the formation of proteins by the translation of mRNA in a mitochondrion.

gene.set.statistics.name: enamel mineralization
gene.set.statistics.description: The process in which calcium salts, mainly carbonated hydroxyapatite, are deposited in tooth enamel.

gene.set.statistics.name: meiotic attachment of telomere to nuclear envelope
gene.set.statistics.description: The meiotic cell cycle process in which physical connections are formed between telomeric heterochromatin and the nuclear envelope, facilitating bouquet formation.

gene.set.statistics.name: protein localization to chromosome, telomeric region
gene.set.statistics.description: Any process in which a protein is transported to, or maintained at, the telomeric region of a chromosome.

gene.set.statistics.name: regulation of establishment of protein localization
gene.set.statistics.description: Any process that modulates the frequency, rate or extent of the directed movement of a protein to a specific location.

gene.set.statistics.name: protein poly-ADP-ribosylation
gene.set.statistics.description: The transfer of multiple ADP-ribose residues from NAD to a protein amino acid, forming a poly(ADP-ribose) chain.

gene.set.statistics.name: protein auto-ADP-ribosylation
gene.set.statistics.description: The ADP-ribosylation by a protein of one or more of its own amino acid residues, or residues on an identical protein.

gene.set.statistics.name: sulfide oxidation, using sulfide:quinone oxidoreductase
gene.set.statistics.description: A sulfide oxidation process that proceeds via the reaction catalyzed by sulfide:quinone oxidoreductase.

gene.set.statistics.name: regulation of T cell apoptotic process
gene.set.statistics.description: Any process that modulates the occurrence or rate of T cell death by apoptotic process.

gene.set.statistics.name: thymocyte apoptotic process
gene.set.statistics.description: Any apoptotic process in a thymocyte, an immature T cell located in the thymus.

gene.set.statistics.name: actin-mediated cell contraction
gene.set.statistics.description: The actin filament-based process in which cytoplasmic actin filaments slide past one another resulting in contraction of all or part of the cell body.

gene.set.statistics.name: mucus secretion
gene.set.statistics.description: The regulated release of mucus by the mucosa. Mucus is a viscous slimy secretion consisting of mucins and various inorganic salts dissolved in water, with suspended epithelial cells and leukocytes. The mucosa, or mucous membrane, is the membrane covered with epithelium that lines the tubular organs of the body. Mucins are carbohydrate-rich glycoproteins that have a lubricating and protective function.

gene.set.statistics.name: peptidyl-serine dephosphorylation
gene.set.statistics.description: The removal of phosphoric residues from peptidyl-O-phospho-L-serine to form peptidyl-serine.

gene.set.statistics.name: necroptotic process
gene.set.statistics.description: A programmed necrotic cell death process which begins when a cell receives a signal (e.g. a ligand binding to a death receptor or to a Toll-like receptor), and proceeds through a series of biochemical events (signaling pathways), characterized by activation of receptor-interacting serine/threonine-protein kinase 1 and/or 3 (RIPK1/3, also called RIP1/3) and by critical dependence on mixed lineage kinase domain-like (MLKL), and which typically lead to common morphological features of necrotic cell death. The process ends when the cell has died. The process is divided into a signaling phase, and an execution phase, which is triggered by the former.

gene.set.statistics.name: cornification
gene.set.statistics.description: A type of programmed cell death that occurs in the epidermis, morphologically and biochemically distinct from apoptosis. It leads to the formation of corneocytes, i.e. dead keratinocytes containing an amalgam of specific proteins (e.g., keratin, loricrin, SPR and involucrin) and lipids (e.g., fatty acids and ceramides), which are necessary for the function of the cornified skin layer (mechanical resistance, elasticity, water repellence and structural stability).

gene.set.statistics.name: pyroptosis
gene.set.statistics.description: A caspase-1-dependent cell death subroutine that is associated with the generation of pyrogenic mediators such as IL-1beta and IL-18.

gene.set.statistics.name: renal absorption
gene.set.statistics.description: A renal system process in which water, ions, glucose and proteins are taken up from the collecting ducts, glomerulus and proximal and distal loops of the nephron. In non-mammalian species, absorption may occur in related structures (e.g. protein absorption is observed in nephrocytes in Drosophila, see PMID:23264686).

gene.set.statistics.name: sarcoplasmic reticulum calcium ion transport
gene.set.statistics.description: The directed movement of calcium ions (Ca2+) into, out of or within the sarcoplasmic reticulum.

gene.set.statistics.name: cellular response to hydrogen peroxide
gene.set.statistics.description: Any process that results in a change in state or activity of a cell (in terms of movement, secretion, enzyme production, gene expression, etc.) as a result of a hydrogen peroxide (H2O2) stimulus.

gene.set.statistics.name: lens fiber cell development
gene.set.statistics.description: The process whose specific outcome is the progression of a lens fiber cell over time, from its formation to the mature structure. Cell development does not include the steps involved in committing a cell to a lens fiber cell fate. A lens fiber cell is any of the elongated, tightly packed cells that make up the bulk of the mature lens in a camera-type eye.

gene.set.statistics.name: lens fiber cell morphogenesis
gene.set.statistics.description: The process in which the structures of a lens fiber cell are generated and organized. This process occurs while the initially relatively unspecialized cell is acquiring the specialized features of a lens fiber cell. A lens fiber cell is any of the elongated, tightly packed cells that make up the bulk of the mature lens in a camera-type eye.

gene.set.statistics.name: G1 to G0 transition
gene.set.statistics.description: A cell cycle arrest process that results in arrest during G1 phase, whereupon the cell enters a specialized resting state known as G0 or quiescence.

gene.set.statistics.name: negative regulation of G0 to G1 transition
gene.set.statistics.description: A cell cycle process that stops, prevents, or reduces the rate or extent of the transition from the G0 quiescent state to the G1 phase.

gene.set.statistics.name: thyroid hormone transport
gene.set.statistics.description: The directed movement of thyroid hormone into, out of or within a cell, or between cells, by means of some agent such as a transporter or pore.

gene.set.statistics.name: actin polymerization-dependent cell motility
gene.set.statistics.description: A process involved in the controlled movement of a bacterial cell powered by the continuous polymerization of actin at one pole of the cell.

gene.set.statistics.name: hepatocyte differentiation
gene.set.statistics.description: The process in which a relatively unspecialized cell acquires the specialized features of a hepatocyte. A hepatocyte is specialized epithelial cell that is organized into interconnected plates called lobules, and is the main structural component of the liver.

gene.set.statistics.name: cellular heat acclimation
gene.set.statistics.description: Any process that increases heat tolerance of a cell in response to high temperatures.

gene.set.statistics.name: ERK1 and ERK2 cascade
gene.set.statistics.description: An intracellular protein kinase cascade containing at least ERK1 or ERK2 (MAPKs), a MEK (a MAPKK) and a MAP3K. The cascade may involve 4 different kinases, as it can also contain an additional tier: the upstream MAP4K. The kinases in each tier phosphorylate and activate the kinase in the downstream tier to transmit a signal within a cell.

gene.set.statistics.name: regulation of ERK1 and ERK2 cascade
gene.set.statistics.description: Any process that modulates the frequency, rate or extent of signal transduction mediated by the ERK1 and ERK2 cascade.

gene.set.statistics.name: negative regulation of ERK1 and ERK2 cascade
gene.set.statistics.description: Any process that stops, prevents, or reduces the frequency, rate or extent of signal transduction mediated by the ERK1 and ERK2 cascade.

gene.set.statistics.name: positive regulation of ERK1 and ERK2 cascade
gene.set.statistics.description: Any process that activates or increases the frequency, rate or extent of signal transduction mediated by the ERK1 and ERK2 cascade.

gene.set.statistics.name: nucleotide-binding oligomerization domain containing signaling pathway
gene.set.statistics.description: Any series of molecular signals generated as a consequence of binding to a nucleotide-binding oligomerization domain containing (NOD) protein.

gene.set.statistics.name: cellular detoxification of nitrogen compound
gene.set.statistics.description: Any cellular process that reduces or removes the toxicity of nitrogenous compounds which are dangerous or toxic. This includes the aerobic conversion of toxic compounds to harmless substances.

gene.set.statistics.name: rRNA base methylation
gene.set.statistics.description: The addition of a methyl group to an atom in the nucleoside base portion of a nucleotide residue in an rRNA molecule.

gene.set.statistics.name: rRNA (guanine-N7)-methylation
gene.set.statistics.description: The addition of a methyl group to the N7 atom in the base portion of a guanine nucleotide residue in an rRNA molecule.

gene.set.statistics.name: negative regulation of thrombin-activated receptor signaling pathway
gene.set.statistics.description: Any process that stops, prevents, or reduces the frequency, rate or extent of thrombin-activated receptor protein signaling pathway activity.
