A thrombin receptor signaling pathway is the series of molecular signals generated as a consequence of a thrombin-activated receptor binding to one of its physiological ligands.

gene.set.statistics.name: interleukin-1-mediated signaling pathway
gene.set.statistics.description: A series of molecular signals initiated by the binding of interleukin-1 to a receptor on the surface of a cell, and ending with regulation of a downstream cellular process, e.g. transcription.

gene.set.statistics.name: regulation of microtubule cytoskeleton organization
gene.set.statistics.description: Any process that modulates the frequency, rate or extent of the formation, arrangement of constituent parts, or disassembly of cytoskeletal structures comprising microtubules and their associated proteins.

gene.set.statistics.name: tRNA threonylcarbamoyladenosine metabolic process
gene.set.statistics.description: The chemical reactions and pathways involving tRNA threonylcarbamoyladenosine, a modified nucleoside found in some tRNA molecules.

gene.set.statistics.name: platelet aggregation
gene.set.statistics.description: The adhesion of one platelet to one or more other platelets via adhesion molecules.

gene.set.statistics.name: protein K63-linked ubiquitination
gene.set.statistics.description: A protein ubiquitination process in which a polymer of ubiquitin, formed by linkages between lysine residues at position 63 of the ubiquitin monomers, is added to a protein. K63-linked ubiquitination does not target the substrate protein for degradation, but is involved in several pathways, notably as a signal to promote error-free DNA postreplication repair.

gene.set.statistics.name: protein K63-linked deubiquitination
gene.set.statistics.description: A protein deubiquitination process in which a K63-linked ubiquitin chain, i.e. a polymer of ubiquitin formed by linkages between lysine residues at position 63 of the ubiquitin monomers, is removed from a protein.

gene.set.statistics.name: response to platinum ion
gene.set.statistics.description: Any process that results in a change in state or activity of a cell or an organism (in terms of movement, secretion, enzyme production, gene expression, etc.) as a result of a platinum stimulus.

gene.set.statistics.name: response to interleukin-1
gene.set.statistics.description: Any process that results in a change in state or activity of a cell or an organism (in terms of movement, secretion, enzyme production, gene expression, etc.) as a result of an interleukin-1 stimulus.

gene.set.statistics.name: positive regulation of vitamin D receptor signaling pathway
gene.set.statistics.description: Any process that activates or increases the frequency, rate or extent of vitamin D receptor signaling pathway activity.

gene.set.statistics.name: mitochondrion morphogenesis
gene.set.statistics.description: The process in which the anatomical structures of a mitochondrion are generated and organized.

gene.set.statistics.name: protein localization to mitochondrion
gene.set.statistics.description: A process in which a protein is transported to, or maintained in, a location within the mitochondrion.

gene.set.statistics.name: calcium ion transmembrane transport
gene.set.statistics.description: A process in which a calcium ion is transported from one side of a membrane to the other by means of some agent such as a transporter or pore.

gene.set.statistics.name: dendrite self-avoidance
gene.set.statistics.description: The process in which dendrites recognize and avoid contact with sister dendrites from the same cell.

gene.set.statistics.name: regulation of protein processing
gene.set.statistics.description: Any process that modulates the frequency, rate or extent of protein processing, any protein maturation process achieved by the cleavage of a peptide bond or bonds within a protein.

gene.set.statistics.name: response to cholesterol
gene.set.statistics.description: Any process that results in a change in state or activity of a cell or an organism (in terms of movement, secretion, enzyme production, gene expression, etc.) as a result of a cholesterol stimulus.

gene.set.statistics.name: interleukin-35-mediated signaling pathway
gene.set.statistics.description: A series of molecular signals initiated by the binding of interleukin-35 to a receptor on the surface of a cell, and ending with regulation of a downstream cellular process, e.g. transcription.

gene.set.statistics.name: L-aspartate transmembrane transport
gene.set.statistics.description: The directed movement of L-aspartate across a membrane.

gene.set.statistics.name: phosphorylation of RNA polymerase II C-terminal domain
gene.set.statistics.description: The process of introducing a phosphate group on to an amino acid residue in the C-terminal domain of RNA polymerase II. Typically, this occurs during the transcription cycle and results in production of an RNA polymerase II enzyme where the carboxy-terminal domain (CTD) of the largest subunit is extensively phosphorylated, often referred to as hyperphosphorylated or the II(0) form. Specific types of phosphorylation within the CTD are usually associated with specific regions of genes, though there are exceptions. The phosphorylation state regulates the association of specific complexes such as the capping enzyme or 3'-RNA processing machinery to the elongating RNA polymerase complex.

gene.set.statistics.name: heterochromatin organization
gene.set.statistics.description: Any process that results in the specification, formation or maintenance of the physical structure of eukaryotic heterochromatin, a compact and highly condensed form of chromatin.

gene.set.statistics.name: bicellular tight junction assembly
gene.set.statistics.description: The aggregation, arrangement and bonding together of a set of components to form a tight junction, an occluding cell-cell junction that is composed of a branching network of sealing strands that completely encircles the apical end of each cell in an epithelial sheet.

gene.set.statistics.name: caveola assembly
gene.set.statistics.description: The aggregation, arrangement and bonding together of a set of components to form a caveola. A caveola is a plasma membrane raft that forms a small pit, depression, or invagination that communicates with the outside of a cell and extends inward, indenting the cytoplasm and the cell membrane.

gene.set.statistics.name: dehydroascorbic acid transport
gene.set.statistics.description: The directed movement of dehydroascorbate into, out of or within a cell, or between cells, by means of some agent such as a transporter or pore. Dehydroascorbate, 5-(1,2-dihydroxyethyl)furan-2,3,4(5H)-trione, is an oxidized form of vitamin C.

gene.set.statistics.name: aggresome assembly
gene.set.statistics.description: The aggregation, arrangement and bonding together of a set of components to form an aggresome; requires the microtubule cytoskeleton and dynein.

gene.set.statistics.name: response to growth factor
gene.set.statistics.description: Any process that results in a change in state or activity of a cell or an organism (in terms of movement, secretion, enzyme production, gene expression, etc.) as a result of a growth factor stimulus.

gene.set.statistics.name: response to epidermal growth factor
gene.set.statistics.description: Any process that results in a change in state or activity of a cell or an organism (in terms of movement, secretion, enzyme production, gene expression, etc.) as a result of an epidermal growth factor stimulus.

gene.set.statistics.name: positive regulation of protein exit from endoplasmic reticulum
gene.set.statistics.description: Any process that activates or increases the frequency, rate or extent of directed movement of proteins from the endoplasmic reticulum.

gene.set.statistics.name: negative regulation of calcineurin-NFAT signaling cascade
gene.set.statistics.description: Any process that stops, prevents, or reduces the frequency, rate or extent of the calcineurin-NFAT signaling cascade.

gene.set.statistics.name: positive regulation of calcineurin-NFAT signaling cascade
gene.set.statistics.description: Any process that activates or increases the frequency, rate or extent of signaling via the calcineurin-NFAT signaling cascade.

gene.set.statistics.name: mitochondrial tRNA methylation
gene.set.statistics.description: The posttranscriptional addition of methyl groups to specific residues in a mitochondrial tRNA molecule.

gene.set.statistics.name: global genome nucleotide-excision repair
gene.set.statistics.description: The nucleotide-excision repair process in which DNA lesions are removed from nontranscribed strands and from transcriptionally silent regions over the entire genome.

gene.set.statistics.name: UV-damage excision repair
gene.set.statistics.description: A DNA repair process that is initiated by an endonuclease that introduces a single-strand incision immediately 5' of a UV-induced damage site. UV-damage excision repair acts on both cyclobutane pyrimidine dimers (CPDs) and pyrimidine-pyrimidone 6-4 photoproducts (6-4PPs).

gene.set.statistics.name: organelle assembly
gene.set.statistics.description: The aggregation, arrangement and bonding together of a set of components to form an organelle. An organelle is an organized structure of distinctive morphology and function. Includes the nucleus, mitochondria, plastids, vacuoles, vesicles, ribosomes and the cytoskeleton. Excludes the plasma membrane.

gene.set.statistics.name: histone H3 deacetylation
gene.set.statistics.description: The modification of histone H3 by the removal of one or more acetyl groups.

gene.set.statistics.name: histone H4 deacetylation
gene.set.statistics.description: The modification of histone H4 by the removal of one or more acetyl groups.

gene.set.statistics.name: CRD-mediated mRNA stabilization
gene.set.statistics.description: An mRNA stabilization process in which one or more RNA-binding proteins associate with a sequence in the open reading frame called the coding region instability determinant (CRD).

gene.set.statistics.name: 3'-UTR-mediated mRNA stabilization
gene.set.statistics.description: An mRNA stabilization process in which one or more RNA-binding proteins associate with the 3'-untranslated region (UTR) of an mRNA.

gene.set.statistics.name: protein K48-linked ubiquitination
gene.set.statistics.description: A protein ubiquitination process in which a polymer of ubiquitin, formed by linkages between lysine residues at position 48 of the ubiquitin monomers, is added to a protein. K48-linked ubiquitination targets the substrate protein for degradation.

gene.set.statistics.name: dephosphorylation of RNA polymerase II C-terminal domain
gene.set.statistics.description: The process of removing a phosphate group from an amino acid residue in the C-terminal domain of RNA polymerase II. Some dephosphorylation occurs during transcription while some may occur after the enzyme is released from the template in order to prepare it for the beginning of the transcription cycle again. RNA polymerase II with little or no phosphorylation is referred to as the hypophosphorylated or II(A) form.

gene.set.statistics.name: nuclear-transcribed mRNA catabolic process, no-go decay
gene.set.statistics.description: The chemical reactions and pathways resulting in the breakdown of the transcript body of a nuclear-transcribed mRNA with stalls in translation elongation.

gene.set.statistics.name: protein localization to endoplasmic reticulum
gene.set.statistics.description: A process in which a protein is transported to, or maintained in, a location within the endoplasmic reticulum.

gene.set.statistics.name: protein K11-linked ubiquitination
gene.set.statistics.description: A protein ubiquitination process in which ubiquitin monomers are attached to a protein, and then ubiquitin polymers are formed by linkages between lysine residues at position 11 of the ubiquitin monomers. K11-linked polyubiquitination targets the substrate protein for degradation. The anaphase-promoting complex promotes the degradation of mitotic regulators by assembling K11-linked polyubiquitin chains.

gene.set.statistics.name: error-free translesion synthesis
gene.set.statistics.description: The conversion of DNA-damage induced single-stranded gaps into large molecular weight DNA after replication by using a specialized DNA polymerase or replication complex to insert a defined nucleotide across the lesion. This process does not remove the replication-blocking lesions but does not causes an increase in the endogenous mutation level. For S. cerevisiae, RAD30 encodes DNA polymerase eta, which incorporates two adenines. When incorporated across a thymine-thymine dimer, it does not increase the endogenous mutation level.

gene.set.statistics.name: demethylation
gene.set.statistics.description: The process of removing one or more methyl groups from a molecule.

gene.set.statistics.name: NADPH oxidation
gene.set.statistics.description: A metabolic process that results in the oxidation of reduced nicotinamide adenine dinucleotide, NADPH, to the oxidized form, NADP.

gene.set.statistics.name: neuron death
gene.set.statistics.description: The process of cell death in a neuron.

gene.set.statistics.name: nuclear mRNA surveillance
gene.set.statistics.description: The set of processes involved in identifying and degrading defective or aberrant mRNAs within the nucleus.

gene.set.statistics.name: CUT catabolic process
gene.set.statistics.description: The chemical reactions and pathways resulting in the breakdown of cryptic unstable transcripts (CUTs).

gene.set.statistics.name: histone mRNA catabolic process
gene.set.statistics.description: The chemical reactions and pathways resulting in the breakdown of histone messenger RNA (mRNA).

gene.set.statistics.name: polyadenylation-dependent snoRNA 3'-end processing
gene.set.statistics.description: Any process involved in forming the mature 3' end of a snoRNA molecule linked to prior polyadenylation of the 3'-end of the precursor snoRNA.

gene.set.statistics.name: protein K48-linked deubiquitination
gene.set.statistics.description: A protein deubiquitination process in which a K48-linked ubiquitin chain, i.e. a polymer of ubiquitin formed by linkages between lysine residues at position 48 of the ubiquitin monomers, is removed from a protein.

gene.set.statistics.name: establishment of protein localization to chromatin
gene.set.statistics.description: The directed movement of a protein to a part of a chromosome that is organized into chromatin.

gene.set.statistics.name: cellular response to molecule of bacterial origin
gene.set.statistics.description: Any process that results in a change in state or activity of a cell (in terms of movement, secretion, enzyme production, gene expression, etc.) as a result of a stimulus by molecules of bacterial origin such as peptides derived from bacterial flagellin.

gene.set.statistics.name: cellular response to lipopolysaccharide
gene.set.statistics.description: Any process that results in a change in state or activity of a cell (in terms of movement, secretion, enzyme production, gene expression, etc.) as a result of a lipopolysaccharide stimulus; lipopolysaccharide is a major component of the cell wall of gram-negative bacteria.

gene.set.statistics.name: cellular response to muramyl dipeptide
gene.set.statistics.description: Any process that results in a change in state or activity of a cell (in terms of movement, secretion, enzyme production, gene expression, etc.) as a result of a muramyl dipeptide stimulus. Muramyl dipeptide is derived from peptidoglycan.

gene.set.statistics.name: cellular response to amino acid stimulus
gene.set.statistics.description: Any process that results in a change in state or activity of a cell (in terms of movement, secretion, enzyme production, gene expression, etc.) as a result of an amino acid stimulus. An amino acid is a carboxylic acids containing one or more amino groups.

gene.set.statistics.name: cellular response to leucine
gene.set.statistics.description: Any process that results in a change in state or activity of a cell (in terms of movement, secretion, enzyme production, gene expression, etc.) as a result of a leucine stimulus.

gene.set.statistics.name: cellular response to antibiotic
gene.set.statistics.description: Any process that results in a change in state or activity of a cell (in terms of movement, secretion, enzyme production, gene expression, etc.) as a result of an antibiotic stimulus. An antibiotic is a chemical substance produced by a microorganism which has the capacity to inhibit the growth of or to kill other microorganisms.

gene.set.statistics.name: cellular response to inorganic substance
gene.set.statistics.description: Any process that results in a change in state or activity of a cell (in terms of movement, secretion, enzyme production, gene expression, etc.) as a result of an inorganic substance stimulus.

gene.set.statistics.name: cellular response to ammonium ion
gene.set.statistics.description: Any process that results in a change in state or activity of a cell (in terms of movement, secretion, enzyme production, gene expression, etc.) as a result of an ammonium stimulus.

gene.set.statistics.name: cellular response to arsenic-containing substance
gene.set.statistics.description: Any process that results in a change in state or activity of a cell (in terms of movement, secretion, enzyme production, gene expression, etc.) as a result of an arsenic stimulus from compounds containing arsenic, including arsenates, arsenites, and arsenides.

gene.set.statistics.name: cellular response to metal ion
gene.set.statistics.description: Any process that results in a change in state or activity of a cell (in terms of movement, secretion, enzyme production, gene expression, etc.) as a result of a metal ion stimulus.

gene.set.statistics.name: cellular response to electrical stimulus
gene.set.statistics.description: Any process that results in a change in state or activity of a cell (in terms of movement, secretion, enzyme production, gene expression, etc.) as a result of an electrical stimulus.

gene.set.statistics.name: cellular response to mechanical stimulus
gene.set.statistics.description: Any process that results in a change in state or activity of a cell (in terms of movement, secretion, enzyme production, gene expression, etc.) as a result of a mechanical stimulus.

gene.set.statistics.name: cellular response to cadmium ion
gene.set.statistics.description: Any process that results in a change in state or activity of a cell (in terms of movement, secretion, enzyme production, gene expression, etc.) as a result of a cadmium (Cd) ion stimulus.

gene.set.statistics.name: cellular response to calcium ion
gene.set.statistics.description: Any process that results in a change in state or activity of a cell (in terms of movement, secretion, enzyme production, gene expression, etc.) as a result of a calcium ion stimulus.

gene.set.statistics.description: Any process that results in a change in state or activity of a cell (in terms of movement, secretion, enzyme production, gene expression, etc.) as a result of a magnesium ion stimulus.

gene.set.statistics.description: Any process that results in a change in state or activity of a cell (in terms of movement, secretion, enzyme production, gene expression, etc.) as a result of a manganese ion stimulus.

gene.set.statistics.name: cellular response to mercury ion
gene.set.statistics.description: Any process that results in a change in state or activity of a cell (in terms of movement, secretion, enzyme production, gene expression, etc.) as a result of a mercury ion stimulus.

gene.set.statistics.name: cellular response to zinc ion
gene.set.statistics.description: Any process that results in a change in state or activity of a cell (in terms of movement, secretion, enzyme production, gene expression, etc.) as a result of a zinc ion stimulus.

gene.set.statistics.name: cellular response to retinoic acid
gene.set.statistics.description: Any process that results in a change in state or activity of a cell (in terms of movement, secretion, enzyme production, gene expression, etc.) as a result of a retinoic acid stimulus.

gene.set.statistics.name: cellular response to ATP
gene.set.statistics.description: Any process that results in a change in state or activity of a cell (in terms of movement, secretion, enzyme production, gene expression, etc.) as a result of an ATP (adenosine 5'-triphosphate) stimulus.

gene.set.statistics.name: cellular response to cAMP
gene.set.statistics.description: Any process that results in a change in state or activity of a cell (in terms of movement, secretion, enzyme production, gene expression, etc.) as a result of a cAMP (cyclic AMP, adenosine 3',5'-cyclophosphate) stimulus.

gene.set.statistics.name: cellular response to glucose stimulus
gene.set.statistics.description: Any process that results in a change in state or activity of a cell (in terms of movement, secretion, enzyme production, gene expression, etc.) as a result of a glucose stimulus.

gene.set.statistics.name: diphosphate metabolic process
gene.set.statistics.description: The chemical reactions and pathways involving diphosphate, the anion or salt of diphosphoric acid.

gene.set.statistics.name: cellular response to cytokine stimulus
gene.set.statistics.description: Any process that results in a change in state or activity of a cell (in terms of movement, secretion, enzyme production, gene expression, etc.) as a result of a cytokine stimulus.

gene.set.statistics.name: cellular response to interferon-gamma
gene.set.statistics.description: Any process that results in a change in state or activity of a cell (in terms of movement, secretion, enzyme production, gene expression, etc.) as a result of an interferon-gamma stimulus. Interferon gamma is the only member of the type II interferon found so far.

gene.set.statistics.name: cellular response to interleukin-1
gene.set.statistics.description: Any process that results in a change in state or activity of a cell (in terms of movement, secretion, enzyme production, gene expression, etc.) as a result of an interleukin-1 stimulus.

gene.set.statistics.name: cellular response to interleukin-4
gene.set.statistics.description: Any process that results in a change in state or activity of a cell (in terms of movement, secretion, enzyme production, gene expression, etc.) as a result of an interleukin-4 stimulus.

gene.set.statistics.description: Any process that results in a change in state or activity of a cell (in terms of movement, secretion, enzyme production, gene expression, etc.) as a result of an interleukin-6 stimulus.

gene.set.statistics.name: cellular response to tumor necrosis factor
gene.set.statistics.description: Any process that results in a change in state or activity of a cell (in terms of movement, secretion, enzyme production, gene expression, etc.) as a result of a tumor necrosis factor stimulus.

gene.set.statistics.name: cellular response to dsRNA
gene.set.statistics.description: Any process that results in a change in state or activity of a cell (in terms of movement, secretion, enzyme production, gene expression, etc.) as a result of a double-stranded RNA stimulus.

gene.set.statistics.name: cellular response to exogenous dsRNA
gene.set.statistics.description: Any process that results in a change in state or activity of a cell (in terms of movement, secretion, enzyme production, gene expression, etc.) as a result of an exogenous double-stranded RNA stimulus.

gene.set.statistics.name: cellular response to growth factor stimulus
gene.set.statistics.description: Any process that results in a change in state or activity of a cell (in terms of movement, secretion, enzyme production, gene expression, etc.) as a result of a growth factor stimulus.

gene.set.statistics.name: cellular response to epidermal growth factor stimulus
gene.set.statistics.description: Any process that results in a change in state or activity of a cell (in terms of movement, secretion, enzyme production, gene expression, etc.) as a result of an epidermal growth factor stimulus.

gene.set.statistics.name: cellular response to follicle-stimulating hormone stimulus
gene.set.statistics.description: Any process that results in a change in state or activity of a cell (in terms of movement, secretion, enzyme production, gene expression, etc.) as a result of a follicle-stimulating hormone stimulus.

gene.set.statistics.name: cellular response to peptide hormone stimulus
gene.set.statistics.description: Any process that results in a change in state or activity of a cell (in terms of movement, secretion, enzyme production, gene expression, etc.) as a result of a peptide hormone stimulus. A peptide hormone is any of a class of peptides that are secreted into the blood stream and have endocrine functions in living animals.

gene.set.statistics.name: cellular response to glucagon stimulus
gene.set.statistics.description: Any process that results in a change in state or activity of a cell (in terms of movement, secretion, enzyme production, gene expression, etc.) as a result of a glucagon stimulus.

gene.set.statistics.name: cellular response to prostaglandin E stimulus
gene.set.statistics.description: Any process that results in a change in state or activity of a cell (in terms of movement, secretion, enzyme production, gene expression, etc.) as a result of a prostagladin E stimulus.

gene.set.statistics.name: cellular response to steroid hormone stimulus
gene.set.statistics.description: Any process that results in a change in state or activity of a cell (in terms of movement, secretion, enzyme production, gene expression, etc.) as a result of a steroid hormone stimulus.

gene.set.statistics.name: cellular response to glucocorticoid stimulus
gene.set.statistics.description: Any process that results in a change in state or activity of a cell (in terms of movement, secretion, enzyme production, gene expression, etc.) as a result of a glucocorticoid stimulus. Glucocorticoids are hormonal C21 corticosteroids synthesized from cholesterol with the ability to bind with the cortisol receptor and trigger similar effects. Glucocorticoids act primarily on carbohydrate and protein metabolism, and have anti-inflammatory effects.

gene.set.statistics.name: cellular response to corticosterone stimulus
gene.set.statistics.description: Any process that results in a change in state or activity of a cell (in terms of movement, secretion, enzyme production, gene expression, etc.) as a result of a corticosterone stimulus. Corticosterone is a 21 carbon steroid hormone of the corticosteroid type, produced in the cortex of the adrenal glands. In many species, corticosterone is the principal glucocorticoid, involved in regulation of fuel metabolism, immune reactions, and stress responses.

gene.set.statistics.name: cellular response to estrogen stimulus
gene.set.statistics.description: Any process that results in a change in state or activity of a cell (in terms of movement, secretion, enzyme production, gene expression, etc.) as a result of stimulus by an estrogen, C18 steroid hormones that can stimulate the development of female sexual characteristics.

gene.set.statistics.name: cellular response to estradiol stimulus
gene.set.statistics.description: Any process that results in a change in state or activity of a cell (in terms of movement, secretion, enzyme production, gene expression, etc.) as a result of stimulus by estradiol, a C18 steroid hormone hydroxylated at C3 and C17 that acts as a potent estrogen.

gene.set.statistics.name: cellular response to testosterone stimulus
gene.set.statistics.description: Any process that results in a change in state or activity of a cell (in terms of movement, secretion, enzyme production, gene expression, etc.) as a result of a testosterone stimulus.

gene.set.statistics.name: cellular response to cholesterol
gene.set.statistics.description: Any process that results in a change in state or activity of a cell (in terms of movement, secretion, enzyme production, gene expression, etc.) as a result of a cholesterol stimulus.

gene.set.statistics.description: Any process that results in a change in state or activity of a cell (in terms of movement, secretion, enzyme production, gene expression, etc.) as a result of a fatty acid stimulus.

gene.set.statistics.description: Any process that results in a change in state or activity of a cell (in terms of movement, secretion, enzyme production, gene expression, etc.) as a result of an oleic acid stimulus.

gene.set.statistics.name: cellular response to low-density lipoprotein particle stimulus
gene.set.statistics.description: Any process that results in a change in state or activity of a cell (in terms of movement, secretion, enzyme production, gene expression, etc.) as a result of a low-density lipoprotein particle stimulus.

gene.set.statistics.name: cellular response to organic cyclic compound
gene.set.statistics.description: Any process that results in a change in state or activity of a cell (in terms of movement, secretion, enzyme production, gene expression, etc.) as a result of an organic cyclic compound stimulus.

gene.set.statistics.name: cellular response to organonitrogen compound
gene.set.statistics.description: Any process that results in a change in state or activity of a cell (in terms of movement, secretion, enzyme production, gene expression, etc.) as a result of an organonitrogen stimulus. An organonitrogen compound is formally a compound containing at least one carbon-nitrogen bond.

gene.set.statistics.name: cellular response to amine stimulus
gene.set.statistics.description: Any process that results in a change in state or activity of a cell (in terms of movement, secretion, enzyme production, gene expression, etc.) as a result of an amine stimulus. An amine is a compound formally derived from ammonia by replacing one, two or three hydrogen atoms by hydrocarbyl groups.

gene.set.statistics.name: cellular response to histamine
gene.set.statistics.description: Any process that results in a change in state or activity of a cell (in terms of movement, secretion, enzyme production, gene expression, etc.) as a result of a histamine stimulus. Histamine, the biogenic amine 2-(1H-imidazol-4-yl)ethanamine, is involved in local immune responses as well as regulating physiological function in the gut and acting as a neurotransmitter.

gene.set.statistics.name: succinate transmembrane transport
gene.set.statistics.description: The process in which succinate is transported across a membrane.

gene.set.statistics.name: malate transmembrane transport
gene.set.statistics.description: A process in which a malate ion is transported across a membrane.

gene.set.statistics.name: hematopoietic stem cell proliferation
gene.set.statistics.description: The expansion of a hematopoietic stem cell population by cell division. A hematopoietic stem cell is a stem cell from which all cells of the lymphoid and myeloid lineages develop.

gene.set.statistics.name: cellular response to hydroperoxide
gene.set.statistics.description: Any process that results in a change in state or activity of a cell (in terms of movement, secretion, enzyme production, gene expression, etc.) as a result of a hydroperoxide stimulus. Hydroperoxides are monosubstitution products of hydrogen peroxide, HOOH.

gene.set.statistics.name: cellular response to oxygen levels
gene.set.statistics.description: Any process that results in a change in state or activity of a cell (in terms of movement, secretion, enzyme production, gene expression, etc.) as a result of a stimulus reflecting the presence, absence, or concentration of oxygen.

gene.set.statistics.name: cellular response to hyperoxia
gene.set.statistics.description: Any process that results in a change in state or activity of a cell (in terms of movement, secretion, enzyme production, gene expression, etc.) as a result of a stimulus indicating increased oxygen tension.

gene.set.statistics.name: cellular response to hypoxia
gene.set.statistics.description: Any process that results in a change in state or activity of a cell (in terms of movement, secretion, enzyme production, gene expression, etc.) as a result of a stimulus indicating lowered oxygen tension. Hypoxia, defined as a decline in O2 levels below normoxic levels of 20.8 - 20.95%, results in metabolic adaptation at both the cellular and organismal level.

gene.set.statistics.name: cellular response to xenobiotic stimulus
gene.set.statistics.description: Any process that results in a change in state or activity of a cell (in terms of movement, secretion, enzyme production, gene expression, etc.) as a result of a xenobiotic compound stimulus. Xenobiotic compounds are compounds foreign to living organisms.

gene.set.statistics.name: cellular response to acidic pH
gene.set.statistics.description: Any process that results in a change in state or activity of a cell (in terms of movement, secretion, enzyme production, gene expression, etc.) as a result of a pH stimulus with pH < 7. pH is a measure of the acidity or basicity of an aqueous solution.

gene.set.statistics.name: cellular response to osmotic stress
gene.set.statistics.description: Any process that results in a change in state or activity of a cell (in terms of movement, secretion, enzyme production, gene expression, etc.) as a result of a stimulus indicating an increase or decrease in the concentration of solutes outside the organism or cell.

gene.set.statistics.name: cellular hyperosmotic response
gene.set.statistics.description: Any process that results in a change in state or activity of a cell (in terms of movement, secretion, enzyme production, gene expression, etc.) as a result of detection of, or exposure to, a hyperosmotic environment, i.e. an environment with a higher concentration of solutes than the organism or cell.

gene.set.statistics.name: cellular hyperosmotic salinity response
gene.set.statistics.description: Any process that results in a change in state or activity of a cell (in terms of movement, secretion, enzyme production, gene expression, etc.) as a result of detection of, or exposure to, an increase in the concentration of salt (particularly but not exclusively sodium and chloride ions) in the environment.

gene.set.statistics.name: cellular hypotonic response
gene.set.statistics.description: Any process that results in a change in state or activity of a cell (in terms of movement, secretion, enzyme production, gene expression, etc.) as a result of detection of, or exposure to, a hypotonic environment, i.e. an environment with a lower concentration of solutes than the organism or cell.

gene.set.statistics.name: cellular response to radiation
gene.set.statistics.description: Any process that results in a change in state or activity of a cell (in terms of movement, secretion, enzyme production, gene expression, etc.) as a result of an electromagnetic radiation stimulus. Electromagnetic radiation is a propagating wave in space with electric and magnetic components. These components oscillate at right angles to each other and to the direction of propagation.

gene.set.statistics.name: cellular response to ionizing radiation
gene.set.statistics.description: Any process that results in a change in state or activity of a cell (in terms of movement, secretion, enzyme production, gene expression, etc.) as a result of a ionizing radiation stimulus. Ionizing radiation is radiation with sufficient energy to remove electrons from atoms and may arise from spontaneous decay of unstable isotopes, resulting in alpha and beta particles and gamma rays. Ionizing radiation also includes X-rays.

gene.set.statistics.name: cellular response to gamma radiation
gene.set.statistics.description: Any process that results in a change in state or activity of a cell (in terms of movement, secretion, enzyme production, gene expression, etc.) as a result of a gamma radiation stimulus. Gamma radiation is a form of electromagnetic radiation (EMR) or light emission of a specific frequency produced from sub-atomic particle interaction, such as electron-positron annihilation and radioactive decay. Gamma rays are generally characterized as EMR having the highest frequency and energy, and also the shortest wavelength, within the electromagnetic radiation spectrum.

gene.set.statistics.name: cellular response to X-ray
gene.set.statistics.description: Any process that results in a change in state or activity of a cell (in terms of movement, secretion, enzyme production, gene expression, etc.) as a result of X-ray radiation. An X-ray is a form of electromagnetic radiation with a wavelength in the range of 10 nanometers to 100 picometers (corresponding to frequencies in the range 30 PHz to 3 EHz).

gene.set.statistics.name: cellular response to UV-A
gene.set.statistics.description: Any process that results in a change in state or activity of a cell (in terms of movement, secretion, enzyme production, gene expression, etc.) as a result of a UV-A radiation stimulus. UV-A radiation (UV-A light) spans the wavelengths 315 to 400 nm.

gene.set.statistics.name: cellular response to laminar fluid shear stress
gene.set.statistics.description: Any process that results in a change in state or activity of a cell (in terms of movement, secretion, enzyme production, gene expression, etc.) as a result of a laminar fluid shear stress stimulus. Laminar fluid flow is the force acting on an object in a system where the fluid is moving across a solid surface in parallel layers.

gene.set.statistics.name: semaphorin-plexin signaling pathway
gene.set.statistics.description: A series of molecular signals generated as a consequence of a semaphorin receptor (composed of a plexin and a neurophilin) binding to a semaphorin ligand.

gene.set.statistics.name: protein localization to centrosome
gene.set.statistics.description: A process in which a protein is transported to, or maintained at, the centrosome.

gene.set.statistics.name: dopaminergic neuron differentiation
gene.set.statistics.description: The process in which a neuroblast acquires the specialized structural and functional features of a dopaminergic neuron, a neuron that secretes dopamine.

gene.set.statistics.name: response to dexamethasone
gene.set.statistics.description: Any process that results in a change in state or activity of a cell or an organism (in terms of movement, secretion, enzyme production, gene expression, etc.) as a result of a dexamethasone stimulus.

gene.set.statistics.name: cellular response to dexamethasone stimulus
gene.set.statistics.description: Any process that results in a change in state or activity of a cell (in terms of movement, secretion, enzyme production, gene expression, etc.) as a result of a dexamethasone stimulus.

gene.set.statistics.name: cellular response to transforming growth factor beta stimulus
gene.set.statistics.description: Any process that results in a change in state or activity of a cell (in terms of movement, secretion, enzyme production, gene expression, etc.) as a result of a transforming growth factor beta stimulus.

gene.set.statistics.name: protein ufmylation
gene.set.statistics.description: Covalent attachment of the ubiquitin-like protein UFM1 to another protein.

gene.set.statistics.name: endothelial cell-cell adhesion
gene.set.statistics.description: The attachment of an endothelial cell to another endothelial cell via adhesion molecules.

gene.set.statistics.name: granulocyte chemotaxis
gene.set.statistics.description: The movement of a granulocyte in response to an external stimulus.

gene.set.statistics.name: vocalization behavior
gene.set.statistics.description: The behavior in which an organism produces sounds by a mechanism involving its respiratory system.

gene.set.statistics.name: negative regulation of transforming growth factor beta production
gene.set.statistics.description: Any process that stops, prevents, or reduces the frequency, rate, or extent of production of transforming growth factor-beta.

gene.set.statistics.name: positive regulation of chemokine (C-C motif) ligand 5 production
gene.set.statistics.description: Any process that activates or increases the frequency, rate, or extent of production of chemokine (C-C motif) ligand 5.

gene.set.statistics.name: smooth muscle cell chemotaxis
gene.set.statistics.description: The directed movement of a smooth muscle cell in response to an external stimulus.

gene.set.statistics.name: negative regulation of smooth muscle cell chemotaxis
gene.set.statistics.description: Any process that stops, prevents, or reduces the frequency, rate, or extent of smooth muscle cell chemotaxis.

gene.set.statistics.name: mononuclear cell migration
gene.set.statistics.description: The movement of a mononuclear cell within or between different tissues and organs of the body.

gene.set.statistics.name: positive regulation of mononuclear cell migration
gene.set.statistics.description: Any process that increases the rate, frequency or extent of mononuclear cell migration. Mononuclear cell migration is the movement of a mononuclear cell within or between different tissues and organs of the body.

gene.set.statistics.name: cellular response to indole-3-methanol
gene.set.statistics.description: Any process that results in a change in state or activity of a cell (in terms of movement, secretion, enzyme production, gene expression, etc.) as a result of an indole-3-methanol stimulus.

gene.set.statistics.name: basement membrane organization
gene.set.statistics.description: A process that is carried out at the cellular level which results in the assembly, arrangement of constituent parts, or disassembly of the basement membrane.

gene.set.statistics.name: ER-associated misfolded protein catabolic process
gene.set.statistics.description: The chemical reactions and pathways resulting in the breakdown of misfolded proteins transported from the endoplasmic reticulum and targeted to cytoplasmic proteasomes for degradation.

gene.set.statistics.name: response to nitric oxide
gene.set.statistics.description: Any process that results in a change in state or activity of a cell or an organism (in terms of movement, secretion, enzyme production, gene expression, etc.) as a result of a nitric oxide stimulus.

gene.set.statistics.name: cellular response to nitric oxide
gene.set.statistics.description: Any process that results in a change in state or activity of a cell (in terms of movement, secretion, enzyme production, gene expression, etc.) as a result of a nitric oxide stimulus.

gene.set.statistics.name: nuclear membrane organization
gene.set.statistics.description: A process that is carried out at the cellular level which results in the assembly, arrangement of constituent parts, or disassembly of the nuclear inner or outer membrane.

gene.set.statistics.name: cellular response to BMP stimulus
gene.set.statistics.description: Any process that results in a change in state or activity of a cell (in terms of movement, secretion, enzyme production, gene expression, etc.) as a result of a bone morphogenetic protein (BMP) stimulus.

gene.set.statistics.name: endoplasmic reticulum tubular network organization
gene.set.statistics.description: A process that is carried out at the cellular level which results in the assembly, arrangement of constituent parts, or disassembly of the endoplasmic reticulum (ER) tubular network. The ER tubular network is the ER part that that has membranes with high curvature in cross-section.

gene.set.statistics.name: endoplasmic reticulum tubular network formation
gene.set.statistics.description: The aggregation, arrangement and bonding together of a set of components to form the endoplasmic reticulum (ER) tubular network. The ER tubular network is the ER part that comprises the membranes with high curvature in cross-section.

gene.set.statistics.name: regulation of podosome assembly
gene.set.statistics.description: Any process that modulates the frequency, rate or extent of podosome assembly.

gene.set.statistics.name: positive regulation of podosome assembly
gene.set.statistics.description: Any process that activates or increases the rate or extent of podosome assembly.

gene.set.statistics.name: potassium ion transmembrane transport
gene.set.statistics.description: A process in which a potassium ion is transported from one side of a membrane to the other.

gene.set.statistics.name: cellular response to catecholamine stimulus
gene.set.statistics.description: Any process that results in a change in state or activity of a cell (in terms of movement, secretion, enzyme production, gene expression, etc.) as a result of a catecholamine stimulus. A catecholamine is any of a group of biogenic amines that includes 4-(2-aminoethyl)pyrocatechol [4-(2-aminoethyl)benzene-1,2-diol] and derivatives formed by substitution.

gene.set.statistics.name: protein localization to adherens junction
gene.set.statistics.description: Any process in which a protein is transported to, and/or maintained at the adherens junction.

gene.set.statistics.name: DNA biosynthetic process
gene.set.statistics.description: The cellular DNA metabolic process resulting in the formation of DNA, deoxyribonucleic acid, one of the two main types of nucleic acid, consisting of a long unbranched macromolecule formed from one or two strands of linked deoxyribonucleotides, the 3'-phosphate group of each constituent deoxyribonucleotide being joined in 3',5'-phosphodiester linkage to the 5'-hydroxyl group of the deoxyribose moiety of the next one.

gene.set.statistics.name: negative regulation of protein serine/threonine kinase activity
gene.set.statistics.description: Any process that decreases the rate, frequency, or extent of protein serine/threonine kinase activity.

gene.set.statistics.name: positive regulation of protein serine/threonine kinase activity
gene.set.statistics.description: Any process that increases the rate, frequency, or extent of protein serine/threonine kinase activity.

gene.set.statistics.name: protein deubiquitination involved in ubiquitin-dependent protein catabolic process
gene.set.statistics.description: The removal of one or more ubiquitin groups from a protein as part of a process of ubiquitin-dependent protein catabolism.

gene.set.statistics.name: mitotic sister chromatid cohesion, centromeric
gene.set.statistics.description: The cell cycle process in which centromeres of sister chromatids are joined during mitosis.

gene.set.statistics.name: multivesicular body sorting pathway
gene.set.statistics.description: A vesicle-mediated transport process in which transmembrane proteins are ubiquitylated to facilitate their entry into luminal vesicles of multivesicular bodies (MVBs); upon subsequent fusion of MVBs with lysosomes or vacuoles, the cargo proteins are degraded.

gene.set.statistics.name: nephron development
gene.set.statistics.description: The process whose specific outcome is the progression of the nephron over time, from its formation to the mature structure. A nephron is the functional unit of the kidney.

gene.set.statistics.name: glomerular visceral epithelial cell development
gene.set.statistics.description: The process whose specific outcome is the progression of a glomerular visceral epithelial cell over time, from its formation to the mature structure. A glomerular visceral epithelial cell is a specialized epithelial cell that contains 'feet' that interdigitate with the 'feet' of other glomerular epithelial cells.

gene.set.statistics.name: regulation of stem cell proliferation
gene.set.statistics.description: Any process that modulates the frequency, rate or extent of stem cell proliferation. A stem cell is a cell that retains the ability to divide and proliferate throughout life to provide progenitor cells that can differentiate into specialized cells.

gene.set.statistics.name: metanephric mesenchymal cell proliferation involved in metanephros development
gene.set.statistics.description: The multiplication or reproduction of cells, resulting in the expansion of a metanephric mesenchymal cell population.

gene.set.statistics.name: metanephric mesenchymal cell differentiation
gene.set.statistics.description: The process in which relatively unspecialized cells acquire specialized structural and/or functional features that characterize the mesenchymal cells of the metanephros as it progresses from its formation to the mature state.

gene.set.statistics.name: negative regulation of mesenchymal cell proliferation
gene.set.statistics.description: Any process that decreases the frequency, rate or extent of mesenchymal cell proliferation. A mesenchymal cell is a cell that normally gives rise to other cells that are organized as three-dimensional masses, rather than sheets.

gene.set.statistics.name: regulation of metanephric nephron tubule epithelial cell differentiation
gene.set.statistics.description: Any process that modulates the frequency, rate or extent of metanephric nephron tubule epithelial cell differentiation.

gene.set.statistics.name: intrinsic apoptotic signaling pathway by p53 class mediator
gene.set.statistics.description: A series of molecular signals in which an intracellular signal is conveyed to trigger the apoptotic death of a cell. The pathway is induced by the cell cycle regulator phosphoprotein p53, or an equivalent protein, and ends when the execution phase of apoptosis is triggered.

gene.set.statistics.name: rescue of stalled ribosome
gene.set.statistics.description: A process of translational elongation that takes place when a ribosome has stalled during translation, and results in freeing the ribosome from the stalled translation complex.

gene.set.statistics.name: organelle transport along microtubule
gene.set.statistics.description: The directed movement of an organelle along a microtubule, mediated by motor proteins. This process begins with the attachment of an organelle to a microtubule, and ends when the organelle reaches its final destination.

gene.set.statistics.name: minus-end-directed organelle transport along microtubule
gene.set.statistics.description: The directed movement of an organelle towards the minus end of a microtubule, mediated by motor proteins. This process begins with the attachment of an organelle to a microtubule, and ends when the organelle reaches its final destination.

gene.set.statistics.name: response to DNA damage checkpoint signaling
gene.set.statistics.description: A process that occurs in response to signals generated as a result of DNA damage checkpoint signaling.

gene.set.statistics.name: ammonium transmembrane transport
gene.set.statistics.description: The process in which ammonium is transported across a membrane. Ammonium is the cation NH4+.

gene.set.statistics.name: T-helper 17 type immune response
gene.set.statistics.description: An immune response which is associated with resistance to intracellular bacteria with a key role in inflammation and tissue injury. This immune response is associated with pathological autoimmune conditions such as multiple sclerosis, arthritis and psoriasis which is typically orchestrated by the production of particular cytokines by T-helper 17 cells, most notably interleukin-17, IL-21 and IL-22.

gene.set.statistics.name: clathrin-dependent endocytosis
gene.set.statistics.description: An endocytosis process that begins when material is taken up into clathrin-coated pits, which then pinch off to form clathrin-coated endocytic vesicles.

gene.set.statistics.name: caveolin-mediated endocytosis
gene.set.statistics.description: An endocytosis process that begins when material is taken up into plasma membrane caveolae, which then pinch off to form endocytic caveolar carriers.

gene.set.statistics.name: reactive oxygen species metabolic process
gene.set.statistics.description: The chemical reactions and pathways involving a reactive oxygen species, any molecules or ions formed by the incomplete one-electron reduction of oxygen. They contribute to the microbicidal activity of phagocytes, regulation of signal transduction and gene expression, and the oxidative damage to biopolymers.

gene.set.statistics.name: establishment of protein localization to mitochondrion
gene.set.statistics.description: The directed movement of a protein to the mitochondrion or a part of the mitochondrion.

gene.set.statistics.name: maintenance of protein location in mitochondrion
gene.set.statistics.description: Any process in which a protein is maintained in a specific location in a mitochondrion, and is prevented from moving elsewhere.

gene.set.statistics.name: protein localization to membrane
gene.set.statistics.description: A process in which a protein is transported to, or maintained in, a specific location in a membrane.

gene.set.statistics.name: protein localization to plasma membrane
gene.set.statistics.description: A process in which a protein is transported to, or maintained in, a specific location in the plasma membrane.

gene.set.statistics.name: lamellipodium morphogenesis
gene.set.statistics.description: A process that is carried out at the cellular level and in which the structure of a lamellipodium is organized.

gene.set.statistics.name: T cell migration
gene.set.statistics.description: The movement of a T cell within or between different tissues and organs of the body.

gene.set.statistics.name: cellular response to actinomycin D
gene.set.statistics.description: Any process that results in a change in state or activity of a cell (in terms of movement, secretion, enzyme production, gene expression, etc.) as a result of an actinomycin D stimulus.

gene.set.statistics.name: cellular response to cisplatin
gene.set.statistics.description: Any process that results in a change in state or activity of a cell (in terms of movement, secretion, enzyme production, gene expression, etc.) as a result of a cisplatin stimulus.

gene.set.statistics.name: cellular response to rapamycin
gene.set.statistics.description: Any process that results in a change in state or activity of a cell (in terms of movement, secretion, enzyme production, gene expression, etc.) as a result of a rapamycin stimulus.

gene.set.statistics.name: entry of viral genome into host nucleus through nuclear pore complex via importin
gene.set.statistics.description: Viral penetration into the host nucleus where the viral genome passes through the nuclear pore complex (NPC) using the cellular importin transport machinery.

gene.set.statistics.name: IRES-dependent viral translational initiation
gene.set.statistics.description: Process by which viral mRNA translation is initiated, where a domain in the 5' untranslated region (UTR) of the viral mRNA called an internal ribosome entry site (IRES) binds the host 43S preinitiation complex, circumventing regular cap-dependent translation initiation.

gene.set.statistics.name: viral translational termination-reinitiation
gene.set.statistics.description: A process which occurs as part of viral mRNA translation which allows expression of a downstream open reading frame (ORF) in a dicistronic mRNA. In this process, ribosomes translate the upstream ORF but following termination, a proportion of 40S subunits remain tethered to the mRNA and go on to re-initiate translation at the start codon of the downstream ORF.

gene.set.statistics.name: establishment of integrated proviral latency
gene.set.statistics.description: A process by which the virus integrates into the host genome and establishes as a stable provirus or prophage.

gene.set.statistics.name: intracellular transport of virus
gene.set.statistics.description: The directed movement of a virus, or part of a virus, within the host cell.

gene.set.statistics.name: mRNA methylation
gene.set.statistics.description: The posttranscriptional addition of methyl groups to specific residues in an mRNA molecule.

gene.set.statistics.name: DNA demethylation
gene.set.statistics.description: The removal of a methyl group from one or more nucleotides within an DNA molecule.

gene.set.statistics.name: regulation of cellular response to stress
gene.set.statistics.description: Any process that modulates the frequency, rate or extent of a cellular response to stress. Cellular response to stress is a change in state or activity of a cell (in terms of movement, secretion, enzyme production, gene expression, etc.) as a result of a stimulus indicating the organism is under stress. The stress is usually, but not necessarily, exogenous (e.g. temperature, humidity, ionizing radiation).

gene.set.statistics.name: histone H3-K4 trimethylation
gene.set.statistics.description: The modification of histone H3 by addition of three methyl groups to lysine at position 4 of the histone.

gene.set.statistics.name: cardiac muscle cell action potential involved in contraction
gene.set.statistics.description: An action potential that occurs in a cardiac muscle cell and is involved in its contraction.

gene.set.statistics.name: regulation of cardiac muscle cell contraction
gene.set.statistics.description: Any process that modulates the frequency, rate or extent of cardiac muscle cell contraction.

gene.set.statistics.name: ventricular cardiac muscle cell action potential
gene.set.statistics.description: An action potential that occurs in a ventricular cardiac muscle cell.

gene.set.statistics.name: membrane repolarization
gene.set.statistics.description: The process in which ions are transported across a membrane such that the membrane potential changes in the repolarizing direction, toward the steady state potential. For example, the repolarization during an action potential is from a positive membrane potential towards a negative resting potential.

gene.set.statistics.name: membrane depolarization during action potential
gene.set.statistics.description: The process in which membrane potential changes in the depolarizing direction from the negative resting potential towards the positive membrane potential that will be the peak of the action potential.

gene.set.statistics.name: membrane repolarization during cardiac muscle cell action potential
gene.set.statistics.description: The process in which ions are transported across a membrane such that the cardiac muscle cell plasma membrane potential changes in the direction from the positive membrane potential at the peak of the action potential towards the negative resting potential.

gene.set.statistics.name: regulation of cardiac muscle cell membrane potential
gene.set.statistics.description: Any process that modulates the establishment or extent of a membrane potential in a cardiac muscle cell (a cardiomyocyte). A membrane potential is the electric potential existing across any membrane arising from charges in the membrane itself and from the charges present in the media on either side of the membrane.

gene.set.statistics.name: cell communication by electrical coupling involved in cardiac conduction
gene.set.statistics.description: The process that mediates signaling interactions between one cell and another cell by transfer of current between their adjacent cytoplasms via intercellular protein channels and contributes to the process of cardiac conduction.

gene.set.statistics.name: bundle of His cell-Purkinje myocyte adhesion involved in cell communication
gene.set.statistics.description: The attachment of a bundle of His cell to a Purkinje myocyte via adhesion molecules that results in the cells being juxtaposed so that they can communicate.

gene.set.statistics.name: regulation of heart rate by cardiac conduction
gene.set.statistics.description: A cardiac conduction process that modulates the frequency or rate of heart contraction.

gene.set.statistics.name: endothelin receptor signaling pathway
gene.set.statistics.description: A series of molecular signals initiated by an endothelin receptor binding to one of its physiological ligands, and proceeding with the activated receptor promoting the exchange of GDP for GTP on the alpha-subunit of an associated heterotrimeric G-protein complex. Ends with regulation of a downstream cellular process, e.g. transcription.

gene.set.statistics.name: amino acid import across plasma membrane
gene.set.statistics.description: The directed movement of an amino acid from outside of a cell, across the plasma membrane and into the cytosol.

gene.set.statistics.name: regulation of neutrophil chemotaxis
gene.set.statistics.description: Any process that modulates the frequency, rate, or extent of neutrophil chemotaxis. Neutrophil chemotaxis is the directed movement of a neutrophil cell, the most numerous polymorphonuclear leukocyte found in the blood, in response to an external stimulus, usually an infection or wounding.

gene.set.statistics.name: positive regulation of neutrophil chemotaxis
gene.set.statistics.description: Any process that increases the frequency, rate, or extent of neutrophil chemotaxis. Neutrophil chemotaxis is the directed movement of a neutrophil cell, the most numerous polymorphonuclear leukocyte found in the blood, in response to an external stimulus, usually an infection or wounding.

gene.set.statistics.name: positive regulation of monocyte chemotaxis
gene.set.statistics.description: Any process that increases the frequency, rate, or extent of monocyte chemotaxis.

gene.set.statistics.name: negative regulation of protein kinase C signaling
gene.set.statistics.description: Any process that decreases the frequency, rate, or extent of a series of reactions, mediated by the intracellular serine/threonine kinase protein kinase C, which occurs as a result of a single trigger reaction or compound.

gene.set.statistics.name: positive regulation of cell migration involved in sprouting angiogenesis
gene.set.statistics.description: Any process that increases the frequency, rate or extent of cell migration involved in sprouting angiogenesis. Cell migration involved in sprouting angiogenesis is the orderly movement of endothelial cells into the extracellular matrix in order to form new blood vessels contributing to the process of sprouting angiogenesis.

gene.set.statistics.name: negative regulation of cell migration involved in sprouting angiogenesis
gene.set.statistics.description: Any process that decreases the frequency, rate or extent of cell migration involved in sprouting angiogenesis. Cell migration involved in sprouting angiogenesis is the orderly movement of endothelial cells into the extracellular matrix in order to form new blood vessels contributing to the process of sprouting angiogenesis.

gene.set.statistics.name: positive regulation of microtubule nucleation
gene.set.statistics.description: Any process that increases the rate, frequency or extent of microtubule nucleation. Microtubule nucleation is the 'de novo' formation of a microtubule, in which tubulin heterodimers form metastable oligomeric aggregates, some of which go on to support formation of a complete microtubule. Microtubule nucleation usually occurs from a specific site within a cell.

gene.set.statistics.name: negative regulation of ribosome biogenesis
gene.set.statistics.description: Any process that decreases the rate, frequency or extent of ribosome biogenesis. Ribosome biogenesis is the cellular process that results in the biosynthesis of constituent macromolecules, assembly, and arrangement of constituent parts of ribosome subunits.

gene.set.statistics.name: negative regulation of inclusion body assembly
gene.set.statistics.description: Any process that decreases the rate, frequency, or extent of inclusion body assembly. Inclusion body assembly is the aggregation, arrangement and bonding together of a set of components to form an inclusion body.

gene.set.statistics.name: negative regulation of canonical Wnt signaling pathway
gene.set.statistics.description: Any process that decreases the rate, frequency, or extent of the Wnt signaling pathway through beta-catenin, the series of molecular signals initiated by binding of a Wnt protein to a frizzled family receptor on the surface of the target cell, followed by propagation of the signal via beta-catenin, and ending with a change in transcription of target genes.

gene.set.statistics.name: positive regulation of extracellular matrix disassembly
gene.set.statistics.description: Any process that increases the rate, frequency or extent of extracellular matrix disassembly. Extracellular matrix disassembly is a process that results in the breakdown of the extracellular matrix.

gene.set.statistics.name: cochlea development
gene.set.statistics.description: The progression of the cochlea over time from its formation to the mature structure. The cochlea is the snail-shaped portion of the inner ear that is responsible for the detection of sound.

gene.set.statistics.name: COPII-coated vesicle cargo loading
gene.set.statistics.description: The formation of a macromolecular complex between the COPII coat proteins and proteins and/or lipoproteins that are going to be transported by the COPII vesicle to the Golgi.

gene.set.statistics.name: COPII-coated vesicle budding
gene.set.statistics.description: The evagination of an endoplasmic reticulum membrane, resulting in formation of a COPII-coated vesicle.

gene.set.statistics.name: C-5 methylation of cytosine
gene.set.statistics.description: The covalent transfer of a methyl group to C-5 of cytosine in a DNA molecule.

gene.set.statistics.name: regulation of synapse maturation
gene.set.statistics.description: Any process that modulates the extent of synapse maturation, the process that organizes a synapse so that it attains its fully functional state.

gene.set.statistics.name: mesenchyme migration
gene.set.statistics.description: The process in which the population of cells that make up a mesenchyme undergo directed movement.

gene.set.statistics.name: actin filament branching
gene.set.statistics.description: The formation of daughter actin filament branches at an angle on the sides of preexisting mother filaments.

gene.set.statistics.name: epithelial cell-cell adhesion
gene.set.statistics.description: The attachment of an epithelial cell to another epithelial cell via adhesion molecules.

gene.set.statistics.name: regulation of mitochondrial fission
gene.set.statistics.description: Any process that modulates the rate, frequency or extent of mitochondrial fission. Mitochondrial fission is the division of a mitochondrion within a cell to form two or more separate mitochondrial compartments.

gene.set.statistics.name: positive regulation of mitochondrial fission
gene.set.statistics.description: Any process that increases the rate, frequency or extent of mitochondrial fission. Mitochondrial fission is the division of a mitochondrion within a cell to form two or more separate mitochondrial compartments.

gene.set.statistics.name: membrane fission
gene.set.statistics.description: A process that is carried out at the cellular level which results in the separation of a single continuous membrane into two membranes.

gene.set.statistics.name: mitochondrial membrane fission
gene.set.statistics.description: A process that is carried out at the cellular level which results in the separation of a single continuous mitochondrial membrane into two membranes and contributes to mitochondrial fission.

gene.set.statistics.name: establishment of protein localization to membrane
gene.set.statistics.description: The directed movement of a protein to a specific location in a membrane.

gene.set.statistics.name: establishment of protein localization to mitochondrial membrane
gene.set.statistics.description: The directed movement of a protein to a specific location in the mitochondrial membrane.

gene.set.statistics.name: endoplasmic reticulum membrane organization
gene.set.statistics.description: A process that is carried out at the cellular level which results in the assembly, arrangement of constituent parts, or disassembly of an endoplasmic reticulum membrane.

gene.set.statistics.name: Golgi ribbon formation
gene.set.statistics.description: The formation of a continuous ribbon of interconnected Golgi stacks of flat cisternae.

gene.set.statistics.name: establishment of epithelial cell polarity
gene.set.statistics.description: The specification and formation of anisotropic intracellular organization of an epithelial cell.

gene.set.statistics.name: asymmetric Golgi ribbon formation
gene.set.statistics.description: The asymmetric formation of a continuous ribbon of interconnected Golgi stacks of flat cisternae that contributes to the establishment of epithelial cell polarity.

gene.set.statistics.name: Golgi disassembly
gene.set.statistics.description: A cellular process that results in the breakdown of a Golgi apparatus that contributes to Golgi inheritance.

gene.set.statistics.name: Golgi reassembly
gene.set.statistics.description: The reformation of the Golgi following its breakdown and partitioning contributing to Golgi inheritance.

gene.set.statistics.name: regulation of Golgi inheritance
gene.set.statistics.description: Any process that modulates the rate, frequency or extent of Golgi inheritance. Golgi inheritance is the partitioning of Golgi apparatus between daughter cells at cell division.

gene.set.statistics.name: regulation of cholesterol metabolic process
gene.set.statistics.description: Any process that modulates the rate, frequency, or extent of cholesterol metabolism, the chemical reactions and pathways involving cholesterol, cholest-5-en-3 beta-ol, the principal sterol of vertebrates and the precursor of many steroids, including bile acids and steroid hormones.

gene.set.statistics.name: negative regulation of branching involved in ureteric bud morphogenesis
gene.set.statistics.description: Any process that decreases the rate, frequency or extent of branching involved in ureteric bud morphogenesis, the process in which the branching structure of the ureteric bud is generated and organized. The ureteric bud is an epithelial tube that grows out from the metanephric duct. The bud elongates and branches to give rise to the ureter and kidney collecting tubules.

gene.set.statistics.name: positive regulation of release of cytochrome c from mitochondria
gene.set.statistics.description: Any process that increases the rate, frequency or extent of release of cytochrome c from mitochondria, the process in which cytochrome c is enabled to move from the mitochondrial intermembrane space into the cytosol, which is an early step in apoptosis and leads to caspase activation.

gene.set.statistics.name: negative regulation of release of cytochrome c from mitochondria
gene.set.statistics.description: Any process that decreases the rate, frequency or extent of release of cytochrome c from mitochondria, the process in which cytochrome c is enabled to move from the mitochondrial intermembrane space into the cytosol, which is an early step in apoptosis and leads to caspase activation.

gene.set.statistics.name: regulation of metaphase plate congression
gene.set.statistics.description: Any process that modulates the rate, frequency, or extent of metaphase plate congression, the alignment of chromosomes at the metaphase plate, a plane halfway between the poles of the spindle.

gene.set.statistics.name: positive regulation of histone H4 acetylation
gene.set.statistics.description: Any process that increases the rate, frequency, or extent of histone H4 acetylation, the modification of histone H4 by the addition of an acetyl group.

gene.set.statistics.name: positive regulation of inclusion body assembly
gene.set.statistics.description: Any process that increases the rate, frequency, or extent of inclusion body assembly. Inclusion body assembly is the aggregation, arrangement and bonding together of a set of components to form an inclusion body.

gene.set.statistics.name: positive regulation of canonical Wnt signaling pathway
gene.set.statistics.description: Any process that increases the rate, frequency, or extent of the Wnt signaling pathway through beta-catenin, the series of molecular signals initiated by binding of a Wnt protein to a frizzled family receptor on the surface of the target cell, followed by propagation of the signal via beta-catenin, and ending with a change in transcription of target genes.

gene.set.statistics.name: positive regulation of mitotic cell cycle spindle assembly checkpoint
gene.set.statistics.description: Any process that increases the rate, frequency, or extent of the mitotic cell cycle spindle assembly checkpoint, a cell cycle checkpoint that delays the metaphase/anaphase transition of a mitotic nuclear division until the spindle is correctly assembled and chromosomes are attached to the spindle.

gene.set.statistics.name: positive regulation of calcium ion import
gene.set.statistics.description: Any process that increases the rate, frequency, or extent of the directed movement of calcium ions into a cell or organelle.

gene.set.statistics.name: nuclear matrix anchoring at nuclear membrane
gene.set.statistics.description: The process in which the nuclear matrix, the dense fibrillar network lying on the inner side of the nuclear membrane, is directly or indirectly linked to the nuclear membrane.

gene.set.statistics.name: positive regulation of wound healing
gene.set.statistics.description: Any process that increases the rate, frequency, or extent of the series of events that restore integrity to a damaged tissue, following an injury.

gene.set.statistics.name: nucleic acid phosphodiester bond hydrolysis
gene.set.statistics.description: The nucleic acid metabolic process in which the phosphodiester bonds between nucleotides are cleaved by hydrolysis.

gene.set.statistics.name: spindle assembly involved in meiosis
gene.set.statistics.description: The aggregation, arrangement and bonding together of a set of components to form the spindle that contributes to the process of meiosis.

gene.set.statistics.name: mitotic spindle assembly
gene.set.statistics.description: Mitotic bipolar spindle assembly begins with spindle microtubule nucleation from the separated spindle pole body, includes spindle elongation during prometaphase, and is complete when all kinetochores are stably attached the spindle, and the spindle assembly checkpoint is satisfied.

gene.set.statistics.name: positive regulation of DNA methylation-dependent heterochromatin assembly
gene.set.statistics.description: Any process that increases the rate, frequency, or extent of the repression of transcription by methylation of DNA, leading to the formation of heterochromatin.

gene.set.statistics.name: regulation of protein deacetylation
gene.set.statistics.description: Any process that modulates the rate, frequency, or extent of protein deacetylation, the removal of an acetyl group from a protein amino acid. An acetyl group is CH3CO-, derived from acetic [ethanoic] acid.

gene.set.statistics.name: positive regulation of protein targeting to membrane
gene.set.statistics.description: Any process that increases the frequency, rate or extent of the process of directing proteins towards a membrane, usually using signals contained within the protein.

gene.set.statistics.name: negative regulation of protein targeting to membrane
gene.set.statistics.description: Any process that decreases the frequency, rate or extent of the process of directing proteins towards a membrane, usually using signals contained within the protein.

gene.set.statistics.name: positive regulation of intracellular protein transport
gene.set.statistics.description: Any process that activates or increases the frequency, rate or extent of the directed movement of proteins within cells.

gene.set.statistics.name: negative regulation of oxidative phosphorylation
gene.set.statistics.description: Any process that decreases the frequency, rate or extent of the chemical reactions and pathways resulting in the phosphorylation of ADP to ATP that accompanies the oxidation of a metabolite through the operation of the respiratory chain. Oxidation of compounds establishes a proton gradient across the membrane, providing the energy for ATP synthesis.

gene.set.statistics.name: regulation of platelet aggregation
gene.set.statistics.description: Any process that modulates the rate, frequency or extent of platelet aggregation. Platelet aggregation is the adhesion of one platelet to one or more other platelets via adhesion molecules.

gene.set.statistics.name: negative regulation of platelet aggregation
gene.set.statistics.description: Any process that decreases the rate, frequency or extent of platelet aggregation. Platelet aggregation is the adhesion of one platelet to one or more other platelets via adhesion molecules.

gene.set.statistics.name: regulation of brown fat cell differentiation
gene.set.statistics.description: Any process that modulates the rate, frequency, or extent of brown fat cell differentiation. Brown fat cell differentiation is the process in which a relatively unspecialized cell acquires specialized features of a brown adipocyte, an animal connective tissue cell involved in adaptive thermogenesis. Brown adipocytes contain multiple small droplets of triglycerides and a high number of mitochondria.

gene.set.statistics.name: positive regulation of brown fat cell differentiation
gene.set.statistics.description: Any process that increases the rate, frequency, or extent of brown fat cell differentiation. Brown fat cell differentiation is the process in which a relatively unspecialized cell acquires specialized features of a brown adipocyte, an animal connective tissue cell involved in adaptive thermogenesis. Brown adipocytes contain multiple small droplets of triglycerides and a high number of mitochondria.

gene.set.statistics.name: positive regulation of cell aging
gene.set.statistics.description: Any process that increases the rate, frequency, or extent of cell aging. Cell aging is the progression of the cell from its inception to the end of its lifespan.

gene.set.statistics.name: phagosome maturation
gene.set.statistics.description: A process that is carried out at the cellular level which results in the arrangement of constituent parts of a phagosome within a cell. Phagosome maturation begins with endocytosis and formation of the early phagosome and ends with the formation of the hybrid organelle, the phagolysosome.

gene.set.statistics.name: phagosome acidification
gene.set.statistics.description: Any process that reduces the pH of the phagosome, measured by the concentration of the hydrogen ion.

gene.set.statistics.name: phagosome-lysosome fusion
gene.set.statistics.description: The creation of a phagolysosome from a phagosome and a lysosome.

gene.set.statistics.name: negative regulation of excitatory postsynaptic potential
gene.set.statistics.description: Any process that prevents the establishment or decreases the extent of the excitatory postsynaptic potential (EPSP) which is a temporary increase in postsynaptic potential due to the flow of positively charged ions into the postsynaptic cell. The flow of ions that causes an EPSP is an excitatory postsynaptic current (EPSC) and makes it easier for the neuron to fire an action potential.

gene.set.statistics.name: cellular senescence
gene.set.statistics.description: A cell aging process stimulated in response to cellular stress, whereby normal cells lose the ability to divide through irreversible cell cycle arrest.

gene.set.statistics.name: RNA phosphodiester bond hydrolysis
gene.set.statistics.description: The RNA metabolic process in which the phosphodiester bonds between ribonucleotides are cleaved by hydrolysis.

gene.set.statistics.name: RNA phosphodiester bond hydrolysis, endonucleolytic
