gene.set.statistics.description: The chemical reactions and pathways involving the hydrolysis of internal 3',5'-phosphodiester bonds in one or two strands of ribonucleotides.

gene.set.statistics.name: RNA phosphodiester bond hydrolysis, exonucleolytic
gene.set.statistics.description: The chemical reactions and pathways involving the hydrolysis of terminal 3',5'-phosphodiester bonds in one or two strands of ribonucleotides.

gene.set.statistics.name: actin filament reorganization
gene.set.statistics.description: A process that is carried out at the cellular level which results in dynamic structural changes to the arrangement of actin filaments.

gene.set.statistics.name: establishment of endothelial intestinal barrier
gene.set.statistics.description: The establishment of a barrier between endothelial cell layers of the intestine to exert specific and selective control over the passage of water and solutes, thus allowing formation and maintenance of compartments that differ in fluid and solute composition.

gene.set.statistics.name: regulation of membrane permeability
gene.set.statistics.description: Any process that modulates the frequency, rate or extent of the passage or uptake of molecules by a membrane.

gene.set.statistics.name: ubiquitin-independent protein catabolic process via the multivesicular body sorting pathway
gene.set.statistics.description: The chemical reactions and pathways resulting in the breakdown of a protein or peptide, via the multivesicular body (MVB) sorting pathway; proteins are sorted into MVBs, and delivered to a lysosome/vacuole for degradation.  This process is independent of ubiquitination.

gene.set.statistics.name: activation of GTPase activity
gene.set.statistics.description: Any process that initiates the activity of an inactive GTPase through the replacement of GDP by GTP.

gene.set.statistics.name: mitochondrial tRNA processing
gene.set.statistics.description: The process in which a pre-tRNA molecule is converted to a mature tRNA, ready for addition of an aminoacyl group,  in the mitochondrion.

gene.set.statistics.name: cellular response to oxygen-glucose deprivation
gene.set.statistics.description: Any process that results in a change in state or activity of a cell (in terms of movement, secretion, enzyme production, gene expression, etc.) as a result of the deprivation of oxygen and glucose.

gene.set.statistics.name: t-circle formation
gene.set.statistics.description: A telomere maintenance process that results in the formation of a telomeric circle, or t-circle. A t-circle is an extrachromosomal duplex or single-stranded circular DNA molecule composed of t-arrays. T-circles are involved in the control of telomere length via alternative-lengthening of telomeres (ALT) pathway and telomere rapid deletion (TRD).

gene.set.statistics.name: cerebrospinal fluid circulation
gene.set.statistics.description: The neurological system process driven by motile cilia on ependymal cells of the brain by which cerebrospinal fluid circulates from the sites of secretion to the sites of absorption. In ventricular cavities, the flow is unidirectional and rostrocaudal, in subarachnoid spaces, the flow is multi-directional.

gene.set.statistics.name: scaRNA localization to Cajal body
gene.set.statistics.description: A process in which a small Cajal body-specific RNA is transported to, or maintained in, a Cajal body.

gene.set.statistics.name: telomerase RNA stabilization
gene.set.statistics.description: Prevention of degradation of telomerase RNA (TERC) molecules.

gene.set.statistics.name: telomere maintenance via telomere trimming
gene.set.statistics.description: A process that contributes to the maintenance of proper telomeric length and structure via the activation of telomere shortening pathways that compensate telomerase-dependent excessive telomere elongation. Telomere attrition is mediated by a mechanism which involves the generation of single-stranded C-rich telomeric DNA, and the formation and removal of double-stranded telomeric circular DNA (T-circles). Telomere trimming is an independent pathway to recombination-mediated telomere elongation and the well-documented gradual telomere attrition that accompanies cellular replication.

gene.set.statistics.name: energy homeostasis
gene.set.statistics.description: Any process involved in the balance between food intake (energy input) and energy expenditure.

gene.set.statistics.name: eukaryotic translation initiation factor 4F complex assembly
gene.set.statistics.description: The aggregation, arrangement and bonding together of a set of components to form the eukaryotic translation initiation factor 4F complex.

gene.set.statistics.name: cellular response to granulocyte macrophage colony-stimulating factor stimulus
gene.set.statistics.description: Any process that results in a change in state or activity of a cell (in terms of movement, secretion, enzyme production, gene expression, etc.) as a result of a granulocyte macrophage colony-stimulating factor stimulus.

gene.set.statistics.name: establishment of protein localization to endoplasmic reticulum membrane
gene.set.statistics.description: The directed movement of a protein to a specific location in the endoplasmic reticulum membrane.

gene.set.statistics.name: L-kynurenine catabolic process
gene.set.statistics.description: The chemical reactions and pathways resulting in the breakdown of L-kynurenine, the L-enantiomer of the amino acid kynurenine (3-(2-aminobenzoyl)-alanine).

gene.set.statistics.name: selenocysteinyl-tRNA(Sec) biosynthetic process
gene.set.statistics.description: The chemical reactions and pathways resulting in the formation of selenocysteinyl-tRNA(Sec). This process occurs through the following steps: a unique serine-tRNA with a UGA recognizing anticodon is first aminoacylated with serine; this is then phosphorylated by phosphoseryl-tRNA[Ser]Sec kinase; lastly, selenium is swapped for the phosphate on the serine.

gene.set.statistics.name: dendritic spine maintenance
gene.set.statistics.description: The organization process that preserves a dendritic spine in a stable functional or structural state. A dendritic spine is a specialized protrusion from a neuronal dendrite and is involved in synaptic transmission.

gene.set.statistics.name: cellular response to thyroid hormone stimulus
gene.set.statistics.description: A change in state or activity of a cell (in terms of movement, secretion, enzyme production, gene expression, etc.) as a result of a thyroid hormone stimulus.

gene.set.statistics.name: synaptic vesicle clustering
gene.set.statistics.description: The process that results in grouping synaptic vesicles in presynaptic structures.

gene.set.statistics.name: neuronal stem cell population maintenance
gene.set.statistics.description: Any process in by an organism or tissue maintains a population of neuronal stem cells.

gene.set.statistics.name: circadian regulation of translation
gene.set.statistics.description: Any process that modulates the frequency, rate or extent of mRNA translation with a regularity of approximately 24 hours.

gene.set.statistics.name: ruffle assembly
gene.set.statistics.description: The aggregation, arrangement and bonding together of a set of components to form a ruffle, a projection at the leading edge of a crawling cell; the protrusions are supported by a microfilament meshwork. The formation of ruffles (also called membrane ruffling) is thought to be controlled by a group of enzymes known as Rho GTPases, specifically RhoA, Rac1 and cdc42.

gene.set.statistics.name: apoptotic signaling pathway
gene.set.statistics.description: A series of molecular signals which triggers the apoptotic death of a cell. The pathway starts with reception of a signal, and ends when the execution phase of apoptosis is triggered.

gene.set.statistics.name: extrinsic apoptotic signaling pathway
gene.set.statistics.description: A series of molecular signals in which a signal is conveyed from the cell surface to trigger the apoptotic death of a cell. The pathway starts with either a ligand binding to a cell surface receptor, or a ligand being withdrawn from a cell surface receptor (e.g. in the case of signaling by dependence receptors), and ends when the execution phase of apoptosis is triggered.

gene.set.statistics.name: extrinsic apoptotic signaling pathway in absence of ligand
gene.set.statistics.description: A series of molecular signals in which a signal is conveyed from the cell surface to trigger the apoptotic death of a cell. The pathway starts with withdrawal of a ligand from a cell surface receptor, and ends when the execution phase of apoptosis is triggered.

gene.set.statistics.name: intrinsic apoptotic signaling pathway
gene.set.statistics.description: A series of molecular signals in which an intracellular signal is conveyed to trigger the apoptotic death of a cell. The pathway starts with reception of an intracellular signal (e.g. DNA damage, endoplasmic reticulum stress, oxidative stress etc.), and ends when the execution phase of apoptosis is triggered. The intrinsic apoptotic signaling pathway is crucially regulated by permeabilization of the mitochondrial outer membrane (MOMP).

gene.set.statistics.name: execution phase of apoptosis
gene.set.statistics.description: A stage of the apoptotic process that starts with the controlled breakdown of the cell through the action of effector caspases or other effector molecules (e.g. cathepsins, calpains etc.). Key steps of the execution phase are rounding-up of the cell, retraction of pseudopodes, reduction of cellular volume (pyknosis), chromatin condensation, nuclear fragmentation (karyorrhexis), plasma membrane blebbing and fragmentation of the cell into apoptotic bodies. When the execution phase is completed, the cell has died.

gene.set.statistics.name: negative regulation of transcription from RNA polymerase II promoter in response to stress
gene.set.statistics.description: Any process that decreases the frequency, rate or extent of transcription from an RNA polymerase II promoter as a result of a stimulus indicating the organism is under stress. The stress is usually, but not necessarily, exogenous (e.g. temperature, humidity, ionizing radiation).

gene.set.statistics.name: cellular response to gonadotropin-releasing hormone
gene.set.statistics.description: Any process that results in a change in state or activity of a cell (in terms of movement, secretion, enzyme production, gene expression, etc.) as a result of a gonadotropin-releasing hormone stimulus. Gonadotropin-releasing hormone (GnRH) is a peptide hormone responsible for the release of follicle-stimulating hormone (FSH) and luteinizing hormone (LH) from the anterior pituitary. GnRH is synthesized and released by the hypothalamus.

gene.set.statistics.name: cellular response to toxic substance
gene.set.statistics.description: Any process that results in a change in state or activity of a cell (in terms of movement, secretion, enzyme production, gene expression, etc.) as a result of a toxic stimulus.

gene.set.statistics.name: mitochondrial respirasome assembly
gene.set.statistics.description: The aggregation, arrangement and bonding together of a set of respiratory enzyme complexes of the mitochondrial inner membrane (including, for example, complex II, complex III, complex IV) to form a large supercomplex.

gene.set.statistics.name: hepatocyte apoptotic process
gene.set.statistics.description: Any apoptotic process in a hepatocyte, the main structural component of the liver.

gene.set.statistics.name: activation of cysteine-type endopeptidase activity involved in apoptotic signaling pathway
gene.set.statistics.description: Any process that initiates the activity of an inactive cysteine-type endopeptidase involved in the apoptotic signaling pathway.

gene.set.statistics.name: plasma membrane tubulation
gene.set.statistics.description: A membrane tubulation process occurring in a plasma membrane.

gene.set.statistics.name: response to antineoplastic agent
gene.set.statistics.description: Any process that results in a change in state or activity of a cell or an organism (in terms of movement, secretion, enzyme production, gene expression, etc.) as a result of an antineoplastic agent stimulus. An antineoplastic agent is a substance that inhibits or prevents the proliferation of neoplasms.

gene.set.statistics.name: response to clozapine
gene.set.statistics.description: Any process that results in a change in state or activity of a cell or an organism (in terms of movement, secretion, enzyme production, gene expression, etc.) as a result of a clozapine stimulus.

gene.set.statistics.name: neutrophil clearance
gene.set.statistics.description: The selective elimination of senescent neutrophils from the body by autoregulatory mechanisms.

gene.set.statistics.name: autophagosome maturation
gene.set.statistics.description: Removal of PI3P and Atg8/LC3 after the closure of the phagophore and before the fusion with the endosome/lysosome (e.g. mammals and insects) or vacuole (yeast), and that very likely destabilizes other Atg proteins and thus enables their efficient dissociation and recycling.

gene.set.statistics.name: UDP-glucosylation
gene.set.statistics.description: The covalent attachment of a UDP-glucose residue to a substrate molecule.

gene.set.statistics.name: establishment of Sertoli cell barrier
gene.set.statistics.description: Establishment of a structure near the basement membrane in adjacent Sertoli cells of the seminiferous epithelium for maintaining spermatogenesis. The structure consists of tight junctions, basal ectoplasmic specializations, and desmosome-like junctions.

gene.set.statistics.name: liver regeneration
gene.set.statistics.description: The regrowth of lost or destroyed liver.

gene.set.statistics.name: protein maturation by iron-sulfur cluster transfer
gene.set.statistics.description: The transfer of an assembled iron-sulfur cluster from a scaffold protein to an acceptor protein that contributes to the attainment of the full functional capacity of a protein.

gene.set.statistics.name: supramolecular fiber organization
gene.set.statistics.description: A process that is carried out at the cellular level which results in the assembly, arrangement of constituent parts, or disassembly of a supramolecular fiber, a polymer consisting of an indefinite number of protein or protein complex subunits that have polymerised to form a fiber-shaped structure.

gene.set.statistics.name: dendrite extension
gene.set.statistics.description: Long distance growth of a single dendrite involved in cellular development.

gene.set.statistics.name: regulation of vesicle size
gene.set.statistics.description: Any process that modulates the size of a vesicle.

gene.set.statistics.name: lamellipodium organization
gene.set.statistics.description: A process that is carried out at the cellular level which results in the assembly, arrangement of constituent parts, or disassembly of a lamellipodium. A lamellipodium is a thin sheetlike process extended by the leading edge of a crawling fibroblast; contains a dense meshwork of actin filaments.

gene.set.statistics.name: double-strand break repair via classical nonhomologous end joining
gene.set.statistics.description: An instance of double-strand break repair via nonhomologous end joining that requires a number of factors important for V(D)J recombination, including the KU70/80 heterodimer (KU), XRCC4, ligase IV, and DNA-PKcs in mammals. It does not produce translocations (as opposed to the alternative nonhomologous end joining).

gene.set.statistics.name: double-strand break repair via alternative nonhomologous end joining
gene.set.statistics.description: An instance of double-strand break repair via nonhomologous end joining that is independent of factors important for V(D)J recombination (as opposed to classical nonhomologous end joining). It often results in a deletion with microhomology (i.e. 5-25bp homology) at the repair junction. Among different subclasses of nonhomologous end joining (NHEJ), alternative NHEJ appears to play a significant role in the etiology of mutations that arise during cancer development and treatment.

gene.set.statistics.name: ciliary basal body-plasma membrane docking
gene.set.statistics.description: The docking of a cytosolic centriole/basal body to the plasma membrane via the ciliary transition fibers. In some species this may happen via an intermediate step, by first docking to the ciliary vesicle via the ciliary transition fibers. The basal body-ciliary vesicle then relocates to the plasma membrane, followed by the ciliary vesicle fusing with the plasma membrane, effectively attaching the basal body to the plasma membrane.

gene.set.statistics.name: mitochondrial tRNA 5'-end processing
gene.set.statistics.description: The process in which the 5' end of a pre-tRNA molecule is converted to that of a mature tRNA in the mitochondrion.

gene.set.statistics.name: blood vessel diameter maintenance
gene.set.statistics.description: Any process that modulates the diameter of blood vessels.

gene.set.statistics.name: membrane tubulation
gene.set.statistics.description: A membrane organization process resulting in the formation of a tubular projection. This may face inwardly (as in tubular membrane invaginations) or outwardly (as in endosomal tubules).

gene.set.statistics.name: histone H3-K27 trimethylation
gene.set.statistics.description: The modification of histone H3 by addition of three methyl groups to lysine at position 27 of the histone.

gene.set.statistics.name: centriole assembly
gene.set.statistics.description: A cellular process that results in the assembly of one or more centrioles.

gene.set.statistics.name: cellular response to virus
gene.set.statistics.description: Any process that results in a change in state or activity of a cell (in terms of movement, secretion, enzyme production, gene expression, etc.) as a result of a stimulus from a virus.

gene.set.statistics.name: cell-cell adhesion
gene.set.statistics.description: The attachment of one cell to another cell via adhesion molecules.

gene.set.statistics.name: glucose import across plasma membrane
gene.set.statistics.description: The directed movement of glucose from outside of a cell, across the plasma membrane and into the cytosol.

gene.set.statistics.name: L-glutamate import across plasma membrane
gene.set.statistics.description: The directed movement of L-glutamate from outside of a cell, across the plasma membrane and into the cytosol.

gene.set.statistics.name: leucine import across plasma membrane
gene.set.statistics.description: The directed movement of leucine from outside of a cell, across the plasma membrane and into the cytosol.

gene.set.statistics.name: import across plasma membrane
gene.set.statistics.description: The directed movement of some substance from outside of a cell, across the plasma membrane and into the cytosol.

gene.set.statistics.name: cell-cell adhesion via plasma-membrane adhesion molecules
gene.set.statistics.description: The attachment of one cell to another cell via adhesion molecules that are at least partially embedded in the plasma membrane.

gene.set.statistics.name: cellular response to interleukin-7
gene.set.statistics.description: Any process that results in a change in state or activity of a cell (in terms of movement, secretion, enzyme production, gene expression, etc.) as a result of an interleukin-7 stimulus.

gene.set.statistics.name: positive regulation of mitophagy in response to mitochondrial depolarization
gene.set.statistics.description: Any process that activates or increases the frequency, rate or extent of mitophagy in response to mitochondrial depolarization.

gene.set.statistics.name: response to mitochondrial depolarisation
gene.set.statistics.description: Any process that results in a change in state or activity of a cell (in terms of movement, secretion, enzyme production, gene expression, etc.) in response to the depolarization of one or more mitochondria.

gene.set.statistics.name: pre-mRNA cleavage required for polyadenylation
gene.set.statistics.description: The targeted, endonucleolytic cleavage of a pre-mRNA,  required for polyadenylation of the 3' end.  This cleavage is directed by binding sites near the 3' end of the mRNA and leaves a 3' hydoxyl end which then becomes a target for adenylation.

gene.set.statistics.name: modulation of excitatory postsynaptic potential
gene.set.statistics.description: Any process that modulates the frequency, rate or extent of excitatory postsynaptic potential (EPSP). EPSP is a process that leads to a temporary increase in postsynaptic potential due to the flow of positively charged ions into the postsynaptic cell. The flow of ions that causes an EPSP is an excitatory postsynaptic current (EPSC) and makes it easier for the neuron to fire an action potential.

gene.set.statistics.name: protein transport along microtubule
gene.set.statistics.description: The directed movement of a protein along a microtubule, mediated by motor proteins.

gene.set.statistics.name: cellular oxidant detoxification
gene.set.statistics.description: Any process carried out at the cellular level that reduces or removes the toxicity superoxide radicals or hydrogen peroxide.

gene.set.statistics.name: postsynaptic neurotransmitter receptor internalization
gene.set.statistics.description: A receptor-mediated endocytosis process that results in the internalization of a neurotransmitter receptor from the postsynaptic membrane endocytic zone into an endocytic vesicle.

gene.set.statistics.name: regulation of cardiac muscle cell action potential
gene.set.statistics.description: Any process that modulates the frequency, rate or extent of action potential creation, propagation or termination in a cardiac muscle cell. This typically occurs via modulation of the activity or expression of voltage-gated ion channels.

gene.set.statistics.name: regulation of membrane repolarization during action potential
gene.set.statistics.description: Any process that modulates the rate, frequency or extent of membrane repolarization during an action potential. Membrane repolarization is the process in which membrane potential changes in the repolarizing direction, towards the resting potential.

gene.set.statistics.name: regulation of neuronal action potential
gene.set.statistics.description: Any process that modulates the frequency, rate or extent of action potential creation, propagation or termination in a neuron. This typically occurs via modulation of the activity or expression of voltage-gated ion channels.

gene.set.statistics.name: regulation of cardiac muscle cell action potential involved in regulation of contraction
gene.set.statistics.description: Any process that modulates the frequency, rate or extent of action potential creation, propagation or termination in a cardiac muscle cell contributing to the regulation of its contraction.

gene.set.statistics.name: regulation of ventricular cardiac muscle cell action potential
gene.set.statistics.description: Any process that modulates the frequency, rate or extent of action potential creation, propagation or termination in a ventricular cardiac muscle cell contributing to the regulation of its contraction.  This typically occurs via modulation of the activity or expression of voltage-gated ion channels.

gene.set.statistics.name: axonal transport
gene.set.statistics.description: The directed movement of organelles or molecules along microtubules in axons.

gene.set.statistics.name: dendritic transport of messenger ribonucleoprotein complex
gene.set.statistics.description: The directed movement of a messenger ribonucleoprotein complex along microtubules in nerve cell dendrites.

gene.set.statistics.name: anterograde dendritic transport of neurotransmitter receptor complex
gene.set.statistics.description: The directed movement of a neurotransmitter receptor complex along microtubules in nerve cell dendrites towards the postsynapse.

gene.set.statistics.name: postsynaptic actin cytoskeleton organization
gene.set.statistics.description: A process that is carried out at the cellular level which results in the assembly, arrangement of constituent parts, or disassembly of cytoskeletal structures comprising actin filaments and their associated proteins in the postsynaptic actin cytoskeleton.

gene.set.statistics.name: regulation of postsynaptic membrane neurotransmitter receptor levels
gene.set.statistics.description: Any process that regulates the the local concentration of neurotransmitter receptor at the postsynaptic membrane.

gene.set.statistics.name: calcium export from the mitochondrion
gene.set.statistics.description: A process in which a calcium ion (Ca2+) is transported out of the mitochondrial matrix, and into the cytosol.

gene.set.statistics.name: regulation of modification of postsynaptic structure
gene.set.statistics.description: Any process that modulates the frequency, rate or extent of modification of postsynaptic structure.

gene.set.statistics.name: postsynapse organization
gene.set.statistics.description: A process that is carried out at the cellular level which results in the assembly, arrangement of constituent parts, or disassembly of a postsynapse.

gene.set.statistics.name: regulation of postsynapse organization
gene.set.statistics.description: Any process that modulates the physical form of a postsynapse.

gene.set.statistics.name: regulation of presynaptic cytosolic calcium ion concentration
gene.set.statistics.description: Any process that regulates the concentration of calcium in the presynaptic cytosol.

gene.set.statistics.name: dense core granule cytoskeletal transport
gene.set.statistics.description: The directed movement of dense core granules along cytoskeletal fibers, such as microtubules or actin filaments.

gene.set.statistics.name: presynaptic dense core vesicle exocytosis
gene.set.statistics.description: The secretion of molecules (e.g. neuropeptides and neuromodulators such as serotonin and dopamine) contained within a membrane-bounced dense in response to increased presynaptic cytosolic calcium levels.

gene.set.statistics.name: presynapse to nucleus signaling pathway
gene.set.statistics.description: A series of molecular signals that conveys information from the presynapse to the nucleus via cytoskeletal transport of a protein from a presynapse to the component to the nucleus where it affects biochemical processes that occur in the nucleus (e.g DNA transcription, mRNA splicing, or DNA/histone modifications).

gene.set.statistics.name: postsynapse to nucleus signaling pathway
gene.set.statistics.description: A series of molecular signals that conveys information from the postsynapse to the nucleus via cytoskeletal transport of a protein from a postsynapse to the component to the nucleus where it affects biochemical processes that occur in the nucleus (e.g DNA transcription, mRNA splicing, or DNA/histone modifications).

gene.set.statistics.name: maintenance of synapse structure
gene.set.statistics.description: A process that preserves the structural organistation and orientation of a synaptic cellular component such as the synaptic cytoskeleton and molecular scaffolds.

gene.set.statistics.name: maintenance of postsynaptic density structure
gene.set.statistics.description: A process which maintains the organization and the arrangement of proteins in the presynaptic density.

gene.set.statistics.name: modification of synaptic structure
gene.set.statistics.description: Any process that modifies the structure/morphology of a synapse.

gene.set.statistics.name: regulation of translation at postsynapse, modulating synaptic transmission
gene.set.statistics.description: Any process that modulates synaptic transmission by regulating translation occurring at the postsynapse.

gene.set.statistics.name: protein localization to axon
gene.set.statistics.description: A process in which a protein is transported to or maintained in a location within an axon.

gene.set.statistics.name: endosome to plasma membrane protein transport
gene.set.statistics.description: The directed movement of proteins from the endosome to the plasma membrane in transport vesicles.

gene.set.statistics.name: anterograde axonal protein transport
gene.set.statistics.description: The directed movement of proteins along microtubules from the cell body toward the cell periphery in nerve cell axons.

gene.set.statistics.name: positive regulation of DNA repair by transcription from RNA polymerase II promoter
gene.set.statistics.description: Any transcription from RNA polymerase II promoter process that positively regulates DNA repair.

gene.set.statistics.name: tRNA (guanine-N7)-methylation
gene.set.statistics.description: The process whereby a guanine in a tRNA is methylated at the N7 position of guanine.

gene.set.statistics.name: protein maturation by [2Fe-2S] cluster transfer
gene.set.statistics.description: The transfer of an assembled [2Fe-2S] cluster from a scaffold protein to an acceptor protein that contributes to the attainment of the full functional capacity of a protein.

gene.set.statistics.name: protein maturation by [4Fe-4S] cluster transfer
gene.set.statistics.description: The transfer of an assembled 4Fe-4S] cluster from a scaffold protein to an acceptor protein that contributes to the attainment of the full functional capacity of a protein.

gene.set.statistics.name: aminoacyl-tRNA metabolism involved in translational fidelity
gene.set.statistics.description: Any process which detects an amino-acid acetylated tRNA is charged with the correct amino acid, or removes incorrect amino acids from a charged tRNA. This process can be performed by tRNA synthases, or by subsequent reactions after tRNA aminoacylation.

gene.set.statistics.name: histone succinylation
gene.set.statistics.description: The modification of a histone by the addition of an succinyl group.

gene.set.statistics.name: protein-DNA covalent cross-linking repair
gene.set.statistics.description: The removal of covalent cross-link between DNA and a protein.

gene.set.statistics.name: cellular detoxification of aldehyde
gene.set.statistics.description: Any process carried out at the cellular level that reduces or removes the toxicity of an aldehyde. These may include transport of aldehydes away from sensitive areas and to compartments or complexes whose purpose is sequestration of the toxic substance.

gene.set.statistics.name: mRNA alternative polyadenylation
gene.set.statistics.description: The process of generating multiple mRNA molecules with variable 3'-end length formation from a given pre-mRNA by differential use of cleavage and polyadenylation signals (pA signals).

gene.set.statistics.name: intermembrane lipid transfer
gene.set.statistics.description: The transport of lipids between membranes in which a lipid molecule is transported through an aqueous phase from the outer leaflet of a donor membrane to the outer leaflet of an acceptor membrane. This process does not require metabolic energy and can be either spontaneous or mediated by lipid transfer proteins (LTPs).

gene.set.statistics.name: negative regulation of cold-induced thermogenesis

gene.set.statistics.name: tight junction assembly
gene.set.statistics.description: A cellular process that results in the aggregation, arrangement and bonding together of a set of components to form a tight junction. A tight junction seals cells together in an epithelium in a way that prevents even small molecules from leaking from one side of the sheet to the other.

gene.set.statistics.name: mitochondrial ADP transmembrane transport

gene.set.statistics.name: lipid droplet formation

gene.set.statistics.name: organelle localization by membrane tethering

gene.set.statistics.name: serine import into mitochondrion

gene.set.statistics.name: antiviral innate immune response
